12 oz bottle from my trip out west over christmas app : a wonderful blend of dark amber , ruby , and garnet . fluffy tan head that fades to a nice cap and thick lace .  m - the feel is sharp initially with a chalky and sublime salty finish on the palate .
the rich smoky aroma has strong tones of roast coffee and molasses and just a whisper of unsweetened chocolate , demanding a taste .  light body , wish it were bigger and more creamy .
smell dark malts , a inviting chocolate smell with a beautiful sweetness .  m-moderate carbonation , medium-bodied beer , with a noticeable hoppy dryness .

aroma is sweet , fruity , ( raisins , plums ) malty with a little milk chocolate ( whoppers candy ) . lively mouth-feel . flavor does not quite come together tho . it has a mix of sweet fruits , sourdough bread , bitter citrus pith , but it just doesnt seem to be balanced .  m : a little spritzy and thin for my taste .

lucky me ... the bartender was so cool about the pour erupting with soch a frothy top , he gave me a 2nd on 'da house . poured into a wide mouthed tulip , ruddy amber with a beige inch cap that decreased with spotty coating .  very light and summer-appropriate . could drink several . definitely a solid brew .

this brew poured a creamy head of fine to medium sized light brown bubbles that left a good lacing and a opaque black brown fizzy carbonated body with a roasted malt caramel aroma .  saison du buff appearance- very hazy golden , lively white head that dissipates quickly.4 smell- hops - green buds to the max 5 taste- wow . delicious . sweet and citrusy but with huge hop and wheat finish.complex balanced . spicy nutmeg 5 mouf- easy 3 drinkable - oh so drinkability 4
hazy dark yellow colour . there is a huge off-white head which lasts and lasts .  carbonation is a little too pronounced .

a : poured a one fingered head while being a beautiful amber with carbonation rising . the carbonation is rising throughout the snifter equally which is rare for carbonation rising and some carbonation even sits at the base of the glass . this also laces beautifully down the glass . this even come in nice and creamy because of its great lasting head .  the mouthfeel is a little crisp but does smooth out .

it pours opaque black with a very generous , long-lasting sticky tan head in my fin du monde glass ( great with stouts i find ) .  m - thin body , or at least thinner than expected . low carbonation .

the beer is unlike anything else available ; and they introduced the nitrogen pour to the world . people find it to be heavy , thick , rich and strong when in fact it is light , thin and low in alcohol . of course , it does have a certain mouthfeel from the nitro head , and it is roasty . the u.s. version is pasteurized and has an alcohol content of 4.2 % by volume ( budweiser is now 5 % in most states ) .  smells very nutty with mild chocolate roast . the beer fairly sweet tasting with the nuttiness coming through . cabonation is a bit higher than i would like , but other than that it is a very good brown ale .

a - crisp , brilliant clarity . bright orange with hints of red . head is initially thick then fades to a persistent thin layer with gobs of lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is not a complex one and is rather unbalanced and nondescript .

aroma is exquisite - spices , yeast , malt , fruit , herbs , in an exotic blend that is beguiling . flavor 's not as intriguing as the nose , but still pretty good . reminds me of a good saison .  typical mouthfeel for a lager i guess , although i do n't know a lot about what this style should be like .

very interesting smell , cherries left in a glass of rum for several hours & sprinkled with sweet malt dust . very nice . black tot mixes genres with the abandon of a dj just discovering the turntable in his parent 's basement . very interesting , & good , beer .  m- much too thin for the style and something this big .

the head on this makes the appearance , a awesome tope head with great retention and lacing that coats the glass the whole drinking experience top to bottom ... the aroma is like a malty ipa , lots of caramel , with grass wet hops , its really appetizing ... taste is grass hops that have a fresh bite which is nice , maybe that bite is the rye .  mouthfeel was a bit thin , pretty amazing for a beer of this gravity , making this dangerously drinkable .
appearance - super pale straw body .  somewhat thin in it 's mouthfeel although a good creaminess creeps up toward the end .

a : pours a beautiful deep mahogany color . a large creamy beige head forms and gently recedes and leaves sticky lace down the glass .  a - poured a black color with a tan head that leaves lacing behind s - is of roasted malt vanilla and some smoke t - follows the nose for the most part the oak gives nice hints of vanilla and the smoked malt seems more present than the regular bottled version which is n't bad to me m - this beer has a thin body with medium carbonation to it d - this oaked version was a very good beer but i 'm still disappointed with the body definitely worth grabbing a pint of if you ever hear about it being tapped

this beer pours almost black with deep mahogany highlights , topped by a rocky tan head that fills my pint glass . the head slowly fades , leaving a thick , sticky lace on the glass .  carbonation scrubs the tongue with perky bubbles ( almost too much , but not quite ) and has a medium-light body .
definitely the best looking of the three with a nice yellow/orangey color , cloudy with tasty yeasties .  medium carbonation and a slight astringency .

rocky , 1cm offwhite head capping a rich amber-brown body . good retention .  wow , i enjoyed the flavor of this beer , the hops are more present in the aroma than the taste , maybe showing up in the extremely dry mouthfeel though . not exactly full bodied , a little light compared to the dark lords we were drinking prior to this , but still it matches the flavors in an appealing way .

light head , soft , beautiful reddish copper brown .  mouthfeel is a letdown - it may just be this bottle but the carbonation is too weak . only have one of these 750ml bottles as it 's imported and a special occasion but i 'd be keen to have another one , if only to compare the carbonation .
s : beautiful - huge fan of coffee 's , so this did not disappoint . espresso , roasted coffee beans , just full-on coffee .  m - high carbonation , but a little watery .

the aroma projects bright floral hops very nice really though i initially caught a whiff of something that said , miller high life to me .  m : the body is medium with a low carbonation and a tooth rotting sweetness . so unbearably sweet and sugary without any sort of balance .
the appearance is amazing .. lots of bubbles on the side of glass when poured , a very strong color orange and hardly no foam on top .  mf is a bit lacking , thin , though creamy .
looks beautiful in a trappist glass . after the bubbles settle , it looks like chocolate milk with reddish edges .  the mouthfeel was slightly thinner than expected .

pours a crystal-clear bright golden , with holy-shit levels of turbulent carbonation that makes the head climb out of the glass . it maintains a tight , bone-white head throughout and leaves decent lacing as i go .  m : mouthfeel was a little thin for the style .

excellent looking beer .  like other ommegang brews , too carbonated , which detracts from what would be a nice heavy feel . nice balance makes for very good drinkability ; biggest knock from me is the excessively fizzy feel .
aromas were strong with sweet grains flavors and an earthy tone .  mouthfeel is okay , but needs to be either thicker or creamier to work with the taste -- as is , it 's just a tad watery .

s : this has the most interesting tobacco note i 've found in a beer yet . its the appealing mustiness of well used pipe with accents of cocoa and cherry playing beautifully off of it . the tobacco is here , just as interesting and as appealing , but the tart , slightly funky cherry is more prominent . d : while i absolutely loved the tobacco i found , i do n't think this was quite what they had in mind .  mouthfeel : has a fair body , but nothing out of the ordinary .

pours a pitch black color with a beautiful brown head into my glass . definitely the color of the style . roasted malt greets the nose followed by grassy hops that do n't jump out too much in the nose .  m : pretty thin and not too lively .

on pouring this looks like it 's gon na be good , dark brown-black with a tan milk chocolate color of foam , thick frothy foam too .  it lingers really well on the tongue , very good aftertaste . the mouthfeel is meh , as it 's a little thin .

a- cork shot off like champagne , pouring pitch black with an ever-growing tan head that retained well and left excellent retention .  well , it looks like a good brown ale and smells like a good raspberry brown ale . the taste of this nice looking raspberry brown was that of nutty , roasted malts ( good ) and burnt raspberries ( bad ) . the charred flavor that came through in this sampling was overwhelmingly horrible . i like the other harbor city brews , so i 'm willing to try this again in case i had a very bad batch .

a : pours a fantastic golden-orange . slightly opaque , with a voluminous yellow head . nice retention , and great lacing . phenomenal .  mouthfeel is slightly thin , with lower carbonation , not bad .

appearance : its body is black as night and opaque with a typical nitro head on top . it has very good retention and makes cool lacing on the glass as i drink .  wow ! what a pleasant surprise ! i tried this beer on-tap at a new restaurant near my apartment called `` kushi . '' i was in the mood for a light , white ale - and this beer definitely delivered . it was crisp and refreshing . taste was tart and light , a little sour , but well balanced . i 'd have this beer again , and again , and again..

very very nice smell . flavor follows the nose , but a bit more bitter than i expected , but dark fruit dominated ris .  got this in the secret santa 2008 - from dmeadows , thanks again ! a bit of a funky musty aroma mixed with the spicy nutmeg , quaff is a boatload of allspice , nutmeg , fig , plum and an underlying hint of alcohol booze - even after 2 years in the cellar . and the elderberries add quite a different take on the solid offering . sweet initial start , boozy and hoppy finish . a true winter sipper , tasty and enjoyable with the football game .

has outstanding appearance for a lager .  after several sips i finished the taster and got a bottle of water to cleanse the palate . the body was average for a wit , but the hops made this sloppy mess nearly undrinkable .

poured into a snifter , the brew appears black in color with the faintest line of clarity and brown around the edges . a dark brown finger of head appears and as it slowly recedes , leaves spots and a webbing pattern of lace . a swirl revives a full finger worth of dark brown head .  m : the body is medium and the carbonation is low to medium i suppose .
beautiful copper/orange body with a slight haze topped with a thick , dense , long lasting head . looks beautiful , tastes good , drinks easy .  mouthfeel : medium carbonation .

pours a very nice clear deep dark amber-reddish-brown with an inch of beige foam that lasts .  deep red-brown color with amazing billowy off-white head : thick and lasting with good lacing s : hoppy and malty balance with yeasty notes and spices t : orange and nutmeg maltiness with a hoppy bitter finish m : a little thin , but this is towards the end of its season by now .
the color and appearance of this ale is perfect ! it 's a deep dark chocolate brown w/ a thick dark tan head .  body a bit light and bubbly .
a : i loved the appearance of this beer it had a yellow murky tint .  the mouthfeel is clean and crisp , with less body than i 'd hoped for .
poured dark dark brown with a brown head .  mouthfeel is medium to full-bodied .

thick , black beer pours with a beautiful , fluffy head that is the color of light caramel . it shows staying power that would make a porn star proud . a very well distributed lace is left behind .  medium finish . a bit too bubbly at first , but a smooth finish .

hop haze and alcohol feet are evident . the aroma is a good one , with predominant citrus and slight bitterness , with a nice malty , caramel aroma .  m - well balanced , but thin and slightly sweet . was hoping for a medium to full-bodied saison .

a - opened the sucker and out came massive foam . poured slowly into duvel , tons of head . lots of sticky lace . brown , fairly clear dark tea color .  o-a nice stout that would benefit greatly from a more viscous and luxurious mouthfeel . with the harsh carbonation it seems more like a coffee soda pop .

lacing is superb but head retention is merely `` well above average . '' color is an opaque blackness that turns a reddish brown only when held up to the brightest lights at the thinnest portion of your glass .  m : too thin and unsustained to be great .

a- in the weisse beer glass this is a very pretty looking beer .  i 'm almost halfway through the pint and still impressed with the carbonation . i 'm also surprised at the body ; it seems a bit thin and makes the beer rather perilously drinkable at nearly 7 percent alcohol . this long , bitter and dry finish is perhaps the most enjoyable quality of this beer , that and i suppose it 's dangerous drinkability .

amazing aroma ! there is some type of wood smell in there , as if aged in a barrel . reminiscent of a belgian strong ale , with the spices and the alcohol content . a beautiful and different beer drinking experience . warms my belleh .  well , what can i say . this is definantly the most unique beer i have ever tried . this beer would make a wonderful cooking beer but for drinking it is possibly one of the worst i have ever tasted . the smell and flavour are just not something i want to drink . very hickory smoked ham . used to flavour a chili it would be wonderful , but like i said , as a drink the nastiest thing in the world . literally like drinking smoked ham .

a deep ruby red with a really dense and creamy light-brown head , this beer is quite gorgeous . with nice , red highlights , this is really a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel is a bit sticky and the flavors stick around for a bit after swallowing .

a- perfect . deep ominous black body with thick creamy dark tan head . the head retention is excellent and a coating of lacing is left all the way down the glass .  smooth and sweet , this is pretty nice . carbonation is a bit low , even for my liking .

alaskan amber i recently drank on tap in idaho . the apperance of this beer is very dark , almost cherry wood looking with a foamy cream head . a very drinkable beer , not to thick and not to light .  m- this beer is very carbonated and somewhat thin , very refreshing .

bottle , served in a wine glass . hazy pastel orange , champagne streams of carbonation . creamy whipped meringue foam that lasts forever , leaving impressive irregular peaks and crags that rise above the rim of the glass .  m : medium , but thicker than expected , this is one of my first lambics , but it really steps up to the plate and is a home run .

it is a big bold german style hefe with a wonderous banana aroma mixed with what i really believe to be brett . now , i know this is not really true to style at all but this smelled like heaven -- all funky et all . the flavor was definately a bit of a let down , as the brett character was not as prevelant , but i could see that it was still there .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied and slightly syrupy . minimal carbonation .

poured a massive light custard yellow head which lasted longest i think i 've ever seen ( almost a merengue ) .  its a huge beer , but the mouthfeel isnt as thick as i would like or expect . good levels of carbonation , and they did a great job of hiding the alcohol .

50cl bottle from system in lund sweden a - beautiful ! very dark indeed . head is a nice chocolate color .  m : sticky and fairly thick , dry , slightly dry , prickly carbonation , hint of warm alcohol , just a little too syrupy for my taste .
( a ) - pours almost pitch black with a large light brown head that slowly dissipated to a solid 1-finger . plenty of lacing present .  mouthfeel : medium body , ok carbonation . pretty average .
visually this beer is flawless . sticky cement lacing .  feels a bit thin , low-medium body and medium carbonation .
it stays forever and looks beautiful like a solid entity .  102 ibu ... tastes sweet , like honey and ginger ale with a touch of malt . little too syrupy to be super refreshing but still awesome .

great looking ipa .  t & m : this is a well rounded stout . nicely carbonated , well balanced with a nice roasted bitterness ( but not offensively so ) and sweetness from the malted oats . feels a little on the `` watery '' side for a stout though .
smell - very malty . chocolate and a slight hint of light roasted coffee .  mouthfeel - the only downside imo is that it has a dry finish and leaves the pallet thirsty .

amazing , huge , fluffy , foamy nut colored head is sculpted and precariously teetering well out of the rim of the glass . damn thats sexy . well crap .  m/d : medium bodied , but seemed a little thin and very easy to drink .
this is one beautiful looking beer . it is a slow pour , due to the vast amounts of light tan head that is created .  m : the mouthfeel is okay but feels a little thin , especially for a dipa .
really interesting and unique smelling . tastes similar , with grapefruit and spice/grain up front , pine , and again kind of a honey and malt sweetness .  it feels pretty average for this style .

bomber poured into a tulip glass . beer pours a mostly clear copper color with a slight chill haze coming out of the refrigerator . initial two fingers of off white head , mix of small bubbles and tight foam . retention was good for a few minutes before slowly dissipating , leaving a thick layer of lacing along the edge of the glass , down to a collar of small bubbles . plenty of fine carbonation floating up from the bottom of the glass .  light-medium bodied , needs to be fuller .
smells wonderfully of grapefruit , hemp and pine notes with some herbal and alcohol notes .  however , the body is a little thin , with a slighlty soapy feel .

12 oz bottle poured into a tulip - best by 12/3/2007 appearance : pours a deep , dark brown that still shows a little bit of light through it . the head is tan with a height of one inch.the head is cakey and has deep craters . plenty of lace clings to the glass .  mouthfeel is not quite as full as it could be , but still does a good job delivering and distributing flavor around the mouth .
smell - very fruity and sweet . raisins , cherries , and honey . delicious ... smells like dessert .  mouthfeel is about medium in weight , but the carbonation is dull .

a : golden appearance that pours 50/50 liquid and foam . i rated this 5 on appearance because this beer has the best head on a beer that i 've seen . it is rocky and tightly beaded , leaving a lace as it slowly recedes .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with sharp carbonation .

a : pour is a hazy light orange , almost like a creamsicle . 3 inches of frothy head sinks slowly back into the beer .  as a williamsburg native , and dark beer fan , i was severly disappointed with this porter . it could have been that the six pack was skunky , i guess . nonetheless , a big disappointment . if one could imagine a porter that is too sweet , this would fit into that category . baltika is also a sweeter porter , but only has a hint . this beer is blatantly sweet .

thanks to mer who imported this from italy ( hey i was hoping there would be italian on the bottle , but oh well ) ... appearance : i sampled this in a chalice ( not a chimay chalice however ) , which effects the color a bit ... the beer was slightly cloudy and blood red , bordering on brown . head was about an inch thick on top , white and megenguey ( alright , do n't know how else to describe it , but it stayed above the top of the glass without spilling over like a merengue pie ) .  the flavor is lightly sweet thought , with some wheat towards the beginning , going to some hops , and a light sweet finish . for me , a pretty good summer session brew .
this beer pours a very large light tan head with great retention and amazing lacing .  mf- a bit thin . leaves a good feeling in the mouth after you are finished . carbonation a bit high .

very clean and very aromatic . taste : the tropical fruit hop flavor really is the main note in the flavor profile . overall , a nice , aromatic ipa with good tropical fruit notes .  there is a lack of head or carbonation , the body is very cloudy with a chunky suspension . the flavor is also adversely affected , the malt tastes raw and grainy , and it masks whatever this beer is supposed to taste like . i will be pouring this bottle out , i am hoping that this is an exception , not the rule from this beer .
lots of full bodied lovely lacing when stirred .  m - medium to light body .

a : it pours a completely opaque black color with two fingers of white nitro froth that laces incredibly well .  very dark with maybe a hint of red if you hold it up to the light . a little flat so the mouthfeel is not as good .

among the best smelling brews ive experienced . t : flavor not as exquisite as the nose but still tight . i enjoy the bitterness of this imp stout matched with the deeply roasted malt . not the best tasting ris but the best aromas in my opinion .  on the downside the mouthfeel was much fizzier than one would expect ... very thin , too .

it started out well pouring with a clear rich amber color and a nice thick head .  the mouthfeel is nothing exceptional but it is also not bad . it is a bit fizzy but this does n't offset the flavors .
pours a light copper/gold with a big creamy off-white head .  the mouthfeel is just average .
very interesting . taste in line with the nose , with the licorice even more asseritve upfront in the palate .  the body is a little thin for my likes .

the pils hops are there , of course , and quite nice , but much more complex and engaging than the norm . drinkability : while not a great pils , the monster nose makes it interesting enough to recommend .  m - maybe a little on the thin side for me -- the carbonation is higher than i 'm used to .

the aroma is phenomenal , the taste backs off just a bit . there is an earthiness , from the garden of eden , perhaps ?  the disappointing : wow , what a highly carbonated brew , almost champaign in the fizziness .

samuel adams latitude 48 ipa is dark and gorgeous , earthy , and thin . it poured dark copper with a massive tan head .  ( 4 ) m : thin with hi carb ( a little too hi ) and a dry finish . would like a little more body or a little less carb to make this a little more palatable .

the smell of this beer is excelent , smells like coffe flavored chocolate and caramel , but the taste is quite dissapointing , the carbonation hides most of it , i only got a little bit of caramel there .  m - uberchewy , sweet . med-light carbonation .

one pint swing-top bottle & gt ; dimpled mug this is a deep , darl mahogony brown color with a rather impressive 3 '' towering khaki colored head that is pillowy with huge clumpiness , very slow retention with plenety of foam everywhere .  body is full with smooth carbonation , but a bit on the low side .
a - it 's damn hot and muggy here right now , and the bright golden body and thick , fluffy white head 'atop this beer looks really damn good .  m : nothing special .

i wanted so much to love this beer . yeti , oaked yeti , and the phenomenal espresso oaked yeti are heavenly ... but due to some unfortunate choices by great divide this beer will go down as a novelty not to be reproduced . the aroma of this beer and the appearance lead you to believe that this is going to be another great yeti , but the taste and mouth feel ruin the beer . there are subtle notes of the chocolate that hint to what this could have been , but alas they ruined it by unbalancing everything terribly by making this a strange pepper brew .  overall quite mouthfilling , cakey , dangerously smooth and rounded . the beer takes a bit of a down turn towards the end as the flavors fizzle a bit and the beer seems to thin out and go a bit watery . mouthfeel , while not ever being truly creamy , comes close with real soft and smooth carbonation .

s : fresh crushed raspberries , sweet and fragrant . does n't smell like beer at all .  the mouth is fairly thick ( for a lower abv lager , that is ) , and the carbonation is too high , unless poured a little hard .

pours out with a cloudy yellow body and a huge white pillowy head of foam . the head breaks down slowly leaving a mountain of foam in the middle and covering the entire glass .  m - thin and a little astringent , but it is very refreshing apart from that .

s- this beer smells of tart cherries and a hint of musty basement and a soft oak note .  i am almost positive this is living under the assumed name of `` doc mason 's ryepa '' at solana beach . aroma is rye , caramel malt , and hops . nice hop bite up front with a smoother rye and caramel back . acidic and alcoholic finish .

pungent candied grapefruit with sharper notes of lemon zest , bolstered with stately light caramel malt . simcoe dry hop character overwhelms , agreeably so . tepid clementine hints provide a softer citrus character .  m : on the lighter side .
huge 3 finger head with lines , legs and lace galore .  the mouthfeel is atypical for a saison . it 's a little heavier and not as carbonated as is typical of the style .

a - the darkest brown possible without being black . head is 1.5 fingers with a beautiful dark tan color that leaves some nice lacing as the brew is consumed .  i 'm sorry guys but another swing and a miss . beer aggressively foamed out the bottle immediately on opening , after sitting in the refigerator for two days , so no mistakes on my part there . the sourness overwhelms any good qualities which are there , lying underneath but truly irrelevent . cigar city is a great brewery with great potential but lets get it together guys . do not put these beers on the shelf when they are clearly sub-par . cheers everybody- it 's only beer . i expect great things from this brewery but let 's please enact some quality control .
awesome retention and structure . the beer was a very dark/murky brown color that looked like rugged/worn leather .  mouthfeel : feels slightly carbonated and thicker than water on the tongue .
very english in appearance , burnished copper tending towards shades of yellow . creamy , sustained eggshell head with lovely lacing .  medium thin body .

huge , frothy head .  the drink was citrusy at the front , with a floral spicy taste towards the middle with a subtle hop kick at the end . i found this beer to be very interesting and enjoyable . it would make a good stand alone , or a good session beer .

rather transparent and light copper in color . good layer of retention and thick lacing .  taste was somewhat bitter , and more of the hops , with alcohol becoming more evident in both the aroma and taste at mid-glass . finish was slightly bitter aftertaste , but mostly smooth and a bit dry .

s-the smell of this beer is amazing ! having had perseguidor 3 , i would say this is the only trait that is better in 4 . insanely complex nose , smells of wood , funk , dried fruit , chestnuts and roasted malt . truely exceptional . there is virtually no stout flavor , i tastes similar to an old bruin , but thiner and less acidic , a sipper to be sure do to the tartness , but very tasty . d-another great offering in this series , captain ron is a master at blending his styles .  m-not very carbonated , lighter body than expected but too light in between the medium .

there are some good things going on here ; the aroma is quite nice , but the flavor comes across as a little rough and it just does n't have enough complexity to justify the huge alcohol content .  m : one of the few beers where carbonation is probably a bit too strong and covers up some of the wonderful and interesting flavors going on here .

sat on my table next to the bottle , the scene looked like the picture you would see on an advertising board . it looks so good , what a pity it does n't live up to the promise its image paints .  m - medium to light bodied . it 's just thinner than i expected .

a - pours a brilliant clear amber with an off-white moundy head that takes it 's time going down . provides beautiful sheets of lacing .  i had this on tap at victory brewing a - a very pale golden with good clarity and small snowy head with small bead , little lacing collects s - the smell is yeasty , with subtle sweet malt and mild floral hops m - the feel is thin , but apropos to style w/ light malt texture sweet herbal hop feel and kind of watery finish t - the flavor is crisp , clean and sweet w/ floral hops not really adding any contrast in the way of bitterness .
i poured this one in a pint glass and was impressed by the large head .  mouthfeel : a little thin ; carbonation too .

it was a clear dark honey color with lots of carb streams and great lacing . it had a massive white head that took forever to whittle down to a constant 1/4 '' foam .  if only the texture was less paper thin and more like cardboard .
appearance : a gorgeously intense brown/amber color with a tremendously dense tan head that lasts and lasts and lasts .  m : mouthfeel is thin , crisp , but a little watery .

smell : this beer has a very sweet and fruity aroma . you can also smell some of the malts .  sampled at the paper city brewery on free beer night . i know that this beer was free so i should n't complain about it but there was something wrong with this beer . my guess is this was a bad keg otherwise they brewed it with their dirty gym socks . reflection : i know that this is a harsh review but unless you were there that night and tried it you ca n't understand the horror of this beer .

extraordinarily enjoyable , i 've had double ipa 's that do n't smell this good . not nearly as complex as the smell would indicate .  a beer haiku for you : '' norwegian beer ? yes ! a great ipa option , seek out and find one ! '' my first norwegian [ that 's what she said ] . nice citrus overtones , not too 'hoppish ' , and very drinkable . a rare find , but well worth the money to have another option .
black with a tan nitro-head and a nitro-retention that leaves a literal wall of lace .  it had a medium to light body .

gorgeous though , one of the most visually appealing beers i 've seen .  modest bitterness , warmth . some great foaminess but a bit too much . malty sweetness . this is high calorie beer , the good stuff .

poured a hazy orange amber colour with a thick head that had very good retention . this was a beautiful beer with tons of visual character .  a little grittiness in the texture . m - a little weird and overcarbonated for a porter . it would be better off less carbonated and as creamy as it appears .

a : appears a brilliant clear copper with hues of red , creamy white 1 finger head , little lacing s : the aroma is quite muted , not picking up much more than some sweet malts and a touch of caramel .  for the most part this is quite smooth , although the carbonation is just a tad too harsh to fully appreciate some of the nuanced flavors .

smell- nice aroma that strikes an excellent balance between malt and aroma hops . a nice sweet citrus aroma along with a very nice malt sweetness comes through the nose as well . taste- taste is not as nice as the smell , but it is still quite nice . it has a nice maltiness with a powerful jolt of bittering and flavoring hops ... for a belgian pale ale .  m - my only complaint about this beer , wish it would thicken up a bit . approriate carbonation .

the nose is very complex and rich with lots of deep rich chocolatey malts and spices . some hops too . very sweet from the get go , and reminds me quite a bit of sn bigfoot .  t-coffee up front followed by a grape raisin in the middle and a cocoa powder/unsweetened chocolate finish . m-kind of watery and a bit syrupy , not unpleasant but not great d-alcohol very well hidden , but warming and at 4.50 $ a bomber could be quite dangerous .
amber pour with an effusive white head that left great lacing and never dipped below a substantial film .  light bodied with a crisp carbonation . this beer is pretty damn horrible .

laces magnificantly ; elegant and 2-toned . nose is powerful and intense , coffee , oak , and cocoa , just as it should be . pretty much spot-on . some oak on the finish , and a lot of robust roasty malt in the middle . quite bitter , but not from hops , mostly bitter cocoa ... cellaring would probably do wonders for this . edit : read the label mention of cayenne and it completely clicked . mouthfeel is very , very , very fine carbonation . overall bitter , but not dry nor particularly rich .  roasted aroma with hints of dark ( bittersweet ) chocolate and coffee . could be fuller bodied , a little less on the tounge then expected . different flavors hint you on the first sip , roasted malt , coffee , dark chocolate , hop citrusness . finishes dry with some hop bitterness and a nice aftertaste . another quality brew from the boys and rogue !

s : the aroma is moderate to strong and is a pleasant mlange of toffee , vanilla and oak . t : the initial taste is predominantly toffee and is followed by notes of oak and vanilla .  the mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side for a stout .

smells hoppy , fresh , and fruity , with a slight floral touch . somebody could write a review about the scent . absolutely wonderful fresh tasting with a hoppy bite .  m : a little bit smooth , medium body , medium carbonation , finishes a little bit sticky , like i said before , its more like juice than beer .

pours with a very large , stable , light tan head . good lacing .  i like the way this beer opens up although it ends up tasting a bit thin for the rest of the drink . m- smooth , sticky , but not thick at all .
s - wonderful coffee scents with vanilla and hints of dark chocolate . just a great smelling brew that i could keep my nose in for hours .  m- medium mouthfeel with a bit of fizz .

poured a medium tan head with fine-small bubbles . this was a smooth drinking stout without the super strong coffee taste ; however , i have had better tasting stouts since i have started my rating of beers .  m : lighter body than i would like in this style , kind of like zywiec porter light in this respect .
slightly hazy dark amber with a big very-light-brown head with great r & l .  m- a bit too carbonated for the style in my opinon .

from a nitro filled pint size can ... pours honey golden yellow with typical nitro-style can head . the head is very dense , creamy and leaves belgian lacing all the way down to the end .  a bit of a thin mouthfeel , for a porter .

the aroma is rife with vanilla bean and a fresh , sharp rye spiciness . caramel sugar daddies and liquefied raisinettes make for a sweet touch that plays well off the rye bill . overall , this is delicious stuff .  this brew can feel a little thin , although it 's so tasty that it hardly bothered me .

wow ! this beer is extremely clear and light looking . was n't expecting that ! gorgeous white head that laces awesome . beautiful beer for sure .  was n't crazy about the mouthfeel of this beer though , as i felt it lacked significant carbonation and was a bit thin and lifeless .
a - a huge frothy eternal mocha brown head .  body is a bit thin , probably due to the low alcohol .

a : deep clear red with a fantastic reddish-white head . great looking beer .  the belgian/wheat characteristics are present in the background but also help to make it such a smooth drinking brew m : average mouthfeel with a slight ammount of tongue tingle d : highly drinkable beer with very smooth characteristics but still beautiful tastes overall i absolutly love this beer and it is my mission to spread its wonder to all

a ) glowing amber , 1 '' off-white , pillowy head .  this one strikes me as kind of flat . needs a tad more carbonation and i think it would be leaps better than it is . nice creamy smooth mouthfeel though .

unstoppable hop aroma . grapefruit and citric character invades my nostrils and inflicts a pleasant sting . good double ipa .  this has got a lot of hop bitterness to it , this reminds me a little of hopslam . i did n't really notice the `` hop backbone '' like everyone else has mentioned . like hopslam , this is best drank slowly due to the high abv .

1 finger of soapy tan foam . excellent lacing .  the taste is thick and interesting . its just a tad lacking , leaving this beer to taste like eating hershey 's special dark chocolate powder . this beer coats the tongue well , but the taste is over-powering . i 'm really impressed with the idea here and think this is a good beer .
a - cloudy reddish brown body with a pale tan head that lasts forever at a height of two plus inches .  alas , the mouthfeel is more watery than what one would come to expect from such a taste .
it 's got a beautiful brown body with a fantastic , super long lasting tan head .  mouthfeel : feels like every other kind of amber ale i 've had , not bad .

one of the best looking beers i 've seen . pours a gorgeous dark copper brown ale , with a lovely foam head that sticks around .  bourbon . fizzy enough to make this way too drinkable , and that does a wonderful job of injecting dryness into the sweet , caramelly notes of woody bourbon that are certainly present here . it would be nicer if this beer was a bit thicker and smoother , but i think that would open it up to extreme booziness .

the smell is rich and malty , almost boozy even , with warm notes of caramel and roasted malts . smells like it 's on the verge of being a doppelbock really . the taste is less complex ... the roasted malts dominate big time . a little disappointing after the look and smell of it .  the mouthfeel is thin with a watery texture , and lively carbonation .

on tap at capone 's , served in a pint glass ( 2/7/08 ) a : an intimidatingly dark brown , nearly black , with a thin , foamy , dark beige head that diminishes rather quickly , but leaves a nice trail of sticky lacing throughout .  i just think it 's amazing what ab will do to make a quick buck . hopefully this will quickly go into the grave along with new coke and chrystal pepsi .

the nitro-can helps give the beer a large off-white creamy head that lasts a while . looks great .  carbonation is quite high , body is medium but filled with bubbles , mouthfeel is creamy but slick . very flavorful , but the carbonation ruins the mouthfeel for me .

clear , anthracite ( hehe ) brew with thin rims of chestnut when held to the light . forms a tan head which quickly thins , atop medium-large bubbles with moderate carbonation . solid sheets of lace are left in its wake .  feels a bit thin , where creamier and chewier would 've done the trick .

displays awesome retention , forms a mesa in the middle of the glass and shows off an impressive formation of 3d lace . an awesome appearance and nice aroma save this one from finding the 'c ' range .  mouthfeel is thick , but a little too fizzy .

smell is exactly what it should smell like -- a very malty oktoberfest . tastewise-there is sweetness and caramel and tones of apple too . in fact a little too sour on the finish .  m : very medium-light body and a slightly bitter but almost watery finish .
looks great . an amber-orange color . aggressive pour produced an inch head with a quarter inch lingering for a while , and lacing sticking to the glass all the way down .  it was very astringent .

extrememly frothy and creamy . leaves large chunks and patches behind . a nice lightly clouded golden colored pour .  the mouthfeel is a bit lighter than expected but doesnt detract , and drinkability is excellent for the abv .

appears a pale gold with a nice 2 finger white head that lasts for about a minute . some solid lines of lacing stick to the glass .  little helper is a good beer . defining it is a bit difficult , i would call it a hoppy but light ( er than normal ) red ale . very drinkable . nearly no head . good beer , but the malt flavor is not very interesting , and not pronounced considering the color . but i am a hop fan so that is just fine . all around great , hoppy , and drinkable red . wish rogue made less expensive beer !
populist has a beautiful appearance- a clear and rich copper color , that is regrettably a bit off set by an only average fragrance .  the body on this one is a little too thin .

the aroma here is all hops . very fragrant . i smell lots of floral and earthy hops .  ... big foamy head in to the glass that seems to break its neck to dissipate , but leaves a tiny ring ... is very refreshing and tangy but when it warms it can be a beast , serve cold ! ! .. better than most bmc products and probably somewhat better than miller chill ...
330ml bottle out of my harpoon tulip . the foamy head almost looks like an espresso , with hints of white and mocha .  mouthfeel is light bodied , light carbonation . smooth , but average .

pours black with the prettiest dark tan head that slowly subsides .  there 's a really nice level of hopping in this one , that becomes apparent in the middle and finish . could do with having a bit more body , but its okay as it is .

poured a hazy golden straw with a huge billowy head that turned awesomely rocky and covered about 90 % of the glass with lacing -- pretty cool .  medium carbonation and thin mouthfeel makes this brew very drinkable .

loved the ginger flavor , but not one of the best spiced ales i 've had . definitely worth a try , especially if you like ginger . the beer spells fantastic ! it 's fresh and easy to drink .  mouthfeel is moderate in weight , but this could really use some more carbonation .
this is a great looking beer .  the mouthfeel is a tad thin , lack of malt .

this is interesting , very hoppy and bitter for the body , but clean , tasty , and light at the same time . the aroma is very nice and very german , bready very herbal with a little lemon and a hint of pine .  m : dry , bitter , light/medium bodied , crisp , too much bite from the alcohol .

smell is dominated by lovely oats , backed up by sweet and rich malts . notes of coffee , too . but the really amazing thing about this beer is how much complexity is built into a fairly small package . i ca n't put my name on all the things in the smell , but i can feel them all there .  body is light and mouthfeel is fairly thin and bubbly , with a very clean finish .

poured a gorgeous ruby red , with a cream coloured , fluffy thick head . excellent retention , thick film of foam on the side of the glass , and thick layer of foam atop the beer . one of the best i 've ever seen from a bottle .  m- now this is a little off , the body is a little flabby , and even slightly watery .
can courtesy of sammy : poured a deep dark brown color ale with huge dirty white foamy head with great retention and lacing .  m - smooth and medium/light body . a slightly dry aftertaste .
guinness looks great when poured right . its all black and has a beautiful creamy head which really lasts .  it had a medium feel in my mouth with ok carbonation .

a - dark , dark brown allowing a mere hint of light through at the base of the pint . the head is substantial at two plus inches and maintains some very nice lacing .  feels lighter than expected . reasonable carbonation . perhaps lacking in body but only slightly .

appearance - perfect honey color . a short lived crisp head manages to maintain a thin cap and collar for the whole sampling .  smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing . the apple/apricot scent is strong but would be overpowering to the tongue , the muted apple notes balanced well . i would definitely order this again .

the head is a massive three inches in height , and recedes extremely slowly into thick , sticky lacing that lasts until the beer is gone .  m - thinner than i 'd like , with very fine carbonation . the finish is very dry and short , which contributes to the impression .
smells so good , that i can not wait for it to warm a bit and have to dive right in to taste it .  it was thin and gave a slight hoppiness that did n't last long in the mouth .
when held away from the light it looks completely entirely black . it also pours a nice 2 finger beige head .  the feel is a little to light , almost watery .

a - very full , dark brown . surprisingly translucent when held up to light .  served on tap in the black angus restaurant at the stoudt 's brewery . body is a dark copper color . thick head with excellent lace . the scent is a bit fruity and has elements of apples and hops . a nice balance of sweet malts and bitter hops make up the flavor . alcohol peeks through , which is surprising as this is a relitively low abv ale .
nice mix of buttery malts and slight hop flower to the smell ... gack !  medium to thin in the body . i thought the carbonation seemed a bit to high and lessened my enjoyment of this brew .
it pours a bright , clear lemon color with voluminous white head that billows out and leaves fine lace all over the glass .  m : smooth & a little flat ( thanks to the nitro i 'm sure ) .
s : coffee . lots of it . caramel and chocolate notes round out the aroma .  mouthfeel is rather light with less than medium carbonation .

pours out cloudy bronze and sits murky reddish-amber in the glass with a massive off-white head . fades slowly to a thick coating of foam with nice lacings all around .  it 's union made , can you tell ? there 's little doubt that every canadian past the age of 16 has tried this beer on more than one occasion . when a little older but not wiser , if nothing else comes to mind when the waitress asks , you instinctively order `` just a blue '' . ice cold it 's refreshing , and that is this brew 's raison d'etre . every time . i 've begun the habit of adding a pinch of salt in the glass , which seems to cut the skunk and make this somewhat palatable .

the beer pours a beautiful deep hazy ruby color with a thin white head .  the mouthfeel on a doppelbock is a tricky thing -- too thick and you wo n't be able to drink your half-liter bottle , let alone your full liter mass .

a : slightly hazy orange light copper color with pillowing white head . great head retention especially considering the abv .  the ringwood yeast just tore this up and gave it a slab of butter on top ... m : crisp , but just tastes pretty bad ... d : a pretty bad beer , the ringwood yeast dominates this brew so much that i had to drain pour the rest , too bad .

a beautiful deep red , yet clear .  smells of sweet malt , grains , hops , toasted bread and honey . very weak nose overall . tastes of roasted malt , grains , lemon , citrus hops , caramel , bread and yeast ... a toasty flavor that is not typical for an ipa and more like a lager than an ipa . it 's a bad ipa , not hoppy or like an ipa at all ... a drain pour , as it was tough to finish this beer . bordered on terrible .

a reasonably average american ipa . pours with a nice head , leaving a thick lacing down the entire glass .  appearance : pours a cloudy amber , moderately carbonated with offwhite foam , leaving moderate foamy lacing . smell : hops are floral and sweet , blending well with the strong raspberry undertones . taste : begins tart , with mellow floral hop taste , very light toasty malts which bring forth the hints of raspberry and honeycomb , finishes witha tangy bitterness that allows a slight yet lasting raspberry lingering . drinkability : very delicious small batch by mbc , its well brewed and the subtle notes of the raspberry are not forced , decent abv as well .

11.2oz bottle poured into my darkness glass ... not a gusher but a huge tope head rises about 8 fingers with great retention , decent lacing ... the beer is a medium gold that looks really good ... the front of the aroma is lots of chamomile , not off to a good start in my book .  mouthfeel : feels soft and smooth at first , but the finish is harsh and drying in a way that really detracts from the overall beer .

deep brown brew with a large , beautiful tan head that sticks everywhere , leaving sticky lace all down the glass . this is a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel- a tad thin for the style but still got a nice solid body .

dissipates after about 2 minutes.. smell - orange zest , maybe some banana , coriander , citrus.. has a nice sweet subtle smell , i like it .  m : pretty low carbonation , which is definitely not a problem for the style . the body 's a little thinner than i 'd prefer , though . a nice , smooth mouthfeel to the beer .
mahogany red , crystal clear , big foamy thick head . smell is heavy hops wafting out as soon as the cap is cracked .  the body has a little chalky hard-water feel to it -- like mineraly .
very attractive looking pale ale .  medium to light bodied .

tall creamy head , and yes black as black gets . i have to say this is a great looking stout .  taste was similar , with a slight sourness . maybe it was n't so fresh , but i drank it within a couple days of buying it . did n't taste the alcohol really , but it was still pretty poor i thought , and not what i was hoping or thinking it 'd be .
the smell is just delicious . it 's just so well balanced . not too much or too little of anything .  m : a bit too fizzy upon sipping , and i was looking for a bit more 'heft ' .

coloration is a nice ruddy brown with a healthy 1 '' khaki head which is simply beautiful in appearance . huge and uneven and thick .  mouthfeel : i 've never been a big fan of the body of almost all american porters as they just seem thin , a tad watery , and big on carbonation , and this one does n't break that trend .

s : very floral and some lemon citrus .  mouthfeel is moderately smooth and prickly but ends with a harsh , dry finish with a medium-light body . the finish is intensely dry with an initially harsh potent hop bitterness which smooths out somewhat and lingers on the palate for a long time . a very fine ipa in it 's own right , but not smooth enough or balanced enough to compete with stone ipa or centennial ipa .

what a beauty . the colour is a beautiful transparent copper with a thick creamy looking one inch off-white head .  mouth feel is a little thin at first with too much carbonation for an english style brown .

thanks to sheepnutz for this tasty brew ... it was sampled in a glass chalice appearance : pours a deep amber with an airy off-white head that lasts during the entire session , and laces incredibly down the glass .  light bodied , with very light carbonation tingle on the roof of the mouth , and a slippery feel .

a-light gold color with a thick foamy white head , and a continuous stream of bubbles spiraling up from the center of the bottom of the glass . laces , but real thin/weak .  taste was very pleasant and hard to describe as well . maybe fruity , maybe nutty , not hard to drink at all with a very slight bitter aftertaste . not a hint of the 7 % abv . given the chance i would share it again with someone because of how different it is . i would also like to get my hands on some of the other brews from hitachino nest .

pours verly clear , bright dark orange/amber with a full , firm and thick pure white head . a beautiful pour .  t- hop fruitiness up front , not particularly citrus from the big c hops but just fruity . aftertaste brings up the rear with a hop bitter whollop . m- average for this style , not great but definately not bad .

pours thick with a nice big head that lasts and lasts .  slightly bitter but balnced for a stout , i like the chocolate/coffee malty-ness mf 3.0 - bitterness makes me pucker a bit , slows me down , it 's a sipping stout , slightly thin for a stout .

a : a careful pour yields an impressive , jet black beer with a dense brown head which hangs around a while .  m- thin to medium body- highly attenuated- with a coarse carbonation which delivers a slightly bloating feeling . could stand to have some softer carbonation .

damn , this smells good . big roasty malts compete with all that chocolate on the palate for quite a while , with nondescriptly bitter hops and a little alcohol warmth bringing up the rear . while the chocolate on the nose smells sweet and milky , in the mouth it 's an equal mix of bitter and sweet , which is just awesome . very well balanced , and you could drink it until the 11 % abv says otherwise .  well attenuated , yet with a little viscocity to it . the carbonation is so soft it is almost impereceptible .
this beer pours black as night with a creamy amber foam . nice carbonation .  maybe this was chilled too much but it seems to have a little too much bite , which might also be the carbonation .

not the most amazing saison , but dang it smelled brilliant . appearance & gt ; good , slightly hazy golden in color .  it was a little over carbonated for my likes but still had a great feel to it in my mouth .

the beer pours a crystal clear red/amber color and produces a huge 4-finger light tan head , so be careful with the pour .  some candy-nougat sweet malt comes up for support but lacks some oomph , imo , which contributes to a slightly thin mouthfeel .
pours a brilliant hazy amber with lots of eggshell colored head .  it was also too carbonated . d- if it was n't for the mouthfeel i would rate this a 5 for sure .
it looks as appealing as any beer i 've seen .  m - it seems fairly still , but there is a sharpness that remains . the feel is unusual , but it works well enough .

smell is very nicely aged , deep aromas of molasses , dark fruit , and anise , with a boozy warmth if you look for it . amazingly complex , it 's right up there with the best . taste is very strong , sweet malt at first , then a hit of boozy flavors that i can only compare to jagermeister .  m : a bit light and quite fizzy for the style .
appearance : deep black in color with a thick 2 '' + head that looked like a dollop of chocolate mousse , very frothy and creamy looking .  a bit heavy on the carbonation .

huge cherry and oak on the nose , followed by an earthy mustiness and barnyard funk . a bit boozy . a damn fine flemish sour ; ranks with the best .  even after the 4 day limit they say for the growler , this is a great beer . very light , both physically and taste wise . it is not something that will bog you down , but it is not like standard light beer style crap . it is very delicate , but potent enough to be something.flat or fresh , this is a very satisfying beer . watch out , becuase the can be gone without a notice - and everyone should drink responsibly ; - ) this is something you can use convince you macroswill freinds and their girlfriends to switch to quality .

a - basically black with almost no light coming through when held up to lamp . very inviting beer .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with low to medium carbonation . smooth , easy to drink , but gets kind of muddy in the finish like some of the other nognes i 've had , which kind of makes my mouth feel dirty , but good winter beer nonetheless .

it pours a nice dark brown with reddish hues and a foamy off-white head that billows high , has great retention , and recedes with exceptional lace . this is perfection in appearance for this style .  m - carbonation is more muted than i thought .

guinness is , for my money , a gorgeous looking beer - this may be a function of the nitro-can , but nothing beats the pitch black pour and the perfect tan head that sticks around forever . it 's beautiful .  other than the slightly thin body , this is a superior porter .

pours a cloudy orange color , with small tints of yellow . the carbonation on this ipa is insane . thousands upon thousands of bubbles streaming upwards . the head was also unusual for an ipa , massive bubbly white head 2 inches thick .  m/d - a little thin , though probably appropriate for a session beer .

the aroma is distinctly malty with soft caramel & toffee notes alongside a light nuttiness with some distinct munich malt , backed by a very slight floral & perfumy hoppiness . quite seductive !  m_moutheel was actually ok except that it felt like sugar was coating teeth . other than that it was thick and full bodied .

s- fruity and malty , no hops whatsoever . slightly sour , and surprisingly plain due to almost perfect balance . m- highly carbonated , almost so much so that it masks the taste .  the sweet smell was picked up in the taste after swallowing the sip but only for a second and then the taste disappears . it is very light and easy to drink without being light in flavor .
bottle , a : pours a dark amber , with a thick soapy white head .  m-a little thinner in the body than i expected , but does n't ruin it by any means .

appears a pitch black hue absolutely no light shines through when held up to the light , although it does form a large tan moccha frothing head rising at least an inch above my gulden draak chalice .  i thought the mouthfeel may have been a tad dry and thin for all that malt , but that just adds to the drinkability , which is very good for the strength of this beer .
aroma is quite interesting . notes of bovril , cherries , soy sauce , and alcohol ... very nice .  m- mouthfeel is carbonated and a bit watery .

the beer pour the traditional atramentous guinness color , the head monsterous and a creamy chocolate brown , with the lace sticky and thick nose is coffee , bittersweet chocolate , nice malt aroma , what a treat for the old schnozzles .  mouthfeel - very beerlike .
smell : the first few glasses from the keg were incredible . lots of fresh piney citrus and grass . very good . i really liked it .  overall , a bit thin .

it 's really unattractive ... but it does look like what 's to come . aroma is a big punch of mango , although it shows off at least initially as mango , guava , pineapple , nectarines and stone fruit . i really enjoyed it , it 's unique , it actually does a good job of allowing the masala mama to show up in the back half , however ... it 's just good . not great . really enjoyable as a regular treat at my local brewpub , absolutely worth trying ( it 's very unique ) ... just a shade short of a truly great beer .  the mouthfeel is slightly thin and foams up in the mouth a little ; the beer needs some sort of aeration .

appearance- beautiful clear , dark , golden color . pretty much the color of apple juice . nice loose but creamy one head with lots of staying power .  the chocolate is the predominate flavor here , but it only enhances the brew . slightly sweet with just the right level of dark roasted malt and hops to balance out the bitterness . good drinkability . great looking head after an agressive pour .
big pour from this brew , my first from this trappist brewery . big foamy white head similar to duvel with a dark orange juice-like tint .  4.5 m a bit on the thin side .
the aroma is wonderful , truly like strawberries . ( sometimes the beer looks a bit murky , like a weizenbock .  it feels a bit thin and overly carbonated for a strong english ale .

on-tap at flying saucer served in a tulip glass an almost opaque not-quite black with a decent frothy light tan head that lasts and leaves great lacing on the glass .  the mouth feel is average , the aroma is less than appealing and the taste is well insipid . lesson learned , do n't send the wife to the package store with less than specific instructions on which beer to purchase .

appearance was great especially the persistant head still clinging to the glass as i finished .  a - deep clear brown with some dark amber highlights ; one finger tan head settled down to a nice frothy cap ; light lacing that seemed to slide down glass s - rich , dark coffee starts to come through then milk chocolate and caramel t - coffee is present throughout but it is understated and just part of the profile ; some malt and bread toward the end with a mildly sweet chocolate and caramel finish m - very lightly carbonated ; thin bodied ; no bite or drying finish d - while this one left a bit to be desired in the mouthfeel and taste department it is very drinkable overall - thin body and light carbonation make it go down easy with a nice light , coffee/candy bar flavor ; what 's not to like right ?
s - wet hay , damp musty basement , light pear , green apple , lemongrass and a bit of funk .  medium to full bodied imperial stout , a bit lighter than i expected .
black as the night , exquisite head .  watery feel for a stout but with just enough body to get you through .
o - great smelling beer that just does n't work out , caramel is overpowering and does n't really taste integrated  m - a bit flat . mouthfeel is so far the best part of this beer .
the aroma was caramel and chocolate with a nutty component . another fruit present in the complex aroma was pineapple .  mouthfeel is on the light side , but there is too much carbonation in this .

very unique aroma for an amber . extremely sessionable and unique ale but the nose leads you to believe it may be more complex than it ends up being .  the only thing i do not like about this beer is that it is a little lacking in body - seems a bit thin .

it pours a leopard skin pattern with a background of black with periodic cherry holes , which is an outstanding feat for a liquid . the head is huge with large frothy bubbles .  mouthfeel suffers from lack of carbonation , but flavors are all right up my alley .
pours like sludge . awesome lacing , thick circles .  mouthfeel is slightly thin .

very fine looking ipa , slightly hazy 'ice-tea ' orange with a very thick head that looked a lot liked the topping on a merangue pie . superior rentention and lacing .  only complaint is it is a little thin but nothing that deters me from wanting more . the rich citrusy hops , leave you wanting another drink to quench your thirst they are so drying , it 's basically a no win situation . mid palate is lacking roundness but otherwise delicious . because of the immense amount of hops it would be hard to drink many of these .

massive chunky pure white head with great head retention on beautiful golden colored , highly carbonated beer . looks incredible .  mouthfeel is light-medium to medium , drinkability is really nice , i bought a six last week and again this week , i rarely do that .
a - reddish , ruddy brown , perfectly clear , thick creamy light tan head that has staying power , lots of sudsy lace .  light carbonation . lacking in creaminess .
a golden mostly clear slightly hazed body with a masssive rocky head that actually climbs it 's way out of my delerium tremens snifter . excellent retention !  low carbonation .
rich , yeasty aroma with raisins , malt , spice , phenolics , and brown sugar . lots of character .  it was watery and smooth with just a little carbonation and a strong malt aftertaste .
it pours a beautiful hazy golden color .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but the carbonation is pleasant .

rich , gold/orange hue with a tremendous looking head ; thick , foamy & quite resilient .  the taste is light liquid sugar : a strong fruit and candy beginning that rolls across the tongue and leaves a sea-like ( read , salty ) aftertaste that crisply dries the back of the tongue and leaves the mouth wanting more . the overall feeling is medium bodied and the beer develops stronger hints of clove , dirt , and pepper throughout the pint . i ca n't wait to match it to a nice cheesy pasa or crostini !

yummy berries !  review to style as they say and for a mass produced macro swill this is my favorite for just chillin and enjoying some beer thats not gon na get me too wasted . the appearance on all of em ( macro swills ) is pretty nice gold straw with continued effervescence throughout and a good carbonation level . extremely drinkable and the flavor is a very mellow german or czech type hops . they arent making it strong but it still tastes like one of the beers i grew up with .

rich aromas of burnt sugar , curacao orange and raisins , but a thinner body , less malt and hop bitterness than it should have had .  m-medium body and a little grainy and rough on the palate with an agressive carbonation the gives it a crisp finish with just a hint of driness .

s. a very pleasant scent of raspberries , raspberries and more raspberries with a hint of hops and sweet malts . one of the best smelling beers around . t. the taste starts off with some earthy floral hops , followed by some sweet sugary syrup and than some tart raspberries and finishes off with a hint of more hops . it has a nice smell and mouthfeel , but the taste was a let down , so unless i get it as an air freshener i know i 'll never buy this beer again .  felt a little weak in the mouth , not much texture .
absolutely decadent . the taste is not nearly as decadent but still very good . the oak really stands out as a great flavor here .  mouthfeel : highly carbonated for the style .

( nov. 2002 bottling ) nicely black with a large , dense and creamy chocolate milkshake head .  there 's a slight bready quality to the mid mouth impact , but the flavor is balanced and lessens evenly as its swallowed . i do n't look for a lot of bite or chewy mouthfeel in vienna lagers , so i 'm pretty happy with firebrick .
a great looking brew .  mouthfeel : thin to reference the entire continuum of beers , but average for a pilsner .

a : huge head on this one , takes up half the glass after a normal pour . beer is a darkish golden color with some amber sneaking through . really good s : different , not what i was expecting .  m : very normal carbonation .

app : pours light amber ( hazy orange ) with a thick white head , heavy white lacing too and good head retention .  mouthfeel : heavy in the front with a dry almost astringent pucker at the end . tastes like it 's been decoction mashed . drinkability : a hybrid of belgian and czech styles , this one does n't really stand out in my opinion , however it is an easy drinker and a much better alternative to bmc .

sampled on 4-11-08 batch 8369 bottled on 4-4-08 pours a super thick clear amber-gold , with lots of little bubbles that slowly rise to the surface .  this harp was brewed in canada by moosehead . this is a very satisfying beer ; especially when all the over-hopped , over-malted , extreme productions . become too much ... which is the true beauty of this harp . it is straight forwardly flavorful without making great demands on the palate . lively with a clean finish . this is the first harp i have sampled in a few years , and is easily the most tasty i have ever encountered .
s- very wonderful aroma here . very nice hop smells come from this .  carbonation is strong ; lots of small short bubbles . nope : another dull beer with an organic excuse .

pretty good lacing & head retention with crazy medula obblingonta ( sp ) & brain lace impressions on the bottom of the glass .  a smoked lager from fort collins brewery . 1.0 liter bottle for $ 8.29 . i was somewhat skeptical about this beer especially because i thought there two other beers edgar and doktor were an abomination , but i opted for it and was it ever worth it ! a slight smokinness stimulates the nose as well as some alcohol , caramel and citrus hops . the palate was dominated with notes of butterschotch , smoked malts , cedar , citrus notes , light fruits and the flavor was very lingering on the palate . i did polish off a 1.0 so obviously this brew was pretty damn drinkable !

big malty aroma , brown sugar , alcahol fumes , cloves , resiny hop aroma with a mostly grassy kick . the aroma is misleading and the taste does not follow the knose 's path .  this is a pretty good belgian , but the spicy character takes away from the drinkability and the mouthfeel .

wow , this one smelled great . tastes of caramel , vanilla , bourbon , wood , nuts , raisins , and a light earthiness .  an astoundingly good dark beer for the price : 10 bucks for a 12-pack at wegmans in state college , pa . it brings some of the unique flavors found in yuengling porter to a slightly lighter beer , but make no mistake ; the stuff is not weak . it might not be the most delicious beer on the planet , but the combination of good flavor and low price are unbeatable for me as a beer-enthusiast college student ( not a drunkard ! ) everyone else has described the taste well enough . my review is mainly economic .
app- dark yellow with a lot of orange highlights . huge two and a half finger head .  the mouthfeel is medium and slightly watery with some sharp carbonation .
this beer pours jet black with a thick tan head that leaves a nice lace .  m_light bodied with a tight aggressive carbonation . d_i am actually pretty impressed by this .

lovely aromatics ... .rose petals , grapes , orange peel ... berries . does n't bother the tongue too much , which is good for some , but not for me . very approachable ale , nice and even-handed .  no real cascade , but a full , rich tan head with plenty of texture over a nearly black and opaque body . heavy lacing clings to the glass . delicious aroma of black bread . espresso and chocolate flavors . labels soak off easily and make an excellent decoration for plain garage walls .
pours nearly opaqe brown with a huge cascading tan head .  that being said , it feels a bit too thin . qutie unfortunate .

a : pitch black beer with a charcoal greyish-brown foamy 3-finger head leaving plenty of lacing all the way down .  it drinks a little like carbonated white wine . the finish is somewhat dry . an interesting and refreshing brew .
very good looking .  the mouth is actually a little heavy and chalky for what should be , and mostly is , refreshing .
it 's a beautiful beer to look at . really great looking .  the mouthfeel is low carbonated almost syrupy , not what i expected .

great smell , but sorely lacks in taste and feel for a `` spiced '' beer  yes officer i have been drinking tonight as a matter a fact i have a fuck of a lot to drink tonight , i think 12 beers but i ca n't remember . yes i will take a breathalyzer and a blood test . yes my breath does smell like hops . no your machines are n't broken , i forgot to mention the beers i was drinking are 0.5 % alcohol by volume .
it smells great . there is a slight bit of sweetness in the background .  the mouthfeel is kind of bland .
dark black in color with garnet highlights . huge , cascading head of super-thick foam that does n't back down for several long minutes .  m- a very fine carbonation .

awesome 1 inch head and great retention and some circular lacing smell : vanilla and chocolate taste : upfront carries some roasted smokiness that i was not at all expecting and then the vanilla takes over and covers your whole palate .  the palate is completely overwhelmed by a hugely complex beastly drink .

pours a deep brown with reddish hues . a nice thick and tan head follows ( it does dissipate rather quickly ) . beautiful lacing lines the glass as the head falls - very nice .  very good beer but does lack with a thin somwhat over carbonated mouthfeel for a stout .

tastes like , smells like , and feels like a lager to me ... ca n't beat the originality in the swing top ! pours amber ( duh ) , and has one of the best head retentions i 've ever seen from something not from belgium .  mouthfeel is a little thin with very little carbonation .

big , dense , rocky head that takes forever and ever to settle down and leaves some big , chunky lacing .  the lack of flavor is the most important part , it 's more like a watery , sour drink with a bit of beer added . i guess that is malt , but it 's ... light . on the bright side , it 's refreshing at first and there is no really offensive `` off '' flavor 's , i 'm not picking up any metal and it 's rather clean .

first off , this brew is a picture perfect pour for a german pilsner . ultra clear and golden body , with a brilliant white head . retention lasts for a few minutes and diminishes into clumpy lacing .  m : well at least it is n't as over carbonated as the macros .

i got a growler of this fresh from the brewery and i 'll be a sinner if i say that this was not one of the finest beers i have ever had . thick pillow head that retained wonderfully .  carbonation is medium to medium-heavy , and mouthfeel is slightly viscous , landing just north of water .
a : bright , clear golden color topped by a perfectly white head of big bubbles . a lot of visible carbonation supporting the head .  m : a bit lighter in body that i would prefer .

forms a 1 '' tan head , slowly receeds to leave a foamy cap of retention and plenty of sticky thick lace drapes . color is a darker brown with alot of red hues glowing when held to light .  the body is better than medium and the mouthfeel could use a little bit more of a prick of carbonation to it .

in the nose , cocoa powder , yeast , coffee grounds , olives , piney hops and wood smoke . beautiful nose . the taste is initially smooth , with notes of dark chocolate , black olives and an oakey sourness .  m - light body . pleasant carb .
pours a pitch black color with a thin brown head into my glass .  overall : very light bodied for the style , but very drinkable .

s-i love the smell of this beer . there 's a twinge of wit beer scent . the hops is n't as present as the nose leads you to believe , although there 's a bitterness at the back of it .  lager quality with a lighter cleaner body and feel . my one `` complaint '' is the bite of the carbonation that holds a particularly sharp feel .

nice white pink head . a thing of beauty . sm : the slightest twinge of the df funk , but very subdued .  even when it 's a 12 pack for $ 6 this stuff is hard to swallow . i 've done it before , sure , but i probably wo n't do it again . always tastes and smells a little ... off ; perhaps skunked but i think it tastes and smells that way when fresh . maybe they 're using moldy ingredients . not even average . blah .
a : pours pitch black , good sized tan head , lots of lacing down the glass s : smell is very stong chocolate and coffee .  m - light mouthfeel overall .
the lacing is impressive as it coats the entire glass . the of the ale is a dark copper , initially cloudy , but then relatively clear .  m : a little thin probably due to low carbonation .

appearance : great head on this one . very fluffy that , after a few sips , recedes to a lower head . frothy would be the word for this head .  body is a little thin for an oatmeal stout , but it still has the smoothness . carbonation feels a little too heavy for this style i think .

33cl into a tulip . pours a hazy butterscotch orange . magnificent pure white towering head remains till nearly tomorrow .  very clear and bubbly , one finger head that looked like the fizz produced when pouring a pepsi . smells hoppy , lively citrusy orange peel and carbonation galore . the hops mildly dominate the brew , just enough to mask any malty flavor . well worth it . would recommend this brew .

it poured a beautiful amber color . a nice white head laced the glass the entire time .  mouthfeel was medium with a curious admixture of cereal adjuncts and a metallic tang on the tongue . this was brutal !
beer poured black as night with a very nice tan head that sustained wll .  m : medium body with moderate to low carb . dry finish .

smell is both light and dark fruits ( once again , odd ) , apples , cherries , plums and currants with a young , almost vegetative oak and light vanilla . it sounds awesome when i write it but somehow it 's just ok .  mouthfeel was medium with a heat that would be completely incorrect for the style .
right off the bat of pumpkin pie -- later cinnamon and caramel malts . essentially , just as i was expecting -- nothing spectacular .  again , this beer was a bit thin for my taste .
s : wonderful , joyous sultry oak scents .  m : medium mouthfeel , slightly thinner than what i was expecting , especially once the carbonation is gone .
no hop aroma . very nice taste : alcohol dominates what otherwise would be a nice beer .  the mouthfeel is crisp and refreshing , although almost too light and dry .

pours tar black with a thick dark tan head with abundant lacing . one of the most impressive beers i have ever layed eyes on .  a light body , but refreshing and enjoyable , i was intriqued by this one .
orange yellow in color , the beer pours extremely clear . a very fine looking dipa .  watery body runs to the back of the tongue .

s - amazing cherry aroma . the aroma and mouth feel are excellent , but the taste is a bit too tart for me . amazing stuff here !  taste was grain almost wheat like , slightly floral hops , light in taste and mouthfeel , lightly toasted barley taste is very clean , hops where rather low . i really like this beer

best before 12/06 stylised hb text on the bottle cap looks damn near identical to a hofbru label . huh . pours an attractive clear light reddish amber color .  mf- medium/light bodied with kind of a watery feel compared to other porters .

a beautiful nose filled with honey ( not sweet ) , citrus , a floral piney note , a tropical cornicopia of pineapple and mango fills out the scents . the taste is a bit dull , maybe too cold , with bready malts , light citrus and a nice lightly bitter backbone .  m : carbonation is practically nil , somewhat watery , and viscous , ethanol character .

drank on-tap at flatbread company , somerville , ma served in a pint glass near pitch black in appearance with a two-finger , super tight and creamy , cocoa-colored head . ( the beer looked like it was poured from a nitro tap . very impressive .  ps : high carbonation , which can be a bit prickely at low temperatures .
a-pitch black with a thick tan head s-smells like a black ipa .  the mouthfeel is also unexpectedly thin - for a beer this dark i was anticipating something more viscous .

pungent , citrusy , centennial hop nose . very assertive hop bitterness hits the palette first , just a hint of malt sweetness follows .  it does leave with bit of a skunky after-taste but its a small aspect of this otherwise delicious beer , m-medium carbonation with a slight watery finish d-the taste seems to lose its quality but it does n't seem to take too much of a dive . its a very thick beer so it does seem to go down slowly .

the smell is great , smoky as expected immediately calling to mind backyard bbq 's and fireplaces . agree with other reviews that mouthefeel is somewhat thin and would not be able to go for more than 1 of these , but an excellent beer nonetheless .  mouthfeel is average , thin and just a bit too carbonated for my taste .

excellent . the beer is the color of honey , and since this is a honey ale , it succeeds in this area as well . the taste and mouthfeel are light , pleasant , and ultimately forgettable .  feels thin for such a high abv barrel aged beer but it is easy to drink and the alcohol heat is mild considering .

very pleasant . taste : mildly fruity , very unibroue . the smell really overpowered the taste in my beer .  smells chocolately and savory taste is even and not too sweet average mouthfeel could be a bit heavier .
awesome , very thick looking pour into my pint glass that forms a two finger tan head .  body is a bit thin , with the malt slipping quickly away under the bittering hops that dominate the finish .
