pours a deep golden copper color with a bubbly white head that sticks around forever .  mouthfeel medium mouthfeel with carbonation that is just over the top in my judgment .

sugary syrup infused dry fruits , essential hop oils and something dirty and plant-like .  bready malts and a faint aftertaste of alcohol is also present beer is way over carbonated . only thing that got to me was the over carbonated .

it pours a gorgeous deep mahogany hue with a small but very long lasting tan-colored head . excellent , excellent lacings remain after the head has gone .  belgium should make this brewery pack up and move to another country ... like france . smelled like your typical macro lager and a skunk . tasted like weak malt with a strange bitterness in the finish ; not a good hop bitterness , just a weird oily bitter flavor . avoid this swill . a black mark on the reputation of a country that brews some of the finest beer in the world .

it is really a nice looking beverage .  excellent flavor , with a great two-row maltiness up front and a great pine and semi-citrus hop flavor at the end that sticks . there is a bit of hop roughness to the beer that hurts the finish , but it 's still not bad going down .

nice dark amber/brown color .  this beer contains the same yeasty , yummy taste as other delirium beers . as a series , their three beers do n't go out of their way to be different from the others . in my opinion , tastes just like tremens with more color ( it looks like carbonated jack daniels ) and more seasonal flavor ( smells of strong caramel and tastes much more tart and spicy than other deliriums ) . had this a month or so ago in a 750ml bottle from a local pub , and it was labelled `` noel '' . to me , it tasted slightly different , or maybe because that night it was my first beer .
oct 19 , 2003 dark , cherry red body with a pink head .  its has a light mouth feel for a stout .
v.06 grade `` b '' molasses , with a root beer float head . nice lacing .  the carbonation is very low .

pours with an impressive 2-fingered very light tan head , which slowly fades . color is a super dark red , could pass for black in less-than-ideal lighting .  medium bodied slick mouthfeel , slightly cloying .
beautiful color s-more malts than hops .  m : where it falls the shortest with a light-for-style body and overcarbonated .

pours a full three finger head . great retention and lacing .  split with the wife at the eccentric cafe in kalamazoo , michigan . looks like a wheat beer with absolutely no odor coming off the brew . very , very wheaty , to the point of being a bit of a turn off . more cherry & less wheat would have been a better combo , methinks . this got actively unpleasant as it warmed - the aftertaste was a killer .

lacing left on the glass aromas of nuts , brown sugar , caramel , and fruity . tastes of caramel , bread , and nuts . tastes a little on the thin side and did not live up to the aroma . alcohol well hidden .  its been awhile since i have had a uk beer so i decided to go with this yorkshire porter today , poured a clear deep amber/brown with a thinner but well formed head that left two nice rings of lace as it settled into a soapy-like mass atop.love the aromas alot of things going on very roasty with hints of wood and smoke a real nutt elemant shows thru as thit lighter bitter chocolate as well.the mouthfeel was a little sharp and maybe not as full as i would like but the flavors are very nice highly roasted and quite dry and woody thee is a touch of molasses-like sweetness underneath a dark roast coffee aftertaste lingers.outside of the mouthfeel there is nothing to say bad about this porter , roasty and dry , very tasty .
huge tan head with really tight bubbles . head lingers for the entire glass leaving lacing behind . brilliantly clear .  m- good carbonation .
pours from the bottle a nice dark copper brown with a thick tan head .  the mouthfeel has decent body , ok carbonation .

appearance : this is a gorgeous looking brew , amazing head retention it just about sticks everywhere .  taste- almost the same as the smell with a malt/roasted taste up front with a strong coffee finish . overall i like this brew . one of the most significant coffee smelling and tasting brews i 've had . good stuff
dark brown with red hues , tan colored head with very good retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , carbonation high .

500 ml bottle poured into a wiezen glass , ur pils is cloudy gold with active streamers forming a large fluffy , white head that slowly settles to tight , creamy skim and leaves nice lace . i like cloudy pale beers , so that 's not a detraction for me .  average body for a stout not too viscous but the carbonation is a little low , makes you work to get the flavors out from the alcohol background .

poured a hazy orange gold with a great couple fingers of head .  mouthfeel : others have pointed out that nuova mattina falls short delivering a creamy mouthfeel . it is highly carbonated and too harsh .
for all intents and purposes it pours like duvel . a fantastically clear golden body , with a billowing soft white head .  mouthfeel is pretty fairly light with decent carbination .

truly majestic appearance - a very ruddy dark brown , almost bordering on black , with a smooth , creamy nitro head that left sheets of lace .  as it warms to maybe 50-55f , really no bitterness/hoppiness can be detected at the finish and i 'm immediately ready for another sip . i think the `` fleeting '' nature of this beer ( disappearing lace , no lingering bitterness ) contributes to the lack of feel -- but i suspect that is n't so much a goal for brewers of this style , so i do n't want to ding it in this category . this ale is at least on the level of samuel smith 's oatmeal stout and could have another or two .

received in trade from muenchenerkindl appearance is clear brown-to-black hue , huge thick brown head of creamy condensed foam dissipates to a moderate thickness , moderate lacing on the glass smell is toasted malts and alcohol mostly , tones of bitter chocolate and coffee , some toffee and earthy green tones taste is bizarre , so much so that i wonder if this may be a bad batch , mostly burnt bitter coffee malts and a strange load of dark fruits and grassy earthy hops , some sour buttermilk sensation creeps through , the finish is bitterly acidic with slight alcohol warming mouthfeel is medium-to-full bodied , creamy smooth texture borders on watery , low carbonation drinkability is poor , i have heard a lot of good things about this beer and would love to give it another shot , perhaps on draft , just in case this was a bad bottle .  as far as mouthfeel , it was rather carbonated and had a bit of a bite going down , especially when it was at its coldest .
a : dark brown , nearly opaque , lovely cappuccino-colored head that falls into a persistent cap with nice lacing .  mouthfeel is tough .

pours caramel with 3+ fingers of fluffed up khaki colored head . insane lacing & head retention s : plummy , some herbal hops , a touch of booze t : rich dark fruit herbal & woody hoppyness , plus much dryness & some boozey pine needles up front .  i absolutely love this beer . i hate the commercial light beers like bud light , miller and coors but i want to drink a flavorful light beer to save a few calories . sal fits the bill perfectly .
first of all , it was an amazing red with a pink head .  m - overcarbonated , light bodied for the style , but really good .

bottle courtesy of jjpm74 : poured a clear dark black color ale with a big foamy head with perfect retention and perfect lacing .  beer is thinner than i would have expected , or liked , but the flavor is there and the taste is long lasting . if it had a richer mouthfeel this beer would be top notch .

a-pours a beautiful ruby red with a thick , billowy cream colored head . there is some cascading and lacing left on the glass . i ca n't say enough how beautiful this beer looks , its amazing . s-grapefruit stands out the most from the hops .  creamy head and taste . drier than i expected yet not too hoppy ; which makes me happy ! the color is the dark murky chocolate you expect from a good stout , but lacks the `` fall effect '' one sees in guinness for example . overall a nice drinkable and easy on the palate brew !

the beer was black with a slight hunt of red at the very bottom . a 1cm sand colored head formed and slowly became a continual 0.5cm head .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin side , but drinkability is excellent .
pours opaque black with a big fluffy brown head that retains well and laces the glass .  m- good carbonation . a little watery for an imperial stout .
darker than i 'm used to with a iipa but this looks nice . brilliantly clear .  m : less smooth than the iv ; it has a rubbery booze component that i do n't care for . otherwise fine .

the orange copper color is brillinat in my glass , and the head formation and retention is great . great lacing too .  feels too carbonated and light in the mouth . just an average mouthfeel though , not too bad .
the dark brown liquid shines with strobe like flashes of ruby red .  the body seems a little thin in my opinion , but otherwise , this is a substantial beverage all around .

s : fresh herbs . amazing . nothing like it .  taste- light medium to medium bodied . the only drawback would be that the body was not very thick as i was expecting . nothing bad , but nothing really amazing either .

it pours deep brown , almost black , with light head .  well done porter ... .looks the part with a creamy tan head atop a black body ... a very nice aroma greets my nose..roasted and sweetish ... milk chocolate as well as some subtle coffee notes milk chocolate and roasted malts are the big players on the taste but the java notes become a little more pronounced ... body is creamy and smooth and slightly thin ... i do n't exect regular ol porters to be high gravity monsters so this is fine with me ... it really drinks easily and quickly ... .

a : pours jet black . minimal frothy chocolate brown head that disappears quickly .  m - lot 's of carbonation is there making this really move . unfortunately it 's to the point of almost being painful . medium body . it 's sort of an odd one because of the carbonation .

this is an interesting concept , iam surprised there hasnt been more forays into melding the two styles.i poured into a weizen glass rather than my nonic for appearance and it poured nicely , hazed burnt orange tinged golden with a fluffy one and a half finger white head that left a broken ring of lace as it settled slowly.love the in your face citric hop aromas , really fresh , slight toasted wheat malt and clove as well.the mouthfeel was much thinner than expected and seemed to take a little of the flavor away , somewhat watery with decent shot of resiny/citric hop on the palate , toasted wheat malt again comes thru a little as well.if the mouthfeel was amped up a little this beer would be great but alas it isnt and the beer is just `` pretty good '' .  f - medium body but carbonation is very weak .

pour lets out a large , just off-white head head over a clear , tan body . excellent retention and lace . tons of carbonation makes this look like one refreshing , attractive lager .  this beer is supposed to be a german style pilsner . the first pilsner that the brewers den has ever made . the first thing one notices is the hops . a little bit too much hoppy aroma , flavor and bitterness for a true german pilsner but a great version of a american style craft brewed german pilsner . dry hopped with halletauer hops . another great uwe-beer .
beer is yellow and clear with a nice white head that has some retention . carbonation is moderate and steady , lots of lacing .  thin body , decent carbonation .

it smelled so good . the taste was definitely like coffee ... but with a sweetness to it .  more of the same in the finish , kept triggering my gag reflex medium bodied , slick with moderate carbonation , skewed way to sweet , needs some alcohol burn to mitigate this horrible drinkability .

bottle , a : pours a cloudy sun yellow , with a perfect cap of white foam , great retention , with extensive lacing .  the body does seema tad watery , i would expect more fo a `` fullness '' , but overall i feel the beer is a great scottish ale , overpoweringly malty , no hops that i could detect and pretty much no smoky presence which i can appreciate , since i 've had one too many smoky sottish style ales .

2 december 2005 , best before apr 06 mostly clear dark orange colour with a large dense whipped cream white head . looks impressive in the glass , the head rises well above the rim and holds its form remarkably well .  m - sharp carbination starts off this beer , and turns almost tart . it seems young .

gorgoues blurry bronze orange hue crowned with an immensely tall and loftly thickened spongey beige foam that sits like a hat that wo n't blow off in a strong wind .  m/d : a light body that is fairly creamy .

the tankhouse ale comes in a tall , skinny non-standard dark brown bottle with printed text and graphics instead of a paper label -- looks great on a shelf with others from the same brewery . the back of the bottle describes the beer 's colour as copper-red , but it looks more amber to me . poured into a pint glass with a nice foamy two-inch head .  mouthfeel is thin with just moderate carbonation .
a truly great looking beer .  mouthfeel is pretty thin as well .

pours a deep , dark brown that allows a fair amount of light through the periphery . a one-half inch light tan head reduces quickly , leaving generous amounts of thick lacing on the sides of my glass . by the end of this beer , large amounts of spotty lacing remain all over the inside of my globe . i am impressed with the appearance !  m- a little on the thin side and a little under carbonated . overall i thought this was a good octoberfest beer , spot on for its style , besides its mouthfeel .

cork marking 0205 ... poured a ruby , garnet color with a medium sized pink head and light lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel is pretty average , but not annoying . carbonation 's good , body on the thin side .
12oz bottle ... a : deep dark color with a milk chocolate mocha colored that never completely fades .  m : pretty darn thick and syrupy .
deep amber in color .  m - nice light carbonation and creaminess , but the body is a little light and watered down .

pours a deep amber color with a big , creamy beige head .  it 's rare that i ca n't even stomach a beer long enough to get a few sips down . this beer gave me one of those rare moments . the smell was a sour , and the taste was dirty and skunky . i did n't want to waste the pack , so i made a couple of michelada cocktails . they were actully quite tasty.. nothing like worcestershire and tabasco to make something taste better !

two finger tan head shows great retention . lots of web style lacing on the sides of the glass .  id love for this to have a heavier mouthfeel , but this is a darn good session beer for a cold night .

smell- this one has a really nice scent . some very sweet chocolaty caramel toasted or roasted malt .  s- old coffee grounds , very roasty t- coffee , roasted malt and vanilla , with a slight oak detection m- thick but not bcs thick , however your mouth will be coated in flavors .

clear garnet brown with a big , bountiful , buttercreme head that shows excellent durability and lacing . it really is a beautiful looking beer .  m : sharp at first , fizzy , but lights up as you hold it . still , a bit strong and that cuts down on how much you can have . d : i had 10oz with no problems , but a second might have gotten bothersome due to the fizz .

it is eerie how perfect this beer looks.. from that reverse cascade pour comes a perfectly consistent black liquid under a similar khaki head . stain is crazy thick and solid like the lace .  mouthfeel is medium-light .

the smell is pretty awesome . just a thick rich , perfect scent for the baltic porter . it is a nice beer , the flavor could be better , but overall it is enjoyable  unfortunately , the flavor and mouthfeel do n't fully deliver on what the aroma suggested . this is still a tasty beer but it 's a bit thinner than i hoped for and has a much stronger roast presence than i prefer .

poured a deep amberish copper with big carbonation and a dirty white head .  thanks kplynch for the bottle . color is orange amber with a variety of floral hops hitting the aroma . it 's on the lighter side , but tasty . just not really living up to the imperial in ipa . i 'd call it a well balanced , smooth ipa with notes of citrus and floral hops ...

produces a big tan head and the color is dark as night in hell ( or northern british columbia , perhaps ) . leaves wide splashes and thick strips of lace on the sides of the glass . looks great .  light-medium carbonation and medium bodied . piney hops and paint thinner nose . flavor starts with sweet malt but quickly goes to hop and finishes with a paint thinner aftertaste . overpriced at $ 1.50 for a 12oz bottle from manchester wine and liquors manchester , ct .

appears , smells and tastes basically the same as the first one i had a couple months back , which is to say that this is a decent beer but a very mediocre ipa . appearance & smell : it looks good in the glass as the creamy beige head rests softly atop the hazy copper colored body .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , with a little creaminess from the malt being nice , but not quite enough .
a - pour is a really nice thick oily black with a super creamy mocha head that is half a finger and never really fades . just rests atop it nicely . s - woah .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin .

the smell was also sweet and very well balanced . i prefer a little bit more bitterness in my beers but this is a respectable amber lager .  mouthfeel is fuzzy and fairly light and chablis-like with a slightly harsh lemony tartness on the tongue .

pours out to a clear dark caramel , with the highly flocculent yeast sticking firmly in the bottom of the bottle , forming a peaking meringue-like whipped head with superior retention and lacing .  m - fairly light and not all that carbonated ; really could use a bit of extra body .
poured out a beautifully clear orange tinted yellow with a nice frothy head and beads of carbonation continually rose to the surface .  the only place i would knock it down is in the mouthfeel .

this brew from yards starts out wonderfully by building expectations with a stellar appearance , but tanks back into the land of average thereafter . pours a great looking cloudy amber colour with a big creamy off-white head . nice stickiness and great overall appearance .  mildly thin body , but not alarmingly so .

stupendous nose . i found the taste to be not quite as amazing as the smell , but this is a really great and enjoyable quad . perhaps a little too much for my taste , but still really good .  mouthfeel : light for darker beer . nothing special . but as in mouthfeel , nothing here will blow your brains out .
pours dark , very dark , brown color with light , light , brown frothy 2 finger head .  m : medium bodied , but the carbonation is lacking .

the nose kills me it 's so good , making me very excited for the first sip . i could just stick my proboscis all the way in to the bottom of the glass and drink this through my nose it feels like . definitely a winner . great yeast character in both smell and taste .  m : light to mid bodied , little watery at first bit smooths out as it warms up .

appearance : the body was black as night with an abundance of small dark tan bubbles that fills the top half of the glass before slowly settling at the top of the glass . the head that forms is thick and creamy with a light tan color .  mouthfeel this beer is a bit thin for what i expect from an imperial stout .

dark fruit , specifically currant , dominates the smell . there is also a good dose of dark roasty malts and definitely creamy chocolate . its even nicer that it is both cheap and available .  it 's very refreshing to the mouth ( do i say that about all the beers i review ? ) , with small , present carbonation and what i 'm finding to be a lighter body than i expected from a wee heavy . by virtue of this lighter than expected body , however , this is an extremely drinkable beer .
poured into a pint glass.. copper orange color , fizzy head at the perfect proportion .  m - slick and slightly thin .

tried this on a whim ... made with raisins and beet sugars , i was hoping for an interesting experiment , but ended up finding one of my favorite recent discoveries , and the best so far by the amazing brewers at dogfish head . the color alone is an experience . i would paint my apartment with that rich , warm , brown-red color .  mouthfeel-par the course for the style , maybe a a little watery thin but nothing that really impacts the drinking , besides , it 's a wit , it 's not supposed to feel heavy .

the pour on this is awesome like every nitro can , nice tiger stripes as it slowly settles out , then you get theat signature nitro one finger white head .  the body was medium full and just a bit less than expected from an imperial stout . missing body for an imperial stout , it is nonetheless a very nice an drinkable beer .

smells of toast and caramel , with loads of hop aroma . amazing hop character is what i taste upfront , backed by biscuit and warming sensations from the alcohol .  mouthfeel is flattish and thin , does n't really compliment the chocolateyness .

very nice aroma of sweet malt , honey , light hops , and toffee . very good for the style .  some bitter to this as well there is still some hops to it a little syrupy but there is some carbonation to it so it is bearable .
crystal brown `` loverly '' color . quite effervescent - copious amounts of sea-foam looking suds .  i would have expected a little more body in this beer . a little skinny for my tastes .

pours a dark , black coffee color with three fingers width of mocha colored head . reduced to a fingers width over consumption . great head retention and the lacing was so thick it just caked the sides of the glass .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts almost sweet but hops dominate , boring , finish is dry and slightly bitter . brewed aug 12 , 2005 . $ 1.79 for a 330ml bottle from lina 's beverages painesville , oh .
what a great looking beer , stylistically . an almost opaque reddish brown with a nice big frothy tan head .  mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side , carbonation level is appropriate for the style .

a : moderate pour down the center of the glass leads to 5 finger head ! wow this head is not going anywhere , sticks around forever . lots of carbonation in this one . looks like it could be unfiltered .  pours black but with some deep red highlights with a slight off-white head that is gone in a flash leaving nothing behind , milk chocolate is very prevelant in the aroma with a little smokiness and a roasted coffee hint.nice deeply roasted flavor with big doses of cocoa and smoke , alot of flavor melding going on but seemed a little light in the mouthfeel department otheriwise a top notch brew.a easy drinker with alot of flavor needs a little tweaking to be great in my opinion .

appearance- poured a luscious fist of a head into my mug . the head retention was very good . the beer poured a cloudy , deep garnet brown with a lot of lacing .  mouthfeel - medium..maybe a little on the more watery side , but still creamy-ish .

quite a beauty in the glass . clear , gold and with a thick , rocky head that leaves a ton of lacing in its wake .  hahahahahaha bourbon my as- . this beer tastes like the worst cake frosting i 've ever had . body 's not bad either if you can get by the taste .

) so i 'll try to play be the rules this time : appearance : solid black and thick as hell ( great looking stout ) smell : mixture of spoiled prune juice and nail polish remover taste : something is wrong with this .  mouthfeel is pretty sharp and fizzy from the bubbles . average kind of body , but mostly just bubbly .
a fantastic looking beer . really grand looking stuff .  m - syrapy with a decent carbonation .

s : lots of malt , caramel sweetness , some boozey spice in there , some darker fruit . very sweet . t : for such an aggressively sweet smell , the taste is a bit on the bitter side for a barleywine .  mouthfeel - low carbonation .

whatever it is , it 's complex and wonderful . t-nice balance of a stout ( i know there 's a trace of that in here ) with subtle sour characteristics : seems to be cherry . very nice finish .  it starts out thin with the wheat malt taking center stage then gets spicier as it goes . it finishes with a lot of banana and touch of yeast that lingers a fair amount for a lighter beer . the rest : a solid , tasty wit ; it checks all of the boxes of the style , and does it pretty well .
a - looks nice .  mouthfeel : medium body with a bit of oil that leaves a coat .

had this out of a bottle poured into a dfh pint glass ... a : copper color with a nice 2 finger white head . the lacing on this one is fantastic ... s : smells of floral hops and sweet malt .  m : yeah , i guess .

the strong aroma of pumpkin and ginger was really promising on this one , but the flavor really did n't deliver .  surprisingly dry finish in the back m - a bit think , could use some more bubbles or hops to round out the malt a bit .

22 oz bomber poured into a duvel tulip glass . massively massive head . that is fantastic head ! the color itself was a very dark ruby red color . that 's an interesting color for an ipa , which i 'm guessing is due to the rye .  mouthfeel - kinda effervescent . nothing exceptional .

aroma of hops , spice , coriander , lemon , and some grapefruit . although for being a wheat beer this is somewhat of the mark but for an interpretation this is excellent . citrus overtones , with few hints of bread . overall this is great .  mouthfeel - average crispness , moderately thin body , i 'm okay with it .

aroma is strong and boozy , tons of whiskey .  m - medium body with a pretty smooth texture , but mouthfeel is a little thin for a porter . body is a little thin , but the aromas and flavors are quite pleasant .

pours out of the dark clad bottle pure black with just a few hints of ruby around the edges . the rocky tan head lasts forever and leaves a lot of lace patches behind .  this was highly carbonated which produced a slighlty unpleasant tingling mouthfeel .

this beer pours a brilliant brown amber with a sandy off-white film that left some nice lace behind . this is truly an attractive beer .  m- a thin body- fully attenuated with no carbonation at all ... which is normal for the style , particularly when served by cask . quite possibly the best kriek lambic i have ever had !

a - pours orange with 2 fingers of white head . refuses to dissipate and leaves beautiful lacing .  first of all , any beer that has rock , paper , scissors bottle caps is a shoe-in in my book . this beer pours nicely to be a nice golden -yellow ( this is actually the first time i have drank this not straight from the bottle ) small head , disappears right away . tiny bubbles , smell of good malts . great drinkability great beer , great brewery , great price
a : solid bock appearance with a crisp , clear brown color with amber hues . a soft white head and not too much carbonation .  mouthfeel : medium bodied . low carbonation .

pitch black color , topped with a very dark tan , thick head .  the taste is about the same , with a distinct nut flavor . goes down pretty easy , but there is a lot of carbonation here , and you can distinctly see many small bubbles rising up from behind the brown color . overall , this is a pretty good beer , and a nice looking one . i recommend it .
the poured beer looks great too .  aside from the dry end this is an easy to drink beer with an average mouth .

very nice , actually ... my mouth is watering . the very beginning of the taste is good , but that first sweetroastiness is eclipsed by a strong bitterness and waxing dryness that detract from the experience such a good smell . man .  m - heavy , almost cough-syrup consistency with light carbonation .
sweet chocolaty aroma .  the body seems a bit lighter than i would have expected .

pours pitch black and completely opaque without even the slightest bit of lighter hues when held to a light source and a frothy dark chocolate neige/brown head that slowly fades into a lasting ring . large chunks of soapy lacing are left behind .  the mouth feel is a bit light for such a porter .

first off this beer smells great ... it 's right up there with green flash for hoppy aroma and complextiy . this is very solid and drinkable do n't get me wrong but it 's under carbonated and there is too much malt finish to make it truly great . when the beer makes contact with your taste buds you get a nice hoppy dose of citrus but it fades so quickly and the carbonation flattens before you swallow the beer that you do not feel total satisfaction upon drinking .  m - medium bodied with higher than average carbonation . it looks and feels a little chalky .

this is what beer should look like ... medium orange with a incredibly mesmerizing swirl of carbonation that doesnt quit for anything rising into a thin 1/4-inch but cozy blanket of off-white puckered foam .  maybe a bit watery because of the low alcohol content ? ? ? but samuel adams boston lager is about the same abv and to me thats more full bodied and a better malt backing .

coming from my hometown , i was psyched to try this one , and it looks like my excitement was justified . pours dark as night with a wondeful nutty coffee aroma .  there is very little carbonation , so the mouthfeel reminds me of a generic malt beverage .

poured with a large 3f soapy off-white head over a mostly clear , burnt orange body , with tons of visible carbonation and plenty of lacing .  it seems to say , above , that it 's cask ... it was certainly carbonated when we tried it - just not highly carbed . a bit light in the mouthfeel like all of the brutopia beers we tried .

zero lacing & head retention s : awesome sour/lactic odors t : an almost sugary sweetness is quickly steamrolled by sourness tartness & dry/wood notes .  i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . kind of a mild coconutty taste , almost pina colada like ? i 'm going to revisit this one for sure whenever i get a chance .
the pour was a bright and brilliant clear red and was topped off with a sparse off white head .  mouthfeel - a bit of a strange after taste but very crisp .

pours a dark , hazy mahogany with a giant off-white head . lacing is just about perfect .  the only real complaint i have with this beer is that it is just too thin ... i do n't buy that this is an ris ... if this was just an american stout , the thinner body would be suitable , but it 's just not on an imperial stout .

we evaluated every stout we could get out hands on here in the western us . we did the same with the non-us stouts we could find . obsidian stout had a robust roasted flavor but a very strong , bitter late bite that ruined it for us .  medium bodied , but has too much carbonation for my liking .
the head is full and thick fading a lingering creme like a great espresso . lacing on the glass is wonderful .  the mouthfeel is a little thin for the style but its still a fairly minor flaw .
appearance : pours a dark auburn body with 2-3 fingers worth of light tan head .  slightly dry malt/biscuit finish m & d : slightly thin mouthfeel , but overall a nice beer .

appearance is excellent , very dark and black like a stout should be .  surprising amount of carbination gets you with the first sip , it foams up in your mouth . but the body is alot less than i was expecting ... not think , just mostly carbination on top of a thin to medium body.. ? the flavors linger on your tongue , mainly at the back sides .
appearance - rich dark amber brown with a cream head . beautiful label on bottle .  m - murky with a low carbonation and a lingering sour .

this is incredibly intense , but also incredibly appealing . excellent !  mouthfeel/drinkability- a very thin beer in general , the carbonation breaks early in the mouth , then goes quickly and smoothly down the throat .
appearance is beautiful - a deep red/gold ( like a maple tree changing colors ) with a nice sticky head .  light bodied , and somewhat flat , though perhaps that is just this bottle ?

pours a super clear fiery reddish orange . a creamy eggshell colored head sits on top and provides some awesome sticky lacing .  makes it look like a blue moon ... i dont know just dont see the drinkability and mouthfeel to be good at all ... it was one and done for me ... .

samuel adam 's longshot weizenbock pours a couple fingers of dense tan foam over a deep brown brew . the nose is mellow and spicy- clove and banana , carbonation is medium and steady . this one does not touch aventinus- the benchmark , as far as i 'm concerned , for this style , but it 's still a way up there .  it 's pretty light bodied with a low level of carbonation .

appearance : pours a clear dark ruby-brown color with a 2 finger , dark cream colored head . the head settles to 1/2 inch and sticks around the whole time leaving a moderate amount of lacing on the glass .  very little carbonation , the beer feels light but also dense .

had this on tap at the brick store pub , served in a regensboog flute . poured a beautifully hazy dark golden with a great pure white head with finely beaded bubbles and that leaves some very fine lacing .  mouthfeel was slightly on the thin side , not quite watery , but close .

the nitro can widget leads to a beautiful cascading effect , pefectly dark beer , with the fluffy white head . looks fake it looks so good .  however the taste is more mellow than the smell and easier than expected to drink . it would go great with dark meats such as beef and pork . not something to drink often but a great change from the usual and like nothing i have ever tasted . it is without a must try .
poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 '' beige head over the slightly cloudy reddish amber brew . pillowy head recedes very slowly , with plenty of chunky lacing .  the mouthfeel is thin .

smells pretty good ; slightly sweet , with mild malts and citrussy hops making up the aroma .  the carbonation is just a bit prickly , it is n't the fullest , but what should expect . this one goes down smoothly , with the only turn-off being the carbonation .

bottle : poured a clear deep brown color ale with a nice huge foamy head with good retention and some nice lacing .  m : somewhat thin and slick ; however , you feel the heaviness in your stomach halfway down the glass .

a beautiful cloudy-golden color with an explosive 2.5 inch head that lasted for a few minutes .  it has a surprisingly thin body for such a bourbon and malty beast . also the carbonation is a bit higher then i would like for the style .

it 's a nice color , like a pretty standard pale ale/ipa . great retention ... good lacing . so it looks great ... aaaand now we fall apart ... why does this smell like garlic ?  should you drink this warm or cold ? when it 's cold the flavors are : dark chocolate , coffee , heavily roasted to burnt malt , and bitter hops . when it 's warm the flavors are more like : sweet chocolate , maybe some sort of fruit , coffee , heavily roasted malt , and not so bitter hops . i perfer the sweeter chocolate , not burnt malt , and less bitter hops flavor when it 's warm .

aroma of toasted bread and roasting chestnuts with a strong coppery head . strong roast nuts , toasted almonds , caramel and hints of apricot and cherry pull together to give a beer that is a little different with each sip as the palate becomes accustomed .  the mouthfeel is quite thin , but leaves a good chocolaty flavor on the back of the palate .
long lasting white , health head , opaque orange-yellow body .  m - medium , slight carbonation , blah .

a : pours a clear golden-amber , tons of carb bubbles flowing up through to support two fingers of foamy white head .  the aroma is hoppy and earthy with some fruity notes , reminds me a bit of orval in this sense . the flavor has a nice character of fruity hopes and a mild malt sweetness , but the beer is dominantly dry . there is a very mild tartness here but generally the beer is dominated by a blend between some spicy yeast notes and pleasant hop bitterness .
this stout pours with a dark brown to black body toped by a medium thick , brown head with lots of lacing .  the body of it was rather thin .

this is the most unusual and most pleasant smelling lager that i ever had the pleasure to inhale . i loved it . there are lots of flavors here for your tongue to enjoy . the best part is nothing over dominates .  m - not bad , but a little thinner than i was hoping for .

11.2 ounce bottle poured into pint glass two finger , tan head last thoughout the duration of the drink . mouthfeels is a bit thin and watery for a stout ... .just average . overall , this stout will do in a pinch , but not in my top 10 .  not very full in the mouth , a bit thin in my opinion .

smutty ipa pours a stunning bright orange , with a nice creamy white cap that hangs around for a minute before coating my glass with lace . absolutely gorgeous .  m- a solid amount of carbonation coupled with a lighter body makes this drink overall a little too light for my personal tastes .
appearance - wow at first it looked like a coffee milk shake , but after it settled it was a pitch black color with a creamy tan head .  it feels just a bit watery .
when held to light , has a reddish hue . this beer looks great . head retention is good , and there is some great lacing from the hops .  mouthfeel is flat feeling and a little thin .

the beer pours jet-black with the head modest in size and a light chocolate in color , the consistency creamy and the resultant lace a fine sheet to conceal the glass .  m- mouth is a little on the light side for a stout .
good retention and strong lacing . very nice .  ( m ) - a very high carbonation level .

this ale pours a copper brown with lots of carbonation and has a big head .  mf : thin for a baltic porter , the big flavor makes up for this , medium carbonation d : this beer has a ton of things going on and i must say it is well executed .
terrific retention , heavy lace . gorgeous lager .  looking at it you 'd expect a stout , smelling it you 'd expect it to be sweet - it 's neither - and it feels thinner than expected as well !
aroma : an absolutely phenomenal aroma , like a fine scotch ale .  mf - medium body , very creamy , light carb .

copper to gold ... lots of light flickering through and a rocky 3/4 '' bright white head ... aroma is awesome ... truly great . some spicy cinnamon and grassy hops ... herbaceous in a very cool herbaceous way with a a hint of basil and nosefull of dill . peppery and delicious . awesome .  m : smooth and creamy , though lacking the body found in non-nitro stouts , not bad though , a fuller body than guinness .

spicy and citrus hops tickle the nose . a very distinct piney and grape smell .  m- not a bad mouthfeel i just felt it to be average . light on the tongue , a little too dry and yet somewhat of a lingering aftertaste .

looks delicious . very good looking beer .  appearance : very cloudy , much more so than an average wheat beer . smell : smells faintly of hops and strongly of yeast and fermentation . it tasted a lot like a bad experiment of mine where i mixed some peach cider with some yuengling because i was sick of drinking yuengling . the only difference was that instead of having a peach flavor , the flavor was more like mixing apple juice and a wheat beer . very difficult to drink since i resented every swig .

recived this from secret santa 08 , poured into my duvel tulip glass , poured a rich black that at its thinest point as a glass is tiped back has a hint of red to it , a great 3 finger tan head rose to the top and stayed for a few seconds befor becoming a light lacing around the rim .  smells slightly watery faint tones of chocolate malts and coffee good although slightly watery tastes of slightly toasted coffee and powerful malts chocolate is also in there mouthfeel well carbonated yet slightly watery some of the best drinkability i 've experienced in a stout however this comes at a cost and the cost happens to be its mouth feel , taste and smell overall its a pretty good drinkable stout it really is not very good unless it is poured from the tap i 'll order at a pub if i want a stout and they do n't have a good micro brew on tap

the smell is very bitter and hoppy : grapefruit juice , grapefruit peels , butter scotch , roasted malt . toffee , but almost no sweetness at all . a grand and very tasty beer , but i like my dipas a little more aggressive . this one is very close to perfect , though .  pretty average looking . somewhat listless and a touch thin although i would imagine that it could translate better on cask .

750 ml bottle bought last summer at gator beverage a : pours a very dark but translucent red brown with a huge foamy head of fine bubbles that does n't retreat s : big ripe fruit aroma of raisins and banana on top of sweet barley malt t : it 's beer but has a strong punch of sweet fruit up front , followed by bitter cherry notes - unique in my experience m : very full - smooth and soft on the mouth , with mild carbonation d : may be a challenge drinking the whole 750 ml bottle not sure exactly what i paid for this , but do remember thinking it was kind of expensive . with so many very good and less expensive scotch ales available , i probably wo n't buy this one again .  body was reasonably light for the style . perhaps the aggressive carbonation helps with this .

i 'm assuming its the same thing.the neck label says dark winter wheat seasonale offerring.poured a huge head that slowly shrank to about half an inch .  mouthfeel is surprisingly light for the style . very little carbonation makes this one almost too easy to go down .
opaque black with a large mud brown head . cavernous retnetion and multiple droopy lace rings .  finishes dry with light floral hoppiness m : light bodied and medium carbonated .

bomber poured into a pilsner glass ... pours a bright golden color , very clear with a decent foamy white head that left good lacing throughout the drink .  m : very light ; low carbonation d : good great beer , so glad stone is in town !

750ml bottle to tulip . a : a huge off-white head of 5 fingers begins to wear out it 's welcome with a retention that could seemingly be measured in days . as the head slowly pulls away from the glass 's edge , it leaves a sticky , perfectly intermittent web of lace .  mouthfeel i kind of like the mouthfeel to this one .

smell : very nice . spicy and floral with a fruity character that reminds me a bit of ramune and a bit of apple cider . a disappointment after such an inviting nose and unusual appearance .  almost zero hops .

lacing is impressive , as well as head formation and retention .  this is an epl through and through . do n't be persuaded by the pilsener title . i had it after a holsen which is a real grain bomb . neither beer is that great but this one seemed inferior . and compared to holsten permium that is n't saying much . i you like stella artois or heineken or something like that in a can then go or it , but it is n't too good .

good thick , 1/2 inch head with great retention and great lacing .  medium-bodied , the froth translates into a shitload of mouth foam , almost got ta shut yer trap to keep it in . more blunt than refreshing , tries to lift but too bottom-heavy and spreads across the tongue . as sweet as bitter , and truly nothing brutal about it .

first of all , consider the deep toffee and caramel aroma ... it 's impressive . also , the yeast strain they use has a nice balance of dry crispness with fruity esters .  it feels a bit light in the mouth , but the finish is sharp , bitter , and with pine flavors from the hops . mouthfeel is average .
as you pour its a light cloudy straw with a huge and lasting white head . the head itself if very attractive as it is very fluffy and creamy .  its actually too carbonated for this type of brew .

s - very nice smell on this beer . very nice and complex nose that covers a range of notes . i would have enjoyed a little more sour spice to complex it out and help finish the beer .  pours a nice orange/ruby color with a thin head . it has a nice bitter `` bite '' to it but it 's not overwhelming . some citrus fruit with a hint of some darker fruit , maybe plum ? weird , i know . i could n't defiantly drink a few of these over the course of a night .

a : this beer looks heavy . it pours slowly , and looks very viscous .  3.0 m : lighter medium to medium body . carbonation is a bit too aggressive and further takes away from what is n't very creamy to begin with .

pleasant nose indeed . that very nice weizeny ester comes through , but pushed back by a spicey , clovey nose , a lot of spicey hop on that aroma , and it comes through loud and clear . a slight champagne sourness on there as well , but a very pleasant , complex fragrance there .  a little bit of sweetness also from the yeast taste : there is a very interesting dark fruit flavor profile going on here with raisin definately standing out as the main flavor mouthfeel : medium body with really high amounts of carbonation typical of lost abbey beers overall : i really dont care for lost abbey and their high levels of carbonation in their beers .

poured with an absolutely beautiful , huge , foamy , fluffy , frothy , billowy , off white head that soon settled down and some lace . color is cloudy amber with a few tiny bubble trails .  mouth feel is medium bodied , but i think it could use a bit more carbonation .

appearance : huge head that never ends with a soft coco color . nice lace trails while pouring followed by deep dark chocolate color to finish it off .  this is way to watered down for me . mouthfeel and drinkability : finishes somewhat dry . this brew also has a super light body with higher levels of carbonation-okay , these are appropriate for the style .

aroma is sigh-inducing with great pine , citrus , floral and peppery hop notes . what kind of hops are in this thing ? it smells like fresh hops .  m : the feel is a bit thin for the style but the creaminess from the carbonation is the best redeeming quality .

truly one of the best looking beers i have even seen ! a nice , light amber colour with tiny , delicate little bubbles flowing into a rock-like head .  the body is full , but lacks the richness or creamy aspect that the best versions of the style possess . carbonation is just a touch too active for my taste , it borders on being a distraction .
clear amber color smell is thick of caramel malts with a pear and apple undertones nice little complexity .  the mouthfeel is ok - just slightly under carbonated .
beautiful fruity citrus orange hop aroma !  mouthfeel : smooth , but a little syrupy .
smells just like the best thing ever . barley and fireplace .  mouthfeel is lacking , but the flavors are right on , carbonation is complimentary .

pours a deep black color with a perfect , thick beige head .  a- i had it in a bottle so i ca n't say . also this was the imported munich gold version s- smells like awesome sauce t- the taste is kind bready with some sweet maltige m- not much slides right on down d- goes down the hatch with ease overall i really like this juice !

aroma is fantastic . the flavor hits the palate like a jackhammer . complex and beautiful . the mouthfeel is light but creamy and lingers on the palate begging for another sip .  very little carbonation in this beer . the mouthfeel seems pretty unexceptional it 's pretty smooth with a medium body .
what a beauty . the head is rich and downright pillowy .  m : medium to thin viscosity with low carbonation .

bomber poured into tulip glass a : wow ! this one is a sight to see . pours with a huge khaki colored head , that reduces slowly and leaves nice full cap on top . tremendous lacing . impressive .  sharp carbonation in the mouth feel . not a very friendly mouth feel but it is very drinkable .

smells like a crate of grapefruit - the crate and the fruit . big malt up front citrus hop finish - not huge though kind of watery finish . drinkability - decent due to the lightness - might keep the interest beyond one but not two but i generally do n't like hoppy for session beer .  that settles into a nice thick lace covering most of the glass yes it 's a chocolate stout and the aromas defiantly back it up lots of sweet chocolate aromas some earthiness to it along with some hint of roasted malts flavor 's of dark chocolate are dominate not overly sweet with a coffee backbone it 's got this mocha thing going on the mouthfeel is medium to thin would have liked it a little thicker this is really one of the great chocolate stout 's especially for under $ 5 a bomber well worth the experience

a - it does n't get any better looking than this ; a brilliant golden color with nice clarity and a dense three-finger off-white cream head . sheets of lace cling like webby veils on the glass .  light bodied . a very good tripel , but i would like to see the carbonation toned down to improve the mouthfeel .

poured a dark , dark brown with a light brown head that started at a quarter inch then magically expanded to 3/4 inch then settled at 1/2 an inch .  appearance : like beer smell : beery taste : like pils in germany mouthfeel : beer-like drinkability : i did n't see jane stop until they stopped bringing it i 'd say its an excellent example of the style .

it looked really appealing , dark reddish orange and hazy with a creamy looking white foam .  it 's definitely tasty but perhaps a tad less complex and more straight forward than i would have liked mouthfeel-very low carbonation though a tad prickly with alcohol heat , rather thin body for an ris , could definitely stand to be plusher and more viscous .
pours a beautiful dark reddish-brown color with a decent head .  mouthfeel is light bodied and a bit undercarbonated overall , which is my only real complaint about this one .

once in the glass from the tap , a beautiful color fils your mind , a perfect not quite brown , honey amber tone with hints of gold . perhaps the best looking beer in the world . strong lacing and great head , beautiful roasted flavor that im sure would be even better with age .  m : thin viscosity ( bordering on being watery ) and moderate carbonation seem out of place here .

on tap in a guinness pint glass a-pours a very deep brown almost completely opaque with a nice creamy head that stay with the beer through out almost looks like sand rising to the top of the glass in a perfect ring.this is most definatly one of the worlds best looking beers .  m : light in body . on nitro , this would be alot creamier ... but it 's still damn good .

misspent youth has the requisite apa elements -- light caramel malt and american hop aroma -- but combines them in a way you 've never had before . light golden amber pour with an average coupla centimeter head . first sniff is an exceptionally balanced portfolio of hops .  it 's very easy to drink , crips , and light , but it 's a bit thin in character & feel .
combined w/ the copious , lively bubbling and clear , light amber hue , this beer is vibrant and visually appealing .  somewhat of a small bite to it from the carbonation .
aroma is a very fragrant load of citrus hops .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly light and so is the body .
pours a very dark brown/red almost black , a nice tan head with some nice lacing .  medium-full bodied , but was too flat , very smooth .
head looks like an almost pure white like the snow outside and has ample retention .  m - very light and crisp .

a : pours a very deep brownish-crimson color with a sizeable off-white head that retains well and lays down a bit of lacing on my snifter . very impressive appearance .  the feel is a little too thin .
notes of belgian candi sugars , beets , and black cherries .  mid palate is substantially thin .

smell : great woody smokiness ; smoke flavor is distinctive for other generic smelling smoked beers . taste : well balanced smokiness ; does not overwhelm , but weaves nicely between senses of taste and smell . sweet malts complement the smokiness ; alcohol is well balanced by the full bodied flavors .  i felt this beer was too carbonated and hence it was too slick and creamy in my mouth .
great lacing & head retention s : straight cornyness & diatechythl t : cornyness & astrigency , iron & cloying sweetness .  mainly a flattish mouthfeel .

smells amazing ! big on citrus and grapefruit , smells like sugar in your nose.. really great.. taste follows well and tickles the tongue in all the right ways without feeling boozy especially for a 10 % beer .  it 's slightly watery , but refreshing and finishes a little dry mouthfeel is pretty average .
a= jet black color with a huge head leaving not lacing but actual sheets of bubbles on my glass .  the mouthfeel seems a tad too watery as well .

poured a beautiful thick white head full of small small compact bubbles ( nitro 's gift ) . definitely looks like a guinness beer except for the color .  feels a bit thin in the mouth keeping this good beer from being a great beer .

very enjoyable . the taste is sweet at first but then the bitterness hits .  my sister always goes on vaction to mexico and says this is her favorite beer . i collect 40oz bottles have about 150 in my collection , so when i saw this in a mexican resturant i was happy to say the least . i got my chance to drink this beer and add a new bottle to my collection . beer was smooth and pretty good for being on 4 % alch , was suprised that it was dark in color . taste was like other mexican beers , but i liked this more , due to it being `` rare '' only problem is the price i paid $ 15.00 for this 40oz bottle .

among the best coffee scents i 've ever experienced . an incredibly appealing aroma . pretty strong as well . a lovely coffee porter all around . not as tailored to it as it could be , but all around very complementary .  mouthfeel is average , not too thin , and i think appropriate for this beer .

the smell was of cranberries and some jasmine , with a hint of alcohol . the cranberries and jasmine were both present in the taste , but the alcohol was very much in the front . this beer is not totally undrinkable , but there is no way i would want to even smell another one of these after having one .  mouthfeel is very light , a little watery , with a somewhat crisp feel to it .

pours with a nice thick head that shows great retention .  the taste was even worse , vinegar , old cardboard , just really gross . i do n't know if the keg was abused or really old but this was one sorry-ass beer . this was truly bad and i only finished it because i wanted to catch a buzz before my flight . i should have asked for a replacement .

pours a clear golden yellow with a monsterous tower of head that engulfs much of the glass and one of the thickest walls of lacing i have ever seen . perfect pale ale appearance , probably the best i 've ever seen for the style .  drinking one of these right now . not the best beer i 've ever laid to my lips but by the same token its much better then some . as you drink it you notice it does n't have alot of flavor going on , a little wheat flavor , but it 's not unplesant . overall it is pretty sudsy . smell is also like grain . fairly good to drink and light enough to multiples of
bottle appearance : cloudy orange/gold with a nice frothy head that retains for quite some time . looks inviting .  taste : very little carbonation .

head is tan in color and has great retention with a solid one finger above the brew . head is creamy in appearance and is looking like it will leave some stellar lacing ... hey what do you know it does !  the hop character , however , does n't overpower the malt and barely-there vanilla . m : not that noticeable to me , but certainly not offensive . the malty taste with a little bit of hops really helps the beer .

the aroma is incredible . all of the dried , dark fruits i 've ever tried at one time . this was really nice . the other barleywines i 've tried have been far too hoppy but this was a wonderful , sweet , thick treat .  the flavor is almost worse ... .damn near made me gag . just a weird fake cherry sweetness that is so cloying it is disgusting . honestly , i ca n't give any more detail because i could n't stomach another sip or smell .

appearance - a hazy/cloudy amber beer with a big head that stiicks for a while and leaves a lot of lacing .  im sure this loses ratings for its thin palate , but taste wise this is spot on . more roasted coffee flavors and a touch of smokiness . an imminently sippable brew . nicely done .
the smell was fantastic though , sweet and yeasty .  m : light , and not as smooth as porter should be . after taste is great , mouthfeel is n't .
beautiful beer in the glass . nice orange tinted red/brown when held to the light with a two finger , tan , creamy head .  mouthfeel is a touch light for my liking , but i 've come to expect that .
it smells roasty , the way a brewery smells when you take a tour . inviting . spicy bitterness up front , and not too much else .  m - i honestly could n't say .

pours out light yehoow and sits amber in the glass with a good sized white fluffy head . great sticking power with wonderful lacings . some of the best head retention i 've ever seen .  m : it feels light- to medium-bodied on the palate and has a light amount of carbonation .
with a dark caramel color , large bubbles and good lacing , it was certainly something to look at .  m - thin body and light carbonation .
very dark brown verging on black with a billowing , fluffy , tan head .  m : very light carbonation but there is just a bit to give the beer some levity .
appearance ; thick , stiff white head , excellent retention and messy spider web-like lacing .  moderate carbonation and a light , slightly watery mouthfeel .
orange-red color with a massive off white head .  m - bubbly and medium on the tongue .

a fantastic looking beer .  ( from notes ) i picked this beer up while living in dublin , i poured it from a .5l can into a pint glass ... a : a nice roasted dark brown nearly black color , with a tannish head , decent lacing ... s : the smell is pretty weak but i am getting some faint burnt malt and slight coffee ... t : the taste is about the same except more fully roasted flavor ... m : smooth and watery ... d : a decent beer from guinness , but once you have had their special export to belgium , you wonder why they make anything else .

poured into a pioneer stein ( # 42 , 2009 edition ) , formed a 2 1/2 '' frothy tan head over the slightly cloudy caramel hued brew . head falls slowly with an audible sizzle of bubbles bursting , with tons of lasting lace .  the finish is on the dry side making for a real crispness . the only bad thing i can say is that it 's kind of thin body wise but it 's still a nice ipa .

pours a beautiful ruby color with some haze . i was totally caught off guard with the color ... .a truly beautiful presentation .  mouthfeel left a little to be desired , carbonation was mild and the liquid was relatively thick reminding me more of a juice i would drink with breakfast than a beer .
wonderful looking brew .  the carbonation is pretty average , the body decently weighty and fairly smooth , and it finishes bone dry , a bit of herbal bitterness hanging on .
fantastic belgian lacing left behind as the head dies down . truly a perfect looking beer , this is just sexy .  a bit sharp and overly carbonated , and thin bodied .

pours pitch black with a huge huge tan head , fades incredibly slow , if i was in a rush to drink it i 'd be kinda peeved it took so long to settle down , leaves a good amount of sticky lacing .  tastes great , but the mouthfeel is a lot thinner than i 'd like for the style .
s- sweet cranberry/strawberry.some pines but not as much as i would have expected in reading the label .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is one of the most drinkable beers around .

the aroma is relatively strong delivering a ton of vanilla on the nose with a finish that provides some nice depth with oak dominating followed by some distinct bourbon flavor .  its actually really tasty ... hints of booze throughout keep you honest but this is really nice ... one of the most luxurious mouthfeels ever in my opinion ... it feels thick and creamy and coats the mouth on the finish very nicely.. overall , another winner ... i do n't like it as well as the first one of the series but this is really nice

awesome aroma . pours a cloudy dark orange color , some nice head with decent retention . very smooth- from the smell , i was actually expecting a more pronounced hop flavor here , but regardless , this is an excellent ipa . mouthfeel- appropriate carbonation , buttery , clean . drinkability- i could drink this one all day .  superb . d - this is a tasty beer , but the fusel alcohol character and high alcohol in general make me appreciate it less fully .

a hazy orange gold with a nice thick white head that leaves decent lacing on the glass smell is of piney and citrusy hops followed by some pale/caramel malts .  soft , creamy mouthfeel smothers my tongue with flavor .

on cask at south coast plaza location ; med body , frothy almost velvety mouthfeel , mild carbonation . notes of floral hops and a big note of lavender .  mf : thick viscous body , creamy mouthfeel , low carbonation d : i have tried many of dfh 's wild experiments when it comes to unique ingredients , and found that some of them fell short and ingredients got lost ( theobroma comes to mind ) .
a fruity banana and sweet honey aroma adds alot to the enjoyment of this brew .  insanely smooth , creamy , and slick body with light-medium carbonation .
or so of this , though the nose is incredible .  mouthfeel is just superb . satisfying .

big aroma of resinous , citrusy hops sting your brain . taste does not try to hide the alcohol - in fact it showcases it . brown sugar taste in more present than i expected from this brew . hops prickly on the tongue . although i would not mind the alcohol and bittering hops knocked down a notch , this is still a wonderful brew .  m : very nice . well carbonated , creamy , smooth , and very full bodied .

nose of full of character and its very easy to pick to bubblegum and bana notes . a little on the confectionary side but very appealing . not shy on the fizz but does n't detract and some slightly bitter notes finish a very good beer .  mouthfeel is amazingly smooth . almost creamy , but not annoyingly so . very good . overall it 's pretty good , the mouthfeel is great .
s - the nose is pretty damn enticing . it still has admirable qualities , but the taste is sorely disappointing in comparison to the nose .  i love the rich , silky smooth feel .

aroma is smokey malts with a beechwood or bologna smell to it . slight hops are found in there as well with a slight sugary caramel ; pretty complex ! taste is rather smokey and sweet ; it reminds me of deer jerky or sweet bologna really .  mickey 's ice has an amazing mouthfeel to it , one of the best in my opinion . the carbonation comes on strong then fades to a creaminess .

very complex . t : sh & # 333 ; ch & # 363 ; tinge up front . d : unique combination of elements feels like a mash-up between a farmhouse ale and a strong ale . will try again .  mouthfeel : this is where it shines . smooth and heavy and very warming .

where was this aroma when i had this on draft ? tons of vanilla , toasted coconut and bourbon notes meld with lightly roasted/sweet caramel malt notes of maple . t-lusciously sweet maple , bourbon , vanilla and oak are strong up front . touch of wood astringency and lightly spicy hop notes help balance the sweetness out . founders strikes again with another masterful barrel aged brew , this brewery simply knows how to barrel age beer ... .period ! i thought it a dud on draft ( or maybe it was just me that day ) but out of the bottle ... shazaam !  mouthfeel is on the dry side with effervescent carbonation that contributes to the crisp clean finish . its a fascinating brew that manages to be both crisp and refreshing yet still rich and satisfying .

the nose is pure and simple - coffee .  this pils is somewhat maltier than average , and the ensuing mouth feel is amazing . i never thought a pils could be `` creamy '' and light but this one was that , and if not , then very close .

the aroma is quite complex and very appealing- grass , a bit of pine and citrus , some hard to identify floral and spice notes , yum yum yum . grass , lemon , and ... watermelon ( ?  m & d : perfect carbonation make the mouthfeel nice , but the alcohol limits the drinkability of this beer ... not that i could n't easily drink a few of these in one session ( if only ! ) reccomended !

a great combination of nutty and bready aromas ; exactly as it should be .  the mouthfeel on this beer was truly exceptional . i 've never had a beer with such great viscosity that managed to avoid being sticky .

s : fantastic floral hop aroma that only dry hopping can produce ! t : the hops have done more than just produce great aroma , they are prevalent in the flavor as well - and not just bittering . i love hoppy beer and this was no exception . a nice smooth base ale , perfectly accented with earthy flavorful hops . great ale !  the body is nearly full with a surprising and delightful prickly feel . excellent carbonation level . really , quite nice on the feel .

aroma brings bright layers of pink grapefruit , lemon zest , mj , apricot , tangerine , etc ... this is one great smelling beer . this ipa has nice balance between bitter and flavor in regards to the hops . not quite as bright and juicy as the aroma led me to believe , but rather , a little rough around the edges , which is n't all bad in an ipa .  spices are well balanced by the soft sweetness , mouthfeel is outstanding .

smell : a punget bouquet of citrus ( orange , grapefruit ) and herbal ( wet grass ) hops comes together . taste : totally flat and boring ... .massive disappointment after loving the nose . mouthfeel : thin drinkability : too sad to have anymore .  much better balance on the palate . crisp , clean feeling with just a bit of drying on the finish .

bottle poured a very dark amber with a large off white head that stuck to the glass .  m- full bodied but does not dominate your mouth , it is silky and smooth on the tongue . great balance and good carbonation .

raisins , grass , chocolate . d - it 's really not that pleasant to drink .  m - mouthfeel is great . a medium-full body with good carbonation . perfect . d - the thicker mouthfeel makes it slightly less drinkable .

it also exposes the most beer to the air developing one of the best beer aromas i have ever known . this is a beer for the nose . it always starts strongly floral and changes with the tempature . there is some hint of citrus followed by fresh hay , and yeast . the beer itself is dark amber and cloudy . i always dump it all in . the taste is at least as complex as the smell . the is just enough carbination to keep it all light . it is an amber ale and exhibits all the malty full bodies character of an ale . orval is in some class of its own and must be experienced to fully understand .  for a supposed potent*ipa* i expected a huge blast , but it is light refreshing yet surprising t. sweeter ipa , nothing too extreme , dry finish on the tongue with an exceptional mouth feel .

nora 's nose is amazing . it 's mainly dominated by spicy peppers but has some distinct fruity notes of coriander , watermelon , apricots and some ginger .  the taste is an initial malty sweetness , followed by bitter hoppy alcohol , followed by dry chewiness . this brew has a great thickness and presence , and the carbonation is not too much to interrupt things . excellent .

the aroma is on the lighter side but very balanced and nice . it starts off very sweet , some wonderful sweet chocolate notes with some vanilla with a finish of coffee .  good body and perfect carbonation .

the aroma was intense . quite sweet overall . chocolate notes dominated . a nice mix of dark chocolate and powdered cocoa . somewhat bourbony and boozy . the lingering finish was very roasty and hoppy , with the hops being leafy , piney and sharp . overall , the beer was rather pithy , dry and bitter on the back end . the mouthfeel was creamy and smooth yet noticeably thin for the style .  amazingly thick and perfectly carbonated .
the lagavulin ( scotch ) aroma is very good . the aroma is only of scotch and slight malt .  4/5 m : very nice . perfect feel .

the aroma is outstanding ! toffee mixed with a strong pineapple scent with a hint of grapefruit . this is an excellent dipa with a strong bitter wallop .  m - the body of this beer with the carbonation is perfect . tiny bubbles , so you have that nice creaminess with a fantastic , medium and not overpowering mouthfeel . d - because there is so much coffee slammed into this beer , it leaves your mouth a little dry and overwhelms the palate , so i 'm good after one bottle .
pours an absolutely nice deep red colour , with an enormous brwonish head that seems to last forever .  the mouthfeel is fantastic if you sip and swish ever so gently .

smell : wow , this one is extra funky ! it 's like he shook the cobwebs a little more , kicked up the dust from the attic and pressed the juice out of the wet blanket a little harder !  gentile mix of flavors , not super complex , but with an incredible silky mouthfeel , and an oragne glow that makes it look great .

poured out of the large bottle a wonderful pitch black , almost like an onyx gem , the way it reflected light . it had a wonderful tan head and great lacing .  fantastic creamy and full bodied mouthfeel .
smells of hops . lots of hops .  m-this is full bodied , extremely smooth , very inviting on the palate , it is quite creamy and carbonated just right .

this smell 's like a messy , dripping , kindergartner 's peanut butter and jelly sandwich : mild breadiness , sticky skippy peanut butter , and sweet strawberry jam ! unique , unusual , and honestly , pretty crazy . this beer is pretty acidic and sharp , somewhat sweet , and there 's a bit of bread and nuttiness left over , but there 's nothing much here to enjoy or appreciate . that being said , the liquid in the glass smelled far better than it tasted .  body is creamy and rich , with mild carbonation , pretty strong abv , but alcohol is not dominant in the taste i enjoyed this beer the more i drank , very impressed .

a=pours a brown color with a deep deep amber highlights and a small one finger thick head that lasts suprisingly quite a while leaving some pretty good lacing s= really caramelly sweet maltyness .  wonderful . i ca n't imagine drinking this all night but this seems as though it 's one of the few beers that would be right at home as a food accompaniment with a seven-course haute cuisine meal .

amazing aromas of strong caramel , maple syrup , coffee , chocolate .  finishes warm and fruity gain with a very sweet exhale that is not quite cloying but just perfect . thick bodied with a light carbonation , goes down easily .

smell : wow . loads of anise , port , dark chocolate , espresso , cabernet sauvignon , and raisins . awesome . taste : alas , my nose seems to have misled my tongue . overall , fairly acrid and not very good . mouthfeel : flat carbonation and surprisingly thin body . but from this experience ... i can not recommend it , no matter how pleasant the aroma .  m/d : velvety smooth and a sensational full body . warming alcohol sensation is just right and is not too hot .
very nice . t - wow !  mouthfeel is top notch though , smooth as hell , velvety , chewy and creamy , medium-bodied and showing a perfect amount of carbonation .

aroma was out of this world , with strong scents of pumpkin pie and spice , similar to a really good straight-up pumpkin ale like weyerbacher , etc . after the aroma , i felt the taste was a bit disappointing , but i received cocoa nibs , vanilla , nutmeg , and clove , with some yeasty notes coming through as the beer approached room temperature . as i drank this beer , i thought it was `` okay '' but that it would have been much better and that the flavors would have translated better if it were a stout rather than a belgian dark .  the taste , and mouth feel are amazing . the taste has a very nice fruity hoppy flavor , followed by a nice bitterness . the mouthfeel is creamy , and as smooth as a silk , with just the right amount of carbonation .

s : aroma is exquisite : sweet dark chocolate , hints of caramel and bourbon , bits of coffee and molasses , lots of scent and very welcoming . t/m : has a low to medium amount of carbonation with the bourbon very well balanced between caramel , chocolate , and coffee notes .  m : as great as the bottle was , as you can expect , the nitro-tap was a homerun . so incredibly smooth and creamy , one of the best mouthfeels i 've had .

gorgeous reddish brown . nice creamy head with little lacing .  m/d - mouthfeel is great , this beer briefly coats the mouth but then almost cleans it 's own flavor out of your mouth and has a slight aftertaste .

a- beautiful crystal clear honey color with mild white lace . s- honey , raisins , toast , biscuits , almonds , barley , alcohol , cane sugar , vanilla , fruit . very spicy , very alcoholic .  for the style , mouthfeel was superb , and drinkability was too .
the tan head is big and creamy and shows good retention and leaves decent lacing .  incredibly smooth and goes down easy .

12oz poured into my flying monkeys pint glass a- slight hazy amber , 1 '' fluffy white head , excellent lacing s- pine , grapefruit , orange , fresh cut grass t- grapefruit , pine , lemon , slight malts bit of sweetness m- chewy , juicy , perfect amount of carbonation , right amount of sweetness d- i could drink this all night . ca n't wait to try it fresh .  perfect . overall , i think it 's really nice beer and i 'm enjoying it .

on-tap at the brewpub : exceptional dark brown nearly black color , thick and rich body , finger high cap of dark ivory thats puffy and whipped smooth with some bumpyness emerging as it settles slowly , very slowly in fact , to a substantial skim and thick collar , good lacing sticks in thick webbings .  m : you tell this is a big beer just by the feel , it 's almost like i 'm chewing it with each sip . the carbonation is right on as well and finish has a touch of dryness ... perfect for a dipa .
just an enormous complex smelling stout . bits of flowery esters float around as well .  taste & mouthfeel : crisp moderate body , perfect level of carbonation not to tamper with the smoothness .

the way these smells mix together is really impressive . the flavor is based on a dry green apple sweetness and a touch of pale malts , but this is taken away by a fantastic dry oak and calm citrus rind that brings out an herbal muskiness .  taste & mouthfeel : so creamy smooth , malty on the palate .

smell- wow , that is exactly what chocolate covered cherries smell like when you have bit into that sugary center . taste- the nose does not transfer as well to the palate , bummer . mouth feel- definitely too thin for what smells like a very decadent beer . overall- this beer was enjoyable if only for the nose that did a wonderful job of portraying chocolate cherry .  very velvety , creamy lactic mouthfeel . the aftertaste lingers big time w/ yeasty stickiness .

the beer pours out a hazy reddish orange , and has a magnificent head that stays around for minutes and leaves lacing down the side of the glass.. has a very clean taste .  a : as others have said , its an opaque black ; the head is tan , and leaves a very slight lacing along the glass s : coffee , dark chocolate , spices , and alcohol ; only wish the smell was a bit stronger t : the flavor is intense with chocolate , caramel , and dark fruits followed by a spiced aftertaste ; it is only slightly bitter and there is no alcohol apparent in the taste m : carbonation is perfect ; definately does not feel watered down d : at 13 % alcohol any more than two drinks is excessive , and one may be the perfect number overall , its a great beer .

the aroma was delicious . i really wish i had had more time to stay and get another glass of this stuff .  the taste and mouthfeel save this one . quite a difference in mouthfeel , but still wonderful .

1/8 '' head , chocolate milk in color . i am loving the smell . taste - 4.5 way more subtle than i was expecting .  mouthfeel : wow this is a big beer with some nice carbonation on it . drinkability : well the alcohol taste was a little bit too much , but its wonderful mouthfeel just blew my mind .
the smell is amazing , perhaps the best part of the stout , it is very chocolatey with a roasted malt sneaking in behind .  mouthfeel is perfect - medium body , plenty thick , nicely carbonated .

s- smell is delightful ! sweet butterscotch maple .  a - this one is pitch black ... nothing light about it ... the head stands one finger and is brown and creamy ... falls into a ring slowly ... the lacing only showed for the first 1/4 of the beer s - right off the bat you can pick up the juniper ... it shows itself with lots of fresh pine aroma ... i 'm thinking a christmas tree or even gin ... there are also notes of roasted malt lingering in the background t - the beer went through a few different changes as i sipped on it ... first sip brings a bright blast of fresh pine from the juniper ... it mellows out in the middle and the finish is full roasted malt with coffee and chocolate mixed in ... now , as the beer warmed the brightness of the juniper faded and became more apparent in the finish and the malt was more apparent at first sip m - full bodied ... this one is thick and smooth ... great cask feel ... roasted flavors coat the palate and the juniper adds a nice bitterness d - i like regular tenfidy and i think this is a perfect brew for winter ... it would have been great to have around christmas time since it smelled like a christmas tree ... nice complex flavors with roasted malt and bright pine ... i think it was served a little too cold but that let me notice the changes in the beer
overall , it looks very sexy .  the mouthfeel was incredible . very creamy and smooth .

smell is phenomenal . pine , citrus , pepper , faint banana , bready malts , and hints of alcohol backed sweetness . i love arrogant bastard and thought this would be spectacular after smelling it but that was n't the case . it was good , no doubt , i just expected better .  good moderate carbonation and a crisp , dryish , oily slick , chewy , creamy smooth full bodied mouthfeel .

smells like hops first , then rye and a bit of medium caramel malt . beautiful nose . i 'd go crazy if i smelled this but could n't drink it .  m = heavy , heavy body , luscious creamy feel , great mouthcoating . one of the best mouthfeels i 've ever experienced in a beer .
smell primarily lots and lots of heavy roasted malt . its also extremely sweet , its a vanilla type of sweetness on this one .  carbonation is perfect and really adds to the beer .
