aroma of caramel malt , apples , brandy , and light oak . pretty much as expected with a little more alcohol showing up in the nose .  perfect balance of sweet and bitter with a creamy smooth mouthfeel .

s : fruity notes of sherry , some alcohol , fresh fruit , cherries , peppers , some wood and spices . biscuits and toffe , and also some strawberries . very hoppy .  m : rich and creamy , exactly what i want in a stout of this magnitude . perfect carbonation with some bitterness for bite .

aroma-this beer has such a phenomenal hop bouquet-super floral , piney , light resin , big citrus with notes of grapefruit and lemon-this beer just plain smells awesome . lurking under the hops is some nice support from the malt , with toast and caramel peaking through . the flavor is good , but the nose just blows other beers out of the park-it smells incredible . love this beer .  mouthfeel is exceptional and creamy . this is what makes this beer so spectacular imo .

nose is pretty hoppy for the style , with alot of citrus and pine showing through . not overly classical , but smells damn good , i am digging on these hop aromas .  m - very rich and full , reminds me of double bastard . dry with a nice low carbonation d - very well rounded , a little dry but bery easy to drink overall a great beer .

smells simply delightful ! pronounced citric ( grapefruit ) hops and a modest sweetness . most impressive . golden amber with pert near 100 % clarity and a large creamy head . light dms / veggitation sensation , may just be the hops though .  the mouthfeel is excellent as it makes an otherwise sweet beer crisp and the lingering carbonic bite lends a lot to the drinkability .

s : delicious mix of citrus and floral hops aromas with smells of mango , pineapple , and orange backed with mild sweet maltiness . t : the taste does n't quite live up to the smell , but it is still very good with big-time floral and fruity hoppiness smoothed by caramel sweet malt flavors .  this beer excells in it 's mouthfeel .

s - raisins , apples , carmel , complex malts , nutmeg and cloves . t - taste goes bland very fast , sweetness right at the beggining resembling dark cherries which gives way to a blandness very quick .  mouthfeel : extremely smooth and crisp .
nicely herbal noble hops showcased in the nose . so far i 'm pretty impressed by this .  m : thick , syrupy viscosity with light carbonation -- exactly as a beer of this style should be .
cherry flavour with acidic and sour aftertaste . this is one of the best fruit beer i have ever had .  tingle on the tongue is amazing . at 8 % abv , this goes down nice and easy .

a- copper colored with off-white head that stayed for a really long time s- has a pretty damn good smell , slight malt and a pretty floral hop character t- considering the strong hop scent , the taste is a little bit of a let down , much more mellow than i was hoping for .  the mouthfeel is excellent . very smooth , with just a little effervescence that gives it a certain crispness . good taste and a perfect feel make this a very drinkable beer , but with the high alcohol content , you 're going to want to take it slow with this one .
a wonderful cinnamon and allspice smell . it reminds me of one of the candles the wife burns in the head .  this beer has one of the best mouthfeel to it .

s - strong spicy , malty , and yeasty aroma bursting fourth from the glass with dark fruit aromas - raisin and plum - with a tiny citrus sharpness to it . d - good but not great in the drinkability department , it has a nice flavor and an outstanding aroma .  fruity , yet stinging ... sweet , delicious , spicy , tantalizing ... taste ... fantastic texture , floods the mouth with flavor , excellent weizen graininess , raisiny , figgy fruitiness , doubled up with richness ... each gulp brings waves of sensation ... i find myself liking this more as i go ... it 's punishing , though , flavorful , yet stinging and slaying , a serious threat to sobriety ... a bold attack on the senses ... the perfect nightcap ... just the thing to knock me out and send me to slumberland .

s. smells of honey , sweet malt , citrus hops , grains , and grass . t. a bit let down on the taste after the wonderful look and aroma . an interesting honey backbone with some graininess starts off the brew only to quickly change into a citrus hoppy bitterness with some earthy hops as well .  perfect consistency neither thick nor thin , but to silky to be described as simply `` medium '' .

poured chilled in ale glass a : cloudy , dark peach color ; good head ; decent lacing s : persistent , buoyant ; esters , booze , pear dominate t : sweet with overtones of pear ; light at first , moving to dry ale on the back end , almost too raw ; complex , flavorful beer a pleasant saison .  carbonation is pretty much perfect , and adds just the right element to the brew .

it looked great in a champagne flute with a big pink head and wonderful raspberry smell . this is where the good part ends . it is like kool-aid which is very drinkable but not very exciting . $ 3.99 at bev'mo .  the mouthfeel is excelent on this one though , very smoothe and crisp and very drinkable .

deep copper in color . 1 finger creamy head so this leaves some beer remaining in the bottle .  creamy and luscious body and wonderful layered complex flavors . pale malts , lead into corainder and tropical fruits with a yeasty belgian spice induced finish that lasts into a tingly carbonation with some hop bitterness . very nice .
the aroma was just amazing - sweet kandi and floral elements i can only assume were from the hops .  full , oily and creamy body with moderate carbonation .

aroma just as you would expect , cherry and dark malts . the name of the beer indicates the brewer 's priorities here : cherry first , stout next .  very drinkable and actually light in alcohol ( at 7.5 % ) for the size and richness of the mouthfeel .

smell : the aroma is full and robus . the funk , lemon zest sour , and musty notes are so well developed and complex . mouthfeel : the explosive carbonation kind of detracts from the experience for me . this also lightens the feel of the body overall : even though there are some great notes in the nose and the complexity is there , the flavor really can not kick this into another  great smooth mouthfeel..creamy .

smell : i ca n't put a finger on what it is i 'm smelling , but the aroma of this beer is incredible ! !  m : spot on with the mouthfeel - very thick and almost chewy , with just a hint of alcohol towards the finish .

garlic and citrus fruit are very present . pine also makes an appearance as well as marijuana . i love it ! t : tastes almost like it smells . i do n't get much garlic , not nearly as much as the smell offered up .  absolute delightful mouthfeel , silky smooth .

very vineous scent hits you immediately . further sniffing leads you into the world of saisons and scents of wheats , bananas and freshness . nice taste to it , good flavor .  very soft carbonation that makes it feel creamy and silky smooth one of , if not , the thickest beers i 've had . love it .
this beer has a remarkable scent . it smells like starbucks coffee .  mouthfeel is thick , chew , viscous .

scent is fantastically tart with some nice chocolatey notes ... very unique . as the beer warms up , i get a delightful chocolate covered cherry aroma . smells very inviting . taste initially sweet chocolate flavors , immediately followed by tart cherries . very complex . nice alcohol burn at the end due to the high abv .  d - i love the dessert like chocolate and cream notes , and the mouth feel is outstanding . a really well done brew , but i do n't think that i could take more than one ... it 's a hair to sweet imo .
nice strong aromas . taste : i was not expecting such a powerful sour flavour for an irish red .  this exhibited a creamy mouthfeel .

smell - very clean , brisk , hoppy smell . big plant-like aroma , earthy pine and slight straw . very full-bodied , but still refreshing . overall- rich , big and bold . a bit pricey , but certainly worth the try .  a light bodied beer but incredibly smooth . leaves the palate feeling dry , making this an excellent strong summery beer .

the aroma is really fantastic . i love the floral sweetness , the citrus , all so bright and fresh , with out being heavy-handed .  it 's mild to medium body with the really great mouthfeel makes me want to swish the beer around my mouth before swallowing .

aroma is strong and inviting . fruity esters abound . cherry , peach & cream , pepper corn , subtle hops and alcohol . deliciously mouth watering . flavor is interesting and unexpected . not so complex as i would have guessed , and the body is a bit flabby , but somehow i 'm enjoying every sip .  the mouthfeel is exceptional , big thick viscous and sticky and is amazingly velvety over my palate . really quite incredible .

smell was intense and amazing . woody with dried fruits and burnt caramel . the taste unfortunately was not nearly as complex . somewhat sweet and malty rich up front with some noticeable hops on the back of the palate .  surprisingly full mouthfeel with lots of carbination ... .almost creamy feel .

as soon as i opened the bottle an overwhelming aroma of wood enticed my flavor sensors . the appearance was the same as any aged brown ale , but the aroma was absolutely incredible ! the paraguayan palo santo wood truly made for a unique `` holy '' experience .  the mouthfeel is fantastic , crisp , clean , refreshing , but tasty as well . highly dirnkable , i think drinkable best describes this beer .
smells of tartness , slight earthy malt , slight must , hint of dark citrus , and a hint of alcohol .  mouthfeel was great . this beer went down smooth and easy .

the chocolate/vanilla combo is lovely . t - woody and earthy with some cola . the aroma is top notch . i just do n't taste any of the aroma in the beer .  m - the feel is as smooth as i 've ever had . unbelievably impressive ! the feel of this beer is really what sets it apart from every other dubbel i 've ever sampled .
initial smell is of sweet fresh fruit .  mouthfeel : full side of medium bodied . silky smooth . overall : as always , a beer with a world class mouthfeel is going to be treated kindly by me .

the aroma is huge pineapple . ive never seem so much pineapple in a wild or lambic before . the pineapple dominates , but there are also notes of grapefruit and mineral as well as a light funk . the initial taste is pineapple with a light tartness .  m - this has a medium body and medium carbonation .

on tap @ east village tavern 09-14-08 a- hazy orange or a reddish yellow , the head piles high on the body , creamy , an off white color , s- nose has a big fruit like aroma , bananas , over ripe peaches t-m- start has a decent malt presence , sweet and a bit of hops at the back , top is middling in feel .  mouthfeel is awesome . smooth and slippery with perfect carbonation .

sweet and fragrant . t faint taste of caramel comes through and just barely a hint of the sweetness in the nose . o nose on this brew is very good but the taste lacks a bit .  bready yeast also comes across the nose t : again sweet sugar , yeast , dark fruit like notes of raisin or prune , just a hint of the kirek in the backgorund m : mouthfeel is super smooth . beer has a medium body and nice carbonation . finishes extremely clean .

smells simply amazing - strong tropical fruit , apricot , wheat and pine notes , all swimming in a yeasty funk . tastes as good as it smells . midway , it twists in a tangy direction and the brett really makes its presence felt . good , complex brew . like it ? certainly  m : completely smooth and wonderful . d : very easy to drink .
black with ruby highlights to a light source , a nice creamy tan head , and nice lacing .  a little bit too boozy , but it is incredibly smooth .
smells really good . hope it tastes this good .  luscious creamy mouthfeel .
one word , hops . taste.. very hoppy with flowery notes as well as a nice malt flavor .  mouthfeel was very thick and rich . i almost wanted to chew it .

bottle 11.7 oz 2004 no p 75340 edition poured into tulip-like mc'chouffe glass pours hazy amber/red with a 1/4 '' off white head . a little lacing 7 film that chases down the glass s : huge oaky notes & hints of brandy & vanilla t : warming alcohol & oakyness , then brandy & cherry .  perfect carbonation .

s - very very piney . never smelled anything quite like it .  really a great beer that has it 's hops really balanced , and the silky smooth malt mouthfeel balances wonderfully with bitterness of the hops .
really stong , and just a rich nose in general .  the mouthfeel , on the other hand , is wonderful : creamy , smooth , full-bodied , with moderate yet lively carbonation .
i loved the smell though . i even got another glass and tried it from there just to make sure it was n't the glass .  mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and thick for the style .

a dopplebock that has avoided me so i bought a pack recently . s : all dark fruit and burnt wood . i actually like the smell far more than the taste . t : dark chocolate , raisins and malt .  mouthfeel : nice thick body , very silky smooth texture with a small hop bite .

s - wow -- fantastic aroma . a sweet , malty scent with fresh fruit characteristics . a definite oaky scent here . t - when that oaky scent turns into a flavor it makes a beautifully round beer .  thick chewy mouthfeel that coats the entire tongue and a little burn as it warms .

hop aroma galore ! ! this beer has a nice copperish color a decent size head . the aroma is amazingly floral and zesty hop bitterness .  mouthfeel : best mouthfeel of any wit i 've ever had ; this has the milkshake-thick , smooth mouthfeels i 've heard described as ideal for the style .

this brew has a great smell - dark roasted grains , coffee , and hints of licorice .  full bodied for the style , definitely one of the fullest dipa 's that i 've ever had . nice carbonation levels as well .

the smell is the most reserved of any surly i have had , but very lively for the style . it 's either the pils malt used or the hops contained in this very fresh can . gummy candies right away , this fades revealing a subtle toasty aroma .  very dark with no light coming through and light head n : nose has lots of chocolate and sweet malts and a touch of hops t : starts with lots of chocolate and coffee , some sweet malts but very slight , a touch of hops are prevelant , some oatmeal taste as well , it 's got a sweet earthiness to it which is somewhat unique , a slight bitterness shines through m : it has a velvet feel in the mouth as it slides around , very thick and smooth f : a touch bitterness comes out in the end with the nice stout and oatmeal taste , coffee lingers on the back of the tongue , it has a sweet quality to start but gets drier as it fades and finishes really dry , its got a great smooth feeling in the mouth to go along with the great taste final thoughts : a great stout , it would be great if it was labelled as oatmeal or irish stout since it seems to have qualities of both , but listed as imperial it makes me wonder since its lacking a lot in the hop category .

the hops take the forefront ( as can be expected ) , but the aroma is just well rounded and wonderful . taste : the taste hits initially with a blast of citrusy , earthy , and piny hops . it looked and smelled fantastic .  very smooth and full mouthfeel .

this is the best smelling pumpkin beer i have come across . the beer smells almost exactly like sugary pumpkin pie ( happens to be my favorite pie ) , i have no other way of describing it . this is one hell of a treat for my big nose .  it is very smooth with a nice medium to full body . i was most impressed with the mouthfeel . every part of your mouth will be involved in the feel of this beer as it awakens all your nerves right down your throat .

nice milky caramel nose with hints of roasted malts and vanilla . hoppy , light body does n't feel watery but does n't match atypical barleywine profile .  maybe a peachlike taste in the mix , but honey and herbs are the main ones i sense , mouthfeel- super smooth and low carbonation . very creamy and velvety . nice !

the body is a light amber , clear and showing carbonisation rushing upwards to the full snowy white foaming head .  looks like a stout should , dark and opaque , not quite black , with a slight tan head smells like burned caramel cookies tastes like coffee with the forementioned cookies great mouthfeel , not too chewy i could drink a couple of these

smell has that strong nice balance of rich malts and floral hops . a nice enjoyable hearty ale .  '' the mouthfeel was silky , the body full and the carbonation perfectly soft . enjoyable , but it 's really an american stout contrary to the label at the bar .

damn fine aroma . the flavors of this x-mas brew are subtle compared to the fresh ones i usually enjoy . this one 's got cinamon , ginger , soy sauce , evergreens , sap and fruits ... ..dark fruits . very nice . just a notch down from what i 'm used to .  mouthfeel - full-bodied , velvety smooth , and creamy with a semi-dry finish and moderate carbonation .

aroma is berries , vanilla , and alcohol . taste is really follows the nose , with fruity maltiness upfront , creamy vanilla and barrel notes in the middle , and a warming alcohol close .  m : leaves a nice stickiness that is not overpoweing .

the aroma is a stand-out , a very complex mixture of ripe fruit , tobacco with a hint of smoke , chocolate , molasses , vanilla , brown sugar and various spices . a very nice scottish strong ale and another bottle may give it a better score .  this really has the acidity and fermentation of kombucha tea , giving it a great , crisp mouthfeel .

this poured from the 12 oz bottle with a black , maroon-tinted hue and a nice rolling-hills head of tan froth .  mouthfeel is perfect . smooth and creamy , light carbonation , just absolutly terrific .

aroma is lovely and near perfect for style : brown sugar , burnt sugar , prunes , cloves , stonefruit . taste is much of the same notes as the aroma , but more muted , and less pronounced on the fruit and burnt sugar that makes the aroma so nice .  very creamy and full bodied , perfect carbonation to keep it moving .

aromas are extremely hoppy giving off a piney , resiny , and lightly floral nose . overall what started off to look and smell like a really excellent hoppy brew , finished quite lacking in complexity and left me wanting to drink something else .  medium bodied and oily . simply exceptional .

the aroma is strong and awesome . tons of malts attacking my senses . overall , this is very good . one of the best oak aged ris with tons of bourbon flavor .  velvet mouthfeel ; tongue coating and heavy .
very enticing aroma . t - burnt dark chocolate malt profile , highly bitter . absolutely terrible when served cold , however it did improve significantly as it warmed .  excellent mouthfeel .
pours an opaque black with one finger of frothy mocha head and speckles of sticky lacing on the tulip .  burly , viscous , lusciously dextrinous mouthfeel . outstanding .

reviewed from notes a - poured into a standard pint glass a wonderous midnight black that had a one finger mocha head resulting in massive , massive side lacing .  first thing i notice is how incredibly smooth this beer is - wow ! highlight of this for me was the drinkability - just ridiculously nice mouthfeel .

appearance - amber color , decent size head with some nice lace .  this is really a very good beer : the finish , the mouth feel , the carbonation , the body , are quite exceptional . it 's the taste .
looks good and has one of the best aroma 's i have smelled in while .  m. incredibly smooth .

s - no lie , one of the best aromas on a beer , ever ! tons of resinous , sappy , piney hops along with pineapple , grapefruit and lemon . basically a massive fruit salad of smells ! t - juicy grapefruit and grassy , piney hops meld well with the doughy caramel malts . damn good beer !  the beer looks thick and chewy , but the texture is perfect for a brown ale .

aroma : rich chocolate , roasted malts , mild grassy hops , dusty maltiness , and dark plums taste : strong , bitter malts transition smoothly into a gentle , watery , creamy body that fades into a mild , clean finish with a touch of roasted , bitter malts emerging at the finish .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it is slightly carbed but still rather flat .

the best aspect of it for me is the smell . the aroma is of fresh picked berries and it really pleases the senses . taste wise it kind of suffers on mouthfeel , but being that it 's a lighter style beer it is sort of expected .  super dense , thick , creamy and full bodied .

aroma is of vanilla , vanilla and more vanilla with some burnt coffee there too . i 'd have to say the aroma was the best part of this beer . very sweet and you would be hard pressed to drink more than one of these .  perfect creamy texture and good body and carbonation .

a : pours with a dark ruby-colored body and a large , dense , creamy white head . almost looks like a nitro pour .  feel is very nice - medium bodied with plenty of carbonation . the carbonation makes the beer feel so smooth in the mouth .

the smell is off the hook ... piney hops that just are incredibly inviting . the taste is more subdued , with a mellow citrusy hoppiness that just begs for another sip .  the mouthfeel was medium-to-full , which was amazing for a co2 pour and i even did a double take at the taps just to be sure .

smells of piney , spicy and floral hops , touch of citrus , unbelievably fragrant . tastes of sweet piney like malt with a good spicy backbone . a very pleasant surprise , the nose on this beer is incredible , everything just works together beautifully . not as dry and crisp as a traditional pilsner , but i really enjoyed this interpretation .  very nice .

smells of very very strong pumpkin pie spices and i ca n't pick any other smells out of it even though they may be there .  mouthfeel : light and airy . the perfect match to the flavor profile . well done .

wish it were a bit more pungent , but other than that , very nice ! taste : hmmm ... not really what i was expecting . while the smell was awesome , the other categories seemed to fall a bit short .  the texture is creamy and smooth . the carbonation that provides the ample head is very subdued , giving a solid finish with a beautifully crafted feel . in my estimation , it is close to edmund fitzgerald , which before this , had blown every other porter that i have tried out of the water .

hints of earthiness , brown pear , lemon peel , dark wine , wood , green apple peel , some sweet and sourness , with that wildness of the yeast , an amazing array , quite a scent . it is like a saison on steroids without the barnyard scent , more refined instead . this is unlike any sour i have had , it is pretty sour put it does n't make you cringe , it makes you pucker the mouthfeel and flavor delivery is incredibly smooth . overall an incredibly unique beer that i could only imagine coming out of belgium , it has characteristics of a wheat beer and a sour but takes the fruit level to new heights and is n't too sour .  mouthfeel - very smooth , the wheat is doing its part here . good crispness and medium weight really help enhance the flavors .

the smell is fantastic . it is fruity , chocolatey , toffee , tobacco , cocoa , raisin bread , apricot , plum , and pudding . it 's interesting .  the mouthfeel was amazing , drinking the beer it had the typical bite of aftertaste that normal ipas have , but i took a drink right when we left the pub and i still could taste the hops about twenty minutes later .

s - nice smell , quite sweet , herbal and perfumy , some notes of chocolate . good point : i can not smell the alcohol !  mouthfeel : amazingly prickly carbonation after all this time -- a nice counterpoint to its velvety body .

the smell is very nice , with some chocolate , ripe fruit , vanilla , and strawberry-banana yogurt .  the best part . smooth as butter , no alcohol detected . fantastic beer , the barrel aged version i 'm sure is outstanding .
aroma is raspberry in a big way . a little bit of chocolate and coffee come through as well . overall , a nice beer . not really to my taste , but well done .  a fantastic creamy mouth .

the nose assails you like a jackhammer , but a jackhammer that is fun and hammers little bursts of joy into your head . i was getting raisin and toffee at first , then earth , some malt , roasted meat , cigar tobacco , and english bread pudding . soooo complex ! the palate was disappointing after the amazing aromatics . mainly malts and dark fruit with lingering sweetness .  love the body on this one . on lighter side of moderate , but the oiliness from the hops makes it somewhat slick and the softest carbonation fills it our gloriously .

and for good reason , because this is easily one of the most aromatic beers i 've ever layed nostrils to . i am bombarded by red fruits in the nose , everything from dark cherry to cranberry , envolped in the malt aroma . other than that , it really lacks the complexity the beer exudes in the nose . i feel like the briarpatch ale tries to be something it is not , and unfortunately failed to live up to my expectation .  very smooth and creamy mouthfeel with a nice medium body .

it smells exactly like wisconsin belgian red , no stout scent whatsoever . it is a nice sweet cherry pie scent with a hint of oak . interesting . i like it better than bell 's take of the style .  smooth and creamy body .
it has a great complex aroma of chocolate and coffee and caramel tones .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth and velvety .
fragrant hop aroma . average mouthfeel .  exceptionally creamy mouthfeel , medium body .

quite a unique and pleasing odor . tastes very hoppy , with strong floral hops that give off a spicy taste , piney hops , sweet malt , caramel , grass , flowers , orange peel , grapefruit , apple , brown sugar , pepper and spices .  superb feel .
exceptional looking beer that poured an amber-orange with a big long sustaining head .  very full , creamy body that 's quite impressive for the abv .

s - really like the smell on this one with lots of green apple . lots of bready wheat in here , but this was a letdown from the nose . m - medium bodied with a lot of carbonation , seems fine .  the texture is perfect , though .

a- orange light amber with a huge offwhite head that fades fairly quickly and good overall clarity s- malt ! and lots of it . a sweet fruitiness with mild spice that bowls you over and makes you want to grab some wurst . i kid you not ... this one made me salivate .  the mouthfeel is very much like drinking liquid chocolate or marshmallow fluff . so rich , creamy , and very full in the mouth .

smells very wheaty , but at the same time quite chocolatey . not a very powerful nose but extremely pleasant . taste is actually quite spicy , and while there are hints of that sweet , chocolatey nose , they 're mostly absent here .  mf : silky and smooth but without compromising its thickness , which is needed as a foundation for the abundance of flavour . not too wet or dry , but the perfect balance between . not a unique mouthfeel , but an expressive suitable one .
the smell is quite nice , its a bit yeasty , and smells like raspberries and oranges .  rich and creamy flavor . mouthful is sweet and chocolaty and flavors get strong with more time in mouth .

this beer had some wonderful aromas of scotches , alcohol , fruits , chocolates , and more and it tasted like more of the same . rogue should start making this stuff again .  with thick molasses and velvety feel to balance a bold and alcoholic content , this one hits me with a lingering hoppy bitterness on the finish of strong malt presence . seriously strong , often incapacitating ... but ever deliciously so !
s- fruity , flowery aroma with a hint of yeast .  very rich , creamy mouthfeel is offset by a lightness at the back of the tongue and roof of the mouth .
aroma here is very appetizing , very floral and screaming amarillo . hopped up ipa aroma , nothing out of the ordinary if you grasp that description .  the mouthfeel is great , perfectly coating .
the smell is amazing . really rich chocolates and malts shine with some mild coffee and chocolate liquor .  mouthfeel is perfect .

very impressed . t- similar to the smell , just less strong .  a- black body with a brown creamy head , nice retention and lacing s- chocolate , coffee , roasty t- nice roasty malts , molasses , chocolate , coffee and a bit of hops at the finish m- creamy , full-bodied and velvety smooth d- awesome mouthfeel and complex malts make it great !

the aroma is awesome . a great mix of spices , mainly cinnamon and nutmeg . the actual scent of pumpkin plays only an ancillary role , but that 's fine given how appealing the overall aroma is . pumpkin comes through in the mid-palate , but it 's quite subtle . pretty remarkable that this is an 8 % abv beer . it 's maybe a touch too thin , but still pretty decadent given the sweetness and minimal carb .  great mouth feel it 's carbonated perfectly making this a great beer .

soapy white head that dissipates quickly . s : i expected the grapefruit greeting of the ipa , but my nose was met with citrus combined with tropical fruit , almost a pineapple or mango and hint of floral . t : same blast of citrus and tropicals ; finishes a little bit quickly , without a lot of bitterness or drying , which i missed . a really fantastic beer and a lucky find since i understand hill farmstead is not found much outside of vermont .  mouthfeel is perfect , medium bodied with a champagne silkiness that is delectable when swirled .

thick foam builds on top and slowly recedes it 's quite pungent and fills the local atmosphere with coriander and spicy hops sweet for a witbier ; certainly not dry .  mouthfeel - superbly smooth and creamy , especially due to the carbonation . overall drinkability - this beer is all about the smoothness of the mouthfeel , and inoffensive characters .

the brew was only half way to my nose when i caught a big whiff of pungent and fruity centennial hops reminiscent of apricots . like spotting a beautiful girl from behind , only to have the fantasy ruined as she turns around to reveal her ugly face , the taste of the centennial ipa was a huge disappointment .  mouthfeel : no real aftertaste ( remarkable for a malt-heavy beer ) , carbonation is excellent and it plays well on the palate .
very nice .  abundant flavor , lush , vibrant texture .

nose is strong , intense , dark fruits about to rot which someone spilt port wine upon - wonderful , very interesting . full bodied chewy mouthfeel . i 've no idea what the six herbs and spices are but i applaud the choices , excellent complexity . phenols can be the bane of a belgian , here they are aggressively , exquisitely blended .  m - the best part of this beer .

the smell hits me before i even pick up the glass . foresty hops burst with grapefruit and cedar galore , while a huge balance of luscious amber malts drop notes of caramel-coated apples , peanut toffee , and sugar daddies . slight booziness , too . a big , chewy malt profile piles toffee and caramel upon a toasted nuttiness . an aggressive hopping takes hold mid-palate , dropping raw , leafy hop notes that suggest pine and citrus peel . finish of booze and more hops , with layers of dark fruit and rum all the way down . mouthfeel is thick and somewhat harsh , even for stone 's insane standards . nice carbonation level , but the aggressiveness could stand to be toned down a bit . congrats on unlucky number thirteen , stone , and here 's to 13 more !  much lighter body than the bottle of extra stout i just had ; also a little more tart which was what i was looking for . roasted malts and hard water . mouthfeel is where it really shines . smooth like silk . goes down like water .

s - amazing ! very floral aroma that actually smells like walking through a rose garden . t - the taste is very different from the aroma . it was funky and spicy with a bubblegum flavor . d - this is a very good beer . i loved the aroma with flowers and rose water .  a- very murky , tan head , and faint hints of a red hue on the outer-most parts of the glass s- muted nose , that such of chocolate pop tarts t- marshmellow , chocolate , cocoa , raisen , over ripe cherry and a nice little chunk of bitter bight m- creamy and gorgeous . this beer is awesome .

holy smells this one has a nice nose ! sweet and meaty with burnt caramel and some smokiness . excited to try this .  mouthfeel : creamy smooth medium body with superb carbonation . swallow is velvet . tasty and the mouthfeel is truely a dream . goes down easy when you enjoy slowly .

nose is a conglomeration of aromas , sweet malt , bread dough , port wine , cotton candy , caramel , and spices , clove i think . start has a deep malt sweetness , some alcohol bitterness at the back with the top moderate in feel . magnificent beer , as belgian strong ( s ) are my favorite style , this was a most enjoyable beer .  full body , incredibly velvety smooth feel with silk touches and superbly pleasant on the palate .

not enormous or sinus cleansing or any other adjective such as that , but still absolutely fantastic . the flavor is not quite the blast of hops i anticipated , but it is still nicely bitter and flavorful .  body is smooth , lightly creamy , and beautifully sparkling .
aroma is a rich sweet malt with hints of raisins , plums , figs , port , and brandy and a slight floral hoppiness -- -right on for a barleywine .  mouthfeel is super creamy , milkshake like .
quite inviting . t : rather roasty with strong suggestions of dark chocolate and thick molasses .  m : elegant mouthfeel , the beer is simply not cloying which i was astounded with .
has a pretty deep auburn color with a 1/2 inch head .  the carbonation is perfect . d-very drinkable , my dad and i shared the four pack , would have loved to have more .

the spice aroma is intense : strong clove with hints of cinnamon and nutmeg . its has a complex flavor that is quite delicious , once you get by the initial sourness .  mouthfeel is exceptional and there is nothing objectionable here .
this brew smells awesome . i do n't even want to drink it , the aromatics are so satisfying alone . good stuff .  there is the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .

s : the nose is of pumpkin mix and spice . the smell is hot and estery , like boiling pineapple juice , but this brew does conjure images of fresh pumpkin pie at grandma 's house . then , suddenly and overpoweringly , comes the hotness from the alcohol . very tasty , but the bitterness of the hops will cloud my palate , the 11 % alcohol is going to blur my vision , and the fusels are going to give me a nasty headache in the morning .  smell : malt , coffee , alcohol , & toasted grains taste : toasted grains , licorice , coffee , bitter choclate , and hops bittereness in the tounge mouthfeel : damn , talk about smooth , great balance and carbonation .

the smell is very nice and very much in line with what you 'd expect from a solid hefe : sweet citrus fruit , a bit of spice and wheat are all prevelent and seemingly well balanced thusfar . while bold yet standard scents were detected , the flavour is less aggressive while remaining very basic for the style . good nontheless though .  incredibly smooth , despite lingering bitterness .
the aggressive butterscotch toffee plum nose is nice and it 's mirrored in the taste ! !  feels great . 5/5 d : yes , for the style and abv , it is .

s- there is a rich perfumed caramel malt flows even during the pour with a cream note and a dark malt hint adds depth to this rich aroma . t- the dry toasted malt has a faint caramel note with a soft bitter hint in the finish with a slight sweetness . d- this amazing aroma is wonderful but the taste just does n't follow through with the same richness and depth .  mouthfeel : excellent . thick yet balanced with the carbination .

smells great . a whole lot of spices , mostly nutmeg and brown sugar . i wish it tasted as good as it smelled .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy and everything i could ask for . the tartness keeps pulling you in like a siren , and i am totally captivated by her song .

s ~ a good dose of coco , chocolate syrup , hint of vanilla in there ... t ~ bitter chocolate ... .dry on the back ... lingering flavors of coco that stay behind well after the sip is gone m ~ lighter to medium bodied bock ... i like my chocolate beers thick and rich - s. tier chokolat ... this was a random bottle i picked up.. o ~ not bad ... i remember the hype behind the beer a year or two ago when it was in the bigger bottles for $ 15 per..glad i did n't buy one then and held out for the $ 1 something 12 ozer ... worth a try..but nothing super special..  the mouthfeel is unlike anything i can recall in recent memory . such a thick creamy texture like i 'm drinking thickness of marshmallow cream with the weight of a large marble .

smells of sweet and doughy , much like pastries that delightfully reminds me of westvleteren , but it reminds me a lot of a creamy lager . nice . theres also a sweet marshmallow and peach beneath .  nice creamy mouthfeel , thick and pleasant and well balanced flavors of sherry , burnt carmel , toffee , roasted bananas and ripe stone fruit with hints of walnuts .
all these flavors and more really hit your nose as well . wow .  the beer featured a very pleasing and creamy mouthfeel .

pine tree , but somehow a more pure pine scent then a standard ipa . t - started really unique but eventually all i was tasting was this overpowering pine taste .  mouthfeel is very nice , i enjoyed it a lot .

delicious ! raisins and coffee ... apparently i poured this waay too cold ... first sip is a slap of roasted bitterness and nothing else , almost astringently ... just ... never mind . much better as she warms . yeah , as it warms some chocolate notes start showing up in the nose , and the flavor mellows out and gets a bit of a mocha hint to it ... but it 's not big enough , the bitterness is still sharp , not as smooth or well-rounded as i would like .  the mouthfeel is wonderful for a beer that is this bitter .

mmmm ... coffee , mmmmm ... . the lace is definitely forming in rings to my glass here , pretty good head retention for something with whole mexican coffee beans . i heard it 's really hard to pull off , the aroma here is primarily in your face eye opener of coffee beans , a whiff of chocolate tones , dark roasts , and a very light hop aroma is hidden in there . the aroma is the best thing this beer 's got going for it .  m - perfect mouthfeel .

nice robust smell for this style : light cappuccino notes , with burnt sugar and whole-grain bread notes in there . the sugar and bread flavors that were promised by the smell are there , but they play a background role .  mouthfeel this is real good for an ipa or dipa , pretty full and creamy , enough heft to match the zip and zing of the hops hopslam also wins for aftertaste which has a long linger yet is not too strong .

the aroma was fantastically oaky and potent . sour cherry notes came through strong . tart , funky and somewhat acidic with a trailing , brown sugar-like sweetness . monomoy kriek drank like a dream . cisco brewers have really stepped to the plate with their woods series .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

the nose is close to downright slutty , piling on the coffee roast , semi-sweet dark chocolate , caramel , butterscotch , pecan , cool whip as well as raisin , fig , cherry , apricot fruit , in turn brings yeast , mineral water , pine tar , white pepper and a good shock of herbaceousness . unassuming complexity , each individual flavor is deep and resonant and plays well with others .  this coats the palate with a burbon goodness . just the right amount of carbonation .
wonderful . t : slightly sweetnened grapefruit , a touch of spiciness , and a bit of spearmint on the finish .  the texture was excellent , not too thick or thin .

the smell had all the lovely malt of a red and the lovely hops of an ipa , and they were more than the sum of their parts .  a - golden crystal-clear , the way a pilsener should look ; frothy , dense head with sticky lacing ; tons of carbonation s - fairly underwhelming ; from what 's there , detect dry-hop and sweet-malt presence t - dry , bitter hops at first ; gives way to sweet malt flavor , with just a touch of creaminess m - light and creamy ; delicious ! d - so easy , like throwing back bud light ; i could easily down 5-8 of these

poured ~4c into a fluted glass . a : copper and hazy with a nice white head and gorgeous lacing .  ( m ) mouthfeel is balanced and superb : substantial enough to linger on the palate without being too heavy . it 's very smooth due to the subdued carbonation yet there is a slight alcohol warming sensation - which i do n't mind at all .

but this beer , the bouquet is fantastic ! and let me set this straight , `` bouquet '' is not a word i use normally but this beer has brought me to a place where `` bouquet '' was the word i needed to use to get my point across .  the body is perfect . honestly .

lots of candied fruit smells and heavy , yeasty dough-like nuances . taste is pretty sweet with plenty of fruit and bread dough , and then a really aggressive alcohol punch .  3.5 m big thick beer , very heavy on the tongue . really nice .

beautiful perfumed floral , spiced , orange and fresh peach assertive nose . mouthfeel is creamy and seemingly rich but with no character .  silky smooth and creamy mouth feel . such body without being cloying .

a : dark cloudy orange , decent head , decent carbonation ; lacing is n't bad s : floral bouquet , very hoppy ( pleasantly so ) , much in line with the style t : tinny right at the front , but moves quickly to a decent ipa-style -- floral , bitter , hoppy ; but the metallic notes linger , unfortunately ; the alcohol is blended rather nicely ; were i given this without being told its style i would have guessed straight up ipa . the main detraction for me is the metallic notes , which i 've detected in other saranacs too , some more than others .  huge taste and mouthfeel . lots of bitter hot chocolate taste and viscous almost chewy feel to it .
nice hop aroma , similar to what i remember when having this on tap in heldsberg . nice bittering , very good ipa , but not very drinkable .  m ) rich , almost slick . rich , long mouth coating .

finally , an american w-bock that nails the nose ! mega bananas and mad cloves , bro ! some chocolate , but takes a backseat . mmmmm , flavor is damn tasty as well .  clean warm finish m- syrupy full mouthfeel , creamy and warm d- i 'd be great having one every night in the winter
strong and funky aroma . tasty , funky , unique dipa , price hurts though ...  mouthfeel - perfect , the creaminess remains with a twinge of bitter , very hearty and drinks like a filling snack .
great smell , but the taste was a little lacking for me .  the mouthfeel is great . what a light and delicate brew .
3.0 d : great aroma , but the taste and mouthfeel simply are n't up to par .  mouthfeel was great , smooth .

the aroma is very nice , with a solid maltiness and caramel balanced by a light citrusy hop .  perfect mouthfeel for an ipa.. substatial , chewy but not syrupy.. drinkable but nowhere near being called 'light ' .
it smelled wonderful . very sweet and aromatic , almost sour . it tastes pretty good too .  the mouthfeel was awesome . just perfect subtle carbonation .

this stuff smells like a friggin ' pine tree ! it 's head remains for quite a respectable amount of time . it 's definitely a red chocolate color . it 's absolutely uncanny how much this smells and tastes like a pine tree .  wonderful body .
the nose is awesome - filled with all sorts of bourbon goodness - especially vanilla & charred oak . very unique idea , that somehow falls short .  perfect mouthfeel , actually .

s : very hoppy - i also smell pineapple and citrus . very inviting ! t : great taste .  the body is amazing and really makes this beer absolutely stunning to go along with its big hoppy flavors . it 's oily , greasy , beefy , big bodied , and largely bold , with a crunchy , grabbing , snappy , zip line long bittering tone of a ton of orange oils and pine oils .

rose petals , mangos . lot 's of floral and tropical aromas ( not citrus though ) . this is not the beer that i 've come to expect as a double ipa . with that said it 's a very good beer that exemplifies the uniques of dogfish head . this is not a hop bomb , but is a very flavorful and complex beer . brown sugar , vanilla , and biscuity flavors lead to a very pleasant fruity finish . mango .  good , creamy body with a low-medium carbonation is very nice for a ba imperial stout that is not overly sweet .

a - get a lot of caramel sweetness , touches of cinnamon , hoppy scents are there and i now i know i let this one sit too long , or maybe the faded hops have really let the malts come through . o - decent brew but the complex aroma led me to high hopes the taste did n't match to my surprise , with that being said i know this isnt the most fresh offering so ill take that into consideration .  m - very creamy . just a small sip seems to coat the inside of the mouth very well .
the smell of this beer is heavy on the malt side , and light on the hops . as far as scotch ales go its very flavorful , with a pronounced coffee taste mixed with dark roast .  loving the mouthfeel .

smells fantastic . sweet and juicy tart cherries . nice . smells a lot like ng wisconsin belgian red .  incredibly easy-drinking and gentle on the tongue . the penultimate english pale mouthfeel . there is so much to love : subtle and well-rounded , both quenching and engaging , plus the mouthfeel is impeccable . i feel foolish for not having tried this sooner .

s : dried tropical fruits ( papaya ? apricot ? ) up front , raisin and dark rum underneath ... possibly a hint of vanilla . one of the most complex aromas of any stout i 've had .  the mouthfeel is perfect -like a cloud in the mouth , and i could no doubt doubt drink this all night..especially in a tiny village with some locals by the fire in a 17th century pub ... .what a treat .

reviewed from notes . 55f $ 7.99 / ea . s : powerful vanilla , caramel , and coffee notes . the scent is rich and thick . a : clear dark brown body with a small creamy head that dissipates quickly leaving little to no lacing and a wispy cover . large amounts of residual sugar leaves legs upon swirling . t : again , a powerful vanilla coffee flavor with hints of sweet caramel and toffee . a lot like a fancy iced coffee . hop flavors are subdued and only make a brief appearance at the very end .  mouthfeel is smooth and velvety with carbonation perceivable at the very end of the swill .

nose is gorgeous vanilla and whiskey , with a nice tart cherry sharpness and a hint of caramel sweetness . still , pleasant . mouthfeel is lightly carbonated , bit crisp , syrupy .  the mouthfeel is almost the best part of the ale . full and velvety .

s - smell is by far the best feature of this beer . a nice piney , peppery , smell hits you as soon as you pop the cap . d - well , this beer is super drinkable , every day of the year . hot , cold , in-between , it does n't matter ... it 's smooth , refreshing , and smells awesome ! !  silky smooth , nice carbonation , and thin enough to drink a few of , but not so thick as to let you notice the 7.4 % .
smell is really nice . toasty nutty malts and a blast of cascadey hops .  m : the carbonation is gentle , making for a perfect silky , but thick , body .
huge sour aroma of lemons and green apples taht really leaps out at you .  the body and finish are absolutely luscious considering this is a 4.5 % abv j-beer out of a can .

the aroma is sweet and inviting , very nice aroma . the sweetmalt is there in the front but a bold/robust roasty flavor powers through to the front of this brew .  mouthfeel is where this beer delights ! so smooth and round , you want to swirl it around in your mouth ! mmmm .

smell is big and complex , much improved from the younger beers in the series . sumptuous creamy chocolate , sherry , vanilla , peaty smoke and oak . mmmm ... . earthy dryness in the finish .  mouthfeel is really exceptionally creamy and smooth . it 's full bodied , oily and just exceptional on the tongue .

smell is sweet and very fruity , scents of fig , apple , tobacco brown sugar , rum , brandy , raisins , and dates . extremely complex , too much really , it is like a mouth full of fruit juice concentrate .  also was surprised by how creamy this went down . this is a pleasure on the tongue .
the aroma is of delicious coffee and chocolate flavors .  its well carbonated , and very smooth . however , i found the beer very interesting solely on the smooth mouth .

smell is nice , very barleywine/old ale like , raisins/figs , toffee , bread , sweet malt , almost smells like a lighter thomas hardys , spicy alcohol . taste is sweet , bready , lots of yeast , citrus , raisin , caramel , bread , not as rich as aroma , apples , not as exciting as the aroma .  extremely smooth , like mink or sable .
beautiful malt nose . man i love it . subtle notes of german hops as well .  mouthfeel : omigaw , it 's so creamy . so very , very creamy . `` luscious '' is the word that comes to mind .
aroma is delightful -- floral , hoppy , with notes of sweet grass and rum .  mouthfeel/drinkability- the mouthfeel is absolutely stunning , slick and smooth with the perfect level of effervescence .

smell - 5.0 powerful and very , very nice . smells of liquor soaked figs , overripe plums , aged port , damp wood and burnt sugar .  its thick and syrupy and full of body and character . the alcohol warmth is soothing as it makes its way to the back of the tongue , leaving a sweet resin .

smell : lots of coffee and chocolate , plus a creamy character which almost makes this thing smell like a frappuccino . quite appealing ! drinkability : after the smell , i was really looking forward to having this beer again . if they really can make it taste as good as it smells ( which i seem to remember from lo those many moons ago ) , this would be one of my favorite beers .  m : silky smooth . wow i am impressed with the smoothness of the beer .
smells super hoppy , with notes of christmas tree .  the mouthfeel is perfect for a doppelbock .

the nose is fantastic . caramel , oak , with touches of coffee and chocolate .  first sip reveals a rich and firmly textured beer of elegant character . an encore presence by the hops closes out the taste in a long and seamless finish . faultless balance , beautiful complexity both in the nose and on the tongue make this beer , in my opinion , a perfect desert beer or soothing winter warmer .

lots of leather and clove in the aroma . mothballs . honey flavours but not very sweet . lovely dry finish . brett is the showcase here , along with some noble dry-hop . very nice and worth trying .  feel is thick and creamy , with a light carbonation of fine bubbles that help give it a velvety character to it . this is a damn fine beer .
very nice . it appears slightly cloudy with particulate floating , yet just dark yellow enough to say this is not like the others .  actually a very good mouthfeel , for this style .

s : citrus , very bright ! spicy yeast , apple and pear cider smell , some nutmeg .  the mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and coating , leading to an extended finish that eventually coaxes out some espresso and a final touch of nuttiness .

s- strong citrus , grapefruit and lemon . pine and floral notes also come through . this is an amazingly hoppy beer with just enough sweet malt to give it a nice depth and complexity .  body is refreshing yet almost full in its thickness and rich , creamy carbonation . overall it 's damn delicious and a great collaboration ; no surprise that there 's yet another beer with the dogfish head logo on it that i love .

nothing nearly so exotic , though . smell was also similar , sharp and spicy , cloves and nutmeg .  rich and textured in my mouth , i really enjoyed this beer , but would n't be able to handle more than 1 in a setting .

fresh herbs and attitude .  dark coffee , bittersweet chocolate , toffee , dark wheat bread , smoke , spices that are tough to identify but clearly at work ... all mingled together in perfect measure . super smooth and velvety , although not what i would call creamy . largely because the body is n't a heavy one , but this texture comes with a terrific caress that does not leave me wanting .

big aroma of spearmint , grapefruit , lime zest , and wild flowers from the hops ... hint of bready caramel malt and esters in the back . hoppy after taste with a fume of alcohol . this beer has a full on grasp of the style , a great beer all around .  moderate carbonation with a strong sticky pine aftertaste make it very very enjoyable . very strong , flavorful , and pleasant .

the aroma is dry and roasty with a good mix of chocolate and coffee . lightly nutty also it smells quite inviting . the taste is a bit of a letdown though .  m- super creamy and smooth . the carbonation level is perfect . a nice clean and crisp aftertaste .

damn this is a good ipa . lots of citrus and flower with a hint of grain coming thru . t - nice full bodied ipa with tons of hop character . more towards the bitter side of ipas but its just what the doctor ordered .  full , fluffy body .

smell : this one has a fantastic scent to it . i 'm not sure if a brown ale could smell better than this . it 's very tasty and the smell is superb . nicely complex but still would make a fantastic session brew .  m - i had it on tap , carbonation was perfect . a refreshing balanced beer .

smell- wow . i would venture to say that this beer showcases hops better than any other beer i 've ever had . oh , and again with the honey . taste- again ... wow . weird for a dipa , but very very good and interesting , as they remain just whispers in the background . mouthfeel- simply superb .  m : creamy , milkshake like , full-bodied , spot on carbonation , very well done .

the smell is floral , piney , citrusy hops , all go well with the yosemite valley setting . the hops are earthy and piney tasting , but the taste also has a toasty and nutty sweet caramel malt that is very appealing .  body and carbonation are excellent for style .

black licorice notes hit the nose at first with a slight medicinal value . very sweet , very fruity , and very bready . orange , banana , tropical notes . the strong scent of alcohol might suggest a rumcake ? ! this bad boy is thick and full-bodied .  unbelievable smoothness , with a slight bite .

huge hop aroma . smells like an ipa . tastes of hop bitterness and malty crystal sweetness . in general i really like over hopped red ales , they 're much more interesting than the usual malty , sweet and boring brewpub reds . i had low expectations for this beer and was pleasantly surprised .  mouthfeel is perfect , goose island is the best of the best in this regard .

bottle poured into a 25 ml pilsner glass ( not all at once ) a : medium copper color with a thin head and subtle lacing that soon disappears s : sweet dark fruit and gentle pine hops mixed with doughy notes t : solid roasted maltiness and hop finish - slightly medicinal and somewhat more bitter than the smell would indicate m : sharp edge with mild carbonation and serious alcohol presence d : i was only planning to have this one , and i do n't regret that decision .  mouthfeel is stunning . thick mouthfeel , but super creamy ... like a properly done oatmeal stout .

no real lacing but it does have some legs smell : smell is decadent ; probably one of the best smelling non-sour beers i have encountered . overall/drinkability : one of the best-smelling non-sour beers i have encountered , but the high abv and hugeness of it really detracts .  mouthfeel is rich , smooth , and silky . soft carbonation .

poured a 12 ounce bottle in a snifter a : black , brown frothy head s : coffee , bittersweet choclate , a hint of heavy cream , malt t : toffee , roasted malt , coffee , chocolate , cream , the bitterness is sharp and nicely balanced between roasted malts and hops .  mouthfeel - creamy , silky smooth . fine , vigorous carbonation .
it 's the smell that 's the stunner on this one . absolutely gorgeous aroma ; one the best-smelling beers i 've come across .  m - perfection , i love the way this feels .

big nose , filled with charleston chew chocolaty filling and some dark plum pudding . nice ... very nice . has a light , airy feel when drinking it , very creamily meringue like . i dont get a whole bunch of rich , yeasty esters but it still maintains a nice complex profile .  very nice on the palate a very full and pleasing mouthfeel .

upon opening , the wonderful aroma of raspberries hits you .  pours a rich crimson color with a creamy off white head that stays put thru out the duration of drinking it , deep caramel aromas along with some milk chocolate quite sweet.absolutely sublime creamy mouthfeel just glides down smooth , flavors of caramel and brown suger hit ya up front but there is a decent dryness midway keeping it from getting to sweet.i wouldnt say earthy maybey more herbal in the finish , its quite heavy a one or two and done for me.this is a doozy a great winter beer , it would real warm ya up , not that i need that down here in nc .

s : smell is very prominent amarillo hops ... i love amarillo 's ! very citrusy smelling ! ! also smells bready and slightly earthy . d : very nice hoppy example of a red ... i love this beer !  f : rich as hell , and creamy . head is pillowy , with good retention . d : damn good , gets better and better as it opens up . admittedly it 's a completely different beer , completely roast obsessed , but still ... raspy is better , and cheaper ... and that 's really the bar for a ris , in my humble opinion .

the smell was intoxicating . the nose on this beer was by far the best part of the experience . malts were most present with the taste of coffee and bitter chocolate . all in all it was enjoyable but i have had far better barleywines before .  love the feel in my mouth .

i sat and smelled this beast for a good 5 minutes . taste follows the smell with the vanilla upfront leading to the oaked bourbon finish . was expecting more bourbon on this one , but still very nice . silky smooth mouthfeel will definite traces of the alcohol , but that 's what is expected . made a trip out today with the girlfriend just to get away from home and am pleasantly surprised to find they tapped a keg today .  m : the feel is incredibly creamy and medium bodied . one of the nicest bodies on an oatmeal stout i have ever had .
smell is awesome with a hint of sweet malty carmel , coffee and anise .  excellent mouth feel as this is full , creamy and smooth not too much more can be asked from a brew like this .

the nose is a wonderful fruity hop blast .  mouthfeel/drinkability- silky , soft , and seafoamy ... the texture in the mouth is liquid perfection , beginning very smooth and quickly gaining subtle carbonation that just hangs right in there for the duration . a wonderfully simple , yet complex beer that needs to become available in north jersey soon .

a : pours a deep golden brown with a decent head that very much clings to the glass s : obviously coffee shines through in this one . also a sweet malty punch at the end . very nice , especially if you 're a coffee drinker t : a classic brown ale with a mellow coffee layer that lingers throughout m : bitter , dry , slightly acidic d : all day , all night . i second the idea of victory putting this one into a bottle .  the real beauty of this beer is in the mouthfeel . it is full and lush - velvety and slick . could n't ask for better .

hugely complex , endlessly amazing . t : sweet sweet sweet . brown sugar , caramel , toffee , bourbon , vanilla , and booze . a bit more heft would have made this a truly spectacular dessert beer , easily the equal of a fine port or sherry .  mouthfeel : medium body with colossal carbonation make this an incredibly creamy beer . de dolle gets this perfect for me yet again .

s- a lot going on here , sweet , spicy oranges and other citrus , light floral hops , lightly vinous , dried light colored fruits ( apricots and figs ) , alcohol shows slowly as it warms . m- creamy , medium-heavy body , good carbonation .  m ~ refreshing and spirited mouthfeel . truly exceptional .

aroma is huge coffee with some vodka and vanilla , overall very strong and wonderful . flavor is again coffee , alcohol , and vanilla .  m - light carbonation and rich mouthfeel . a very fine dopplebock in mouthfeel d - although i 'm sensing some alcohol the sweetness takes this thing home .

s : very nice orange cream like notes with some crystal malt with a touch of hops . t : good balance with the amber malt , piney hops and orange peel .  a very smooth and creamy cask ale , that goes down very well .

what a nose ... huge espresso , black currant , dark chocolate ... and that special , unique character that brings to mind the dark lord itself . a beast of an aroma . taste- bittersweet chocolate and the roastiest of malts , with a robust backbone that carries all the flavor throughout the mouth ... the finishing hop blast lingers on for days . mouthfeel/drinkability- thin and easy like a true ids , but not nearly as impressive as compared with the massive head , nose , and taste . it would be easier drinkin ' if the ingredients were downplayed , but then where 's the fun ? this was a real treat to sample , and at 5.25 % i ca n't believe this lasted for 2 years in the cellar . another sheer pleasure from three floyds that deserves praise for its incredible character .  very smooth . the lubricious mouthfeel enhances the drinkability ( for a barleywine . ) i love the combination of chinook hops and caramel and munich malts .

s : pine , soft citrus , christmas spruce/fir , grapefruit , smells a lot like the inside of a christmas tree , wonderful . t : piney definitely , this is the dominant flavor , some soft grapefruit , and citrus , and a little too much ethanol in the end for my tastes , but overall very good .  palate : full bodied and medium carbonation . great feel . full bodied and enjoyable .
holly hallelujah , this is hoppy . i love the hops , been known to eat 'em raw .  mouth- full , creamy mouthfeel . fine carb .

fantastic `` fantome '' nose of barnyard funk , sour , honey , dandilions and unripe peaches and a heavy nose of corn tortilla ( yeast ) . flavors are sour , bitter apple and while assertive somehow thin and not particularly appealing .  m - has a lovely and distinctive soft quality .

the nose is huge . heavenly hops aromas of pine , citrus and resin and backed up by a malt backbone that miraculously isnt completely shut out by the monster hops . fabulous . the taste follows suit with more of the same balance between the two heavyweights . however it almost met up to my expectations , i think mostly because of its fantastic aroma and great balance . im not sure if id consider this one of the best dipas in the world , but it certainly was an enjoyable experience that brought a smile to my face .  carbonation feels perfect . this beer is also easy to drink .

smells ( i was smelling this the moment i was pouring it out ... . big and powerfull nose , that is mainly fruity . i 'm definately liking this so far . tastes of sweets , chocolate and carmel , and fruits , raisins mainly . this beer had such a great nose to it , i was sure i 'd be getting something great from sprecher .  very smooth , almost velvety mouthfeel . excellent brew , but the 8.4 oz bottle is entirely too small .
i do not find the beer to be as tasty as the nose indicates , but it is still a damn fine pumpkin ale .  just perfect . this is one of the better stouts that weyerbacher has done .

the cascade show that follows is always a treat , and the resulting head sits forever ... literally ... a half-inch thick on the surface . looks like a guinness , you could 've fooled me .  velvety and soft-spoken , yet deeply sexy . more to the traditional side .

the aroma was amazingly complex , with sour cherries and bread-dough , plum , ( maybe some raisin ? ) and mild malt . the taste was focused on sour cherries and mild roasted malts , chocolate and alcohol . overall a fantastic beer , and a great surprise .  biscuity sweetness , a boisterous alcohol presenece , and nearly perfect on the palate ... a little too expensive to drink on any sort of regular basis , but quite a treasure if you find it somewhere .
smell : very strong . alcohol up front with nice raisins and molassas and a bit of sweetness .  extremely thick mouthfeel .

nice malted caramel , really liked the smell . whould i buy it again : yes would i recommend it to a friend : yes would i drink it if i was offered at a party : absolutely overall : very good second review a - nice amber color s - smell is nice , but similar to package malt extract .  the body is just about right , medium , with a smooth as satin mouthfeel .

one wiff of this garden-like beer will smack you with hops , with a touch of ginger scent in there . spicy hops .  body is rich , creamy , smooth , and damn near perfect . another excellent offering from d'achouffe .

smell oh hoppy goodness . this was honestly the first thing that i noticed when i poured , the aroma really came through strong . taste lively green hops are dominant .  mouthfeel : exceptional . creamy and syrupy with an intense peppery hop finish .
very nice complex , yet clean nose .  mouthfeel is very rich and full , nice amount of carbonation .

the smell was fantastic . strong piney hops and woody resin . i would not turn this one down due to the wonderful nose .  m : probably the crowning achievement of this brew . perfect carbonation and a nice smooth feel .

smell , now this is where it gets interesting . honey , apricot , cherry , and grape . this almost seems like a wine , very different . i just do n't know where the 9 % abv is ? i had a tough time just finishing this one , not because it was n't enjoyable , just because it was so sweet .  m : incredible bitterness that lingers , with a great crisp carbonation and bone dry .

seriously sexy looking beer .  mouthfeel is creamy and exceptionally full , yet really heavy , on the lighter side , and very soft . mouthfeel was clearly the biggest beneficiary of the addition of the bivalves .

bottle purchased at julio 's liquors , westboro , ma poured a somewhat hazy , light straw with a huge , five-finger bubbly head . the resulting chunks of froth eventually faded to a dollop of foam in the middle of the glass , which lasted for most of the drink . tons of bubbly , sticking lacing throughout .  mouth on this one is perfection . somehow light and airy despite the thickness .

s- i can smell this all night . crust comes through a ton , making this a pumpkin pie beer , instead of just pumpkin . pumpkin , spice , vanilla are all prominent as well . t- not quite as nice as the smell , but still great . cinnamon , vanilla , clove , ginger , pie crust , and oh yeah ... pumpkin ! o- this is most likely the best pumpkin beer i 've had . it 's not for the sugar-wary though , but if you have a sweet tooth , ( i usually do n't ) this is a perfect beer for you .  mouthfeel/drinkability : this beer feels pretty creamy in the mouth , and is just a touch heavier bodied than i expected , actually . excellent .

there it is in my glass , billowing foam , crystal clear and straw colour . i anticipate great things , but bring to my nose and can smell only sweet bready malt and a vague floral hoppiness .  it was lush , creamy , smooth , rich , decadant and full . a very full bodied stout with a low carbonation .
big notes of sweet and sour bread , light fruits , yeast and spice drift to the nose .  an absolutely fantastic mouthfeel .

s : one of the best ipa aromas around with tropical fruit hoppiness of mango , pineapple , and passionfruit , coupled with pine resin and floral notes . pale malt with a little medium crystal sneaks in there to provide a little resistance to hop deluge .  gorgeous mouthfeel .

glass : snifter temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees pours a very , very dark , golden brown . the first scent to hit me is 'dutch style ' chocolate milk . very good milk chocolate sweetness .  the mouthfeel is very silky with no aftertaste .
pours black with a big , fluffy brown head that is slow to dissipate . looks rich and forboding at the same time .  still it is very full bodied .
the odour is lovely . rich malt , milk chocolate , slightly burned grains , alcohol , sweet-bitter citrus , candy .  the mouthfeel is wonderful . silky smooth .

this beer almost goes over the top with spices - but holds back just enough . cinnamon and nutmeg blast out of the malt - like they stuffed a mincemeat pie into the bottle . must be brewed by little elves at the north pole . one bottle at a sitting is all i care for of this beer , but this is a great change of pace - ho ho ho !  goes down incredibly easy with a silky mouthfeel .

aroma is terrific , a sweet , nutty , milky thing with a huge roasted leaning , but not at all burnt . the lactic element from the aroma takes a back seat in the flavor , but still manages to appear , taking on a mellow sweetness like steamed milk .  this is a tasty beer ... m - a good thick and creamy full bodied beer ... d - a little expensive for my liking ; however , definitely something worth picking up if you have n't tried one before .

absolutely beautiful . it was heavier in my mouth then i thought it would be , which cuts down a bit on the drinkability , but still good for two or three pints probably .  smooth on the way down and a very dry finish . this stuff is heavy and good .

immense aromas of alcohol , vanilla , burnt malts , woody hints like oak , dark chocolate . overall , this was an intense beer for me and it had some great qualities .  very low carbonation contributes to the smooth feel . full bodied , minty , earthy finish . satisfying sipper from skilled craft brewers .

aroma has a tone of citrus and tropical fruit notes with big loads of caramel , a really nice brew that i could sit with and smell for the enjoyment . there 's grapefruit , pine , and earthy goodness in the hops here . overall i really enjoyed it the hop oils due coat the palate and carbonation worked well for the style .  feels like heaven in my mouth ; it 's silky with an appropriate yeasty zing .
smell : great aroma !  thick smooth mouthfeel , very silky .

warm & deep dark chocolate smell , nutty & coffee-like and very thick in aroma . surprisingly light in flavor compared to the smell , so it does a better job decorating your nose than your mouth .  m : incredibly smooth and creamy .
smells delicious . a little bit of citrus , lots of tropical fruit .  the mouthfeel was perfect , i kept swishing it around my mouth on every drink .

huge aromas of buttery nuts , woody breadiness , creamy sweetness and an overall strong aroma that is just beautiful . heavenly smells and a creamy character that is drool-inducing . a relatively relaxed brew , honestly , despite it 's blue-blood title . intriguing and unique , to say the least . spritzy would n't fit here .  love it.5.0 d fair plus drinkability as this is a huge beer , one that i could probably only have one of .

slight hint of malt , too . great , great ipa aroma ! taste is similar to the aroma with a bit more malt and a bit less assertive hop flavor than was present in the aroma .  the mouthfeel i think is perfect for the style .
the aroma is nice and fruity with an added floral essence .  mouthfeel is incredible , maybe an even better quality than the taste .

smells luscious and pineappley with a hint of coconut .  ( m ) - great carbonation level & balance . very smooth going down . sweet & rich but is balanced with nice lemon citrus plus a nice wheat-like neutrality .
nice reddish amber color that had huge aroma of berries . awesome tart raspberry flavor accompanied with the burn from the alcohol .  the mouthfeel is exceptional . nice and thick tasting .

this beer has a great aroma and then lets you down big time . nice golden color and pretty white , billowy head and nice lace .  i honestly would think this a stout or porter , rather than a bsda ... m : this is soo smooth and nicely full bodied , its literally coats your mouth , and leaves your mouth wanting another sip , just perfect ... d : well this beer is still a little hot , a year or two would make this even better .

this beer smells absolutely amazing once the cap is off . it pours a nice dark stout body , with a nice tan head . the first sip of this beer is really overtaken by the aroma . definitely serving it at 42 like described is a good idea .  mouthfeel great creamy thick milkshake like mouthfeel with medium-light carbonation .

it 's a great , thick , luxurious smell . thaste is much the same , but the burned malt/coffee flavor blanketed by cloying sweet/sour taste .  very tasty indeed mouthfeel was very alive great carbonation with it 's light in the ass body and a very easy drinkability can enjoy anytime of the year .

aromas of sour fruity esters and spicy yeast , and a light caramel malty , actually quite tasty smelling . good carbonation and a crisp , dry and smooth lightish bodied mouthfeel .  mouthfeel is wonderful . creamy with smooth carbonation .

estimated at 200 c purchased at : super saver pennington , nj for $ 3.00 aroma : amazing , chocolate , syrup , heather . visuals : beautiful design , deep brown , mostly opaque , thin white head , little lace . overall : a real disappointment , more of a brown ale than an imperial stout , not a repeat , not a favorite , little value , medium craft .  the carbonation is spot on , it carries the beer extremely well on the palette . this drinks like a slightly hopped up brit but not so much to kill you with hops .
it looked like autumn in a glass , with the color of pumpkin and a massive creamy tan head .  thick and chewy with all the perfect elements . the real stand out for me was the mouthfeel .
it has a lovely , sweet cherry smell .  mouthfeel is top notch , so smooth and light yet complex at the same time .
s : fantastic big malt t : american sweet malt , the hops have faded substantially , to be expected , slight caramel .  very smooth feel to this brew overall .

very unappealing color smell : wonderful grassy , earthy , and piney hops . very aromatic . taste : hops aggressive .  had a nice , velvety texture that reminded me somewhat of trappist ale , but without the bite of alcohol you would encounter .

smell : the most varied mix of spices as i have ever smelled ... you got mint , ground pepper , basil , thyme , lavander , cloves , it 's like he emptied his spice rack in there ! unbelievable stuff . taste : pretty complex , quite heavy on the spices .  mouthfeel is the creamiest thing i have ever tasted . ridiculous full body and amazing texture to this beer .

nose left no doubt as to the presence of peaches from nearby heller 's orchard , just down river . finish had a great tartness that was reminiscent of lindemann 's . yummy .  great mouth feel and easy drinking , starts and ends dry ( without being bitter ) , but gives up a fair amount of sweetness in the middle .
definitely some nice , big bourbon on the nose , with rich dark chocolate , tobacco , plums , and figs . good nose . flavor is big , rich , and decadent .  felt great , and was easy to drink .
it smells of donut-topping sweet huckleberry fruit , and creamy malt - very reminiscent of the huckleberry ice cream i had somewhere on that trip .  nice mouthfeel of solid carbonation .

aromas are incredible with this one ! rich medium-body with smooth texture and finish . overall , a very well crafted porter . extremely complex and delicious . will definetly be looking for this one again .  m - very creamy ; a superb feel .

the smell was my favorite part of the brew . lots of vanillia sweetness up front blending nicely with dark rich coffee and dark chocolate . taste was much like the smell . the vanillia added a sweetness to it that i really enjoyed . great balance though with the coffee slick mouthfeel , full bodied  m - fantastic . perfect amount of carbonation , just enough to tingle the palate , complementing the sour flavor .
a : pours clear amber . looks tasty .  mouthfeel is great . super dry , well carbonated , and smooth going down .
smell was impressive . one of the most floral and fragrant beers i have ever encountered .  very neutral , no real taste at first . ) it had a great mouthfeel .

a very good nose on this . mild toast and cinnamon , with a whispy grain malt punch . i like this little bit of dry sweet cinnamon it 's very nice and fits so well with this toasty character . everything from the nose is missing , toast , sweetness , malt balance , ca n't even find it .  medium bodied with soft and delightful carbonation in a smooth , creamy body . hands down the best in the series thus far in terms of body .

pungent aromas of dark fruits , spices , pumpernickel-bread-dough , are followed by sweet floral notes , oak , honey , and light mustiness . harsh astringency and bitterness was unexpected and is unwelcome . the sharp alcohol accentuates metallic notes . the astringency prevents this from being considered a sipping beer .  m : absolutely the best part of the beer .

aroma : frivilous hopping here floral , piney , and citrus toned hops explode upon my senses but that does n't set aside this beer from other rogues what does is the malty syrupy sweetness that is also represented here in teh aroma very balanced . taste : syrupy sweet mixture of hops so good the piney edge to the hops complements the caramel malt so well , true to the style by bringing true balance to the table that can only be compared to the american amber that they brew .  it 's full bodied and smooth with a very clean finish .
a surprisingly long life on the head of this . about two and a half finger , creamy and sticky .  it pours a brilliant gold , and the mouthfeel is very thick and chewy .

aroma is bready , hearty , and contains everything a rich slice of pumpkin pie should . wonderful spices on the nose - strong cinnamon , nutmeg , some cardamom . sweet and spicy , very fulfilling aroma . wonderful pumpkin pure taste , with a noticeable hop biterness .  mouthfeel is awesome . full , luscious , and smooth .

) poured into a glass , `` blind tiger '' smells wonderful . sadly , the taste did n't live up to my high expectations .  mouthfeel is very appetizing - just the right amount of smoothness and carbonation .

this smells delicious . t-sweet bananas followed some mild cloves .  m - nearly full bodied but despite that and the abv , it is extremely smooth and leaves just the right amount of flavor behind leaving you wanting another sip .
beautiful and strong aroma . t - some booziness .  body is perfect for the style , rich and semi-thick with restrained carbonation .
