smells of apple skin , young pears , a slight funk , and a fresh fallen rain on a field of wild grass fill the nose . i 'm getting excited . with gorgeous lacing that looks like a painting of a true belgian saison .  the carbonation level was perfect . the body was exactly what i wanted- not too watery but still very drinker- friendly .

the smell is fantastic , berries , flowers , a little bit of grass , very sweet .  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect . perfect thickness ( almost sludgy it is so thick ) , extremely chewy , with subdued carbonation . flawless .

the aroma is amazing ! it was hard to pull my nose away from this one . the whole hop gamut fills my olefactory senses . huge hoppy beer . it 's a damn good beer .  mouthfeel is exceptional . big , small foam mouth , which smooths down , edgy all the way -- but never sharp .
has an absolutely wonderful fruity smell ... . some nice head on the pour ... .  unique and quite charming , with some tasty complexities , yet easy to drink due to it 's wonderful mouthfeel .
wonderful . t - huge hop flavor without being too bitter .  m - thick and creamy , very full bodied . complemented by the right amount of carbonation .

s : wow ! really fresh pliny smell , citrusy fruits , smell does not fade when you inhale , just what i 'm looking for in a dipa . really nice blend of hops used in this if you like them ibu 's . overall , underrated .  very refreshing .

a- pours a golden , yellow color with very little head s- this thing smells amazing , very sweet aroma t- pretty nice taste , a little bitter for a pale ale , i would say this falls between ipa and pale ale , though its not hoppy enough for an ipa though probably more hoppy than your average pale ale . very interesting taste , very nice . m- nice and smooth d- could drink a lot of these , though for the price i paid , i certainly wo n't be  the mouthfeel is some kind of amazing . this brew is thick , chewy , ultra creamy smooth and goes down like heavy cream . if you like your imperial stouts with an unapologetically brash , bold , slightly raw taste , but with a refined , well-mannered mouthfeel , then you 'll enjoy expedition stout immensely .
s : nice blend of roasted coffee and chocolate . probably my favorite part of this beer .  mouthfeel is absolute satin .

nose is pretty good , however - hazelnuts come through with a nutty , milk chocolatey presence , with the spicing from the rum coming through pleasantly much more than the rum itself . really , surprisingly nice nose considering my initial impression from the appearance . fairly straightforward , not too complex , but what 's here is pretty nice . any richness or fullness promised from the beautiful hazelnut presence in the nose is completely missing .  medium body with perfect amount of carbonation .

as soon as i opened the top smells of bliss poured out . i loved the smell . smells of orange , a hint of grapefruit , and even rose filled filled my nose . i only have good things to say about this brewery .  m : close to perfect : rich , thick and creamy .
the smell is strongly like pumpkin , some spices , very similar to pumkin pie .  m : fairly high carbonation with a great body . the body is absolutely spot on !
pleasant but not overbearing taste .  the mouthfeel is perfect . the carbonation , weight of the brew , taste and viscosity are all well matched .

the smell is sweet and has notes of cocoa and maybe some brown sugar .  you can `` dig '' this one out of the corners of your mouth ten minutes later , which is to me the ideal feel of the style , this beer feels great . d- this guy could probably use at least a little while in the cellar , as it is so intense in malty and hoppy , it could stand to chill out a bit .

when i openned it , a strong fruity smell came out from the bottle , berries and berries and more fruity berries flavours came out . a very dark ruby beer with a shy white head that comes out quicky to say hi . smell is deeply fruity and berry like , some shy hops smells are present followed by yeast and end with a shy malted presence . very nice  very creamy mouthfeel , very sweet .

smell : very nice aroma of citrus & orange . a nice sharp smell of coriander and maybe cloves . smells quite zesty . taste : not as good as the aroma . very discreet and flees the scene before i can grasp any taste .  m : lovely viscous feel . perfect .

chocolate and raspberries permiate the nose and leave nothing else to come through . very rich , smells like a chocolate cheesecake with raspberries on top . very rich  perfect mouthfeel for this beer .

on the other hand , i can smell this bad boy from a foot away ... the nose is profound , showing milk duds , coffee , whiskey , vanilla and considerable booze . this beer just smells flat out decadent . for the most part , the flavor profile replicates the nose , though it 's a bit one dimensional and is dominated by sweet chocolate and coffee .  carbonation is moderate with a medium-full body yet still decent drinkability . the one thing that really stands out with this fest is its remarkable smoothness , definitely the smoothest octoberfest ive had .

nose was by far the best thing about this beer . tremendous floral and citrus aromas . taste is earthy floral hops with a little citrus , but the floral notes dominate with a twinge of spiciness . citrus peaks out in the finish . unfortunately the flavors are very subdued and i like the flavors in my ipa 's to `` pop '' more . though i do n't think this is a bad ipa , by any means , i feel it is just good , but not great and with so many stellar ipa 's available , i would not go out of my way to drink this again .  mouthfeel is beautiful with sweetness up front followed by a sting from carbonation and finishing with a crisp dry bitterness .

s- very fresh pale cereal grains and fruity floral pineapple and fruit blossom aroma . i appreciate pilseners with ale complexities . t- very crisp and perfectly bittered and balanced .  coats the tongue just right , insulating it from the alcohol .

as a proponent of doug fir tips , spruce tips , etc . on tap at the midnight sun house , it is a deep dark brown , nearly black , with plenty of roast and spruce tips blazing through . it is definitely a bit astringent , and i ca n't be sure if that is from the roast or from the spruce , but nonetheless , a very tasty brew .  outstanding mouthfeel ! d - drinks like a champ for a ris at almost 10 % abv !

the smell is amazing - lots of sweet , citrus hops and complexity . the taste was a bit maltier than i expected - tasted mostly like caramel , but then finished off with some bitter hops .  this has a wonderful mouthfeel which i absolutely love .

a - very dark , just short of black , some light passes through , looks clear , thick mouse-like tan head s - beautiful caramel notes , hints of toffee and milk chocolate , light herbal hop t - rather `` lean '' tasting , not much sweetness , a light bit of hazelnut , the dominant flavour is some earthy/herbal hop , but even it is quite light , virtually no aftertaste . m - fairly light body , combined with the mild flavours comes across as watery , d - the flavours are just too mild to get excited the aroma is incredible on this beer , but unfortunately it is far and away the best thing about this beer .  very smooth , exceptional mouthfeel .

laces well very nice pine and citrus hop aroma slight malt very nice the taste is bitter upfront and throughout the carbonation starts upfront and dissipates i would like this more if it was n't just bitter hop flavor there is n't a full hop profile i 've come to like in my ipas .  m- huge in the mouth chewy , creamy , and smooth . mild carbonation . nice clean finish , indicative of the nice alcohol levels .

considering how bitchin ' the venom was , i wanted more a- deep amber with a thick creamy eggshell head s- smell was amazing ... .had a little more complexity than dfh 90 with with some etoh kick t- not as strong as the smell led me to believe .  m - almost syrupy . i love the mouth feel .

the smell is fantastic . rich , sweet pumpkin pie aroma which is almost better than the real thing . spices of cinnamon and nutmeg balance well to make this the best beer i 've ever smelled . t : i wish i had the same enthusiasm for the taste as the smell . it started off well enough , after the build of the beautiful sweet aroma , but it faded quickly for me after that . that being said , this beer had the best aroma that i 've ever smelled in a beer .  m : perfect ! coats the mouth great ... slightly creamy , with the right amount of carbonation to bring out the flavors .
smells of a huge dose of brown sugar with some gooey barley beneath and perhaps some molasses .  i love it .

anchor 's humming ale looks like a nice thick wheat beer , turbid and dense blond in appearance . the first sniff reveals a rich and fresh bouquet of american citrusy hops .  super smooth and creamy body that glides down your throat like butter . so smooth and delicious that i had finished 3 pints in less than a half hour .
the smell is rather sweet from lots of chocolate along with some dark fruits ( cherry , plums ) & molasses .  mouthfeel : wow is this stuff smooth . very silky and perfect carbonation .

appearance : good , white foamy head , 1 '' off the tap ; dark copper color smell : awesome , fresh hops taste : at first it was really good , but i got a little sick of the hops toward the end ; kind of dry ; nonetheless , a good ipa taste mouthfeel : kind of a sticky head that hangs around ; other than that , it was pretty good drinkability : not the strength of this beer ; after i finished this one , i did n't want another , you get a little bit tired of all the hoppiness  mouthfeel is really very rich : like a good stout on the palate , smooth and full , thick and chewy , but it 's got that pilsner crispness .

s -- grapefruit bomb . there was also a wonderful pinecone and resin smell . this is one of the strongest beers i have smelled . t -- definitely able to taste grass , pinecone , and hops .  the mouthfeel is smooth thick goodness . a heavy beer to say the least .
the aroma was most definitely amarillo or similar hops . very lovely .  ever so rich and creamy in the mouth with soft and forgiving carbonation . medium-full in body .
s : wonderful , i could really pick out the chocolate and coffee notes .  smooth and oily with moderate carbonation - great mouthfeel .

this brew smells absolutely delicious . the first thing that came to my mind was fresh gingerbread cookies ginger , cinnamon , and sugary molasses sweetness .  m : quite thick moderate carbonation , love it .

the aroma is wonderful flowers and pine very nice . the taste unfortunatly leave the nice bitter bite of its little brother into the taste of pine resin .  thick , creamy , chewy , and lush , but with just enough carbonation - everything the style should be .
upon pouring it i was extremely impressed with the dark color , creamy brown head , and intriguing smell .  this did not effect the mouthfeel at all it was perfect as is .

the smell is the best part of this beer . too many kosch style beers are lacking expressive notes , while this really pops with flowery hops and crisp , slightly sweet malt . really nice and just under the top of the heap for the style . too bad my excitement over the pleasant smell did n't continue as i took my first few sips . the rest of the beer is nice , clean and just slightly sugar-kissed malt couples well with flowery hops that are n't bitter at all . major bummer , this could be up there with the coast kolsch , summit kolsch , or even victory 's amazing rendition .  m - good and thick in the feel . the finish is fantastic .

s - big juicy citrus hop aroma . i love ipa 's that smell like this ... big fruity nose with almost nothing else to it . a very easy drinking and tasty ipa , just like every other hop project of theirs i have tried .  m : they nailed the mouthfeel on this .

sour citrus goodness blends with balsa wood and hop pine to create perfect austerity . the sour nose does n't really translate - i hate t say it but i 'm getting some andre cold duck here !  fantastic creamy full mouthfeel .

s : wow ... the smell was amazing , i could taste it without even drinking it .  the mouthfeel and the drinkability of this beer are the stars for me , it was so smooth and almost milky ( in a good way.. not like gagging thickness or anything.. just very smooth ) .
wow this really has a lot going on in the aroma !  this one comes together nicely as it warms and the , big , sticky , thick , creamy mouthfeel is a big highlight .

it has a copper color but has a great smell . as i poured it into my glass the head was very large  m : mouthfeel is awesome ! slick , heavy and chewy . it gets fluffier and chewier as i swirl it in my mouth .

no sharpnes of a dryhop but still nice carracter . furter the sweetness of best munich & carramelic malts in litle sournes bathing of the wheat malt .  the mouth feel is outstanding , to the point of being lip smacking and among the best i 've had .
very promising smells . tastes sweet , spiced and with some definite squash flavors along with dark chocolate and roasted malt .  wonderful mouthfeel .

a lot going on here . chilled is ok , but warm is sublime .  good balance of sweetness and alcohol warmth full body creamy mouthfeel rich is a good word sippability is great would n't mind having a few of these for special occasions

it still looks and smells great . a nice brown/amber color with a two finger tan head .  feel is thick yet subtle soft and a fairly easy clean finish . this beer is a politician : drinkability talks an easy talk but once this gets going , the abv will lie and before you know it ... . thanks to our fellow ba resident calvinist geofffromsj who astutely taught me today that `` jesus saves , moses invests .

average pour nothing special.a clear amber in color.a small white head that didnt last long.aroma is nothing but raspberry and lots of it.aroma is very tart and very sweet smelling.the taste however wasnt as sweet as the smell.i smelled more raspberry than what i tasted.hints of honey on the finish.a light and refreshing ale that had a very crisp mouthfeel.no bitterness on the finish at all.a very good light and refreshing ale that has a different taste.i would buy these again.a sweet light raspberry taste .  mouthfeel was outstanding . the lush , creamy and full body was absolutely amazing .

aroma is heavy malt ( cookie , meal ) , average hops ( perfume , grass ) , heavy yeast ( barnyard , earth ) with notes of plum , apple , pear , and ginger . medium bodied , sticky texture , lively carbonation , and a bitter finish .  mouthfeel : great creamy , smooth mouthfeel .

nice american hop aromas , some pine and grapefruit some sweetness . this is a little too much for me , i prefer the regular and less bitter arrogant bastard ale .  m - perfect carbonation in a perfect medium body , godly smooth .

everything was tasting weird yesterday , all the aromas were strange . this one was like dipping your face into a fresh bag of weed . aside from the juicy marijuana nose on this it 's pretty uninteresting .  m : very smooth , sticky , and thick . light to medium carbonation .

a hard pour of this rosewood colored beer produces aromas of tea , ale fruit , dark stone fruit , red cherries , blackberry , baked bread . amazing eggshell colored frapped rootbeer float style head that totally laces the glass . taste is more tea with a chewy amber malt body , metallic red ale twang , and floral to spicy hop bitter in the drying finish .  the mouthfeel is incredibly thick and creamy , chewy enough to bite down into .
4.5 a : exceedingly dark brown , nearly black . a very good start .  m : this beer is full and lush . it is almost chewy . the carbonation is noticeable .

was holding on it until i receive the oak age version to do a side-by-side comparison with some friends , but none are hopheads like me . s : wow , a very strong aroma . i could smell this beer without my nose being close to the glass . i get mainly hops , resinous and some grapefruit .  the body of this beer was exceptional , thick , clean , and enjoyable .

as soon as you pop the top the room is filled with a wonderful aroma of bourbon , oak , and vanilla . it is an enjoyable sipper , but for the money there are better ones .  the one characteristic of this beer is its incredible silky smoothness on the tongue . the beer is moderately carbonated , medium bodied , and just wonderful on the tongue .

smell is awesome . roasted malt , a touch of coffee , and milk chocolate . taste does n't measure up to the great aroma . mostly roasted bitterness with a burnt coffee finish . there is a metallic quality that is pretty unpleasant as well .  m- very creamy , milky texture .
however the smell and taste was excellent . it tasted of roasted coffee and raisins .  palate is perfect , rich and chewy .

smell : first off , i really love dried apricots . the scent is entirely built on dried apricots therefore i enjoyed it quite a bit . taste and mouthfeel : the taste is primarily that of dried apricots only slightly less sweet .  the mouthfeel is superb : sticky and chewy but also very creamy , with fluffy carbonation .
wonderful hop aroma , nice and citrusy with some pine malt and spice .  the body is surprisingly thick and coating with a rich slick mouth feel .

smells good , and like it should . overall- well it smells quite pleasant . though unfortunately the rest of the aspects dont quite stack up .  this beer is full bodied and velvety smooth . it is a little high in alcohol , but the smooth mouthfeel and nice flavor would go a long way .
smell is incredible - full of citrus and piney hops with a bit of pineapple and a little malt underneath .  mouthfeel is great .
o : this aroma of this beer is amazing . it is like diving into a basket of fresh raspberries .  mouthfeel is so silky .

very fresh and aromatic . t- starts out very creamy and smooth but leans into a bit oaky ( odd ) caramel , slight butterscotch and burnt coffee note . the finish is quite dry and is pretty one dimensional and has an out of place green apple note . granted nitro stouts should be a bit thinner but still creamy . d- this is a decent stout at best .  m- the mouthfeel is fantastic . full bodied with a perfect amount of carbonation .

bold assertive bittering , much like what i picked up in the aroma , with some herbal and floral hopping as well . the hops are really strong here , possibly the hoppiest i 've had .  medium carbonation and fairly full bodied ; with a huge creamy and slick mouthfeel , that drinks super smoothly for being over 11 % . big creamy and lush body ; with a very dessert-like flavor profile ; without being cloyingly sweet .

aroma- moderate and balanced bouquet of cherry , berry , and herbal / spicy hop , alcohol , and malt with faint notes of apple and an acceptable showing of d. hardly intense , but complex nose . taste- firm but decidedly one dimensional malt base supports baked pear and apple notes as it fades away into big buttery d , melted right off the palate by alcohol , for what would be an unpleasing finish if it were n't for a brightly herbal hop contribution which aids an unexpected dryness . does n't last long though , before you are left with an unfortunate aftertaste . its kind of like sucking on an old cherry pit and licking a wine cork at the same time .  palate- chocolate milk with some espresso , toffee and campari bitterness , a touch of winy acidity , and a very creamy mouthfeel .

pours black with nice head and lacing smells amazing . i get creme brulee with a bit of underlying funk . lovely rich and inviting . blowing me away .  damn this is one thick beer ; milkshake is about the best way to describe it .

aroma of honey and lavender . very complex and almost reminiscent of a west coast barley wine . aroma is dominated by pineapple with hints of peach , vanilla , and a little raspberry . definitely the fruitiest non-citrus aroma i 've ever smelled from an ipa . taste is just mild sweetness , then a huge clean bitterness , with a feeling of a bitter tea finish .  mouthfeel is fantastic , super thick and syrupy , perfect for the style .

very nice . this was my final beer . not nearly the flavor i was expecting based on the wonderful aroma . easy to drink but need a little more uuuumph !  love the mouthfeel . smooth and creamy through the swallow , with a very mild , slightly dry finish and pleasant aftertaste .
nose is excellent with roastiness and hints of chocolate .  m. thick and heavy , strong and chewy , with plenty of carbonation .

i will have to give this another try next winter , as a siletz brew has never let me down until now ... .but damn it smelled so good !  mouthfeel is really silky , solid , and smooth in the carbonation .
d - nice appearance and great smells led to a slightly disappointing taste .  a nice , balanced beer with a clean taste and a smooth , exceptional mouthfeel .

s - the simcoe rings grapefruit like no other . personally , i really enjoy the ride and think the smell , flavor , and mouthfeel all compliment each other in a great way .  taste : toast , caramel , white pepper , coffee bean , tons of malt , chocolate , banana , vanilla bean , ripe strawberry - the most flavor i 've gotten out of a brown ale mouthfeel : soft , calming mouthfeel with nice smooth tannins leaving the mouth coated with a slowly vanishing flavor profile that 's rather fun to dissect .
i thought this smelled wonderful , these guys do get the aromas ' of there brews right .  mouthfeel , exceptional , like champagne ... exactly , close your eyes its champagne .

crystal clear gold color with an off white head . the foam is 2 fingers high and leaves a surprisingly thick coat of lacing on the glass . great retention too , none of the fizziness of the typical crappy pale lager .  beautiful mouthfeel -- really does n't overpower as it fades to a nice hoppy finish .

low carbonation , no head retention , but this is a cask . s - wow . what a nose on this . vanilla , caramel , sour notes , dark fruits ... it was quite a complex nose actually.. t - i was expecting sour notes.. but the front really took me by surprise.. very puckering .. i taste a lot of whiskey and burnt sugar notes on the mid palate and some great oak and deep vanilla on the finish . very interesting . but a tad too much lactic acid coming through . d - like i said . pretty darn sour , but the sourness played well enough against the vanilla .  leaves very thick lacing , almost like a nitro s_toasted bread , caramel , not very strong t_burnt toast , chocolate coffee beans , no real aftertaste m_ultra-smooth and creamy , so mellow , balanced , very little carbonation .
rather disappointing after such a wonderful aroma from this beer .  mouthfeel is magnificent . again , like a thin syrup .
s- coffee , chocolate , toffee , molasses rotate in the nose . it smells heavy and sweet . very very sweet .  the texture is creamy and silky .
smells absolutely fantastic . super-hop odor with sugary sweetness too .  m : perfect mouthfeel , light , crisp and very refreshing . excellent carbonation .
one of the better smelling beers i 've come across .  mouthfeel is lush and satiny smooth as the beer effortlessly flows down . mellow carbonation adds to the ease of drinkability here .

330ml bottle served in a pint glass.enjoyed on mar11 orangish light amber.yellow froth , dense & lasting.small bubbles.chill haze.high & intense perfume profile.on palate lemon zest & resins.very smooth bitterness at first sip but increasing in the middle.medium carbonation.abv is not felt.good & refreshing drinkability .  m : for some reason , the mouthfeel is great ! perfect balance of body and drinkability .

body was an intense brown with highlights on the edge . a big beige head of three plus fingers sat on top . minimal lacing but a ring of foam remained throughout .  medium body with a wonderful rich texture that is soothing in the mouth . just enough carbonation to keep things lively .
the aroma is quite pleasing . juicy banana , bread . a very nice smelling hefe .  m- creamy , thick , and very rich on the palate .
it has a delightful smell like a homemade pumpkin pie . spicy and fresh.there was n't much head even with a rough pour .  m : mouthfeel is perfect , rich and creamy .
smell is definitely that of hops , very nice hoppy smell .  the mouthfeel fits this beauty of a beer - it is thick and pleasingly rich . the full amount of suggested aging did this beauty wonders .

s - hops , hops , hops , citrus , grapefruit , sweet orange , and a hint of pine . some slight caramel sweetness might be coming through , though that could just be the vast amount of hops playing tricks on me . malt is well balanced . sweet caramel malts balance out the bitter middle .  the mouthfeel is full , warming and fabulous . flavor is full with lots of yummy esters holding hands with the sweetness and the fininsh is where i get the coriander .
very nice . t : not as good as the aroma here , but still not bad .  palate : a perfect 5 overall : rather murphy's-esque .
s : floral and very very sweet . strong raspberry scent coming though .  really fantastic mouthfeel - silky and full on the tongue .

there are chocolate and raisins on the nose and hints reminiscent of the leathery cherry notes from a belgian quadruple .  mouthfeel is perfect for a porter , chewable but not too much , this is a meal in a bottle .

smell is terrific for an ipa , the nose is hugely pine and grapefruit with the edge going to the pine , citrus makes a good presence , eventually the hop front melds with a caramel malt backing as part of the `` afternose '' .  awesome thickness , yet not throat-closing thickness -- more like smooth milkshake thickness , where carbonation does n't feel like bubbles , but simply a collective , chilled push down the throat .
smell : smells of orange rind , a touch of grapefruit and pine as well . very aromatic for a wheat beer ... .much better than most pale ales out there as well .  m : pretty much perfect for me .
very attractive smell , grainy with some yeast and a fresh sweetness .  excellent body that just coats your mouth .

that said : the aroma is quite special , and definitely brings memories of the holiday season . it 's almost nice enough to enjoy by itself ; reading a leatherbound copy of `` a christmas carol '' in front of a low burning fireplace with its sweet and spicy aroma continually reminding you that your glass is sitting beside you . the head is pillow-like at first , but receedes to a nice 1/16 '' that lasts to the end . this year 's seems to have much less hop flavor and a reduced bitterness which gives the malt and spice a rounder flavor .  mouthfeel/drinkability- just when i thought the perfect mouthfeel of a belgian ale was locked up with tripel karmeliet , this beer dazzles with a sublime , gentle texture that lasts throughout the entire duration in the mouth . absolute perfection , it further emphasizes the already impressive quality of the beer .
s - world class . raisins , sweet fruitiness , definitely some oak - it just smells like dessert .  indulgent , creamy mouthfeel . and i really ca n't get over how pleasurable the mouthfeel is .

appearance- beer pours a ruddy reddish brown with a substantial finger and a half of head and lacing clinging amply to the sides of the glass when swirled .  tastes much like it smells and goes down really well with a creamy texture and some lively carbonation playing with your tounge .

decadent as well , somewhat like chocolate covered cherry cordials . absolutely fantastic in the nose ! syrupy and mellow with buttery brown bread and nice fruit : apple , berry , citrus , and fig . sweet and woody and not terribly pronounced provided the outstanding nose . mild hops and vanilla with a ghost-like smoke note . very complex and earthy but rather understated . very nice however . a unique and enjoyable rendition of the style .  mouthfeel is also top notch . low carbonation that goes down very smooth .

s - strong milk chocolate flavor , more creamy than bitter . good espresso addition . d - tastes , smells , feels , and looks like a stout , so why not call it one ?  near perfect carbonation and body .

very nice . whoa ! it 's tastes ok but so far off from the fantastic nose . the sweet grains you smell taste like wet toast wrapped in paper towel . the flavor has a slight mustiness to it that i find to be very boring .  mf - this it where this beer shines the most to me . very nice carbonation that tickles your mouth as you savor it . also reminds me in some ways of an eisbock albeit less vinuous and more carbonated and roasty .

s : great smelling beer . extremely herbal , coriander , yeasty and fresh like a spring breeze . if the beer tastes half this good i 'm in luck . d : too many spices added , detracts from the flavor of the beer .  thanks to ba greggy for this one . the beer is very thick and smooth . not overpowering but just the right feel . the only thing that i have a problem with is the fact that this beer is so thick and rich , there is no way i would be able to drink more than 2 of these in one sitting .

stunning citrusy orange-grapefruit-lemon-passion fruit and pine aroma . could sniff this one all day . exceptional aroma carries the day here .  mouthfeel is perfection , smooth , crisp , with just the right amount of carbonation ... and the tartness in the finish leaves you wanting to pour more of that big bottle .

the aroma was of fresh harvest hops . in fact the lovely dry hopped aroma of this beer made my mouth salivate wildly in anticipation of the wonderful nectar that was forthcoming .  m - this is what really sets this beer apart for me . incredibly creamy and thick mouth feel .

a - pours a nice translucent darker orange with a nice finger of off white/light caramel colored head , poured ~20+ minutes ago , still has a nice layer of head . lacing is dense . awesome s - lots of citrusy hop aromas , a little bit of malty caramel sweetness .  m : i have to say that this was the most impressive aspect of this beer . oftentimes porters end up a little too thin-bodied , but this one had a very full body , and combined with the very nice carbonation made this a pleasure to drink .

s- second brew i 've tried from kuhnhenn , second absolutely intoxicating aroma . deep raspberries much like new glarus raspberry tart but there 's something behind it , namely a well hidden alcohol aroma that lingers in the nostrils . t- much more interesting of a brew than the aroma let on . nice , however truncated , raspberry flavor followed by quite a bit of alcohol warming .  mouthfeel is excellent , coating and thick with well-done low carbonation .

awesome smell ... this one really shows off a great bouquet of hops . about as good as it gets here . still good , with the great hop character , but not quite as good as the nose .  the beer didnt quite taste as good as it looked , but it was still quite pleasently sweet and i highly enjoyed the creamy mouthfeel it had .

a : nearly clear off-white yellow with puffy fine bubbles head that kept it all the way , great lacing s : mild nose with spicy yeast , some soft floral aspects too t : traditional saison with earthy/floral qualities probably from elderflowers , noticeable hop bite in finish , hops were more than normal for a saison but not offensive m : decent mouthfeel with all the qualities of a saison ( yeasty , spritzy ) but with stronger hop finish  mouthfeel was perfect for me ... .slightly tingly , but at the same time silky smooth and gentle on the palate .

strong aromas of roasted dark chocolate , malts , coffee , whisky . great . taste is full bodied and powerful ; flavors of coffee , malt , unsweetened dark chocolate , a touch of hops , warming alcohol notes likely from the bourbon ageing .  m - very full bodied , nearly stout full .

i get some raisin and vanilla in the middle and molasses , chocolate , and black licorice on the backend . awesome ! perfect !  high carbonation . probably the silkiest body in a dipa i 've ever encountered .

the nose of the beer was simply amazing ! probably the best smelling beer i have ever experienced . something about it was very comforting , it reminded me of buttered toast with cinnamon and sugar piled on then a hint of alcohol .  m : i love the low carbonation as it works really well here .

s- big nose of hops mostly pine and grassy . hard to pick much else out through the hops but some roasted malt and caramel is hiding in there . t- big blast of floral hops right away that lasts through to the finish . hops change in character from floral to bitter at the finish . some notes of malt , chocolate , and caramel at the finish as well but hidden behind the bitterness of the hops . finish is astringent , boozy and with the lingering feeling of the hop oil .  the body is light , clouded amber with a perfect fluffy mouthfeel delivering high quaff quotient .

very enticing ... s- thank you surly for this aroma that i have now gotten to experience . in your face grapefruit , pineapple , oranges , and just a tiny bit of pine/wood to add some complexity . i literally sense no malt sweetness in this to back up the hop aroma like you get in other beers , and that is great by me ! t/m- very bitter forward . o- very good ipa .  the mouthfeel is perfect for a stout .

nice ! maybe this one suffers from where i am in my own personal `` beer journey , '' but i 'm getting a little tired of ipa that smell great & fragrant & then assault you with aggressive , tongue-battering bitterness .  the mouthfeel is exceptional -- thick , chewy , syrupy , andincredibly smooth .
smell : one of the best hefe smells ever , since i 'm not the biggest banana-hef fan .  smooth creamy mouthfeel , it 's a satisfying brew for my palate . very good stuff .
citrus , raspberry , lemon , and a hint of oak .  mouth is silky smooth with a full body a great carbonation , did n't go flat like alot of darker brews have .
this beer looks and smells great . the taste is very average - i was expecting more with a name like ambergeddon - still good .  it 's pretty full bodied and very smooth with a clean , dry finish .

nose is really different - chocolate , caramel , and the hops lend a lot of juicy citrus notes ( orange in particular ) , bordering on juicy fruit . black coffee comes on strong as the nose settles down some , though still what i would consider to be a rich , sweet nose . very nice . taste turns the sweetness from the nose on it 's head - right from the start , the hops take charge in this one . finish is bitter , a bit acrid , roastiness edges over to char , and once the dark chocolate in the beginning of the finish fades , becomes a bit unpleasantly one sided . still a really nice experience , but could use a bit less bitterness towards the finish .  mouthfeel is very rich , smooth carbonation .

a beautiful copper colour , with hints of candied pear in the nose and some peach . nice , full mouthfeel but the taste lacked the wholesome maltiness that i expect in a bitter .  creamy , smooth mouthfeel goes excellent with the flavor profile .

love it . my type of stout aroma . t : more balanced than the smell .  light to medium in body , with significant carbonation , and an amazing palate to mingle with the generous abv make the mouthfeel very impressive . one of my favorite styles , and certainly one of my favorites amongst it .
wow , awesome aroma for this beer . really nice pour , medium tan head . really unique brew .  m : incredible mouthfeel .

thanks muenchenerkindl for such an excellent extra 12 oz bottle poured into a duvel tulip an awesome midnight black with a good two fingers of tan head that settles into a large curtain of lace that lasts to the end aromas of oatmeal , malts and grains , yes almost barleywineish with a light alcohol smell oatmeal , chocolate molasses and fruit with a lite hop end note wow i like the taste almost like some sort of hybrid oatmeal stout barleywine palate is medium to thick you need to sit back , relax and sip this one .  mouthfeel is phenomenal , like liquid velvet down the throat , and with a good bit of carbonation to tingle the tongue .

a : pale golden in colour , coming with a very creamy and thick off-white head that sustains throughout the drink , on top of light carbonation - looking superb !  i do n't find much to be said really , excellent balance , medium body shows a perfect carbonation to my liking , quite creamy lager , pretty crisp dry herbal hops finish .

aroma is absolutely delicious , malty and sugary , caramel , fruits , plums and prunes , very close to the aroma of a port wine . it lasts a long time , and all the way to the end i keep smelling this . already very impressive , i will hold the rest of the case , still feels like it has room to improve .  taste the weizen gives way to the bock as it warms mf : medim/heavy bodied with low carbonation & nicely balanced drinks very easy for the abv , a really nice weizen bock .

aroma is great and not your typical apa/ipa . elegant . very balanced , ending just a tad bitter .  m : the feel is super creamy which makes it near full bodied . this is the biggest difference between this bottled version and the on-tap version i had last year . the mouthfeel was a huge step up .

lots of yeast character in the aroma . apricots and esters and honey . pale gold , no head , little carbonation bubbles .  mouth feel is absolutely fantastic with light carbonation and small bubbles .

aroma - dark chocolate dominates the nose . overall - it smells much better than it tastes .  m - smooth , a delicate sudsing that tickles the palatte , and quite refreshing with a subtle warming effect from the alcohol .

nice malty aroma with a healthy dose of roastiness - chocolate , espresso , and caramel . simple , straightforward , and tasty . light in body - silky smooth , crisp and a bit thin .  very nice dry finish . overall super smooth and super crisp mouthfeel .
a - medium to dark brown colored body with a good inch of medium tan head . the head fades slowly into a frothy foam at about a quarter inch .  very nice mouthfeel .
the nose was really pronounced . very charred and smokey smelling .  smooth and full mouthfeel .

pleasantly fragrant . slightly bready with some fruitiness and hop bitterness in the afteraste . taste does n't quite live up to the aroma , but it 's very drinkable .  creamy , oily , perfect weight .

strong fresh hop smell -- very much like a double ipa . surprisingly , there 's very little hop up front .  simpler flavor and wonderful mouthfeel enhance the drinkability ; but it is slightly boring .
the smell is really good , warm , but hopeful of spring , because it has just the right amount of alcohol bite .  m- full bodied , creamy , thick luscious mouthfeel .

aroma is bright with citrus and syrupy with alpha acid promise . this is without a doubt the most unique and hardest nose to describe that i have ever come across .  mouthfeel is highly pleasurable , with perfectly gauged carbonation .

smell : a very sparkling smell , with loads of sweet candi sugar . smells very clean and crisp . taste and mouthfeel : this basically a hotter , unbalanced la fin du monde .  mouthfeel : medium to full bodied and incredibly smooth . just a hint of carbonation tingle .

a - dark cherry red , some light getting through , little head , a few tiny carb streams , loose lacing s - black licorice , chewy root beer candy , unsweetened bubble gum , tart dry cherries , anise , strong alcohol t - dark toasted pumpernickel , raisins , dried figs , dark cherries , almost too-dark toffee , alcohol m - medium to medium heavy in body , lots of alcohol warmth . i have a feeling that a fresh tasting would not even compare to a vintage tasting . i imagine that the strong alcohol aroma , flavors and warmth will mellow over time letting all these earthy fruity aromas and flavors come to the foreground .  mouthfeel is about the creamiest i 've ever had a beer feel . drinkability is great too .

22oz bottle ( best by july 2010 ) poured into a dogfish head signature glass . a - pours a mostly clear bright orange with a beautiful whipped creamy one finger cap of foam with excellent retention . when the beer level falls ( the head never really goes away and stays with the beer throughout the glass ) , it leaves behind lots of sticky spiderwebs of lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel was the best part of this beer .

from tap to maredsous glass pours an opaque apricot-orange , thick sudsy , sea-foam head with lots of lacing s : strong nose , big bouquet carried by ample alcohol volatiles . floral , sweet , citrusy . flavors are big and bold but disjointed . very sweet , almost cloying . d : loses some points here ... interesting brew , lots of flavors and layers , but they 're all over the place . but it 's far from boring .  a great , thick mouthfeel makes this beer very satisfying and drinkable .

aromas of sour cherries , malt vinegar and rhubarb come across very strongly with subtle notes of vanilla and rich chocolate fudge ( likely from the oak ) in the background . as it continues to warm , i pick up some definite cheese aromas as well ( fresh gorgonzola comes to mind ) .  mouthfeel is full and round .

very nice and refreshing . the flavor is saison earthy funk with a little sweet fruit and a little spice .  on the palate , this beer is very much alive still with plenty of carbonation , a full body , and a super-long finish . the alcohol is almost non-existent on the palate , leading to a very balanced and easy-drinking ( although fairly heavy ) beer .
smell is delicious . pure honey , reminiscent of sam adams honey porter . ends up being pretty tame .  m : full bodied with an awesome carbonation feel .
nose is wonderfully syrupy sweet with great complexity . showcases notes of vanilla taffy , honey , soft spicey slchol and banana .  creamy mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is very creamy and chewy .

very nice smelling beer . currants are the first flavor i notice , following that comes a punch of coffee and dark malt . cherry is the most pronounced flavor here , and overall it is an interesting , rather good stout .  mouthfeel was excellent . very slick and smooth , almost oily in fact , with a medium/thick body .

smells great , black licorice and sweet molasses malt . a little pine coming through on the nose now too . flavors remain unbalanced and even a tad harsh on the front end .  incredibly smooth and creamy in the mouth .

the massive , whipped egg-white head on this tarnished gold beer offers up an awesome bouquet of fresh lemon . lemongrass , herbal hops , sour yeastiness , white pepper , and just a touch of pine or maybe even juniper .  creamy , almost soupy mouthfeel .

best by date : 03/29/2011 a - a crystal clear beautiful rosy copper color with a medium off-white head that settles to a thick ring and some bubbly patches on the surface . this looks fantastic . s - creamy grapefruit , pine , and some balancing malt .  but the nose is fantastic-and the mouthfeel is exceptional . another great brew overall by ccb .

served from the bottle into a tulip glass a- poured black with tight creamy mocha head that leaves some spotty lace s- big sweet citrus and piney hops , dark roasted malt , currants , and molasses t- some citrusy/piney flavors in this beer , big licorice , molasses , some currant , and chocolate like flavors . odd soy sauce like taste developed as i got towards the bottom quarter of my glass .  mouthfeel is very good and creamy with good carbonation levels .

purchased a growler of this at big z 's in huntington , ny . pours black and opaque . nice brown head that goes down to a thin layer of foam rather quickly .  mouthfeel is big and full , very smooth and satisfying .

extremely hoppy and no doubt delicious two hearted ale t : taste falls flat after smelling it . corny , hop dominated , yet not very bitter .  notes : well structured , perfect mouth feel with a german like pilsner flare .

splendid , rich bouquet of floral hops , very aromatic . too overfiltered for my liking , but this does n't seem to effect the potency all that much .  big , smooth , and slick . this is a particularly rich baltic porter . very dark , dense , and well crafted .

sour tangerines , grapes , musty oak , spicy clove , and coriander make up the complex aroma of la roja . orangeish brown in color , with a persistent white ring and very fine bubbles across the top of the beer . an excellent brew from my new favorite american brewery .  mouthfeel is superb , very rich and creamy , gently coating the palate and then closes with a clean , dry finish .

i love the aroma . t : to bad non of the aroma carried over . the nose is really amazing , but not much else stands out .  texture is silky smooth and it does n't feel nearly as strong as it actually is .

s : caramel , toffee , and brown sugar up front with a biscuity malt character swirling around . lots of different fruits - figs , plums , raisins , some light citrus , and green apples . t : big fruit presence up front with plums , raisins , figs , citrus , and apricots all playing a part . caramel , toffee , and some toasted graints show up on the mid-palate before giving way to a sweet , fruit filled finish . m : has a very wine like feel , light to medium bodied with the faintest of carbonation ... usually an undercarbed barleywine feels too heavy and syrupy , but this really works .  massive body , and silky smooth . fruity , creamy , wine-y , and then comes a stiff roast/coffee crack of the whip .
the smell is terrific . loaded with citrus scents and a nice blend of bitter and floral hops , this one has the makings of a winner already .  mouthfeel was incredibly creamy .

aroma : smells amazing . tons of grapefruit and sweet cotton candy in the aroma . drinkability : this is an amazing ipa , full of great west coast hop aromas and flavors . it 's easy drinking , and quite delightful .  mf is creamy , and quite nice .

very , very enticing . the taste is grapefruit rind , bready , biscuit malt , some pithy tropical fruit , and a bit of pine .  it possesses the best mouthfeel i 've yet to come across , rich and velvety , it just rolls over the palate and tongue , and goes down incredibly smooth .
a-full and wonderful piney , resiny hops full the nose with some faint malt in the background . nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is where this beer really , really shines .

pours dark brown , ruby highlights.the aroma on this thing is outstanding . huge hop aroma of pine and citrus jump out of the glass . it really detracts from the drinkability too .  it marries hops with malt in a beautiful way and the mouthfeel is pleasantly grainy . it 's mouthfeel is flat-out perfect and it 's taste is wonderful .

very nicely hoppy aroma . piney and bright with a background of grapefruit rinds and peaches .  could be banana..pretty complex smell for me to pick out everything present.. t -- belgian yeast shines through beautifully ... fruity and extery with just very small hints of hops to balance this one out very nicely ... as with the smell the amount of tastes here i just can not begin to describe yet ... i will have to re-review again when i train my palate more m -- very smooth and bubbly ... fills your mouth and coats your tounge with taste ... but it is not a sticky coating ... just a full bodied taste.. d -- i could drink a few of these but would eventually have to switch styles to something very bitter since the belgian styles arent my favorite ... but i enjoy having a few due to the complexity of the flavors and they arent usually as strong so i can have a few in a row ... very tasty i will grab a 4 pack next time im out..

poured a translucent reddish brown , with two fingers of offwhite head . horrendous for the style , but intriguing nonetheless .  t - bananas , caramel , and mild dates swim around sour-yeastiness and vanilla , concealing well the alcohol that lies beneath ... m - very , very smooth , medium body massages the palate and dries the cheeks . d - nice , very nice , do n't know if i 'd get it again , but very nice .

the smell was quite complex . heavy in malt with mixed fruit smells , citrus , dates and various other fruit . an almost nutty undertone in the rear of the nose . the drink started clean and fruity with just a hint of hops in the middle and a lingering dried fruit flavor to finish . clean mouthfeel , heavy in carbonation at the start but this dissapates and leaves just good beer to speak for its self .  mouth : first thing to comment on is the tiny carbonation that tickles when it enters and , as it moves through the mouth and warms , becomes creamy and chewy . excellent mouthfeel !
nice .  the lack of carbonation really helps the mouthfeel of this .

tough soapy and sticky white head hangs onto the glass and aroma is piney and deep resin with sticky citrus , sweet orange oils and a light alcohol grand marnier like finish . overall an excellent example of the style that would drive most of the drinking public running towards the nearest case of keystone .  the mouthfeel is the best part . lush , creamy , and thick despite the deceiving pale colored body .

smell : vanilla & oak ; awesome taste : malty , some caramel , some vanilla . excellent `` sipping ' beer , but unless paired with hearty food , 2 pintseasy to drink , but will drink better older ...  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is outstanding . medium bodied , with just the right amount of fine carbonation .

smells of fruits with a gentle spice in the back . caramel and bready malts are used and compliment the beer nicely . with such a huge head i figured it would be too much , but its very nice .  taste is very smooth with a great mouthfeel .

poured up jet black with a bit of a rocky , caramel coloured foamy head that hung around for several minutes before subsiding to a layer of khaki coloured frost . very sticky lacing looks like cake batter stuck to the sides of my glass . beautiful ! !  m - carbonation cleans the palate nicely , the tartness and funk does n't linger long . the carbonation is just spot on , love it .

smell is pretty good , a great balance of the malt and hops .  mouthfeel is the best part about the rasputin - just the right amount of chewiness and the malt and alcohol linger heavily on the sides of your tongue .

`` first off , the smell is what hits you first , lots of dark fruits , sugar , rum , plums . . is massively bitter , yet still a tad sweet- never has a beer been so wide in that spectrum ! the flavour is complex but at colder temps , the alcohol can be a bummer , wait ! -- - & gt ; warmer shows some real class , tasty yet assertive .. bold .  lingers long and leavs a soothing feeling on the palate .
smell : smells unbelievably hoppy . smells very hoppy and promising . taste : meh , i really was expecting a big bold aperican ipa from this .  mouthfeel- silky smooth with a creamy feel as well .
wonderful spicy aroma , pears , apricots and healthy spices sitting in fresh doughy crust before the oven .  creamy medium-full body with soft carbonation .
pours with a thick creamy head over a dark black body , beautifully cascading .  mf : masterfully fizzy but light and balanced .

s : smell of citrus and yeast . a heavy wheat aroma and candy sugar . t : syrupy sweet from candy sugar takes the lead with flavor of crisp wheat and sweet dried fruit , raisins and currants .  the mouthfeel is incredible on this beer .

wow . there 's plenty going on here . i literally sat here sniffed uncovering a new scent every time . amazing ! tastes of nougat initially . the entire mix is quite curious , but begs you to drink more to uncover further complexities and intricacies . comes off as a highly unique english barleywine to my tastes .  great mouthfeel , full bitterness balanced with light maltiness .

s- excellent nose . sweet pineapple , citrus , grapefruit/orange , hops . m- medium bodied , but very smooth . light oiliness . d- awesome . i love the complex flavor .  this is a big bodied , chewy brew with medium carbonation , and a full palate .
smells quite nice , gets the salivary glands working overtime .  creamy , full bodied feel to it . really outstanding .

the aroma is heavenlywith a boatload of skunky tropical fruit hops . there is skunkweed , mango , pineapple , grapefruit and pine in there ... wonderfully full and fresh . mouthfeel is smooth , sleek , with a dense body .  the mouthfeel is delightful . up front the beer is very rich and the oak really shines through with this age on it . nicely mouth coating , and the intense finish with a great deal of carbonation and bitterness refreshes the palate for another sip . love this beer , 2010 and 2011 review to be added another day .

s - fantastic sweet , brown sugar , syrup and malt . it 's still worth it just to smell the nice flavors it has to offer .  mouthfeel is terrific . great , rich , creaminess . completely coats your mouth .
the aroma is of a beautiful fresh hop . nice floral hop aroma with tropical fruit .  m : this is where this bottle shined . a thick , and almost cream-like mouthfeel .

4.0 s : the nose on this beer is really nice . its a great looking and great smelling beer . however , the taste and mouthfeel come up short .  the mouthfeel is astounding . with all the charged up carbonation , i was expecting a soda like fizzy mouthfeel , but i am pleased at the silky smooth , well rounded and succulent body of this ale .

a nice aroma . abv undetectable .  mouthfeel is full and velvety smooth with a crisp finish that could n't be better .

actually quite complex when i dig deeper . vanilla makes itself present as well as a little wine musk . t= really really nice . great tartness in it that is a refreshing bite but it is n't the only component of it .  mouthfeel is excellent . it 's creamy and almost chewy .

nose is the most superior aspect of this beer , nice and fruity pear , apple , white grapes , touch of graininess , esters , honey . body does n't seem as integrated , bourbon coming through and not really jiving with the rest of it imo . honey sweetness , coconut , vanilla , pear and apple , orange , grains , alcohol shows in the finish too much , pretty hot . heavy carb which seemed slightly overdone . not really bad ( in fact , still pretty good ) but with all the bruery beer we had this one was kinda `` meh '' for me , a bit of a mess that perhaps would integrate better with some time .  mouthfeel : light-medium bodied with a super slick/silky and creamy feel .
it smells really good . t : brown sugar , cinnamon , light nutmeg and allspice .  carbonation is spot on and really helps lighten the mouthfeel .
quite an interesting nose for a lager .  m : mouthfeel is very nice .

seriously , filter your beer guys ... s : the nose is the best part of this beer . loads of floral/citrusy hops that is very reminicent of nugget nectar . if they would reduce the bittering hops and increase either the malt or citrus hops this would be great . m : the feel is nice and creamy with great carbonation . pretty good if you like your ambers hoppy .  touches of carbonation throughout , the mild breakups of tingling yield a remarkably smooth bevvy .
incredibly complex , balanced , and appealing .  molasses and toffee sweetness m - rich and chewy caramell . low carb form the bottle and slightly dry d - wonderful !

the aroma is fantastic ; the hop aroma is simply fantastic with the citrus smell that highlights grapefruit . that hop mixes well with the sweet malt aroma , very inviting ! the flavor , while good , does not live up to my expectations based on the nose .  mouthfeel- creamy and a bit thick . super smooth and very drinkable .

s- hype or not this stuff smelled amazing . baked bread , brown sugar , figs , cinnamon , prunes , raisins , licorice , basically smells like if you mixed everything that is the color brown that tastes fantastic and liquify it . t & m- pretty much what i expected ... a heavy , earthy hop tone with hints of malts , sugars and dried fruits . d- smooth and delicious , lives up to the hype for me !  mouthfeel : a very creamy , very smooth ipa . carbonation is perfect . body is malty and medium-bodied , and aftertaste is mildly dry .

smell : incredible hop aroma starts floral with hints of citrus . notes : a fantastic beer that i will definitely drink again . i 'm not usually a fan of american ipas because they 're so unbalanced , but this was nice . good job bell 's ...  quite possibly the best mouthfeel i 've ever experienced in any beer .

the nose is rich fruit ( fig and banana ) so typical of the style .  this is the mouthfeel i yearn for in every brew o- very glad i got to sample this one and will most likely re-review it once i have more barleywine experience .

three finger high foamy tan head with decent retention and some sporadic patchy lacing the aroma is full of peat and chocolate , malted milk ball a little bit of butter scotch , caramel some smoke , sweet and malty . the taste is pretty in line with the aroma one gets of the nose , no real surprise here .  m- medium/high carbonation . fairly smooth .

interesting . sour is n't as present in the taste as the smell . disappointing after the smell especially . mouthfeel is ok. a little too highly carbonated but goes a bit with the wood/fruitiness , although it 's less of a beer feel and more like a wine feel . the smell is excellent but the flavors just are n't blended in the right way to make it a great beer .  light , crisp , refreshing body and feel- would be great on a hot day .

s strong aroma of extremely floral , piney hops .  smooth somewhat creamy and drying mouthfeel , i have had much creamier kolsch and want something hoppier as well .

very interesting and really makes you want to taste it .  great brewery , terrible labels . this beer smells exactly like fresh paint . but then it really got to me and ruined my whole heresy experience . smooth and reserved heresy is an introvert in the double stout world .

has large , foamy head that dissipates quickly and leaves some nice lacing .  finishes fruitty & dry mf : light/medium bodied with minimal carbonation drinks okay , should 've known a beer this low in abv would n't fare well with it 's trans-pacific journey

laced nicely . smell - pine needles with a hint of pears .  ehh.. let me start by saying i adore irs 's . the anise , in my humble opinion makes this beer taste absolutely terrible . do n't get me wrong , you still get the nectar like , frothy delicious chocolate experience in the background , which is almost good enough to save this beer for me . theoretically the sweet/bitter flavor of the yeast should play off of and enhance the chocolate and coffee flavorings , but it does not . a change in proportions could make this a great , unique brew .

malt , crisp apple , some citrus smell , some cloves too . this is a rather dryish beer , and particularly so for a hefe . the cloves are noticeably absent from the taste , but you will get the pepperish snap at the end , but very subtley so . the mouthfeel is significantly more creamy than i would have expected , and the after taste is a bit more pronounced as well . this is a hefe that is complex because it borrows characteristics from other styles .  it has a good mouthfeel , thick but creamy , goes down smooth .

a : hazy orange with a massive , rocky head with everlasting sustain .  i liked the mouthfeel of this beer .

appearance : jet black , nearly opaque brew with dense head of foam .  mostly yeasts with minimal hop notes . taste : for a lager , not too bad . smooth inception leads to yeast , hops , then smooth and rounded end . almost methodical in its sequence of flavors . overall : pretty drinkable ; good for barbecues and other events that require a well-balanced lager as to not overwhelm the taste of other foods .
beer poured a golden color with a beautiful head .  the mouthfeel was a fluffy consistency .

deep mahogany to chestnut colored , still ( not carbonated ) , and smelling of maple syrup , prunes , toffee , and a hint of chocolate . enjoy this novelty `` triple bock '' , think of it more like a brandy and enjoy !  incredibly astringent finish that just keeps lingering until the next sip . mouthfeel almost is pretty viscous .

this is a barrel-aged version of florence with brett . notes from my phone : beautiful hazy orange gold with thick creamy bone-white head . this is perhaps the most beautiful beer that i 've ever seen !  overall : good mouthfeel , well carbonated with a bit of oiliness .

the aroma is one of the best from a wit i 've ever had . the taste disappointment after the great aromatics . it 's pretty bland , and it misses all of the citrus and spice found in the nose . slight spice , and a lot of the strange , off flavors i find in a lot of adjunct lagers .  m - i really like the mouthfeel of this beer . it is perfectly carbonated and that takes over when it first hits the tongue .
above average lace sheets . looks very tempting . smell- very restrained scent .  their is a pleasant caramel base behind it with a good creamy mouthfeel .

proclaimed as an american pale ale on the label and one sniff would validate that - a beautifully strong cascade aroma .  smells kind of like dishwashing liquid , very soapy , but distinct of certain hop combos ... or so i 've discovered over the years . there 's an even malty / big dextrin sweetness and medium-mouthfeel , but the depth of flavour is one dimensional . hops come in as a gentle bitter citric tingle on the palate , then turns into a faint tea-like character as it fades into the malty blandness . hops are a bit oily . earth flavours run through the middle . finish has some residual hop and soap-like flavours . or perhaps the way the hops played out , combined with the dull malty flavours , rubbed me the wrong way ?
a bit of a disappointment given its amazing aroma but still very good . mouthfeel : medium-bodied and well-carbonated .  m - fairly light-bodied , with nice carbonation ; quite good in this aspect .
smells sweet , citrusy , yeasty , fruity , pithy , and spicy .  m - the mouthfeel is actually right on point .

s - sugary sweet malt is way up front on this one , blended with a heavy dose of caramel , some fruity esters , and citrusy/grapefruity hops . balanced way towards the malty side . very good - probably the best aspect of the beer . almost candy like in its intensity and ends up being somewhat cloying .  500ml bottle poured into tulip mar27 2011 a pours out black with some oil like globs towards the bottom of the bottle , thumbs width of mocha head quickly falls to a thin film leaving a partial ring of lace followed by some unorganized patches s worcestershire sauce and soy with a little booze and mint , not what i was hoping for t slightly better with some smoke , woody earth , vanilla , cola and whiskey but that worcestershire is hard to miss after you catch wind of it m fairly thick and creamy with just a little heat that could be better concealed but still feels good o lea & perrins would be proud , that worcestershire smell and flavor is holding this one way back hard to believe that before this hit the barrel it was one of my all time favorite stouts , i love the beer geek breakfast but this one just did n't do it for me , not a bad brew but i 'd rather drink one before the barrel aging edit : after reading some reviews i suspected i got a bad bottle and tried another .

from bomber to pint a : pours a copper-tan , light carbonation , little head and no lacing n : pumpkin and nutmeg , light lemon-citrus hop poking through t : hearty rich pumpkin pie , lightly bitter hops with an earthy , tea edge .  taste : light body , smooth mouth feel .

so much funky goodness , which seems a bit abnormal for the style , but pretty damn good . i like what 's going on in my glass ... huge letdown ... hay and grass with only a hint of brett .  mouthfeel is medium - light with good carbonation .
this is actually one of the sweetest ipa 's i have ever sniffed !  moderate carbonation and more oak on the finish .

smell is rich with sweet sugary notes , vanilla , coffee , roasted malt , chocolate , burnt sugar , very nice to smell . taste is malty and roasted , lightly astringent , light sour lactic like notes , some bitterness comes out , mild vanilla and chocolate , some coffee , this was pleasant at times and at times a little on the bad side .  the mouthfeel is all right . it 's full , sticky on the finish and carbonated enough to keep the tongue tingly without providing much lift and volume .

s : very interesting ! dark syrupy malts , prune , licorice , bitter orange . t : similar notes from the aroma , but far more dominated by the malty flavors .  mouthfeel : crisp , clean , and refreshing .

the nose also shines.. it 's belgian sweetness accented by a unique floral combination of spicy zings and zips . for a lighter , saison style beer , this showcases alot of the darker , overripe belgian-associated fruits in the nose like figs and dates . also , a dark brown sugar syrup aroma wafts ... competes fiercely with the scents of a flower garden . this is one outrageously complex nose to wrestle with . thick and spicy ... that 's the best way to describe this . a base more suited to a bspa allows for a silky , syrupy , stomach-warming beer that insists on sipping for enjoyment . very floral character is perfumy in the way that hops are n't , and the bitterness associated can be quite jarring . almost like eating the non-edible petal of something aromatic like a rose . perhaps not the most drinkable beer due to three floyds ' patented excess , but a noble effort at a style- applause-worthy .  m- medium body with good carbonation .
it has a strong aroma of roasted malts , coffee and lots of semi-sweet chocolate . the hops are very bold , but not quite over the top .  the palate is super smooth .

drinking it out of a frosted pint glass the appearance is a very appealing light caramel color that is very clear .  m - mouthfeels great , medium body , well carbonated and very drinkable o - not bad , not impressive either.. pretty good .

from the token `` snow '' effect to the jet black body to the creamy firm head , you ca n't beat the visual effect . it leaves nice rings down the entire glass .  a touch of burning alcohol on the finish , shocker . mouthfeel : actually pretty full , smooth , and round drinkability : 1 can after two other beers ( earlier ) is gon na get me buzzed i think , but the sweetness means i could never have more than one of these ( even if i wanted to ) conclusion : we were having crappy beer night tonight as a joke .

1/2 cap has great retention and produces massive lacing . beautiful golden sparkly color is exactly what i look for in a summer beer .  the mouthfeel is on the heavy side of medium bodied , and it glides down your throat as smooth as hell .
i may be a little biased , but i love to just admire and look at beers this black and opaque .  m/d - crisp , medium body with excellent carbonation .
sugar & cinnamon cookies as it warms . phenomenal . t : hot !  body is medium with medium-low carbonation .
insanely sweet . is there even hops in this ? ? ?  it had a smooth feel with slight carbonation and a crisp finish .
s- wonderful , big oak presence in the nose , vanilla and coconut as well as some faint floral undertones .  smooth and soft , mouthfeel alone is not bad at all .
very rustic labeling , i like it . the smell is unique . it has a ton of citrus an coriander , it almost smells like a wild witbier .  mouthfeel was nice . nice carbonation with a boozey sting .
smells like a fresh bag of kind hops . this is the beer that got me into hoppy beers about five years ago .  nice carbonation level and easy to drink .

pretty typical looking ipa . tons of tangy citrus tangerine and ripe grapefruit with a touch of dankness . this is pretty much my standard for west coast ipa aromas - very few brews smell better , and if they do they deserve a perfect score . d - solid example of the west coast ipa style - i just wish it tasted as awesome as it smelled . the feel also makes it a little less drinkable , as the burning carbonation becomes a little unpleasant .  the smell is malty , with noticeable alcohol and more hops than seem to be present in a sip . there are a lot of flavors in this mix -- fruits , caramel , chocolate -- and these flavors pack a complex punch in the smell and taste , as does the alcohol , which causes sensation up the nose . overall , it was too sweet for me , like figs buried in sugar . i suspect i would have enjoyed the malt flavor greatly if the sweetness and alcohol were taken down a notch . i do n't consider this highly drinkable : 500 ml was far too much for me to finish .

it 's nice , but a bit too one dimensional for me . the aroma is quite good , but it 's just too much of a one trick pony .  it tastes nothing like a real peach . i would compare it too a jolly rancher piece of candy . i do like the fizzieness , and crisp finish , but thats it .
complex and excellent scent . taste of vanilla , oak , hops , alcohol , and clove .  mouthfeel was good .

tart and sweet ... just as a lambic should be . notes of berry , plum , tart , wet paper , and some definate earthy notes ; alot like eathing a blackberry that has yet to fully ripen . accordingly , a sour tongue-lashing ensues after each sip .  still interesting for the genre , but certainly not one of the crowning achievements m : the mouthfeel is creamier than anticipated , not as light as the color would imply , a mild chewiness , with regular coating levels .

a light brown very fluffy head with a dark brown body with mahogany light coming through . good lace left on the inside of the glass . interesting , inviting . i really appreciated the look of this beer but the smell , taste , feel and drinkability were like many other more readily available beers in this area from great lakes brewing company .  mouthfeel : just the right amount of carbonation on this one which i was delighted with but the aftertaste is a bit tart .
the smell is wonderful , fruity at first , and then chocolatey , with maybe a hint of coffee .  m : light-to-medium body , highly carbonated . pretty nice .
s : holy chocolate and coffee batman ! this is extremely interesting . i 'm not sure if i 'm drinking a chocolate latte or a beer .  the mouthfeel is actually decently creamy and well-carbonated .
a : really pretty beer . extremely rocky with good retention and lacing .  mediumish mouthfeel , solid , almost too solid .

pours a copper color with two fingers of sticky , rocky white head .  i get tomato , celery , black pepper and then a wave of cedar . the hops were definitely present in it , but i could n't get past the heavy cedar flavors . sorry , but not to my liking .
wonderful cascading head from this nitro-can . creamy thick head with a clear , amber colored appearance . excellent lace as expected .  texture is quite fizzy and lively .

a - i love pouring stouts and porters . either way , it 's friggin dark . i love the smell of coffee , but besides that , there are smoky notes , and something mellow in there like warm cream . t - love it . definite coffee ( obviously ) , but also a little of a hoppy twang , and a zip of charcoal . d - i loved this beer , but i would n't drink to many .  m : light bodied and crisp like a pilsner should be .

the nose is amazing . i have to say , i just kept going back to smell this one before every sip..and sometimes just to smell it .  the mouthfeel is rich while remaining light , the carbonation is much higher than expected , but it works well for this brew .
smelled excellent , almot identical to ( the amazing ) hop rod rye .  mouthfeel is good but overall this is either not good or not fresh .

s : amazing , get a ton of hops . citrus and pine just exploding into your senses . t : getting a lot more pin than citrus in the taste , a great piney taste though .  mouthfeel is slick and medium bodied .

out of a nitro can this is a classic and beautiful beer . black , even when held up to the light and a creamy smooth head . one of my favorites before i really knew anything about beer .  it is light in the mouth with almost an airy feel to it .
looks really nice .  mouthfeel : medium bodied . lightly crisp and dry at the start , smoooth and dry at the finish .

enticing aroma . probably the best aroma of any beer i have ever smelled before . vibrant fruit notes ; apple , pear , berries and cherries along with a maltiness of cookies and caramel .  m - nice chewy mouthfeel , what i 'd expect for the style .

however , i 'm not sure this beer does credit to the artist ... bilious creamy toasted head tests the very laws of physics on the rim of my glass . tight and thick lacing coats the sides . the head eventually falls to gracefully dusting the surface , like frost on a frozen lake . the color is a deep burnt umber with warmer red tones . its very dark , but not quite opaque .  mouthfeel is light with good carbonation .

massive tan head with pretty solid retention that takes about 15 minutes to settle to a thick disk , leaving patchy foam on the glass s : hoppy with a earhty , citrus hop character ( cascades ?  m - mouthfeel is nice and full and goes down nicely d - pretty decent dunkel .
the appearance is as good as they come .  m : medium bodied with medium carbonation .

i really enjoyed the smell . very interesting mix of peat smoke and fruity , like strawberries preserved in a mix of syrup and scotch , with maybe a bit of starch ( curious to know if this was due to aging ) . the aroma stole the show , the flavor did n't quite make the grade for my taste but i still enjoyed quite a bit .  m : pleasant .

s : delicious . like fermenting dough and just a touch chocolate .  you get a slight taste of toasted malt and honey , then at mid-palate the flavors develop from slightly sweet to mildly tangy . do n't get me wrong , i love punchy beers , but sometimes it 's nice to enjoy something a little milder . this is mild and easy-to-drink without being bland . it did n't exactly rock my world , but it was n't bad at all .

a- these stouts are beautiful black with a nice thick off white head .  fruity , yeasty smells are overwhelmed with sourness . there is some sour fruitiness up front , which is quickly overwhelmed by a vinegar-like taste , finishing off with a bit of bitterness . i really wanted to like this beer , liking more saisons , and various sour beers , but there is too much of a vinegar-like taste for me in this beer .

s : very fruity nose . some dark fruits mixed with candi sugar and sugared candy fruits . strawberries , raspberries , pineapple , tart white mango . grape juice .  m : mouthfeel is generally good and like most stouts i 've had .
appearance : wow . viscous , opaque , chocolatey black with a luxurious cappuccino head that retains very well .  mouthfeel : this has a full creamy mouthfeel .
all very pleasant here . a mouthfull of this beer gives first a fair amount of cloves , then the fruits fill out the rest of the mouth .  m : full body with little carbonation .

special thanks to vapodge for sharing poured into a dogfish head goblet a- dark brown with a small white head s- vanilla , fruity and some alcohol/rum t- caramel , spiced in the end , there 's a nice sequence , one after another with a nutty flavor after the end when you breathe ! m- creamy and smooth with good carbonation d- great brown and easy going !  medium mouthfeel .

appearance this is a brilliant , crystal clear lager halfway between orange and brown with a nice , off-white head that left lacing on the inside of my pint glass . i just couldnt stop staring at it the color was so brilliant and perfect .  it has a very thick mouthfeel and a kind of grapefruit like flavor .
great aroma . complex and deep .  nice creamy body as it goes down .

complex aroma of sweet malt , dark fruit , peanuts , and alcohol . very interesting and every time i took a whif i could smell something different . it is still delicious however . sweet , milky , and fruity with a hint of alcohol on the finish . a very good doppelbock and worth seeking out .  the body is creamy and light with prickly carbonation .

great belgian smell.. dark fruits , sweet raisin paste and brown sugar delights waft gently into my nostrils . tastes very sweet.. very sweet.. fruit is there , but it 's overripe and accented by a slightly metallic disintegrated hop character .  tastes like it smells , with sweet malt , light caramel , corn , grass , light floral hops and grains ; basically it 's a lager and just ok. mouthfeel is light and crisp , with a light body , light carbonation and good drinkability ; a light a refreshing beer that basically has no flavor .
this brew is pretty nice looking . huge carbonation is apparent . lacing and retention are both actually quite good for the style .  the mouthfeel was good , as it was heavy and grainy .

pours with a massive , 1/2 glass full of foamy white head , over top of a pretty hazy golden body that masks the ever so tiny bubbles .  there is a definite hop bitterness that tries to balance out any sweetness that is left over , but gets lost in the wash. that being said , it 's bold in the body and has a pleasantly smooth but lively mouthfeel .

aroma is milky and roast coffee grounds , mild chocolate , overall smells fresh and real , nice for a coffee beer , if not a little one dimensional .  good and refreshing crispness in the mouth , which provided some balance to the flavor .

a nice orange color with the most impressive head i 've ever seen : absolutely solid .  the flavor may have been off but the body is very nice as it has a semi-thick viscous texture without overwhelming the drinker . the body allows the flavors to be conveyed more smoothly than a higher bodied beer while the carbonation is mild enough to not contribute any carbonic bite .

( t ) - similar to the smell in alot of ways . a dry grassy earthy cheese to it . ( d ) - a decent gueuze . smelled and looked great , but some off-flavors keep this from being great . still enjoyable though .  medium mouthfeel .
appearance ; clear , deep amber , light tan head , excellent rention and beautiful lacing . about as perfect as it can be .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation . pretty smooth .
this brew pours with a vast amount of carbonation and produces a beautiful sticky and light tan head .  all that being said it felt quite nice on the palate with good levels of carbonation .

canned pumpkin and nutmeg . like other st big beers , a tremendous smelling beer . t : somewhat heavy on the spices and less on the actual pumpkin and earthy squash but the sweetness is far from artificial . maple syrup , graham crackers again which is fantastic . best way to describe the taste of this one is a well made pumpkin pancake .  ... the aroma is super malty , brown sugar , bread , prunes , dark fruits and grape soda dominate , a hint of yeast and alcohol on the finish . a super malty aroma , taste crushes your senses with hops and alcohol . almost makes me gag . this is so bitter , like they confused a dopplebock with double ipa . the hops are totally misplaces , trying to be creative , just ruined the beer .
