served in a pint glass , the beer pours a hazy dark amber color with a huge 2 or so inch off-white head .  the mouthfeel on this beer is very creamy and pleasant , however this beer seriously taste like they made a guinness and then ripped out all the good taste .

thick , black , totally opaque . gorgeous head that forms a meniscus on the glass before slowly dropping , leaving sheets on the sides as it does .  mouthfeel is nice though , smooth and just right in the carbonation .
very nice aroma of hayloft , some barnyard , molasses , dark syrup , coffee and german bakery .  just as smooth as it is crisp . wet maltiness , toasty with a slight tiny sugary note .
the smell is awesome . think if someone dropped a banana in a glass of orval .  the feel is almost chewy and very dry .
exceptional . taste offers only a hint of sweetness on the aftertaste . it is really quite good .  fairly full in body , awfully fruity for an ipa with distinct apricot flavors .

the smell is strong and elegant with lots of rich hoppy flavours ; lots of fruits ... red apples , raisins , apricots , fresh raspberries . there are some very fragile spicy notes of cinnamon and allspice .  m : thick and heavy , but not cloying .
nose : a nice rich pine , grapefruit , and floral is the initial aroma . the nose is better than the flavor .  the palate is smooth .

a - poured into a squatters ipa glass , it had a deep pruney appearance , big nice-looking head for a doppelbock . s - big and raisin-y , cinnamon-sugar , like a pastry at a bakery . t - raisins encrusted with sugar , this was a sweet brew - too sweet to my palate , i could not find anything to dry it out .  mouthfeel is medium and highly spritzy with tons of champagne-like prickle .
looks great , smells even better , but tastes just about as fake as a spontaneously fermented beer can get .  m & d- i do like the mouthfeel , it matches the style nicely .
beautiful looking beer .  the mouthfeel is quite good .

smells sweet with bubblegum and marshmallows with a little hint of lime , but the sweetness is contained with an awesome , herbal spiciness . if you just pour this one into your glass and just look at it and smell it , you wont be disappointed . sadly , the flavor isnt all too hot .  mouthfeel is good .

falls at a decent rate and clings to the glass leaving gorgeous lacing . everything you 'd want from a great stout .  the mouthfeel was decently thick . this beer needed carbonation and some balance to it .

aroma is absolutely great . big chocolatey sweet roasted malts and complex floral overtones . quite nice . chocolate and some whiskey-like flavors .  m : medium carbonation , light body and a nice dry creamy finish .
retention is pretty impressive and it leaves quite a bit of lacing on the glass . really pretty looking barley wine .  really good smooth , medium mouthfeel in this one , probably its best feature .

this beer , when poured , is as black as oil with a great nice tan head that is fairly thick that lasts a good bit . this beer looked so amazing but when i tried it , it tasted really mild as if i were drinking a coffee watered down with milk .  on the plus side , very smooth .

s - this beer smells awesome . it really smells like a biscotti , it 's like i can actually smell wafers . t - taste is not quite as good as the smell , it 's a little bit flatter , but still nice . sweet chocolate , little bit of coffee , vanilla , oatmeal , touch of cinnamon maybe .  decent mouthfeel , medium-full with the right amount of carbonation ; probably the best aspect of this beer .

s : perfect ! candy-sugared-bananas-and-pink-bubblegum-yumminess ! very nice .  m : nicely bitter , typical ale feel with alcohol front and center , no foaming action . t : overpowering alcohol made this seem like i was having a shot , the licorace flavor and hops fruitiness were strong but a bit of a can taste and a thin malt flavor ended it .
i like hoppy beers and this was a great balance with hops and malt . t= beautiful . not to hoppy not to malty .  very true mouthfeel for a lager .

big raspberry aroma . drew a `` this smells like lindemans raspberry '' from my wife . it shows hints of some real fruit , but i definitely get a slight nutra-sweet tang toward the end , and the bottle lists sugar and raspberry syrup as ingredients . otherwise , this one belongs on its own as a cheap fruit drink .  mouthfeel : fairly heavy and smooth overall : i 'm not at all sure the whole 'double wit ' thing works .

a - big thick black brew with a perfectly creamy , thick , and tight head that lasts for the duration of the beer . solid tan sheets of beautiful lace .  i dunno i expected more from this m - medium bodied with a decent amount of carbonation .
very pretty reddish brown .  body is medium with nice carbonation and a semi dry finish .
overall , bad appearance , but good aroma , feel , blend , and body .  this beer was quite thick in body but not too smooth .

appearance and color , just what you would expect from a quality ipa aroma : wonderful , very piney hops , and even a little bit floral i would say taste : better than i would expect from an average ipa , but i just cant quite taste the hops they way i can smell them in this beer . overall an excellent beer , hoppy to the core , a very solid ipa  m - on the thin side of medium bodied , nice and foamy carbonation .

bottle courtesy of hopdog : poured a light amber color lager with a super huge foamy head with great retention and lacing .  nice mouthfeel with good carbonisation and te freshness of the esterpalate .

poured a nice hazy golden color with a foamy , bubbly whitish head and a large column of bubbles rising up from the middle of the glass .  one saving grace for this beer is its mouthfeel , which i thought was quite good : light and not too carbonated . a poor geuze , overall .

a steady pour yielded 2 fingaz of semi dark tan dense foam , well not that dense as it 's dying down quickly . some flimsy spots of lace .  mouhfeel is sticky with a full body and medium carbonation .
gorgeous oily hop nose , citrus and pine .  pretty good carbonation .
smells awesome !  mouthfeel is dry and crisp , with a medium-light body .

wonderful aroma , smells like a strong hefeweizen , wheat , clove , banana , honey , bubblegum ? my first wheatwine , and it was quite nice . i 've been impressed by terrapin .  nose is a creamy butterscotch sweetness , and palate of creamy sweet butterscotch with a balanced bitter and a touch of gypsum . absolutely one yummy ale and a must try for anyone . bass pale ale has been on my list of beers to buy when the price is right . bass pale ale is a good tasting pale ale that has been around for a very long time . well , i just went through a twelve pack and lo and behold this brew has turned to banta podo , it is nothing at all what it used to be !

very nice color , reddish brown . the beer is very clear , without a hint of haze or sediment . the head is an off-white color , pours a two inch head that settles down to a solid quarter inch through the rest of the beer .  head poors thick and has good retention though s - nice hoppy aroma t - strong hop flavor , but i find it unbalanced , i like a good hoppy beer , but the best in my opinion have a good malt balance m - the only aspect of this beer that i truly consider high quality is the mouthfeel ; it is smooth and dry , very good .

the appearance of this beer is superb . it poured out a clear and bright ruby , almost cherry color . it gave a big lacy head in the glass and had a nice carbonation .  the mouth feel is great , but the musty basement taste is not .

s - what an orgasmic aroma ! i have n't had my socks knocked off like this in a while ! rich milk chocolate , dusty cocoa , notes of cold coffee , and a roasted barley aroma flourish with the brilliantly blended bourbon barrel aroma . not hot at all . no hops at all . while it 's still good , a lot of the subtle nuances and richness do n't make it through . very nice dry finish with just a small hint of warming . a good beer regardless , i like the subtleties of tyranena 's barrel-aging .  i dont know if they have sour tarts in va , but this incense of baby and elderly lambic beers has a unique flavor . it has definite lambic feel to it .
very bold and zesty aroma . lots of bready and yeasty smells with a very spicy character .  the mouthfeel was good with real depth .

presentation : 12oz brown pop top , date clearly stamped , nice ditty about the beer on the back ... damn , seven hop varieties ... appearance : nice hazy dark burnt orange beer with fluffy whipped cream ivory cap with good retention and lacing smell : whammo with the hops ... a nice mix between huge citrusy and pine notes , backed up with just a bit of sweet malt taste : actually not as hoppy in flavor as i expected , though the dry , slightly astringent , mouth-drying puckering bitterness is there ... the flavor profile is actually a bit odd ... it 's kind of earthy , woodsy , and raw , but neither the malt nor the hops really stand out , it 's just bitterness , and while the bitterness is n't overly aggressive or overpowering , it 's just that there 's not too much here to this beer ; the aftertaste is a little bit piney/woodsy and that 's nice , but that 's about all i 'm really finding here . drinkability : so-so for the style conclusion : i was kind of disappointed in this , i must say ; it 's definitely interesting , i 'll give it that , the earthy/wood flavors are nice , but it 's just not quite what i typically look for in a dipa .  huge caramel malt aroma is kept in check by an equally huge grapefruit accented aroma ... simplistic , but i if you like those smells ... its ambrosia . finish is citric , grapefruity and wow massively malty . if i liked massive quantities of hops and caramel malt , id love this ... i dont though and it gets boring to me like i imagine big doses of flavors i like would get boring to someone who didnt like then as much as i do .

bomber into chalice : a : beautiful ruby-brown near black body , with a solid dark-mocha head , with solid retention and lacing .  a smooth , creamy , but still slightly crisp-feeling beer , with enough body to keep a better tasting beer on par with the best of them . the mouthfeel tries to carry this one , but there 's just not much there to propel .

from the bubbles emanate a glorious woodfire aroma that dominates , without obscuring , sweet roasty malts . oh man , that smells good and oh boy does that taste good .  light bodied and smooth yet dry .

the alcohol adds a nice touch that goes perfectly with the sweet malts without making it too spicey/hot . incredible smell . t : the bourbon really comes to the forefront here . notes : man ... if only this beer tasted like it smelled ... the smell was such a tease here . like a cheap bourbon ... the smell was too damn good to not have a slightly sweeter beer and halfway through it i was more interested in sniffing a few more times than finishing it .  good mouthfeel , and went down well .

its balance is unmatched -- orange scented coriander on the nose and coriander spiced oranges on the palette . this beer defines summer to me -- more than lemonheads and bazooka joe , more than bubbles and ice cream trucks , more than open fire hydrants and afternoons on the swings -- this beer is a memory of my childhood , matured enough to hold me in the sun .  good smooth mouthful , did a good job on carbonation .

as i poured it the whole room began to smell like a fresh baked pumpkin pie ... fantastic aroma . appearance wise its a hazy golden pumpkin color ... beautiful . taste wise is where it begins to falter .  mouthfeel : medium carbonation and medium body .
smells great ! t : lots of hops , alcohol definitely noticeable , not very sweet , not much citrus .  it had a very nice texture on the tongue as well as in the back of the mouth .

the nose is all ipa goodnes with considerable orange citrus and lemon zest . considering how great this beer smells , the flavor profile was all the more disappointing . this beer smells so good , i was excited to drink it .  the body of the beer 's great , and pretty ideal for the style .

s : piney with hints of citrus and some herbal notes with just a hint of sweetness . this smells like an ipa should t : flavors kick off with some nice herbal notes and a dash of caramel sweetness from the malt .  emphasis on the hops really drew me in a- a full amber body of a beer . nothing but malt . you need some type of hop flavor when you write six hops on the label though m- creamy and overwhelming taste that attacks your mouth . i do like this aspect of it d- just being honest ... if your battle cry is hops , you need to have some . the unstoppable malt attack makes this not enjoyable .

an attractive hazy orange-red color , with a rim of foam clinging to the glass .  i loved the smoothness , but just ca n't get past strength of the cherry . it had a medium mouthfeel that seemed extremely well balanced . my only complaint here would be that the carbonation is just slightly more than i prefer .

s : great pure nose of lactic acid , direct and full . i also get a lot of lemon and some orange peel .  nice carbonation but remains smooth going down ... not bad at all ... this is a stout ... .by nature not all that drinkable .

smell is huge brandy . lots and lots of brandy followed by a strong sweetness . one of the most drinkable barrel aged beers i 've had and one of the best smelling beers i 've ever encountered  m - medium bodied and slightly chewy . moderate carbonation .

smell was incredible . tons of rich , dark chocolate and some coffee . surprisingly hoppy and quite dry ( almost bitter ) on the back end . this definitely was not one of the easier drinking oatmeal stouts i have tried , but it was one of the most interesting .  m : chewy . good feel .

it smells awesome but when it comes to taste , it in no way shape or form rivals the creamy balance of bcs .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation . pretty smooth here . it did have a very nice mouthfeel though .

aroma : the smell is quite unique . a mix of orange , yeast , and fresh apple blossoms with a very floral , strong bouquet . there is some banana notes in the taste , along with the yeasty smell noted earlier , but very pleasant . perfect balance between malt and hop , so neither is very evident , allowing the more citric , floral , yeasty tastes to come through .  milky , filling , decent carbonation and not overly assulting ... pretty decent feel .

m - good carbonation almost too much but its still very good . nice and smooth too . d - extremely drinkable . while its got a lot of stuff going on it retains a great level of crispness and smoothness that means i could drink this all night with zero complaints .  m - fine . right where it should be . my favorite part of the beer .

s - reference quality barrel-aged barleywine . surprisingly little overt alcohol too . m - full-boded , sticky , chewy , and just plain weighty - perfectly suited to the flavor profile and abv . d - i finished this faster than the other two , lower alcohol , beers .  mouthfeel ; nice almost creamy my first winter warmer and i expected more taste ...
poured a deep oily black hue with a two finger creamy tan head . there was excellent retention and sticky lacing .  mouthfeel is very thick but a nice amount of carbonation .

medium gold color with an enormous , billowing white head that shoots an inch over the rim of the glass . luckily it 's dense enough to keep its shape and not overflow . outlandish amounts of sticky lacing as it slowly recedes , displaying excellent retention . one of the best appearances i 've seen on a beer .  good carbonation .
very sweet . t - sweet slightly toasted brown sugar with alcohol being noticeable . taste like it smells but more robust .  medium bodied and highly carbonated and crisp .
poured opaque black with a nice looking dark tan head and nice lacing on the glass as well .  t- very dissapointing . a peppery start with a soapy finish . md- thick and creamy .
poured a gorgeous oranged amber color with a bubbly off-white head , good slow lace , and a little staining on the glass .  m- good carbonation and quite smooth .

a : espresso color , almost black with a tight creamy head .  not if you like an imperial stout , no . there is a little too much pitch ( black ) in the brew . that is a yummy chocolate nose about half way through , but a little chipped too much with yeast over-all , and maybe a bit too much biscuit ? you can have both better beers and better baltic porters .
big lumpy head that fades quickly but leaves behind clumpy sticky lacing .  medium-full in the mouth with soft and fine carbonation . a meager beer by all accounts .

nose is phenomenal , it 's very fruity and floral , dank and spicy . not sure how he does it with these ipas , but they all smell amazing . wow , this is so creamy and juicy and dank .  the mouthfeel is nice and soft , with pleasant and light carbonation .

pours a dark brown-tinged orangey colour , very healthy beige head , nice dense and bubbly , sinks slowly but great retention , leaving some pretty thick sheets of lace that cling to the glass . looks very nice .  the mouthfeel is pleasantly bubbly , with just enough body to make one quite happy .
poured into a stemmed tulip : deep crimson body with ruby highlights - beautiful color .  decently carbonated beverage with a mild body .

awesome smell t : citrusy , sweet malty up front with a bitter , but not too bitter aftertaste m : seems a little overcarbonated , a little bit prickly d : one of the tastiest beers i have had in a while , would for sure buy this again .  great feel . creamy and heavy , but not in a bad way . the feel is great , but the aromatics and flavor depth are lacking .

s : very fruity , specifically mango/papaya/tropical fruits , very interesting and enticing !  crisp , vegetable flavor but more than the average adjunct lager . nice body and pleasant aftertaste as well .
looks awesome . aroma-yum , some serious belgian funk going on here .  m : the body is medium with a moderate level of carbonation .

the aroma is incredible ! i 'd heard that nelson sauvin smells almost wine-like , but this is amazing ! ( looking on the label , it actually says that . ) delicate , fruity , floral , this is a beautiful aroma hop .  it is smooth , with soft carbonation . it is crisp and refreshing with a clean , short aftertaste .
it is a luxurious dark ruby , has a nice head and lacing is good .  it is extremely smooth with only a tingling initial mouthfeel that smoothens in its finish .
smells like chocolate milk ... only stronger . a really sweet chocolate smell .  and lingers on my tongue . m : extremely creamy head .
pours a big creamy mocha head over a deep black body . outstanding lace and head retention .  the mouthfeel is creamy and the finish has a creaminess to it as well .

this maerzen came out to be with a decent two finger thick , light tan head . the body is a picturesque dark golden amber color , and very well filtered .  mouth : heavy and very smooth . good carbonation level .

while the beer may not have looked all that great , the aroma and flavor profile were outstanding . on the nose i got an aroma of sweet grape juice , brown sugar , toffee , vanilla and considerable smoked salmon . the flavor profile replicates the nose pretty closely , but if anything was even better . given the richness/sweetness in this beer , i was amazed by how noticeable and prominent the smoke quality was in this beer .  mouthfeel is light medium and pretty smooth , crisp .
a : beautiful .  mouthfeel was smooth and medium bodied .

s : strong chamomile and lemon/orange peel aromas and pale malts with mild wheat twang . t : a strongly spiced brew with chamomile taking the most charge , and its power increasing through the brew , to the point where it becomes a bit too much .  m : full-bodied and well-blended with good carbonation . definitely a sticky feel .

s : smells like maple bars and bbq smoke , an intriguing mix which i quite liked . t : tastes a lot like american amber , has that typical rogue pacman yeast with crystal malt base .  good carbonation .

the beer arrives an extremely dark black with a creamy mocha head that 's there for the duration .  md-light body with a smooth feel . moderately carbonated , but the carb sting on my tongue augments the sour .
very nice retention and great thick sticky lacing . excellent appearance .  the beer is light and refreshing with just medium carbonation , so it leans towards the smooth side .

anyways it is extract brewed here so i didnt expect much poured into a standard pint a deep copper with a well formed two finger slight off white head that had great lasting power , aromas of earthy hop and deep brown sugar maltiness neither overpowers the other really.not a real big hop profile on the palate mainly earthy tones with a touch of citrus finishing with that ever present brown sugar/molasses malt extract flavoring in the finish.not bad really with some nuance to it you would never know the alchol content of the beer but it is what it is a extract brew but a decent one at that .  mouth is good .
s - pumpkin pie - sweet pumpkin pie , all the way .  the mouthfeel is nice and dry with a good body and carbonation level .

a- red brown body with an airy off-white head s- spices and fruit , very inviting ! sweet delicate fruit t- spices , bready malts , more sweet spices , alcohol warming m- medium-bodied , good carbonation and alcohol warming d- that nose is great ! a nice beer and the high abv makes it a sipping beer  m - it was crisp , sharp and very smooth . a medium bodied beer with a dry finish .
it really smells like banana bread .  mouthfeel was fine , not too thin , smooth going down .
amazing aroma of freshly mowed grass and hay .  mouthfeel : the carbonation of this beer makes it super crisp with a dry finish .

nice , but not excessive , lacing all the way down the glass . smell : light yeasty aroma , with a belgian spiciness and sweetness . very smooth nose , without being overly mild or harsh . the look and the smell are amazing , but the taste is only just above average .  taste : just as smooth as it is crisp with a creamy medium body , not too much on the clove spiciness but it is there and holds on through the finish .
appearance- deluxe looks , clear red-orange with an abundant tan head and much lace . a beauty .  thick , smooth , lightly carbonated .
a- a hazy orange liquid with some streams of carbonation creating a massive , craggy white head that has excellent retention .  m : good medium body with a smooth feel throughout .
a big fat foamy off-white bubbly head with great retention and superb lacing .  has a creamy mouthfeel and was mildly complex .

walnut colored pour with a very healthy mocha colored head that stays put .  nice puckering sandy dry mouth feel . the key to the witbier style is taming the coriander ... making it present but complimentary , not dominant ... i 'll take hoegaarden thanks ... .this wit is not ddc 's strongest offering .

appearance- pours an off-gold color with a big , white , rocky head . it tries to stick around for a while , but dissipates leaving a respectable amount of lacing .  despite this , the mouthfeel is solid and fairly creamy with a nice dry finish .
grapefruit notes from the hops dominate upfront , followed closely by a bit of sweet malt . yep , this is certainly hoppy .  the mouthfeel is at least good . very crisp and clean .

i treated myself to a bottle of this sweet stuff . as for aromas this maybe the most aromatic beer i have ever had . tootsie rolls and chocolate pop tarts is what comes to mind . good but not great . oh and tampa bay stunk up my parlay today too ..  full bodied and slightly smooth .
pale golden with a huge , cavernous , frothy , white head . the retention is insane and the lacing is phenomenal .  a nice mouthfeel , with plenty of creaminess .

the appearance is just stunning . it pours like silk , just this great smooth 'motor oil ' type liquid pours so so smooth . both brews came to a two finger head that was the color of light chocolate . it left a really weird lacing that is sticky and spread all over the sides of the glass .  very coating mouthfeel , stays with you .
smells great . t : a little sharper here than in the nose .  the interesting thing is that the body did not feel light ... . actually pretty full .
wonderful aroma consisting of black malt , coffee and molasses . overall , this is a good brown ale sporting a hefty abv .  nice , filing carbonation , medium-high drying at the end . very nice .

great divide hercules ipa 22oz bottle 3 month recent bottling of review date 07/06 slow pour in a tulip glass poured copper with a thick fluffy , slightly gunky , yellowish long-lasting head smelt of floral and citrus , a hint of pine and alcohol taste was a deceptively fast accent to hops with a lingering hoppy finish .  this was best part of this beer .

pours a dark amber with a massive dark amber head of dense foam that slowly melts to very sticky and thick lace .  mouthfeel is big surpy almost very full but how could it not be considering the malt in this beer .

delicious coffee smell , you can really tell its added for aroma . but a nice bittering finish to carry out the nose . d : a good beer to definitely be drank chilled . i am pleased that it is now in a 341ml bottle as opposed to the 650ml of old .  mouthfeel was refreshing and zesty .
smell - best smelling beer i have had yet ! the coriander mixed in really boost the smell of this beer .  mouthfeel is good with a nice clean finish .

the appearance is black with a thick tan head . because of the carbonation , it 's easy to pour this beer a little too aggressively .  mouthfeel was the most notable portion being medium/light , crisp , and coats the mouth nicely .

this dissappeared quite quickly and left only a thin line round the edge ... aroma - full on peaches and cream , floral notes.. taste quite sweet with a big peach hit.. nice lambic tartness in the background.. feel - very smooth with almost no carbonation . overall - a good fruit lambic ... maybe slightly sweet for some tastes but very drinkable none the less ... recommended ...  m : highly carbonated to complement the pepperiness .
wonderful rich coffee nose . cocoa , campfire and sweet cream/milk chocolate . outstanding .  has a fairly refreshing clean finish , and nice body .
appearance is very nice . a smooth amber body that 's fairly transparent and filled with nice small sediment .  not very sweet . solid body with a lot of carbonation .

smells fantastic . loads of caramel , toffee , dried fruits , nuts , and earthy hops with wisps of roasted and toasted malts .  m : average , fine ... . good carbonation , nice density and thickness .

an aggressive pour into my stone levitation glass resulted in a 2.5 inch light tan head wit good staying power and impressive lace as it fell . when held up to the light it was nearly garnet in color . this color is a little off for the style but none the less quite attractive .  medium carbonation and a thin body that finishes mostly clean with a touch of dry euro-hops .

great aroma , detectable hoppiness and aroma right up front . beer was looking very promising at this point . it was faint , they may have just rushed this one by a week .  mouthfeel : crisp and clean , it feels more like a pilsner than an ipa , which , in my book isnt necessarily a bad thing , but it is unusual . overall : alaskan made a half-way decent ipa here , but it seems much more suitable for a hot night in georgia than anytime in alaska .
the smell is what i liked best because of the caramel & chocolate , smelled like the worlds best desert .  feel is medium body with ample carbonation .
absolutely fantastic . taste is surprisingly sour .  m- the mouthfeel is medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . pretty average when compared to other beers within the style .

the aroma of this one is pretty intense . rich dark malty odor but also some sweet hints in there as well .  mouthfeel is pretty full-bodied , with good , medium carbonation that fills things out . overall , this beer has only the minor trappings of a successful one ( looks , mouthfeel ) .

bottle labeled , `` limited spring 2003 release '' the apperence is a nice thick stout with a deep dark brown body and a chocolate-mocha colored head that retains low but the thick lacing proved to be quite nice .  m - not bad ( if it were not for actually having to experience the taste to experience the mouthfeel ) full and smooth with active carbonation .

smell - wow , nice strong hop smell , also quite fruity , hints of orange and grapes are present . really great smell . taste - pretty darn good , starts out with a hoppy citrus taste that makes way for a powerful hop bitterness that sticks with ya .  m- medium bodied , moderately carbonated .

twelve ounce bottle , moderate pour into a tulip glass , yields a solid two finger off-white head over a deep amber-mahogany body . extensive lacing . pretty beer .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied and quite smooth & viscous . moderate carbonation .

an average winter offering with kudos on the varied , season oriented smell . maybe letting one rest for a year would bring the flavors together .  it has a refreshing dryness that definitely aids this beer and makes it very drinkable . it is a decent beer but i wish the jasmine was complimented by hops instead of ( maybe , if they are there ) overpowering them completely .

poured 40 degrees fahrenheit into a dogfish head shaker pint . pours a lucid gold with a tall 3 finger white head settling into a persistent cap . endless stream of champagne bubbles coming up from the bottom .  mouthfeel was pretty good , it was medium bodied , on the thick side , and quite creamy .

smell - exactly like banana bread.. smells delicious . that 's all i really can smell .  mouthfeel - the mouthfeel was pretty good . even tho the head was essentially nil , the carbonation was very active which was noticeable in the mouth .
s - very strong pine , come citrus . o - holy hoppy . a little thick and heavy , but a i enjoyed it .  the mouthfeel is full bodied for the style , with subtle carbonation .

easily the best pumpkin beer , ever ? mayhaps . but the aroma ... oh my lord , the aroma . this is awesome . this is everything aroma in a beer can be . the taste is almost as shocking as the appearance in how it comes across ( frankly , after the aroma , a deep , hazy , dark brown color would have been my guess if i had n't seen it first ) . it 's a pleasing and easy drinking experience .  very thick and viscous with a fairly light amount of carbonation .

the bottle was filled to the brim and looks like it might have leaked a little while shipping , so i decided to crack this one open the day after i got it . being so thick and having the bottle so full made it tricky not to spill when pouring . there was about 3 fingers worth of a deep brown head that clung to the sides of the glass the whole way down .  even though the menu at goose island says that sticke alt is usually a unadvertised `` secret '' beer made by alt brewers in dusseldorf to reward its regulars , it does n't explain that sticke alts are usually made with more malt and hops and brewed to a higher alcohol percentage . and after tasting it , i see why . at 4.5 % abv , its is a little low for a sticke and the hops were nearly non-existent . aromas were rather off putting with a stale malt aroma dominating . this was a very sweet cloying alt with not enough hops to balance and the aftertaste was reminicient of a ringwood brew . they could just take their hex nut brown ale and call it an alt and be closer to the style .
after the smell i was expecting a bit more , but pretty good . mouthfeel is smooth . enjoyable . aroma is very pleasant here .  medium body with moderate carbonation . quite smooth .
its nice , floral , bitter , sappy . nice .  m : decently carbonated but morphs into a nice creaminess . pleasant .

great looking beer .  first off , let me say that unibroue is my favorite brewery and belgians are my favorite style . that said -- dude , the smell of this beer is definitely funky . pretty disgusting . luckily , the toe jam does n't come through in the taste . it tastes like a witbier with a hint of apple . if i want a witbier , i 'll buy ommegang witte instead .

s-bright sour cherries , roasted malt , coffee , dark chocolate -- really nice . wondering though if this should really have a sour aroma though ?  m | a refreshingly smooth mouth feel with a gentle bite that keeps you going back for another sip .

thanks to chad for this tick , drank from a cigar city snifter ... a black body , looks decent . lots of carbonation here , at least three fingers of tan head , good retention and lacing . looks good ... bitter chocolate , roasted bitters and lots of alcohol , off tartness , hint of maple which i attribute to the barrel .  it 's syrupy and thick with a snappy carbonation , and the combination of the taste and the mouthfeel are not quite cloying .

a : pours a clear straw yellow , nice 3 finger bone white head settles to a small cap , lacing everywhere and sticks to the glass like almost no other beer i have drank , save for duvel .  mouthfeel/overall : body is light to medium with light carbonation . pretty smooth drinking .
smell is absolutely fantastic ! ! lots and lots of bright , fresh fruity smells .  mouthfeel is full and syrupy will sufficient carbonation .

) pours an opaque black with a short cinnamon head smells awesome . chocolate covered pork rind ? road tar , smoked ham , alcohol , milky malt , and cheap bacon .  the moutfeel is big and bold , full bodied but again , overpowering on the pallette .
great hoppy aroma . floral , piney and some citrus hops .  m : full-bodied , frothy carbonation , pretty smooth , easy drinking for its size .

it pours out a beautiful beer with a tall head that recedes to a nice thick film and great caking to the glass . it is an amber color . as soon as i open the bottle it has a strong salty hoplike smell that hits me in the face .  mouthfeel medium body with nice low carbonation .

has a huge earthy and pungently roasty aroma -- coffee and raw , bittersweet chocolate . strongly flavored , but pretty smooth . more tangy than sweet . smokiness that reminds me of a rauchbier , but only vaguely . nevertheless , this is an incredibly flavorful stout and you 'd think it would be heavier based on that .  very clean finish and very easy to drink , it goes down very smoothly .

the beer poured well , a very dark ale with a nice creamy bubbly head that settled to a 2mm thickness and then displayed good retention .  a really nice creamy feel to this which matches the beer , not the style imo .
a : looks great , deep red , very vibrant , with a nice off-white head and great head retention . fantastic lacing .  very good mouthfeel .

this beer has a wonderful sweet smelling nose , that exhibits characteristics of , brown-sugar , carmel , butterscotch or a light milk-chocolate .  m - medium , lots of carbonation , coats mouth well .

smell & gt ; yeast , orange , cinnamon , white pepper ( seriously.. it 's strong enough that i guessed it and noted the scent with a few questionmarks beside it in my notebook ... , and then read it later on the menu ... no cheating for this lass ) taste & gt ; sweet , wheat , hops , spice . refreshing . peppery hang with perfume notes . nice even . not my bag , but very drinkable .  mouthfeel : pretty good mouthfeel : full and creamy .

inital pour was impressive ; nice clear caramel brown color , good head , and excellent aroma . distinct hazelnut odor , along with caramel and sweet malt aromas .  m : light body with a very well done carbonation feel .

lot and lots of foam reminiscent of a soda more than a beer , but once gone , left great lacing . it feels a bit thin for a stout but you would never know it was eight percent .  m - nice mouthfeel . does n't feel thin .
the smell is a very nice bourbon smell with a hint of vanlla and mild spice notes .  m 4 the best part . medium plus body , creamy carbonation .

i 'm not generally a fan of fruit beers , but i am a fan of pete 's so i tried this one on a whim with some friends . smell : they do n't call this strawberry blonde for nothing . a rather strong but not overwhelming strawberry scent from the moment you pop the top . if you like the smell of strawberries you 'll really enjoy opening this beer .  light body with fairly high carbonation makes for a decent mouthfeel for a summer brew .

appearance : very nice golden orange glowing body with a vibrant bubbly white head ( amazing retention ) , the lacing coats the sides of the glass with very large bubbles .  mouthfeel has a pleasant sheen to it , but the flavour is either thin or phenolically unpleasant , so it does n't have much to work with .
a- pours a nice shade of black with a lovely brown head .  the medium body is smooth and prickly , and leaves an almost medium finish - nice .

the aroma is loaded with dark toasted malts with caramel , toffee and dark fruits . wow , the malts seem to explode into your nose . the taste like the aroma is dominated by the toasted malts with plums , toffee and caramel . wow , this brew is nothing short of delicious !  mouthfeel : thick and creamy . ignoring the taste of burnt things the nitro rocks for mouthfeel .
aroma is vanilla , coconut , browny fudge , and delightful chocolate .  taste/mouthfeel : medium body with nice carbonation .

poured a delcicious deep amber that was absolutely clear . the carbonation was perfect ; a two finger head persisted for several minutes before leaving a thin lace .  the mouthfeel has nice carbonation but the smell is bland .

s - big fruity cherries , pineapple , and apricot up front balanced by a strong hop backbone ... a little piney and a little citrusy , very nice . solid maltiness comes through as it warms leading to a great balance with the fruit and hops . nice , but very hoppy and not enough of the sweet fruit in the taste . decent , but i would like it to be a little smoother for as a barley wine . the hops are a little over the top to keep a very drinkable balance . decent , but not one of my favorite barley wines .  good mouthfeel with nice carbonation that is very smooth on the tongue with a somewhat crisp finish .

the bottles poured a nice dark brown with a tan head that stuck around really well , considering it was poured into a plastic nats cup .  almost belgian levels of malt-fruitiness . other than the foul taste , the body was decent , but the nasty flavours killed any drinkability .
pours pitch black even at the thin edges of the glass . darkest brown head i 've ever seen , very thick and creamy .  good carbonation makes for a crisp and clean mouthfeel .

great smell , absolutely great , a full nose of american hops with a great floral and citrus kick to it . good taste , but it does n't match up with the scent ; good hops , nice floral and citrus american style , but has a slightly watered down taste . worth it for the scent alone .  i do like the creamy mouthfeel this beer has , but by now , it is too late .
an explosive light white frothy creates an almost three-finger head .  mouthfeel is fine . reminds me of abrasive .
s - freshly brewed coffee dominates . earthy .  body is light with good carbonation .
this beer , in a tulip , was exceptional . gold color , thick white head , lots of lacing .  m : good feel , nice level of carbonation and just the right thickness .
this is the best beer ive erver smelled . period .  taste is good , mouthfeel is quite good .

drank on-tap at plan b burger bar , glastonbury , ct served in a pint glass the crystal clear , amber colored liquid was topped by a tight , sticky , two-finger , sea foam cap . a thick spiderweb of clingy lacing stuck all down the sides of the glass .  the hops jump right out from the bottle and sting your nose as the beer pours into the glass . do n't get me wrong there are plenty of hops , maybe too much , but i think as an effort to try and dry out this beer , the brewer added a lot of simple sugars which created more alcohol , and then to counter or mask , he added more hops . the finish is dry and clean with very little lingering hoppiness at least for a iipa . i was very excited to see this brewery 's beer being distributed in ohio . we do n't see many style defining west coast iipas in the midwest so it 's a real treat to find something that stretches your palate . even though this beer deserves low marks for drinkability , its intense aroma was worth the eight dollars i paid for the bomber .

a very nice sweet citrus and tropical fruit tone dominates the aroma . the taste fails to deliver on the promise of the smell . i 'm happy to have tried it , but i do n't really understand the hype .  quite thick body , but also slick enough .
smell : a tropical sweet fruitiness . a mix of flowers and grapefruit .  low carbonation with a nice chewy mouth feel . very thick !

aroma is intense with apple cider , yeast , and a touch of alcohol . smells exactly like hard cider . no hops . starts out nicely sour and tart , balanced by apple cider sweetness , phenolic esters , followed by a peppery warm wave of alcohol , fennel and anise .  the mouthfeel is fullbodied with good carbonation .

head dissipates at a quick pace , and lacing is nonexistent ... s - lots of sweet notes come through . caramel , vanilla , oak , and toffee . very smooth and well balanced ( especially considering the abv ) .nothing is over the top or out of place ... m - goes down extremely smooth . medium bodied with a medium/moderate amount of carbonation ... o - one of the better american barleywines i have tasted to date . definitely something that i am looking foward to trying again in the near future .  feels good in the mouth , mostly sweet to start , but there is a hint of bitter at the end of the swallow .
beautiful garnet red pour with excellent lacing and two finger lingering head .  m : good carbonation with nice palate clearing abilities .
hazy orange with a yellow hue at the edges . massive , creamy white head that fades very slowly . good lacing .  mouthfeel is a light medium with good viscosity going down with fair carbonation .

s-tropical & citrus fruits and hops dominate . i could have sat there for 10 minutes with my nose in the glass , but many beers to get through on this night so i carry on .  the mouth feel is nice and creamy .

aromas of honey and flowers . there 's a bit of a sake-ish sour tinge to the aroma , and you can certainly smell the minerality and fruit of the muscat grapes used to make this . this is an interesting beer , very cool to try , but i do n't find it to be particularly tasty .  m : lighter side of medium body , medium carbonation , light on the tongue with a sticky dry finish .

after a moment of warming up in the glass , the coconut aroma starts to become very powerful . tastes like toasted coconut and vanilla .  medium body , medium effervescence , good aftertaste where the malt comes out after the hop start .

the aroma is amazing with strong fruity hops and maybe even a hint of coffee ... although i may be crazy .  it has a medium body and a smooth mouthfeel , with the sour flavor laying on the tongue slightly . inbetween a medium and high carbonation , but fairly drinkable .
s : smells pretty damn fantastic . citrus fruit shows up all over the place .  smooth yet thick on the palate .

nelson is west coast ipa incarnate , and i 'm just talking about the aroma : fresh pine needles and citrus rind pair up to wallop the nostrils something fierce . with the freshness of a dryer sheet and the hops sizzling off this thing in waves , there 's nothing not to like about the aroma here . there 's a spiciness to the flavor that points to the rye used ; it 's an earthy and very bright graininess , electrified by the nelson sauvin hops that give it even more vividness . bitter , vinous , earthy , bright , spicy and fruity , all in equal measure .  maybe i got a sixer that went south because something was just not right about this beer . i 'm not going to go through the usual breakdown except these overall comments : i ca n't quite place what hop ( s ) were used for bittering and aroma but it had a really funky smell and taste to it attributed by the hopping . it was n't a skunk smell , which anyone can pinpoint for spoiled brew , but it was enough of an off smell and taste that makes me think the hops in this particular batch were rank . i 'm through the fourth beer over the past week and they all have tasted the same . in general i 'm a fan of what lagunitas puts out but i 'm sorry to report that this particular release has been hard to get down .
really good staying power and pretty heavy lacing .  mouthfeel = very crisp overall = this is my go to cheap beer .

s : sour-sweet lemon , light mangos , faint bananas , soothing aroma of bready wheat-malts mainly , while sweet syrupy sugar on top of belgian-pale-ale-like fruit esters reveals after a swirl ... all in all , a well-integrated and beautifully-balanced aroma , with every `` usual suspect '' for a weizen firmly in place .  mouthfeel was fine , i guess with reasonable carbonation .

the aroma is very pungent but very good . super sweet malts , cloves , banana , spices in the nutmeg family , and maybe a touch of raisin .  mouthfeel : big exploding bubbles , thin , lots of good , filling , `` evaporation '' feel . very interesting .
s : nice belgian yeast and spice aroma .  m -- fine for the style d -- perhaps the union jack ipa i had before this ruined my palate ?

very nice stickage . nose is packed with cloves , some banana , vanilla , lots of higher alcohols and some clearly present honey sweetness as well , and just a bit of graham cracker . not as impressive as i had hoped from the aroma . mouthfeel is undercarbonated and a bit syrupy .  mouthfeel is pretty good but at this point who cares ?

aroma is strong and sweet ; brown sugar and dates , raisins and prunes . the surprise was that the finish was very clean for a beer of this heft . flavor : strong and intensely sweet .  texture is pleasantly smooth so it goes down pleasantly .
the aroma from the sadly spilt beer is delectably complex and strong , and off the nose of the glass the primary smell i get is one of raw hops .  mf : light and carbonated well .

poured this into my pint glass it has a murky orange color with a freaking huge slightly off white 5inch head . lacing is scattered all over the sides of my glass , man oh man this beer looks fantastic .  the mouthfeel was full and approaching creamy .
smells of an overload of milk chocolate , but in a really good way .  the mouthfeel is good though with a medium body .
a - orange-amber with a chunky white head . retention is great and there 's soapy lacing left on the glass .  the mouthfeel is tasty and slightly creamy for a pilsner , but i am liking it .

s : fresh spicy belgian-y tripple nose with a slight hint of alcohol . really smells highly drinkable t : spicy taste , some slight maltyness , and some residual bitterness on the tongue . finishes clean m : bubbles in my mouth and finishes pretty clean o : love the pour and the smell of this one .  m/d - mouthfeel is full , creamy and quite pleasant .

smells like a crazy bouquet of citrusy hops , but i can still detect a hint of malt . this may have the best aroma of any beer i have tried to date . perfectly balanced . body is perfect for the style .  mouthfeel : drying and fairly clean and light .
great retention and great lacing .  m- smooth and well carbonated , with a little zing on the tip of the toungue .
a very satisfying aroma overall .  light-medium body , ideal carbonation smooth .

aroma is sweet malt and pine hops . beautiful head and golden red apperarance .  tastes very much the same : like a slightly above average macro pilsner that has the same aftetaste as old diet soda . '' well , if nothing else , this sure as heck is a cream ale : the body is great .

pours deep , rich mahogany with a one-inch head that descends to half-size and stays ( very impressive for abv level ! ) . some lacing sticks to glass .  taste is smoooth on the mouth . nice feel , but the vanilla isnt working for me completely . seems a bit too artificial .
bountiful and fragrant fresh hop aromas . very inviting for those who enjoy the hop bite of a good ipa .  the mouthfeel is done well , pretty thick , with low carbonation .

this was a nice smell . it was fruity and nutty and sweet all at the same time . t - tastes almost as nice as it smells . d - very nice . it is light on the stomach and great on flavor .  m-grainy and rough on the palate , huge carbonation to balance a creamy syrupy body that coats the throat .
smells of wonderful dark fruits enveloped in some spiciness with a strong malt presence , some phenols and a hint of alcohol .  the mouthfeel has a medium to full body , with light carbonation .

smells fantastic ! can detect slight caramel and alcohol in the background . delicious . tastes a little hot right now though , slightly decreasing its drinkability .  the mouthfeel is well carbonated , light , and smooth .

the nose has become heavily and enjoyably influenced by the brett with a earthy hay scent . the yeast plays the biggest role of all and i 'm loving it . the taste is slightly more subdued as the earthy yeast tones seem to have recede as the hops and spices combine for a quick zip of flavor .  m - great prickly carbonation , light and crisp .
pure black with an imposing tan cap .  the body is on the fuller side of medium with a low carbonation level that gives some wateriness . pretty good .

) with other hop nuances and malt to balance it out , very nice . taste-spicy hop at the beginning and then balanced out by some caramel malt finish , huge hop hits on the end of the toungue , very nice .  very crisp , no real aftertaste .
aromas are great , and very powerful . noticed them from the pop of the bottle .  mouthfeel : thick and creamy , not nearly as assaulting as i 'd figured it would be with the carbonation level .

smell is fantastic , pure belgian .  carbonation is right on and adds to the fullness of the beer , however , the `` hop '' factor of the ipa is overpowered by the malty bitter bite at the end of each sip .

pours a lightly hazy yellow , almost golden , huge fluffy white head forms , settles down to a pretty thick layer , lots of lace chunks stick to the glass .  the carbonation is ideal , one of the best results in my opinion .
nice smell . t starts out with a nice roasty flavor .  mouthfeel was good , as the carbonation made it 's way to the tongue and was well received .

this beer smells positively freaking divine - full of spice and oats and raisins . i mean , i was practically huffing this like glue .  a slightly creamy mouthfeel with moderate to low carbonation is present throughout .
a- pours pitch black . the on this one is awesome , huge , foamy , brown and has the longest retention maybe ever .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

poured from growler into tulip glass . a - poured cloudy dark amber color with huge off white head that slowly dissipated leaving moderate lacing around the glass .  this is a fresh batch : `` the batch id that you entered '7089 ' , is a bell 's pale ale . your bell 's pale ale was packaged on september 28 , 2005 , '' but i have no idea where the hops have gone . the only hint of them is the bittering in the finish ; there is no hop flavor . it does n't taste bad , but it also does n't taste like an apa . very disappointing , especially when compared directly to founders ' superb version of the style .
decent stick and retention .  mouthfeel : fine . refreshing . nicely carbonated .

blackest pour i may have ever seen from a bal-aged imperial stout . beautiful head on the pour that stuck around longer than expected , great lacing .  there is a nice carbonated mouthfeel that you might expect from a lager . the carbonation has grown less as i drink it , but even near the end there is carbonation to speak of .

the smell is strong and alluring , hops flow out the glass . the hops are strong and aggressive , though there is a slight burnt taste that compliments the finish .  m- good thick syrupyness , i do enjoy this aspect of this beer . the really only redeeming quality is the good mouthfeel .

pours a crystal clear light gold with a pillowy 3 finger head .  m : light body and heavy carbonation . oily up front , but crisp in the end . the aroma was fantastic , and the mouthfeel was very good , but in the end i just ca n't keep tipping this one back .
a : pours a lovely brown with amber hues . a striking , 2 inch head sits on top and sticks around at 1/2-1 inch for a bit . looks lovely .  the is good carbonation and thickness .

nose is a mix of rich dark roasted milky chocolate , granite , some soft soap , peaks of alcohol , a nice subtle fruitiness , mild touches of earth , fresh roasted grain , mild fire , but just this overwhelming milk and chocolate smell . very inviting . taste is medium to full bodied with lush sharp dark chocolate and extremely strong espresso bean flavor .  mouthfeel : medium bodied , the carbonation was right on the button as soon as i cracked the bottle .

it looks a little lighter than i remember maduro . it smells like big sound , of all things , mixed with a shot of espresso . it gives aromas of chocolate , sweet malt , cream , with a light coffee bitterness . overall it 's a solid beer , but maduro is far superior in my opinion .  m & d : refreshing and light on the texture ; while the hop bitterness is very welcome in this otherwise very sweet ale , the overall flavour is awkward and shows no balance ... more an intriguing ale than a delicious or quaffable one .
s- very nice smokey malt scent .  decent amount of carbonation , which seems to fit with the flavor .
impressive head with lots of rockiness while it recedes slowly . nice lace . the color is deep , dark brown .  m : medium bodied with a medium level of carbonation .

candy like and distinctly phenolic aroma . taste is phenolic and candy-like . warming on the palate yet hot with alcohol.. musty and earthy with undertones of blood and iron . mouthfeel is very distinct , light to medium bodied with an aspect of wine to it , ca n't quite find the word to describe it , other then winy .  mouthfeel is oily and well carbonated .

the smell is of very strong bananas and cloves and has a brown sugar sweetness to it . it actually smells like a dunkel . it 's very sweet .  mouthfeel : a thick , chewy feel , with little carbonation .

poured from a half-gallon mason jar `` growler '' ... creative i suppose , yet not worth the 15.50 they charge for it ... the barkeep informed me that this was hands down the strongest brew made by hazel dell ... this seems to most definately be a dopplebock ... pours with a decent head and nice lacing , smell is of very floral and fruity hops.. a bready malt character looms over the palate with the hops and some mild alcohol sugars on the finish.. alcohol kicks in after the fact , so beware.. cheers !  m - it was crisp , sharp and very smooth .

if i were to mention smoked salmon , mocha , and fruit cake to someone , they would probably say yuck , but it really works in this beer . the mouthfeel is big and creamy , very good . the drinkability is pretty good as the alcohol content is n't too strong .  m - really well carbonated , yet smooth .

produced a huge foamy light tan colored head with great retention behind it . plenty of lacing here and there .  note : this is the review of creamy mcstout , not the cream stout . says on the menu it has a `` special ingredient to make it taste more like bailey 's irish cream . '' that special ingredient tastes like it is vanilla syrup extract , and a lot of it , and it really brings down the beer . in my opinion cream stouts have enough sweetness on their own , but this syrup blunts any of the potential subtleties found in the flavor . it was dark , rich , and smooth , but too sticky-sweet and one dimensional for my liking .
this beer has an immense aroma , which sets a high standard that the flavor does n't quite meet .  mouthfeel is smooth and warming .
smell : sweet and malty but dominated by citrus hope . hints of pineapple and tangerine .  it has a medium to full body , with ample carbonation , a prickly middle and dry finish .

sweet citrus , fresh sliced oranges and tangerines hit the nose in the initial blast . later on it becomes more `` green '' and herbal , still extremely resiny and pungent . best belgian ipa i 've ever smelled ... though this one has a decidedly american slant .  the mouthfeel was good .

this one poured out a rich , reddish amber color with a decent-sized , off-white head . bottom shimmers beautifully and the puffy head maintains itself for a while .  carbonation was spirited making for a tingly mouthfeel .

smells like some type of healthy breakfast cereal- bold and full of grains . the grains are very apparent again with a very sweet lingering effect .  it 's the opidomy of light , the smoothness of velvet , and the price of mexican dreams . degrading this beer comes at a great insult to anyone with a ba , mba , phd or techinical certificate for the lessor of us . i swear the old texts , properly translated , would describle jesus actually making water into natty . it 's constant . this beer is the appertif of beers .
aroma was a beautiful array of fruits , just the right amount of sweet caramel , and floral hints for good measure .  average . m- very refreshing feel .

i can hardly see the beer underneath a gigantic foany and frothy cream-colored head that obliterated my glass ... dark-brown caramel-colored hue underneath the immense top ... strong aroma of cider , sugars , and alcohol noticeable ... red bottle logo specifically states `` 9 % alc./vol. '' ... the taste also complements the hefty abv with a noticeable alcohol presence underneath flavors of figs , prunes , malts , caramel , vanilla , and raisins ... not my favorite beer from de dolle , but a worthy sample nonetheless ... good , creamy and rich mouthfeel , but drinkability took a hit due to the noticeable alcohol both in the flavor and taste ... also present is an undeniable essence of syrup , mollasses , and a medicinal-characteristic in the flavor ... different ... worth a try ... as a side note , for a belgian strong dark ale , this is a rather bitter depiction of the style with an apparent toffee flavor included ...  m : nice , crisp , and & light-bodied as expected . goes down smoothly . carbonation matches perfectly with style .
smell- creamy , milky , mocha aroma . the best smelling milk stout i have ever come across . as it says on the bottle `` utterly amazing ! '' .  mouthfeel is medium to full .
it pours with a large white head ; lots of lace and good retention .  mouthfeel , in nice and smooth for an adjuct lager , not overly dry ( maybe it 's supposed to be ) .
wow ! ! ! nice . on second sip the honey really is apparant , very nice .  left a very dry crisp mouthfeel .
nice big smell witha bite in it , very much like champagne or a dry cider with some yeast in it . looked bad , smelled great and tasted ... strange .  m - medium to full body , creamy carbonation .

s : rose water , peach , banana , kiwi , spices and some strawberry . t : starts off with a soft blend of pear and banana , really on the basic side and not sweet or sour .  mouthfeel is good as this beer is light on the tongue and not very thick when it goes down .
very promising . smells better than it tastes .  it had a medium feel in my mouth and good carbonation .

appearace - a brilliant orange color with 1 finger of head .  it drinks much more harshly when cold . now is all wintertime spice . and cherry , of course . otherwise , it mirrors the nose being the most palatable . whew . quite an experience and one that everyone should have ... once . props to unibroue for coming up with this , but i 'm not so sure it works .
a- dark brown with a off-white head that laces nicely .  smooth moderate mouthfeel and not too filling - not a bad beer , too .

this beer has an absolutely intoxicating aroma . just a spectacular aroma . the flavors in this beer do n't quite live up to the aroma , but they are still quite tasty . notes of honey mixes with nice malt notes and the finish has notes of higher alcohols that somehow do n't reach harsh , but ultimately provide some sharp balancing notes to the other flavors .  very good mouthfeel . the malts and hops dance around the edges of the tongue with the adequate carbonation .

appearance : this is a real beautiful pint . gold in color , slight chill haze . great 2 finger , fluffy beige head . diminished into a real tight lace that slides all the way down the glass .  m : light body , good carbonation .

a : beer poured black as night allowing no light to penetrate . it was beautifully topped by a 2 fingered , frothy cocoa colored head with great retention and loads of lacing .  m - the feel was nice and even when i swished and swallowed . probably the best part about this beer .
smell is a strong malty syrupy carmel scent , very strong , almost burbon like scent that impressed me .  mouthfeel is ideal for the style .

very sweet , but not overly so , and with a nice hop presence , but not as strong as i was expecting . a great scent , overflowing with tropical fruit and hops . too much caramel and maltiness combined with very little bitterness makes for one disappointing imperial ipa .  the best thing about this beer might be the mouthfeel - good carbonation , and an easy drink .

deep brown with lots of carbonation , huge tan head and it looked really good !  in texture , the ale is very weakly carbonated and quite smooth ; the overall impression is more like a pinot noir than a beer in this respect , and i probably enjoy it more than i should .
s : sweet , chocolate , caramel , roasted coffee , malt , very slight citrus hoppiness .  mouthfeel is decent , not too thin or thick .
very nice . a nice somewhat chocolaty taste with some coffee hints on the swallow .  m - english style carbonation ( soft ) and lighter bodied . appropriate for the style .

s : strong hop aroma that is of strong pine and earthy notes . a touch of alcoholic heat and caramel comes through later ... t/m : wow , what an incredible disappointment .  m : the body is thick and creamy with a moderate level of carbonation .
as this warms up , it keeps smelling better and better .  the liquid 's nicely velvety , smooth as it moves about . body between medium and medium-heavy . very light fizziness .
light copper color with a good head and great lacing .  the mouthfeel is light to medium body with mild carbonation .
aroma is killer , sweet , smooth smelling with floral fruity notes .  pretty nice texture for an aal .

pours a fairly deep black , letting in only a tiny bit of light , with a dense 2 finger head . great retention leaves behind abundant creamy lacing , and a thick blanket of foam on top of the glass . looks great .  m : chewy o : ehh i 'm not so pleased with this whole concept .

nose is hoppy alright , juicy with bubblegum and minty notes . has a nice aroma , but i prefer nn over it . i prefer nugget nectar to this , but it was a fun beer to try .  while i thought the mouthfeel of this beer was quite good , i was not a huge fan of its sour grape and champagne flavor .
perfect . seriously cloudy lace all the way down .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied , lightly carbonated , and smooth .
appearance : more than two fingers of dense , creamy white foam which had excellent retention . straw color , very clear , with a profusion of tiny bubbles .  medium-thin body , nice effervescence .
s - i was very impressed with the smell . you could almost get a hint of each individual berry , yet somehow they all melded together with one sniff .  medium carbonation . a bit dry for my taste .
sweet , wonderful nuts . candied hazelnuts . nice . the sweet nuttiness is subdued in the mouth a decent alcohol burn . potent , but not very complex .  it is quite smooth .

d - after the really nice aroma , i expected more from this one .  body is on the lighter side of medium , drinkability , along with quality , seem to be the missing ingredients in this concoction . & # 428 ; & # 943 ; c & # 409 ; .

a : dark mahogany , bubbles with every drink restores a wonderful white head s : sweet coffee t : dry , nutty , cocoa , and of course lots of coffee , very balanced and smooth m : medium in body d : tasty and smooth , reasonable alcohol , very enjoyable spot on for the style with a nice coffee twist .  mouthfeel is pretty soft but not to thin .
it was poured leaving about two fingers-worth of head . fine lacing appeared after each drink .  very creamy mouthfeel , but i must admit that this brew was far too heavy for my taste .
it fades leaving nice lace , what a great looking brew .  body is quite good and so is carbonation .
the appearance was superb . the beer had about an inch of head and a good amount of carbonation coming off the bottom of the glass . overall , just a great looking ipa .  decent enough mouthfeel .

it poured a good foamy one and one half inch head that slowly dissapated and left a slight creamy lace on top that stuck to the glass throughout the entire drink .  m : medium-bodied with light carbonation .

a : darker than expected , mid-toned brownish amber .  the dry , champagne like finish along with the funky yeast was pleasant , however . mouththfeel was right on with the style , and was my favorite part of this beer .

375ml bottle bought from beermerchants.com ... 2009 bottle poured almost pitch black even when held up to the light ... dirty mocha brown head poured quite very loose and bubbly and faded instantly to nothing ... no lacing.. aroma - very strong sweet oaky bourbon to the fore straight away , very woody and earthy , lots of fresh vanilla , roasted malts , hints of tar , cigar smokiness , rich stewed dark fruits ( blackcurrents and prunes ) , molasses and burnt brown sugar , alcohol is pretty noticeable , fresh black pepper taste - tons of roasted and charred malts mixed with strong molasses / black treacle sweetness followed closely by warming bourbon , lots of vanilla , liquorice , defnite cigar / tobacco smokiness , rich dark sweet fruits ( prunes , figs , raisins , blackcurrents ) , very earthy , espresso , light soy notes , alcohol definitely comes through , dark chocolate ... feel - smooth and slick although as with the ordinary old viscosity not as full bodied as i would have expected ... suprisingly drinkable for a 12 % brew although you definitely notice the alcohol after one bottle.. overall - an amazingly complex stout ... highly recommended .  i 've used pine to describe beers before but never has it been so true . smells like they really got the spruce tips going in here . lingering earthy bitterness and an aftertaste that kind of reminds of what it feels like when you eat something that is n't meant to be edible ( like for instance a pine cone ! ) somewhat crisp , drinkability only suffers because personally i am put off by the flavor .
aroma has scents of roasted nuts , sweet malts , and some cocoa .  m - full bodied , nice carbonation level , and a pleasant warming effect .

i slowly pull the cork out , glass ready , and bam , the cork flies and i immediately get that panic , even though i was still half expecting it ... glass in hand almost right away to catch all the nothing that flows from the bottle . nose is very bready , and actually quite boozy ... then turns into a somewhat of a 99 bananas smell , but not quite as boozy or as banana ... after it warms it turns more toward the saison ... earthy with a hint of sweetness . this is very interesting smelling the changes as this changes in temperature .  on the palate , medium-bodied , nicely carbonated , but not an easy drinker .

nose is fantastic : huge and sweet , dried fruit , cotton candy , maybe some aprioct and kiwi in there too . surprisngly light alcohol , given the abv . overall , a delicious and really unique saison . maybe not one i 'd go for every day , but an excellent beer nonetheless .  mouthfeel is full and round .

this beer smells wonderful . very rich and nutty . it has a nice head and smells great , but it tastes horrible .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel although sticky and overly sweet is not harsh at all in terms of alcohol bite .

aromas of lemon , lemon zest , spicy , peppery yeast . finish is short , lemony , and a little medicinal , almost minty . overall a good bpa . but the minty and medicinal qualities clash , reducing the overall enjoyment .  nice and heavy feel . too big and lacking flavors from the malts to balance off the alcohol and bourbon .

why not ? appearance : golden orange , with a pearly white head with gorgeous honey-comb bubbles that were perfectly aligned one next to the other .  m & # 8211 ; kolsch always has good mouthfeel , it is one of its hallmarks , to me .
a : very dark and delightful , a wonderful looking stout .  a buttery mouthfeel which is unique and nice . medium body and medium carbonation .

s - pungent , fruity hops that are reminiscent of jaialai ipa . d - very nice , the malt and hops are perfectly balanced , especially in the aroma where the fruity notes perfectly compliment the sweetness of the toffee and caramel .  this shows a lot of warm nutty flavors , which is nice , but this is just too sweet , with a little odd , steely bitterness on the finish ... this , combined with the sweetness , just does n't really work mouthfeel : fairly full , which makes the sweetness seem more intense drinkability : medium at best conclusion : this has really nice aromas and appearance , but the flavor just falls a bit flat .
this one goes into my glass colored deep crimson brown with a fat head and amazing lace .  mouthfeel : medium body , medium carbonation , smooth and sticky .

wonderfull crystal clear dark amber with a rich creamy two inches tall , tan coloured head . good but not enough aromatic smell of toffee , wet grass , light chocolate and butter .  m -- -medium bodied with good carbonation .

aroma is fantastic , this all centennail hopped ipa is heaven to wiff in . it does have a little bit of everything wood ; pulp , fresh leaves , green , not as resin filled as the smell leads one to believe , there 's a bit of a strange tang ensueing as it goes in . the smell is wonderful , but beyond that this would n't be one to continue with .  m - very smooth with good carbonation , well rounded .

22 oz . the aroma is extemely full and rich -- - a supersweetness slings tothe resinous that is wrapped around a loaf of bread .  the taste is bitter , more of the citrus but it just taste wrong or something , it 's not very pleasant and leaves this as a long , lingering after-effect , mouthfeel is medium and decently carbonated .

attractive foam/lacing s - love the aroma . it 's like a chocolate covered banana .  the willamette & tettnang hops gave it an interesting bittering character , although i 'm not sure i liked it that much . you do get some malt up from but the hop bitterness really overshadowed any malt character .

but , geeeez , what a wonderful aroma lurks underneath the mess . tangerine and grapefruit along with rock candy and toffee . pears and apples , raisinbread , and a meadow of wildflowers add to the divine nose . mouthfeel lacks carbonation ( it must be on top ) , but is medium bodied and has a unique fruity apple hops bite . taste is well balanced and very complex . much of the aroma is reflected in the taste , so i will simply say that this is one unique pale ale .  m - this has a nice smooth feel to it .
the smell of wood , complex sweetness that i could not place my finger on . i called it `` sour slap '' on my blog .  m - medium mody and moderate carbonation .

nose is still incredible - just exploding with tart fruit ( currants but could easily be mistaken for raspberry ) and some hints of his wheat origin . this is an excellent summer beer and would be great with spicy food .  has a good body , definitely fuller than most ipas . some creaminess .

d : great start , with looks and smell , but once i really got to know this beer , its palatability went downhill .  the mouthfeel was smooth , creamy and fuller bodied with a fine , moderate effervescence .
appearance and smell were excellent . the dark color and rich scents promised so much . the aroma was fantastic , reminiscent of the dogfish world wide stout .  very good for the style .

please dont be infected ... please dont be infected ... bottled 1/13/2010 ... smell is lovely with some alcohol scents and some great maltiness and chocolate ... but the taste ... dammit !  mouthfeel : good body , unfortunately probably the high point of this beer .

aroma- very fresh smelling with a nice mellange of different malt sweetnesses , mild hops , bisquits , etc .  smell - malt smells dominate , chocolate msotly from what i can detect , not overpowering , in fact it 's very pleasant to the nose . the first thing i thought of was wine , sour and not pleasantly so . frankly i do n't like it . overall - a beer that 's exceptional in every area except the most important one : how it tastes .

i poured the bottle straight down the middle of a pint glass and was rewarded with a deep dark color and a nice thick head . the head stuck around for most of the beer which i was thankful for .  it does have a great thick mouthfeel and if i could n't taste anything i would enjoy this well enough .

it is a beautiful looking beverage .  mf : low carbonation , medium body , smooth d : interesting pairing- coffee with doppelbock.. ca n't say that it 's my favorite combo , but i 'm not sure if that is more due to the stale coffee character or if it is the pairing i 'm not the biggest fan of .

poured a dark , golden amber into my affligem gold-rimmed goblet . looks beautiful .  a little bit of hop dryness at the end m : full bodied , smooth , creamy mouthfeel d : this beer was not easy to finish , however i did .

average head retention & lacing s : bready , grassy , lemony , white pepper & coriander . i wish this tasted it like it smelled t : lemons , orange peel & grassyness up front , then some coriander up front , along some nice wheat tartness . finishes crisp & slightly grassy mf : light bodied with slight carbonation drinks really easy , liked this much better than a previous time when i had this on draft years ago ( served too cold imo ) , nice if simple take on the style  appearance : dark chestnut brown with ruby highlights , good clarity , medium layer of tan froth aroma : light roast and malt ; bit of brown sugar flavor : medium malt sweetness with a weak coffee bitterness on the back end ; hints of brown sugar and vanilla pipe tobacco ; finishes semisweet mouthfeel : medium body , spritzy carbonation , soft texture other comments : meh ... fairly lacklustre .
s : it smells great ! very citrusy/fruity and somewhat spicey .  m : a soft and fluffy texture , no carbonation , medium body .

i had this beer at a freinds house and was very impressed with its inviting color and head . i almost wanted to just sit and admire its appearance , but this beer looked to good not to taste .  mouthfeel : heavy bodied .
smell is excellent with some defininte brown sugar present .  m : smooth and balanced . body is light-medium .

smell is fantastic ; the brewery truely nailed this one . i could simply drink this beer forever because of its great taste and smell . plus the great flavor that hangs in the mouth afterwards is so pleasant its almost damaging to pouring another one .  full mouthfeel .

the aroma was easily the best part of this beer . i 've summed up the aroma like this ... .imagine a freshly baked fruit cake with sweet white icing glazed all over the top , sliced apples dipped halfway through the cake and sprinkled with cinnamon . tons of pears , apples , cinnamon , sweet malts , yeast , caramel , dried orange peels and alcohol . i really enjoyed this !  mouthfeel - i actually have no complaints in this department . it 's comparatively crisp and the carbonation is appropriate .
this looks great . perfect amber color with a steady one inch head that stayed the whole time .  well-carbonated and oily on the tongue .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever had . huge , gushing pineapple notes lead the charge , followed by some pine notes . some pale malt notes in the background .  mouthfeel - a good mouthfeel . smooth and slightly oily , crisp carbonation , one of the better areas of the beer .
nice looking pour with a great head retention and lacing .  m-really pretty rich and smooth in body with medium carbonation and a slightly slick mouthfeel .
the head is very nice , about 2 fingers high of medium tan heat that is just beautiful . it is full and creamy and lasts forever with nice lacing .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

*takes breath* appearance- four fingers of light chocolate brown head grace this ridiculously fabulous looking beer . the sheer density of the crown is stupefying , with large craters rather than bubbles marking its surface . like some object from space , it looks like a chunk of ice or rock from the outer limits .  mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with low carbonation .

hell yeah . f'ing chocolate , hazelnut and of course coffee , with a minimum of roastiness . every now and again , it 's great to have an imperial stout that is n't roasty to all hell . whatever coffee they use for this , it seems like a light , bright roast ... dare i say it , a breakfast blend . ok , obviously there is a shitload of coffee in here , but the underlying beer is n't half bad either . i have become a coffee stout fan , actually ... .yeah , mr. farmhouse ale likes to cross over to the dark side every now and again , for sure .  mouth feel is light and smooth . this `` bock '' is very plain and offers little flavor .

i drank this from the bottle into my rochefort glass ... the beer is a cloudy very nice looking peachy orange with a watery head white head that is gone fast ... the aroma is super nice , very matly on the front with lots of orange and peaches and balanced ever so lightly on the finish with some grass and hops ... the taste is also very good , does n't quite live up to the aroma . there is some of sweet on the front not enough to really balance this beer .  mouthfeel : nice light mouthfeel with a decent amount of carbonation .

nose shows a rich mix of hops and malt . big piney , resinous , earthy and minty notes from the hops , while the malt adds prominent caramel , nutty and toasty characters . very nice !  mouthfeel : light carbonation . good to form .

this is overflowing of hop aroma . tropical fruitiness ... a bouquet of citrus ... the taste does not live up to the aroma . i love the aroma . at fist the taste is great , but wears down as it progresses . alcohol and plastic become more noticeable as it progresses .  mouthfeel is good but drinkability is hurt because this is just not something you would want to drink much of .

beautiful aroma . taste is also excellent . bourbon , cherries , dark fruit , caramel sugar - but not overly sweet . not terribly complex , but delicious . mouthfeel is dissapointing .  m : nice feel and goes over easy with lighter carbonation .
