pours dark brown with ruby highlights . tan sea-foam head settles to a surprisingly thick film . lacings completely coat the glass , and absolutely refuse to slide down the glass . impressive .  m - slightly oily , but not cloying at all , which is quite nice . the chewiness is enjoyable as well especially in the throat . i did n't feel ruined for the night from this beer , which i worry about with such strong flavors in this style .

pours a crystal clear deep reddish brown color with a huge fluffy tan head that slowly recedes .  the mouthfeel is a bit creamy as the name implies . overall i 'd say the mouthfeel is the best part about this beer but nothing to get excited about .

an inch and a half of thick creamy foam head is a milk chocolate brown that fades to just a skim as i finish this sentence . body is a usuall suspect jet oil black .  m : moderate body , moderate to high carbonation . appropriate for style .
lovely resinous leafy hop leads the nose . touch of citrus comes through . great to smell , possible to drink .  the mouthfeel is good . it is a low bodied beer with good carbonation .

very stout-like - dark black with a huge , creamy , tan head that had great retention and stuck to the glass on the way down .  m : a light and refreshing mouthfeel that i feel was the best part of this beer . unfortunately , it is more alcoholic than malty , which takes away from its decent body and mouthfeel .

s : initially there 's a bit of delicious yeasty funkiness and as it warms , a much stronger belgian yeast aroma dominates .  this is my first review on beer advocate and i will try to do my best with reviewing beers . a very sweet taste goes down very smooth .

smells fantastic , huuuge hop aroma . overall , this beer is very good , but i wonder if hops are dried before using them in beer for a reason .  very nice carbonation with a hint of heinecken aftertaste .

a clear but dark garnet color at first , it clouds up considerably , chunks up actually , with the bottom pour . the head is three to four fingers , and fades to a thin covering with a dark cinnamon-like corona about a third of the way inside the rim .  mouthfeel : the body is on the thick side of medium . the carbonation is tingly with a dry finish .

the smell is amazing . not sure if i poured a beer , or the sweetest can of ruby grapefruit juice i have ever smelled . a little hop bitterness and toffee scented malts at the very end . nice !  more like a cider , apple-ish and very sweet , low carbonation . mouthfeel is full and round .

smell is very spicy to say the least , lots going on , orange peel , lemon zest , coriander , pretty citrus , a full aroma for this witbier . taste is similar to the smell , very citrusy and spicy , lots of carbonation though typical of the style but could be toned down a bit , very light hop bitterness if any , crisp and easy drinking .  mouthfeel is medium to almost thick . creamy . carbonation is big and loopy , coating the mouth , but at the same time this is not characterized as chewy .

very beautiful . best looking beer i have ever seen .  appearance : golden , cloudy , with minimal head retention ( & # 9733 ; & # 9733 ; ) tastes like : a mild lager should - a touch malty , but none too bitter , with only the faintest hint of hops present ( & # 9733 ; & # 9733 ; & # 9733 ; ) overall drinkability : at the end of the day , schwag clearly bests any and all of the low-end macro-lagers which one may find on the tap ; it 's a pleasant alternative for both the thrifty and the hop- and dark malt-averse ( & # 9733 ; & # 9733 ; & # 9733 ; )
sweet hop aroma , could be dry hopped , maybe a little peppery .  '' m- as with most milk stouts , the mouthfeel is nice and smooth . almost creamy with a little carbonation to add a nice spritz .

drinkability : a great smelling beer , but the extreme head of the first beer and the sub-par taste makes the beer a bit of a chore to drink .  look : brassy hue , crackling lace smell : medicinal , musty yeast , herbal , grainy , exotic fruit , mint , watermelon rind , green peppercorn taste : mild crispness , slick mouthfeel , spicy , mint , orangey , exotic fruit , peppery , bready , mild funk , yeast , warming alcohol , biscuity , faint tobacco , grainy semi-dry finish . a good stab at the whole saison thing , i personally think the saison fad is wavering and only a handful really stand out .
a unique , well balanced , clean smelling brew . the taste brings on a more smoky malt profile .  m : the light body is slightly dry and has ample carbonation .

beer is bright gold and clear , basically looks like a good pils . this one tries to jump out of the glass as it pours with a lively carbonation that creates a thick white long lasting head .  best by 4/25/11 .

the nose is complex like the mind of a woman ! sweet malts right off the bat , a little molasses , a lighter fruit like a ripe pear blended with lemons , does n't smell like maple syrup but it has the same aromatic texture as hot maple syrup , subtle hints of cocoa powder . although this bottle is starting to slightly turn , you still get notes of red apple , sweet malts , nice crisp hop balance . very smoothe , low carbo , best beer by independence brewery by far .  i must divulge that i am somewhat ignorant on strong belgian ales . smell is super caramel and alcohol is present . it says brewed with rasins but the alcohol is so overpowering that it could be mangos for all i know . addmitatly this beer has a time and place to be consumed and at my house tonight is not it .
good lacing & avergae head retention s : big-time citrus & piney hops t : piney & citrus hops up front , then a little fruittyness .  mouthfeel is pretty good , though .

a- dark , dark brown with a tan head s- vanilla and caramel , creme brulee ! i hope it tastes as good as it smells ! t- not nearly as strong as the nose -- malts underlie it all with the vanilla and caramel creme brulee taste staying with you for a while afterwards m- full bodied and creamy d- quite a unique beer ! it really tastes like creme brulee !  mouthfeel is great , smooth , mild aftertaste , does not have the pasty roof of your mouthfeel like other shitty macros .

the nose is beyond sweet , smelling of candied raspberries , followed by light roast , then a vinous smell . spicy alcohol joins the olfactory chorus as it warms .  i ca n't really appreciate much else in the flavor because of the bitterness . still , it feels good going down after the initial taste and i appreciated it more at about 2/3 full .

black with a huge foamy tan head . falls to a tan ring with a continent of bubbles sliding on an ebony ocean .  a semi sweet with hints of orange and lemon twists and a bit of hops for good balance mouthfeel - a good carbonation that matches the flavor and sense of the beer .
pours nearly black and opaque with a huge dense dark brown head .  the thick and coating mouthfeel means the tongue ca n't escape the fusal fumes .

aroma : highly impressive nose . sweet caramel base , with all the farmyard attributes one expects in a good saison and then some . the nose got me all hyped up for something unique and interesting yet the taste is just blah .  m : creamy mouthfeel - high in body for the style and low in fine and ticklish carbonation . slick and yet dry finish .

s : a wonderful sweet chocolate smell with hints of coffee . i was taking a whiff of it before every sip i had . smelling the beer with a sip in my mouth is just fantastic . a nice roasted coffee aftertaste .  mouthfeel- smooth with decent carbonation ... was expecting a lot more ... i had the 2010 version last year and remembered it not being as bitter as this years .

s - holy crap , this smells insanely good . i did n't want to like this , but if the smell indicates anything , this will be a buy-again .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .

s- the aroma is absolutely fantastic ! the nose is very floral with a hint of mint and spices . very complex . t- the taste like the aroma is floral with some spices and the alcohol really does n't stand out very much at all in this one .  light body with good carbonation .

on tap at o'brien night of a million zillion speedways look : black and totally opaqu with a 1/8 inch head and good retention smell : the slovenian hops used to dry hop it created a piney note that did not really work with the coffee backbone taste : sadly the flavor was worse than the smell .  the mouthfeel spoils it . far too coarse .

this fine brew has a big fluffy dense head and lacing that sticks to the glass .  the mouthfeel kind of sucks . it 's medium bodied , but feels watery . i 'm usually a fan of more of a still mouthfeel , but this feels flat basically , probably because the body is so thin .

from a 500 ml brown bottle . massive head development on the pour , a solid foamy mocha coloured entity with amazing retentio that settles very slowly . the body is deep pitch opaque black , faint almond nimbus when held to light .  oily mouthfeel . not at all stout of body - thin in fact .

poured from a 12oz bottle into a delirium tremens tulip glass . the appearance was nice , burgandy colored , clear , with a thin white ring of head .  the feel of the beer is very dry - too dry for me but others may like it .

a- pours a beautiful copper color with a chunky 1.5 finger head that sticks around for a while .  overwhelming carbonation , especially for the style . it is refreshing though , once you get past the overwhelming carbonation .

a - a big thick three finger head of densely packed tiny bubbles distributes a huge amount of creamy lace on the glass , and shows outstanding retention . the lace on the glass looks like icy frost on a window in the wintertime . this looks outstanding , and gets a rare five for appearance in my book .  mouthfeel - very watery .

a : quite a beautiful looking beer , looks brown in the glass but when held to the light it shines a brilliant clear ruby color . topped with a thick foamy light mocha head , and leaves a little lacing , but it does n't matter , this beer looks great .  its corona , does it really need a review ? tastes like lime juice and pulp . head n/a as much as i would avoid buying a corona to drink with a nice steak dinner , theres always a certain appeal to buying it as ambience at a cookout .

poured into a stemless tulip glass with two inches of ivory head that dissipated within a minute or two . leaves heavy lacing along the glass with striations that create some beautiful patterns on the top of this tawny-ruby body . tight bubbles remain on the top as the drink progresses making for an all out beautiful ale .  i 'd never had anything but mexican lagers ... and they range from decent ( dos equis , tecate ) to trendy and crappy ( corona and sol ) . no trace of hops . the one good thing about this beer is that you can really drink it like water .
this beer is absolutely gorgeous , i only wish the head remained a while longer .  mouthfeel is way thin , and drinkability is just not that great for me .
a : pours jet black with a thin caramel head that laces the glass nicely .  very lightweight in the mouth .

bottle courtesy of hopdog : poured a deep clear golden color ale with a super huge bubbly white head with average retention but great lacing .  the feel was thick , creamy , and depressingly flat . almost no carbonation persisted in this pour , which i partially blame on how custom brewcrafters poured the growler , and partially on myself for the long trip from honeoye falls back to syracuse .

this pours a deep reddish amber with head just cresting the top of my glass . retention is about average , but lacing is very good . nothing to really make it stand out ( besides the extremely inviting appearance ) , nothing to love here .  this is too loose on the mouthfeel ; no structure at all .

very dark , resembles guinness in appearance ... tones of chocolate , coffee , even toasted bread ... .very guinness-like in taste as well ... only one small complaint : there is a little too much carbonation for perfect mouth feel .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery .

appearance : pour creates a great looking dense head , very dense . it fades slowly , but almost seems to disappear the way it dissipates , and the fact that the head is so dense and frothy . the beer has a dark caramel color , very inviting .  carbonation is too strong , nearly soda-like , with a plastic-y feel that coats the mouth . lightly sticky .
pours dark and thick like motor oil with a thick fluffy dark brown head .  m/d : the body is very thin and watery .

pours crystal clear dark red orange color with a nice 2 finger dense khaki head with incredible retention that reduces to thick lacing cap that lasts forever . overall this is an absolutely outstanding amber ale/ipa .  mouthfeel was a bit of a disaster , for the style anyway , as it was very thin and lifeless .

the smell is the best part , very fruit with a slight hop scent and a strong yeast scent , taste fruity as well almost like a hard cider , not something i 'm a big fan of , but something thats interesting and an occasional pick up at the beer store  nice but not much mouth - a bit thin , somewhat watery , disappointing given the 'from guiness ' on the label which compelled my purchase . watery again .

a- pours a very nicely bronzed gold color , that while not cloudy , is n't exactly clear either ... just foggy ! the head is awesome on this one , starting out about 3 fingers thick , and eventually settling to a superbly thick cloud sitting on top of the beer . the carbonation looks soft and fine , and the lacing is excellent ... thick sticky foam clings to my pint glass !  m - light bodied , overly acidic .

it also has some of the best head retention in its class . the head is a dark khaki . its very pillowy and once it retreats it leaves a ring around the edge and an island in the middle .  by having a high carbonation with a watery finish .
pours hazy orange body with a tornado of dark yeast swirling around . head is big and frumpy , extremely long lasting and clingy .  m : light on the carbonation , thin & watery .

a- a very hazy orange/ brown liquid with a massive light brown head that has astounding retention .  mouthfeel is unimpressive . medium bodied , but seemingly syrupy ( only slightly ) and really lacking in the carbonation department .
great looking beer .  fairly light and crisp on the palate , the hops snap an edge to it , but then it goes watery on the finish . not an epic beer , but a decent cold mug type brew .
a : nice deep copper color , head is about 1/2 '' and fades off to a film . quite a good amount of lacing .  mouthfeel is extremely light and overly carbonated - doing nothing for me at this point .
pours a beautiful crystal clear amber color with a couple fingers of sudsy white head .  mouthfeel : like i 've said , it 's kind of watery .

look : black and totally opaque with a red ring at the bottom . great 1 inch plus tan head with great retention and some circle lacing as the head resides smell : piney hops mixed with the carafe malt creates a very unique scent that i can only compare to like a fruity pebbles cereal smell taste : upfront is quite a bit of alcohol followed by very sweet i 'm assuming from the carafe malt in the middle and finishes off with that same fruity pebbles smell and obviously taste very unique mouthfeel : medium body and medium carbonation and leaves the mouth just a bit sticky and dry overall : very unique black ipa .  m - watery and very light .

poured a dark walnut color . as the beer hit my glass , it came alive producing a nicely controlled enduring head that laced the walls of my glass .  m : painfully overcarbonated , even after multiple swirls have created multiple heads .
s- smells awesome ! very sweet and coffee-y with strong roasted aroma .  m - thin mouthfeel d - very easy drinking beer but not much character .

pours pretty damned opaque black , slight red tinge when really held up to the light , very decent head - ochre in colour - sticks around at about half a cm thick , leaving some gorgeous clingy lace , really sticky webs of beige foam . very nice stout appearance .  weak body , thin mouth feel..a let down after the looks and smell of this ale .

a huge cottony off white head with some pretty fantastic lacing leaving a magnificent cling down the glass . quite a sight ! when swirled the foam becomes a frothy cap on top of the beer .  i find it to be very flat in both mouthfeel and complexity though . mouthfeel : flat and surprisingly disappointing . it is thinly bodied and is quite bitter . the flat body is a disappointment .
appearance : clear golden yellow in color sporting a bright white one finger head that lasted a while .  mf ) watery , thin , and lots of carbonation d ) pretty good for this style !

hood uses over 3oo pounds of pumpkin and winter squash per batch of this beer . the squash is then roasted to caramelize its fruit sugars and is brewed with a judicious blend of molasses , cinnamon , allspice , nutmeg , and ginger . pumpkin ales have a long history of being brewed in colonial america . this beer smells and tastes like a-1 steak sauce , and though this may sound odd ( and unappealing ) , its actually intriguing and palatable . this is a fun beer with great appeal .  texture is far too thin and watery .

a - big white creamy head that does n't stick around for long but leaves nice lace behind . good clarity and beautiful orange , copper color .  the watery , loose texture certainly did not help things .

appearance - large offwhite head with a thin lighter colored lace on top of that the head .  a- light , golden , clear , no real head or lacing s- sweet , honey , cinnamon , hint of liquorice/mint t- very light , not much pumpkin m- very light and thin d- i could drink this for hours ( not in a good way ) it does n't have any of the weight or warmth that i want in a fall beer .

liked it last year ; let 's see how this stacks up pours caramel with 2.5 fingers of rocky off-white colored head . stellar head retention & lacing s : subdued hop nose up front .  very sugary -- makes my cheeks swell and bloat . unoffensive , like a root beer . m- watery and bland .
appearance - a rich , cloudy red-brown with a two to three finger head of creme foam .  m - hot and sticky . a loser .

pours a hazy reddish orange with a big creamy off white head that retains well and laced the glass .  the addition of the yeast helps , but not much . d - good beer that will be much better if i leave it sitting for awhile so the carbonation will disperse . addition of the yeast make a huge difference in all aspects and is highly recommended , but overall drinkability is negatively affected by the mouthfeel .
the apperance is exceptional , gold honey in color , the usual amber color . the head was a gorgeous cream color that lasted the whole way through .  awful thin too .

the beer had a substantial and creamy head that showed excellent retention . was a good looking beer .  taste was blah , watered down and unexceptional . very drinkable but why bother . ca n't say that i would give this beer another try , maybe if i was burning up at a disco and it was ice cold i could handle it .

i had this on tap at ashleys , a bartender recommendation ... it pours nice and black with a full creamy head that has really nice lacing , my hopes are high ... the aroma is really dead , hard to pull anything out but a little roast coffee , my hopes start to fade ... the taste is better than the aroma , it has a light flavor but not much here and its super thin to drink .  feel is watery and thin , characterless and boring .

a - wow . a beautiful , crystal clear orange amber with a fluffy little pilow of head that retains decently and leaves oodles of frosty white lacing .  the taste was descent enough mostly bitter coffee with a bit of fruit but there was little , to almost no , carbonation that really made the beer fall flat for me ( no pun intended ) .

the color is black with just a hint of brown when held up to a light . the tan head looks quite creamy and appealing , and it leaves plenty of lacing on the side of my glass . this beer could not look more attractive .  very light mouthfeel .
bottle : poured a deep amber color beer with a thick off-white foamy head with great retention and lacing .  light body and literally no carbonation .

a : pours pitch black with a huge head - seriously like 4 '' of light mocha foam that has huge staying power and prevents me from pouring the entire beer at once . while this is the first time i 've had this from a bottle ( had it once on tap before ) so i ca n't say if this level of head is normal , but it is absolutely the most gorgeous head i 've ever seen . m : given the insane amount of head , this is as smooth and creamy as any stout i 've had .  really thin .

consumed on 2/21/09 poured a really nice copper/light brown with a darker brown center . the best part about this beer is it 's beautiful appearance in the glass .  mouthfeel is absolutely awful and inconsistent .
deep red color , like blood ! one of the most truly red colored beers i have seen .  just very watery and has an odd mouthfeel and finish to it .

i now know why i like the belgian darks . this poured an ultra clear beautiful burnt orange tint w/ a dissipating head . quite odd considering the glass was sterile and the ale was cold-could n't find a fresh date anywhere .  ) version of carlsberg 's elephant bock . this is one of my standard `` crap beers , '' the ones that you 're ashamed to admit you enjoy ( hey , we ca n't drink belgians all the time ) . it 's cheap , easy to stomach , tastes decent and has a cool elephant head on the label .

a- thick , motor-oil , dark brown beer , slow-growing 1cm creamy thick oatmeal cookie head . nice initial lace ring .  the mouthfeel is so thin and watery that i just can not get past it to enjoy whatever else this beer istrying to deliver .
bottle : poured a clear amber color ale with a bug white foamy head with great retention .  mouthfeel is quite thin and watery for a witbier , with very little carbonation after the head burns off .

nice head and great retention .  thin and watery mouthfeel with more carbonation then desired for the style . carbonation comeing through strong and man , i just cant get past this watery thin , frail mouthfeel .

reveiwed from a bottle 2005 apearence- beautiful caramel , clear color with a nice pancake colored one finger head . great lacing effect from this bottle i mean incredable .  come to think of it , drinking peeber is like drinking water . very thin .
a - great clarity with a light amber color . nice frothy head that sticks around for days s - great citrus notes .  thin mouth feel .
a : it poured a thick , black with a massive dark chocolate three finger sticky head .  mouthfeel was watery and dry with nothing to stick on the tongue .
lots of lacing left behind , incredibly impressive appearance .  m- thin and carbonated . probably the worst dimension to this so-so beer .

first pumpkin beer this year with a good head . the smell on this beer is intense . it smells like a very aromatic crumbled pie crust with light cinnamon with a whipped cream aroma .  rather thin . left a grimey feeling in my mouth .

pours out to a sparkingly clear copper , forming a tall whipped beige head with excellent retention and very solid lacing . despite appearing filtered , there is a small amount of sediment in the glass .  however the body of the beer let it down , very watery , no head retention ; this very quickly started to remind me of lager .
poured a light coppery color with a thick , persistent white head . very pretty to look at .  mouthfeel is seltzer water + a little .

it always pours this magnificent , humongous ivory white head that leaves chunky lace . a perfect presentation .  mouthfeel was very disappointing - none of the creamy smoothness that i love and was almost cola-like in its carbonation level .
dark copper color with a big off-white head and great lacing .  mouthfeel was a bit thin and slippery .

2010 vintage green wax poured into my glass the beer is the thickest blackest beer i 've ever laid eyes on . about one finger of dark chocolate head forms on top nad leaves sticky lace gobs as it recedes .  could barely detect any spices , very thin body .

pours a dark chocolate brown color that appears pitch black and completely opaque in the glass with a one finger beige head that quickly settles into a thick , lasting ring .  mouthfeel : high carbonation . mouthfeel hurts it 's `` sessionability '' despite the abv .
a - pours a brilliant dark reddish orange with a finger and a half khaki colored light bodied head that dissipates quickly .  body is watery to excess .

750ml bottle poured into a cervoise , inferno ale is a murky gold with lots streamers forming a large , very rocky white head that leaves lots of spidery lace . wow , very nice .  m : very high carbonation .

as black as a raven 's wing , this beer is really impressive . the feel on the tongue is smooth like a dark chocolate bar , the alcohol was n't really noticeable . this beer goes down easy and is one easy to drink more then one glass of .  mouthfeel - thin body , high carbonation do n't match ideally to the bigger taste .
really beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with zero carbonation .

good pristine golden color with some seriously fluffy head .  way too much carbonation..and the mouthfeel is too bubbly . even if the carbonation was done well , i do n't think this would be anything better than an `` above-average '' porter .

oddly after the gorgeous appearance the aroma was pretty pedestrian , maybe my nose is blocked..i dunno its distinctlly average..some malts and a little fruits , thats about it .  poor amount of carbonation .

pours a dark black with a creamy white head and the standard brownish alive cool looking action in the beer before it settles to black with the cream head that lasts . this is not lacing , as the beer moves from the glass the creamy composition of the head literally stays on the glass .  too carbonated for my taste and has a dry character on the tail as it warms that i do n't care for .

pours a very clear but very dark scarlet , clear enough to se through but dark enough to soak up a lot of the light . buttery tan head froths up out of control and sits there as if it were a solid object . it leaves frothy , thick lacing behind , and absolutely refuses to diminish to less than a full finger throughout the glass .  the aroma makes you think this will be a rich and luscious beer , but i was disappointed with its watery body and complete lack of depth . this is a lightly flavored , light bodied beer that has a slightly fruity sweet finish .

a very large head is formed off the pour that is a nice creamy tan color . while drinking lacing is big and sticks in giant clumps.. oh that 's sexy ! gorgeous clear dark red body with wonderful red ruby hues , i love this color it looks just wonderful . bouquet is a nice roast and coffee at first then gives way to some smoky meat character like jerky salts , a small hint of sweet brown sugar but very small .  mouthfeel is pretty watery with not a good amount of carbonation .

750ml blend 1 , 2010 poured into a chalice a black color , very nice carbonation , huge thick/creamy three-finger tan head , which leaves some thick/creamy sticky lacing behind .  the feel was too thin . what smoothness there was came more from thinness than anything else .

a- black , brown head , thick , oily , leaves lots of lacing s- sugary malts , coffee , alcohol t- malty sweetness up front , some roasty earthiness going into a great finish/aftertaste .  however - carbonation is a real problem here , with sherbet-like tingling insistence on the tongue , which kills the remaining flavour .

it is wonderful . notes of oak , barnyard funk , and vinegar . virtually no lace , but nice oily looking legs . this is amazingly tasty . for $ 9 per bottle , i glad to be ableto pick this up whenever i want !  mouthfeel is awful due to the lack of carbonation . absolutely no carbonation whatsoever - none , nada . a very interesting beer but the lack of carbonation easily keeps this one from being world class .

aroma is sweet with notes of cloves , candy , and overripe pear . it 's a very nice belgian , but it 's certainly not a dark ale . that they grow all the ingredients themselves is very remarkable . it is a very nice effort at a belgian , but the lack of a real hop profile makes this simply too sweet for my palate .  mouthfeel is not so good , since the beer is basically flat .

a : amber/reddish-bronze ; light tan head ; some retention , great lace .  had the banana and clove aroma and taste but the body is just way too think and the lack of carbonation makes it tough to drink .
( a ) - pours a deep dark crimson burgundy color . produced a nice frothy pink colored head with good retention for the style . plenty of lacing .  m : light , fizzy , thin finish .
perfect color and head for the style .  carbonation is stupidly high .
some roast , some background sweetness , a bit of that typical oatmeal stout smell , a real nice sweetness in the background .  far too over-carbonated , and watery mouthfeel .
a : murky tan with a large robust off white head with amazing retention .  mouthfeel was pretty weak .
a : pours a nice and cloudy amber/red color . a large beige head forms and leaves lots of patch lace down the glass .  ok mouthfeel is pretty bad . thin and watery .

pours a brilliant ruby red with a rose-colored head that has very good retention and leaves behind some lacing .  mouthfeel : smooth but horribly dry , especially on the finish , which is reminiscent of a stale cracker .

a= pours a caramelly brownish color similar to coca cola looking . the head is a nice two fingers and appears to be a just off white color . nice retention and lacing on this one as well .  the taste is average with a slightly bitter aftertaste the mouthfeel is lacking . it feels a bit watered down .

a- pours a clear bright golden with a very nice creamy eggshell colored head . for a style that i consider to be boring , this one looks as good as i can imagine .  felt very thin in the mouth for a stout , with a little bit of carbonation .

pours black and completely opaque with a large inch and a half mocha colored head . excellent retention and some nice lacing as well .  m - this beer was way too overcarbonated and it distracted from the taste .

as with all of the beers at the sn brewery , the carbonation is constant and active ; however the column of bubbles is not quite as dense . a big , fluffy , white , foamy head sits on top - looks just like a bubble bath . great head retention and tons of clumpy , foamy lace all the way down .  mouth is really thin , watery almost .

pours a reddish amber color ( duh ! ) with an off-white 1/4 '' creamy dense head ; very sticky on the surface and sustainance is good .  m - not much carbonation ; watery d - no reason to drink more than one .
lacing is tremendous . the head on this beer is magnificent , probably from the pour , but holds well regardless . beer is dark , dark brown with a light brown head .  the palate is thin .

poured an extremely murky cider color with a great , 2-fingered head of frothy , beige foam that loved to just hang out and leave terrific lacing behind on the glassware . beautiful looking beer ... like an apple cider with a frothy head on top .  m - medium body with a dry finish , yet an odd carbonation that again reminds me of soda .
poured amber colour with creamy white head which retains well and has good lacing .  m- one thing that can not be salvaged , of course , is the thin body and high carbonation .

pours an absolutely gorgeous deep chestnut brown colour , with a huge and frothy head of pale creamy white foam .  nearly flat and medium-bodied , the mouthfeel becomes slick towards the end and the drinkability suffers .
a - pours a large dark brown head with great retention and nice lacing . very dark brown nearly black beer .  feel is flat , untextured , un-nuanced .

dark golden , sorta amber , about a finger of frothy white head . lacing and retention are both great .  thin taste of belgian white beer . most other beers i 've tried from unibroue has been fairly strong , maybe that 's why i thought this one lacked body ? still , it 's not as good as hoegaarden if comparing to another belgian wit .

appearance : it poured out a light brown color that quickly turned into a beautiful black color that you have no chance of seeing through . it poured with a beautiful thick finger and a half of darker tan head that just will not die down . there is also some really nice lacing . i mean this is just a beauty of a beer .  mouthfeel is super thin and watery .
pretty clear golden color with a humongous white head . tons of stick here , crazy frothy , and overall just beautiful .  mouthfeel is light considering how malty this is . thin .
good retention and great lace .  mouthfeel - extremely watery overall - an uninteresting yet swilling pumpkin ale .

pours a light shade of black with creamy , tan , guinness head .  the middle is thin and sweetens some . when cold , the finish is slightly metallic with some obvious alcohol . this is n't bad compared to american macros and some other strong export lagers , but that 's about it .

smell is strongly of c type hops with a strong bitter orange aroma . grapefruit , onion , mango and pineapple . smells like a hop bomb . starts out dry and earthy .  fairly thin with a lot of carbonation , watery , with some hop flavor . i am really enjoying all the craft beer i 've been drinking lately , but a bunch of miller lites iced down in a cooler on a hot summer day will work for me anytime .

2009 vintage pours a dark beautiful amber color with a perfect amount of head and some patchy lacing .  the real indicator was the body too thin and the general overall weakness will not make this a serious porter contender .

pours a dark brown with a red tint . a large tan head forms and has excellant retention before settling to a thick cap . heavy lacing is left on the glass . at least it looks good .  the body was very thin .

a : 1 and quarter creamy , fluffy white head with fantastic , thick lacing clinging to the sides of the glass . brew itself was a cloudy goldenrod color .  mouthfeel is extremely thin for the style with no chewiness at all .

the brew is bright light gold with a magnificent , thick creamy head that slowly dissipates to leave thin bubbles and a slight lacing around the glass .  t/m : the mouthfeel is thin and quite watery ; the taste is equally limp . mouthfeel and a general weakness of character ruins any chance at more than a passable brew .

appearance- clouded golden pour with a larger 1 inch + creamy looking head and nice lace .  m- horrid ! lacked any body whatsoever . i mind as well have been drinking seltzer water that had no carbonation . d- given the water-like mouthfeel , it went down pretty easy .

pours a brilliant copper-golden liquid with a 1/4 finger light-tan head that stays . quite attractive .  it hinders the mouthfeel and makes it seem more syrupy and cloying that originally intended ( just guessing ) .

this looks like a piece of modern art . the crack & glug action presented me with two fingers ' worth of explosive bone-white foam with moderate retention . color was a beautiful golden-yellow with ne-plus clarity . liquid sunshine in my glass !  mouthfeel was also very light and thin .

this is a good looking beer .  clearly a lawnmower/party beer , but its quite refreshing and a lot more tolerable and most of the other cheap beers , plus it 's the same price ... one of my favorite cheap beers .

there is no information given about freshness , but some nutriant info is given , and there is the cool widget inside the bottle . this beer is one of the more impressive looking beers out there . as it was poured into my bell 's pint glass , a creamy head instantly formed , with nitrogen bubbles cascading to the bottom of the glass . after settiling a bit , a creamy tan half inch head remains throughout the whole experience . the beer is very dark , hints of brown are visible when held to the light , but this brew is pretty opaque .  the mouthfeel is medium to light bodied and watery .

bomber at mad mex in pittsburgh ... a- deep golden color with a nicely carbonated head but not much lace left in the glass s- big , fresh hop aroma ! mf- lots of carbonation and slightly oily d- the bomber was plenty . i was n't big on the bitter finish - if you like earthy hop flavors , this is your beer .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel does n't carry the taste evenly - it 's too smooth and yet too coarse at the same time .

pour : 750ml to flute glass . comes out about half clear golden effervescent body and half white head . a nice cap of lace remains behind .  palate is watery , but drinkable . as i commented to the purveyor , for a pale lager in a can from wisconsin , its not bad .

a - an absolutely gorgeous cloudy golden amber with a tall , frothy pillow of foam on top with great retention . my mouth is watering just looking at it .  light to medium body with a watery texture .
hazy golden body with good carbonation . huge white butte head , pillowy and creamy with good retention and amazing lace .  a bit heavy despite the watery feel in the mouth .
a- amazing deep amber , almost ruby in color .  it drinks well but it does n't leave much of a feel in your mouth .
dark auburn with ruby hues . thick tan head , 2 fingers tall , great retention and lots of creamy lacing .  and the mouthfeel is oddly thin , does n't fit well with the boozy vibe .
bottled nov. 2007 , batch 3 this looks fantastic . very thick , black , with a dark tan fingers of head .  m - low marks again . thin and not up to snuff .

smell : the smell is wonderfully complex and full of fruit and nut notes . truly a treat to enjoy , and i enjoyed it heartily . quite taste , and quite drinkable .  the mouthfeel lets this drink down , as the carbonation is too intense and overpowers the flavour , so i found myself agitating my glass to draws some of it out .

nice fruity touches in the aroma , and the more i `` drink in '' the nose , the more i seem to find ... tropical fruits , mango , banana ? well-balanced , and enjoyable . i can imagine a pleasant session with these . funny name .  mouf & gt ; overly carbonated and full . the mouthfeel sucks . '' drinkability & gt ; we finished the bottle because it still tasted good , but it was not as good as the 2008 .
a- dense thick white head that lingers , adds a creamy appearance to a creamy beer . sits atop a light golden body , very inviting .  m - low carbonation , slick , flat finish .

375 ml bottle pours a brilliant dark ruby/purple ( actually quite close to the color of the label ) with a sizeable bright pink lasting head .  mouthfeel was light and thin , due to the low carbonation , so it was lacking the smooth velvety body that you would expect from a oatmeal stout .
the beer is a super dark red or amber . it looks delicious on appearance .  much too much carbonation .

this beer starts off with a huge , everlasting tan head .  the flavor follows those same tastes with with an overall malt sweetness and thin feel to it . not thin in a good way , thin like flavor is missing .

came out with the typical tan thick and creamy head . very dark and thick looking , with good lacing .  very rich , sweet and no carbonation to balance it . what i like least : the lack of carbonation .

appearance : deep , clear red color with a very excited , very foamy white head that lasts forever . once in the glass this is a very impressive looking beer .  thin bodied with a watery finish , this could still be a passable summer brew for when you have little else in the fridge .

clear mohogany with a thick creamy creme-colored head that laces very well . thick and slick , this comes off a little candyish , which i tend to like in a beer , but this is kinda dull .  m - the one flaw . too wet and smooth .

purs a nice , dark brown color , with a slight dark red color around the edges . 3 finger head , with really nice lacing throughout .  mouthfeel is where this brew suffers : it 's really just pretty thin .

a- black with beautiful light brown head ... perfect appearance .  too thin and the carbonation is too high given the taste . overall : the taste and smell of this beer are amazing , but the mouthfeel really took away from the beer .
thick fluffy head that slowly receded into a ring around the glass and left some decent lacing .  mouthfeel is the most dissappointing part of this beer ; it 's far too watery .
12 oz bottle poured into mad elf tulip . pours reddish amber very clear with a nice fluffy white head .  the carbonation is way too strong with small sharp bubbles .

it pours a really pretty reddish brown with a nice off white head that just lasts and lasts . very pretty , lol .  the mouthfeel is very lively , very slippery/oily and buttery . too carbonated , which is strange for a stout . drinkability is ok given the high abv , but the bitterness , aftertaste and carbonation cancel that out somewhat .

from notes reviewed on 11/19/10 : bomber poured into a duvel glass , best by 4/17/11 a : golden orange , clear , huge 3 finger foamy white head that looks like pillows of clouds bursting out of the glass . great head retention and lacing .  mouthfeel : very thin , body like water .
appearance - looks great , black as night with a nice caramel tan head that hangs on the whole time .  the mouthfeel is extraordinarily watery .

pitch black with a large 1 '' creamy redish khaki head . looks like black coffee ( with an added head ) .  just a touch of carbonation zing at the swallow . i just dont know what to think , and that slimey mouthfeel is really starting to irritate my gag reflex .

the appearance is ideal for an american adjunct lager .  pouring out in a sweaty yellow with high carbonation and zippy flavor , lionshead light offers enough personality and taste to get you past its weaker qualities ( gritty mouthfeel , odd aftertaste , general banality ) and is definitely there for you when you need a night of drinking without the cost of high-quality suds .

pours the familiar very dark brown that looks reddish when held to the light , with the ultra creamy off-white cap that lasts and lasts .  m : very thin and dry a low carbonation and a bitterness at the end .

pours black with notes of ruby when held to the light . the head stays very well and leaves pretty nice rocky lacing .  it 's a cheap american beer produced for the masses . i actually like this beer and if i 'm drinking bmc and am going the light route this is my preference .

appearance- given to me with a sturdy tan head that started at two and a half fingers , and eventually receded to a one and a half finger head that stayed the whole enjoyment of beer . color is a deep brown when held to the light , but other than that its a translucent black . smell- pretty subdued in every way .  a - this beer poured a light golden color , crystal clear , that produced a foamy white head that disappeared quickly and left no lacing on the glass , not surprised s - the only notes on the nose where malts and lager yeasts t - this beer had a one dimensional taste to it , as one would expect from a regular lager , not a harshness i get from adjunct lagers , but still pretty lame m - this beer had a very thin watery body , and was loaded with carbonation d - this beer would be a very drinkable beer in the summertime to quench the thirst , if not for the high amounts of carbonation , which seems to accompany most abitas .

one of the blackest stouts i 've poured . never would have guessed if the bottle had n't told me - the dryest oatmeal stout i 've run across , and probably the least sweet . there is an interesting smoky aspect to the roasted malt - sort of like alderwood or some other wood used to smoke salmon . an oatmeal stout that marches to the beat of a different drummer , but i can dig it .  the flavour is rather thin and feels watered down .

appearance - light copper , mostly clear with a solid sticky layer of head throughout .  in the appearance , is a coppery color , with a poor head of foam , the bottle and the logo are retro ; lot of caramel and sugar in the smell ; some essences of caramel and roasted malts in the taste ; the drinkability is good ; the mouthfeel is watery and fizzy , with a low bitterness .

a=this beer is very nice to look at . it was huge and very lumpy with great retention .  the mouthfeel is actually kind of weak and bitter , surprisingly , given the pleasant look and smell of this beer .
lacing is superb as is the head retention . truly a great sight in a pint .  flat and watery mouthfeel , very thin , no body .

was surprised to see a summer beer that was dark reddish/brown/ glimpses of ruby . slight head that holds fairly well - beer looks good .  there is no body to this wit . it drinks like a cheap lager leaving very little for the finish .

it poured a perfect deep copper with a two-finger tan head , and it let perfect thick , tight rings of lace .  smell-fairly clean , i do detect some malt but not much else , no hoppiness , alcohol , or otherwise . taste-fairly tasteless , some malt does come through again but for the most part this tastes like water . drinkability-somewhat malty and low abv , you could pound these that 's for sure . overall-yawn , sorry for the not so detailed review but this is another not so detailed light beer , even from an ok brewery like pocono .

not much head at first , however after setting the glass down the head flows down into the beer for an awesomely presentable beer . color is almost black with a dark head .  mouthfeel is bad . it burns there is so much carbonation .

this was poured at 60 deg into a large belgian glass from a capped belgian style bottle . thick frothy dark brown head sits atop a velvety black abyss .  mouthfeel - this is probably my biggest problem with this beer a very watery mouthfeel and it is very under-carbonated , almost flat .

drank from a 750 ml bottle purchased at julio 's liquors , westboro , ma poured a slightly hazed , bright , orangey-golden yellow with a huge , bubbly , off white , sea foam head that ever-so-slowly dropped to a thick , moussey cap of froth . dense patches of lacing stuck all down the glass .  the mouthfeel just might be below the level of previous commented on mab , with the watery feel and the slight body .

( a ) - pours a clear yellow/orange color with almost a minutes worth of cascading action followed by a ridiculously thick pure white billowy foam that is sticking everywhere and was still present down to the last drop !  my biggest disappointment was the mouthfeel with no lasting carbonation or creaminess .

full , thick ivory head , lacing all the way down , keeping strong all the way through . leaves a dollop of head at the bottom of the glass .  i 'm not a huge brown ale fan but i 've had some dang good ones lately so i 'm hoping this will be another winner ... pours a warm brown with a very thick creamy head of off white ... very warm and fall-like and makes me wish it was october ... very faint malty earthy aromas that seem rather muted ... toffee and caramel notes for sure but just not pronounced enough for my tastes ... very thin and watery , this one falls short in several categories ... definite caramel malt presence but there 's not enough substance to really enjoy it . almost get a little yeastiness here that mingles with the malts that give this a weird almost oxidized flavor.. sort of sweet and toffee-like but this could really use a little more thickness ... very average brown to me ... might do in a pinch but not one i 'd reach for by choice

too bad because it 's really a great looking beer in the glass ie good head retention and lacing .  m - this is where the beer is odd ... when cold , a really carbonated mouthfeel that is unappealing .
the beer appears dark ruby colored with a thick tan head . lasting retention and plenty of lacing coats the tulip glass .  body is way too thin for the style and way too filtered imo .

appearance of this relative rairity is peachy , with a head and impressive architecture of vertical-creeping bubbles . brown blobs of outgoing yeasters are observed . nice sculptures pre-sip .  m- thin , watery with crisp prickly carbonation throughout .

poured a tall , dense , bright-white head that left a beautiful coat of lace . glowing pale golden beer holds a swarm of fast rising bubbles .  the beers got a big body , almost too big for its style . its not terrible , the body is really killing this one for me .

great retention leaves a lace storm splattered within my glass .  m : this is where the beer loses me ... it feels thin and watery where i was expecting a richer , creamier texture . it 's just too bad it 's so thin ... if they boosted the maltiness a bit this would be a killer beer .
appearance- a rich golden amber with a full head of foam that slowly dissapates leaving lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel : very light , watery body with not much to recommend it .

appearance- pours a standard two fimger head with an awesome thick foamy film retention throughout the whole beer . add to this a lovley deep amber and a constant stream of bubbling , and the best lacing i'v seen on any english pale ale .  mouthfeel : very thin with a little bit of bubble .

enticing , very nice taste differs significantly than what the nose predicted .  poured chilled in flared glass a : dark caramel , clear ; very thick head ; good carb beads ; great lacing s : a bit univiting ; thin , malty ( sweet ) aroma ; but i do n't smell a bock here t : one-dimensional bock ; little double about it m : watery , thin , dead it looks fantastic , but 'tai n't .

served in a pint glass this beer pours a motor oil black . it may be categorized here as a smoked beer , but this has the rich sexy dark brown foam and black body of an amazing stout .  probably too carbonated , almost prickly on the palate . this is a thin bodied beer , and other from the carbonation it goes down easily enough .
impressive . and the lacing is dusted across the glass in a nice etched fashion of tiny snowflakes and frosting .  m - light bodied , harsh carbonation level , odd , gritty texture .

liquid pours a nearly opaque bole with brilliant ruby/crimson highlights , a light-khaki creamy head which recedes to a thin ring of foam with a small peninsula in the center . decent lacing , and noticeable leg formation due to the high alcohol .  flavor is rather thin , but consists of light chocolate and roast , and a dash of hops on top of a thin , very dry body that leaves a short finish .

label is black and white with a woman 's head on the left side overlooking a countryside . bottle opens with a loud pop and some beer fog . a - pours a beautiful deep orange with a large head that eventually turns into nice lacing towards the end of each glass . this would look great for a fresh saison .  sticky & flabby .

a - it looks like any of the other bcs series , which is generally impressive . black , oily looking beer with a fine brown bubble head that did n't leave much on the sides .  mouthfeel was loose and watery ( though the taste did not seem to reflect the watery nature of the beer 's feel ) .
this lager smells like it was infected with brett . awesome ! taste : smooth lager flavor has a spicy bite .  the mouthfeel was too full bodied for the style and was a major negative point .

the head is fluffy first and rocky later , ivory white in color and incredibly long lasting . huge peaks and craters cover the surface . as it eventually fades , chunky sea foam lace coats the glass .  it 's body , unfortunately , is fatally flawed : this beer feels more watery than water . an interesting beer that starts off at a sprinter 's pace for excellence and quickly slides downhill .
this brew pours a beautiful ruby red color with a small tan head .  the mouthfeel is crappy . maybe not terrible , but too thin and too fizzy when it first hits the palate .

a ) opaque black with 2 inches of creamy light tan head that sticks around for a really long time . leaves lots of lacing in the glass .  f - pretty limp , even more than i remember . like stout-flavored water .
wonderful looking beer .  mouthfeel - watery and thin .

amber orange in colr with tiny bubbles constantly rising to the surface and infultrating the constant khaki head .  thin mouthfeel , just like drinking sparkling water with raspberry flavoring . sparkling water .
the look is decidedly porter-like , with a magnificent head of darker froth that would make that style proud .  slight caramel flavors present mouthfeel : thin and highly carbonated .

a - dark black and viscous with oily stains that recede into the glass as you drink it . the pour produced a 1/2 inch dark tan head that dissipated fairly quickly .  taste is very mild , with almost nil carbonation . no hops , only water , malt and honey as noted on the label .

presentation : 16 oz bottle , poured into a weizen glass appearance : cloud , dark amber with an enormous , beautiful frothy head that took a while to dissipate . outstanding appearance .  drinks : warm , the obnoxious funk flavor , paired with the unsettling mouthfeel , makes this beer nigh undrinkable .

appearance : dark brown to black with large pillowy head after an aggressive pour . the head recedes more slowly than i would have thought leaving nice lacing .  unfortunately thin but carbonation does what it can .
black as night , with a head the color of chocolate milk . it 's a full pint , so it fits the glass perfectly .  m/d - it is unbelievably thin .

basically pitch black with a creamy tan head that just rests and barely settles during consumption . great lacing and just all around excellent to the eye .  the mouthfeel is very gaseous . i 've had 3 of their beers now and they have all felt shitty in the mouth .

poured into a 20oz tulip pint glass with samuel smith 's insignia . nearly black in color brown that has amber glimmers toward the bottom of the glass .  a very wimpy brew , foamy in the mouth , with a twinge of a soapy taste .

nice straw pour . up front the aroma is pretty standard saison with some dusty yeast and very nice lemon touch . rosemary and thyme follow through pretty quickly , mingling with the citrus for a very nice combination .  the mouthfeel is hot as hell . let a mouthful of this rest on your palate for 10-15 seconds , and it feels like the insides of your mouth are being dissolved . it 's very astringent and has a monster bite.the aftertaste is just ... boozy .

from notes written 12/02/07 : large brown glass bottle , 18.7 oz , gold foil wrapping around the neck . pours a beautiful deep and bright ruby , with a healthy white head .  mouthfeel : watery in comparison to a pint drawn in a good pub with a nitrogen system . the watered down mouthfeel really detracts .
a great looking pour .  body is terribly watery , the pacman yeast ( which i usually like ) just does n't fit with this beer . the mouthfeel is as hearty as a hawiian death metal band .
sampled on 7-8-09 best before 2-6-10 pours completely pitch black , with a smooth tan head that reminds me of a guinness .  thin mouthfeel with a dry center and a rather silent finish .

a : golden orange colored , hazy with some floaties . two fingers of off-white head..tons of texture . loads of caked on lacing around the entire glass . thick , foamy film with a good bit of larger bubbles .  mouthfeel is very flat , yet not undrinkable .

a : clear deep amber body with an inch and a half of light , creamy off-white foam . great retention and lacing . dark for a gueuze , but otherwise perfectly gorgeous .  very little aroma , mouthfeel 's watery .

a : served with a finger and a half of medium light brown head , frothy/creamy and excellent retention . excellent lacing in cracquelated sheets .  the mouthfeel is medium to light bodied and pretty watery which washes out the flavors .
quick review : looks really pretty with lots of fluffy bone-white head atop an orange-amber hazy body .  mouthfeel is watery .

poured with a healthy 3f of foamy , white head , atop of a fairly opaque orange-tea colored body . plenty of lacing .  body is thin and woefully under-carbonated , but in it 's defense , roswell alien amber does n't have any detectable off-notes .
great looking pilsner , maybe the best out there next to prima pils .  mouthfeel is disappointingly watery .

this beer poured a large head that was tan , creamy and had fine sized bubbles . the hue of this beer is dark brown and the lacing was fair .  extremely thin mouthfeel . drinkable , but not recommended .

appearance - very nice deep copper/amber color . a solid almost two inches of soapy off-white head . looks great .  except for the very poor mouthfeel , a great beer , one that i would recommend from the bottle .

pours a super black thats tick and oily .  a bit slick on the tongue and a little watery for a barley wine . good carbonation level . not a strong malt profile to speak of and the mouthfeel was watery .

quite nice . bit of a hop in there , but malt dominant .  taste/mouthfeel- watery feel to the beer , some grain and alcohol , hops and malt are present but do n't really make much of an impression . drinkability-refreshing on a hot summer day , other than that the thin feel dissapoints .
pours a nice amber/ golden brown with a nice fluffy white head .  the feel is super watery .
very pretty looking , lots of bubbles .  2.0 m : water body . good moderate carbonation . too light and watery to appreciate .

pours a deep , opaque black-brown with a fairly thick and fine-bubbled light tan head , quite appealing .  mouthfeel : thin body , watery texture , moderate-lively carbonation drinkability : well , not bad for the style .
a : pours a slightly hazy golden with a mega-massive , frothy head with a sticky , long sustain .  m : mouthful was disappointing , bland and thin .

smell is of dark fruits , raisin , sweetness , a little bit of coffee .  it is thin bodied despite the nitro , with a masked , watery aroma . the beer may perhaps be too traditional to appreciate as it shows more modesty than american craft beers usually do . shannon 's core values are a dry grain and chaff taste with some show of dark lace . but the lack of body and flavor are obstacles to appreciation .

appearance -- pours a bright golden hue with a finger width of creamy lily-white head .  a- typical clear pale yellow with fast fading head s- corn and just a pinch of hops t- corn and just a pinch of hops and some sweetness m- thin watery mouthfeel d- as far as the mexican/south american beers go its decent but its still a diluted session beer .

the white , fluffy head is a good inch thick when poured and has very nice lacing . head settles to a good 1/4 inch and then does n't go away . good retention !  extremely light on body , even for an old ale .

pours a clear light ruby brown with a huge rocky off white head that retains well and laces the glass .  mouthfeel is thin and watery , not helping to blend the flavors together , but rather separating .
pretty good stuff .  since it is so thin compared to other stouts , i do have to rate it accordingly . sorry but it could be thicker .

pours from the bottle to a nice copper color , with thousands of infused carbonation bubbles and a thick off-white head that lingers thru most of the glass and leaves very good lacing .  beer is lightly carbonated .
great looking beer . looks like carbonated orange juice or maybe a mimosa .  the mouthfeel is too undercarbonated and watery .
huge sheets of lacing and good retention .  the first mouth , however , leaves a slight citrus hand over her mouth to deliver a body too thin , very watery and the obvious lack of spices .
nice amber color with a good heavy 1.5 inch head . it receded quickly but left excellent freckled lacing down my pint .  the mouthfeel is very thin .
exceptional retention .  mf : very coarse and dry for the style .

a - seriously a great looking beer ... what i would think a great looking ipa would and should look like .  a weak attempt at a flemish sour . the beer has good light redish color and the lactic sourness is present but it is thin and watery . no hop aroma or other funky lambic type aromas , just a lactic beer .

this brew poured a copper color liquid with a foamy off-white head . the head stayed around for the entire time , and the lacing left was tremendous . the carbonation seemed a bit out of control .  not what i want from an ipa . mouthfeel - watery . flat .

poured a beautiful color , phenomenally shiny , that shifted slowly from gold edges to deep but lustrous amber in the middle . had a thin and simple soft head , sat very well , with thick and slow lace that leaft a stain of sloppy but wide horizontal strings and splotches . a good looking glass of beer , no doubt . smelled of soft pumpkin , moderate toffee malts , with notes of sweet cinnamon and hearty nutmeg poking up , as well as small hints of cinnamon .  the body is decidedly watery , or maybe that 's the too-high carbonation producing a spritzy , foamy finish .

1 pint can poured into a pint glass a : gorgeous rouge with striking amber and orange tones . really great lace like a timeline down the glass .  mouthfeel is thin and fizzy , not at all what i want in a chocolate bock .

a- nice looking beer , bright white head with a clear light copper color . leaves awesome lacing and has nice head retention .  a text book pilsener-which is a positive note but the bready quality is not full . finish is clean but it has the after-taste of the gaterade power water . drinks ok , and i would enjoy this on a hot summer day-just a bit pricey for a miller lite clone in a nicer bottle .
it reminds me of a good piece of saddle leather . simply beautiful !  m thin and really kind of boring .

what a gorgeous beer ! dark coppery brown . white , light , fluffy head with clingy bubbles .  tingly carbonation . thin and watery on the tongue ; not what i would expect from a wheat wine . the intense carbonation dances with the crisp flavor and light body similarly to a belgian saison .

the beer pours a coppery amber color , topped with a thick , creamy ivory head . great lacing and retention , leaving tons of clumpy lace all the way down the pint glass .  finishes a bit metallic , grainy & a bit of toasty malt mf : thin with low carbonation this alright , i remember it darker back in the day , but i could be mistaken .

excellent , grassy smell ; very strong and awesome . taste follows the aromas , but it is surprisingly well-balanced with a bittersweet aftertaste mixed in with the supreme amount of hops . excellent .  there 's no bite , no kick , to the mouthfeel , and it 's not creamy or dense either . that said , there 's nothing to prevent you from having many , because it goes down like water .
as good as the three finger ivory crown looks , it laces even better .  the palate is thin and poorly carbonated .

crystal clear straw color with an extensive stream of upwardly mobile bubbles . impressive three-finger , snow powdery white head that recedes in a rocky fashion .  m - dry finish , kind of tough , alcohol harshness , medium bodied .

mississippi mud is a super clear deep crimson brown beer with a soft , foamy light khaki head that has outstanding retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is watery with a lackluster carbonation . would n't seek out again as the finish was too medicinaly and the feel was thin and watery .
i love the brilliantly white foamy two finger head . the beer underneath is a perfectly clear golden color .  mouthfeel : thin and watery .
a : pours a dark brown with ruby highlights . it has two fingers worth of light tan head .  thin mouthfeel i could down a lot of these .

aroma is intense , incredible , overpowering . what 's in that nose ? blueberries , of course , and nothing else , but it 's a very pleasant , tasty flavor .  i was really looking forward to my first sip of this years bbcs on draft until the chap next to me said it was thin . my first sip tasted fantastic but yes it did indeed feel thin . as it warmed it should have gotten tastier but the thinness was more obvious than it was cold .
poured a dark black color with an averaged sized brown head .  nasty aftertaste which lingered , a kind of alcohol with no body to it .

pours amber/caramel with humungous white head that held a 1 '' head throughout . lacing was very good smell : some fruittiness and hops , but very subtle for style taste : intense hops bitterness followed by some malt fruitiness .  mouthfeel is thin and watery , with little-to-no carbonation .

1 pint 9.6 ounces no date appearance orange/brown slightly clouded body ; white head crackles away quickly ; very light stream of rising carbonation in body after head disappears ; no lasting lace ; pour slow late to avoid the cloud smell take a deep whiff ; earthy ; woody ; coffee ; fruity - a bit brut-like ; i actually had to step away and smell some ginger to be sure but yes , theres a solid ginger tone taste grapes , caramel and spice ; some alcohol and grains , especially in close mouthfeel steady shot of crispness on the tongue but its not overwhelming ; medium body that thins a bit in the end ; dry close drinkability certainly warming about 2/3rds into bottle ; the dryness drops the drinkability pangaea is not exactly my cup of tea or tulip of beer for that matter .  very thin and watery .

a : poured a sexy orangle color with good carbonation and a nice fluffy white cap s : bread , caramel , citrus and pine t : starts off with sharp booze , pine , orange peel , other citrus and sharp bite m : medium body , tasty , booze is stinging and pungent but not to bad , lots of flavor here o : this ia big , bold in your face hoptacular iipa .  mouthfeel : very thin for a stout not a chewy texture to note very much light to medium body when it should be medium to full in body .
pours a slightly hazy golden copper with a medium frothy head that retains well and laces the glass .  it 's almost watery .
super coppery color thats pretty deep and glowing , thin ivory head that fades fast , lace minimal but sticking in thin ink blot patches .  the mouthfeel is thin , carbonated , and sickening .

a monstrous and thick whipped-cream head that is still standing minutes after the initial pour . the best head retention i 've ever seen from a dipa , hands down .  next to no beer flavour of any sort , may as well be soda water with a lime wedge .
this beer looks super thick and smells great like chocolate and dried fuits . the smell and the look was gerat but the taste was just ok .  chalky astringent mouthfeel .

500ml bottle with batch code 5368. tasted in late april 2009. very dark , brownish amber . lots of thick tan head , which recedes very , very slowly to creamy wisps and a foamy ring . amazing lace for a bock !  the body is much more a brown ale similar to newcastle , thin and watery , without much aftertaste .
sampled on 3-25-09 pours cloudy red/brown color , with a filmy white head that leaves behind pretty good lacing .  the mouthfeel is way too light and thin .
carbonation looks extremely well done , and the streams are impressive . good appearance .  mouthfeel : on thin side .

the beer is dry-hopped and if im not mistaken , it is dry-hopped with fresh hops taken from the bines growing outside the brewery on 9th ave. , making this both a dry-hopped and wet-hopped ale . the aroma was a primal scream of hops though the flavor itself was not otherwise bursting with hoppiness . the aroma alone is worth the price of admission , but cask beer should be drained in under three days and i may have missed this beer at its peak .  m - overly carbonated .

pours a light hazy shade of dandelion tinted amber with a monstrous puffy , bright white head and massive visible carbonation .  m : 2.0 a very watery beer , while the flavors are constantly present there are no real stand out characteristics in the feel . d : 3.0 goes down easy thanks to its thin consistency .

appearance = beautiful golden color smell = like cheap malt liquor taste = like one of the transformers urinated in a can or this is what the inside of oscar the grouch 's trashcan taste like , metal tasting with a slight taste of beer mouthfeel = nothing too bad here drinkability = not good , however i would drink more .  m : awful dry , tannic bitterness d : not so average

it arrives at the table a cloudy brown with a dense , persistent tan head . it leaves nice lacing and makes me thirsty looking at it .  light-medium carbonation and light bodied . grapefruit hop nose and flavor is same - grapefruit hops with hints of caramel , watery . $ 1.85 for a 12oz bottle from colonial spirits acton , ma .
the kbs poured a rich black color .  the taste can only be described as `` extremely watery '' . as far as mouthfeel goes , once again the key words are `` extremely watery '' . flat and dull .

forms a cap like a quicksand plug inviting you into its opaque blackness beneath . random lacing , some of it spotty and some huge patches in other places .  mouthfeel - watery , no bubbles , flat . drinkability - obviously not very drinkable for the fact this is 98 % flat .

so many coulours from red to yellow passing through orange , amazing head with different size of bubbles , last for long , there is some waste . nice aroma , candy and spice taste is nice , for being a 11 % beer you can drink some without any effort nice `` american '' bspa , also i love the bottle  mouth-feel is light and watery .

dark gold in color , but zero light coming through . really impressive for the abv .  m : pretty dry and heavily carbonated with an unpleasant metallic aftertaste . body is pretty thin and in line with other macro lagers .

pours golden amber with a rich white creamy head that slowly settles and stays . frothy lacing covers the glass .  thin body , but still somehow manages to stay around on the palate as if i drank lme .

watching the head form is a truly delightful sight . it looks like you are pouring liquid vanilla ice cream out of a can . the tiny bubbles cascade furiously up to the top as a beautiful head is formed . it is similar to a guinness nitro-can but more intense .  m - thin and watery with a weakly carbonation and a flimsy neutral finish .

on-tap at the cafe , drank from a 5oz tasting glass ... dark brown with a hint of amber , very clear on the edges , looks great . a big head rises a couple fingers but then fades immediately , light lacing ... the aroma is totally dead , nothing going on ... the taste is light coffee , boring , ca n't even tell rye is here .  flavor is malty with a thinnish mouthfeel . high carbonation , too much alcohol , not very drinkable , however it does n't have a bunch of absurd off-flavors like most organic beers .
gorgeous coppery amber color with a great fluffy head .  really takes away from the mouthfeel leaving too thin for the style .

i was honestly not expecting much after having the sink the bismark and being unbelievably unimpressed . the smell is very complex . it 's filled with bourbon notes . layered with vanilla , burn oak , and roasted marshmellow . it 's actually a very acceptable and rich nose . the taste is unique .  body is very thin and rather watery , and the finish is akin to a watered-down lemon-lime soda .
good fluffy rocky tan mocha colored head with a dark brown clear color .  the mouthfeel is where this beer really falls short .
a : simply gorgeous . it was black and viscous , coating the sides of the glass on a swirl , almost too thick to leave a lacing .  mouthfeel is painfully thin .

pours a very clear light copper color with a large and impressive cap of off-white head . retention is very good , as is the lacing . an exceptional looking beer .  a hint of sweet dark malts , but no body to speak of to give these flavours any context . it is a very , very thin amber ale , hardly an alt .

this artwork , like all of their `` artwork '' ... pours a perfectly clear , light copper color with a massive rocky light cream colored head . excellent retention and lacing .  also , way too much carbonation for what i would have wanted in a beer like this .
-12 oz.er poured into pint glass , pours a lovely amber-copper with a very frothy head , like clouds , lasting quite a while . lacing is really lovely .  very thin in the mouth .

poured into a new belgium snifter a - transparent blood red , half finger head , off white almost tan/brown and some serious lacing s - sweet .  taste : i thought it had a burnt tar like flavor with some coffee and chocolate tones mouthfeel : it was very thin and watery for a stout .

a midnight black , picture perfect stout , with head to spare that never goes away ... the beer is gone , can i lick the foam out or is that just trashy ?  m/d : sticky , syrupy , and way under carbonated .

a- looks great a dark rich black with a dark carmel head , though a thin head .  m - there simply is n't enough texture here for a great dunkel . at first it seems almost medium but the brew quickly becomes far too thin for the style .
huge three to four fingers of very white head . looks great . great head retention with some lacing , but not much .  it has an ok flavor , but it 's very thin .
the frothy head is immense , this had the appearance of a fine hefeweizen but looked great for a saison too .  m : mouthfeel ruined it . way too fizzy , drinks like a coke .

dragonmead sir william 's esb 12 oz bottle moderate pour in an english pint recent brewing , knighted 04/06 poured a slightly hazy ruddy copper with a huge off white mostly lasting rocky head with fair lacing .  the feel is pretty terrible ; flat , lifeless , sweet with some metallic bitterness . it is sweet from the dark fruit which is nice but no carbonation just kills this beer .

bottle date : oct 07 , 2010 a- this is a beautiful looking beer , dark pitch black color , opaque , really nice lacing , two finger brown head .  lightly hopped and sparkling on the tongue , this brew is quite flavorful , and has a mouthfeel of carbonated water .
it 's a really inviting looking beer .  m - very watery , light bodied and even undercarbonated .
pours a hazy golden orange with a creamy white head that retain fairly well and laces the glass .  mouthfeel : very thin and watery .

) my ba 1 year birthday beer a - absolutely jet black used motor oil color , yielding nothing else no matter how close i held it to the light . dark brown head , one of the darkest i 've seen , fades to a patchy eighth inch . lots of little lacing bubbles .  m- thin with pretty high carbonation .

a : pours a murky , hazy , fully opaque yellowish orange color with a good inch of stiff , fluffy , off-white head . excellent retention and copious amounts of lacing .  mouthfeel is unremarkable , almost like water .

a : a somewhat vigorous pour ( i already sampled and ris tonight ) yields a pitch black beer with 2 fingers of frothy tan head . extremely dark ... looks like a good stout should .  m - pretty light bodied . surprising lack of carbonation given the beautiful head on this .

a very impressive pour . pours dark brown with glints of mahogany edges ; brown carbonation cascades upward from the mid-body to the top where it settles in thick , craggy tan head .  however , i was very distracted from the taste of this beer with a watery and flat-feeling mouthfeel . this is a good tasting beer , but the mouthfeel issue led me to be slightly disappointed with it .

gorgeous deep candy burgandy . little to no head . vibrant looking .  pours dark dark brown almost black with a 1/2 finger tan head that faded to nothing and left no lacing smell is almost identical to dfh palo santo - very intoxicating taste - again palo santo clone with out the wood - vanilla booze chocolate mouthfeel is not good - the body is too light and the carbonation mixed with the booze stings my mouth drinkability takes a hit due to the mouthfeel but the flavor on this beer is great and maybe some age will mellow the carbonation ?

11.2oz bottle a- pours a dark brown color with a huge light tan head that sticks around forever and leaves a lot of retention along the glass . this is a really pretty pouring beer .  the mouthfeel is medium and watery with almost no carbonation ( seems to be common of ep beers ) .
this beer has a dark brown , almost black colour and a great head that really lasts .  no carbonation whatsoever , so it pours like an extremely dark port .
the appearance is flawless . the contrast of the thick tan head and deep black body is visually appealing .  mouthfeel : watery .
it poured light orange in color with a very active white head nearly overflowing from the glass . great head retention with some thick sheets of lacing as i drank it .  mouthfeel - thin and watery .
tap : clear amber ale with a huge creamy-like head with excellent retention .  thin feel .

interesting . mouthfeel is light-medium bodied , silky-slick with a fair amount of soft carbonation . overall a fantastic looking and smelling ale . i ca n't remember a beer with so much to offer in the color and scent , and then practically bottoming-out when it hits your tongue . the flavor is there and gone in an instant , very strange .  do n't like the mouthfeel in this - fizz seems a bit harsh and the body a bit watery .
a : wonderful sunny body cloudy with some specks of yeast , great white head with good staying power and amazing lacing .  the finish is extremely light , almost watery .
pours a nice fluffy one and half finger head .  m - again thin and watery .

s : great tropical fruit nose , almost like a mini sculpin . grapefruit , pineapple , very enjoyable . lots of hop character for 4.5 % . overall the hop profile is enjoyable , but the carbonic acid makes a play which is hardly ever good .  mouthful is thin and reminds me of rice .

poured from a can into an imperial pint glass a-like it or not this beer looks damn sexy in its own glass .  very light body , coupled with carbonation and sweetness , this was closer to soda pop than banana bread . m=very loose ; no body whatsoever .

s- grapefruit , lemons , oranges ... fruity awesomeness . decent hop profile , not my favorite , but solid . sweet , but i think the oak cuts down on it compared to the og unearthly . m- pretty good considering the abv .  but the bottle i had was too carbonated which gave it a bad mouthfeel , blocking the tastes .
quick review : pours a clear and bright amber with some orange hues and 2 fingers of fluffy off-white head with great retention . leaves lots of lacing .  thin and filmy .

black brew that has a red tint to it when held to the light . thick light brown head that clings to the sides of the glass .  i had a really weird reaction to this beer - it caused me my mouth to water . the mouthfeel clings , even as my mouth is fighting back with spit . did i mention it makes my mouth water ?

the stiff head sits on a clear yet dark brown body . the head remains throughout . the appearance of this one is the highlight .  fizzy carbonation ruined the mouthfeel for me here , this one seemed a bit over carbonated .
pours a light copper /amber colour , lovely frothy head and lacing throughout .  * mouthfeel is thin and watery , with a plethora of fine carbonation .
