a - beer poured with a dark amber colored body ; perfectly formed 1-2 finger size head , white in color ; made the beer look very healthy and full of character and life ; the head of the beer held well ; the body of the beer was well carbonated and clear ; a moderate amount of lacing formed on the side of the glass s - dark malt scent ; roasted nuts and caramel notes touched off with a pleasant aroma of corn and wheat ; some sugar and orange peel ; spice t - heavy dark malt flavor ; crisp corn taste , that washes away rather quickly ; somewhat nutty and nice mixture of wheat and grains to compliment the rich fibrous characteristics of the beer ; slight caramel touch ; touch of spice flavor hits the front of the tongue m - fluffy ; crisp taste and a dry finish ; slightly bitter and tangy ; thin body d - made from authentic corn straight from the maranello ( modena/bologna ) region ( as claimed by the company website ) of italy ; i found this beer to be full of lager scents and clean finish ; a bit harsh to consume , but overall , a notch above average for a lager  i really love the taste but the complete lack of carbonation is disappointing . i like this but even with some mild carbonation i would love this !

absolutely excellent scent . t : dry cocoa powder , dark chocolate , and some fresh oak . o : one of the best smelling imperial stouts i 've ever had , and the taste was good too , but just not quite as good as it smelled .  flavor is one dimensional : black coffee . just tastes bitter and thin , like someone aged seltzer water in a used-coffee-filter-lined barrel .
smell : it has the aroma of very ripe bananas especially when first poured .  the mouth feel is watery and chalky .

visuals : beautiful packaging , fort knox , black , opaque , thin tan head , intricate lace . overall : hard to tell what this even tastes like after the mikkeller black , but the quality shines through .  the taste is pretty much the same , grains . there is a sharp bite of carbonation , and the coldness is getting to me . this is the beer that defines drinkability , they go down like water .

a : hazy golden blonde with a fantastic head ... retention is amazing and it leaves a lacing that has me trying to pick out shapes like in the clouds .  the body is unexpectedly quite thin and as a consequence seems to have too much carbonation .

pours a murky brown , almost opaque except for a small ruddy glow near the bottom when held to the light . it stiffens into a creamy peak , showing great retention and leaving fluffy whisps of off-white lacing .  peppery tongue from the over carbonation ... weak aqueous body , light on malts , raspberry flavor over powers ( flavor additive ? ) tart , dry fast finish ... no after taste . not much here ... too fizzy ... too soda-like in the smell and taste and weak ... .a good girly drink .
nice 2 inch creamy light tan head . good carbonation . rather transparent gold color . patchy lacing that lasts .  kinda on the watery side , not much for carbonation .
the beer is nearly black . some deep scarlet red streaks can be seen against light . decent size and retention as well .  the beer is failed by its thin and bubbly mouthfeel , though .
a beautiful amber color , clear , nice head .  overly attenuated , skimpy and lean in overall body , with a mouthfeel that lacks any firm viscosity .
a : amber red in color but slightly darker and cloudy , good head to start and stuck around for a while .  the palate is thin .

bubbles racing to the top everywhere . big 2-3 finger tan head is medium thick , fluffy , and retains very well . a good brew that looks certainly looks appealing , but is unfortunately very average in the nose and taste .  m : very thin on the palate , incredibly light bodied with high carbonation .
and of course the very cool cascading bubbles which build the creamy tan head , which dutifully hangs out for the duration of the beer .  m : the mouthfeel was very slippery .
pours a slightly hazy golden yellow with a big creamy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  the mouthfeel is thin and watery with little carbonation .

a very nice looking beer . the initial pour looked great , the aroma was good , but after that things kind of went downhill .  the consistency of this beer was watery , and the mouth feel was rather weak .

a : pours a bright glowing golden with a huge frothy bright white head that slowly faded into a thick rocky film that left patches of sticky lacing down the glass .  m - thin with too much carbonation .
poured into a tulip glass . this is just a seriously killer looking beer for an ipa .  m - very little carbonation and does not engender any real tongue sensation .

the aroma on this is really impressive , and though not quite as impressive , the flavor is quite clean and pleasing .  huge carbonation ( for a cask ale ) in a hazy golden orange body , with a low pure white head . mild flavor , thin body , mild bitterness .

very interesting brew , just as i would have suspected from the first triple ipa that i have ever tried . for a beer this strong , the balance of hops and malt hold sup pretty well . then again , if they had , it probably would have been just another double ipa .  no carbonation , flat . but it 's flat .
looks quite beautiful .  mouthfeel is cloying and thick . too thick and cloying , long sour finish is too much for me .

fuller 's 1845 appearance- dark mahogany brown with a very thick head . nice looking ale .  light roast lingers in the finish , not much bitterness , but again a very thin body detracts majorly from this beer and keeps it from being recommendable .

pours an awesome looking , somewhat cloudy amber colour with a big frothy/chunky tan head that subsides somewhat quickly but leaves globs of residue on the glass . great looking stuff .  thin , watery mouth , very little body .
leaves a nearly solid tan curtain of foam on the glass , some of the most impressive lacing i 've ever seen .  extremely watery .
dark amber hue with red highlights . nice one and a half finger , frothy , off white head .  carbonation is annoyingly high , yet still manages to fail at drying out the sweetness .

appearance : looks alone , this is nice - dark but not as think and luminous as an imperial stout . has a light beige head - just under a finger think that is going no where . very good lacing .  m - medium bodied with poor carbonation levels . the carbonation is just wrong for this style of beer .

the appearance of this beer is quite fabulous . it 's crystal clear and the entire vessel is teeming with effervescence . the color is a light shade of yellow . the head is huge and white , containing a plethora of bubbles .  it is watery and just doesnt taste as strong as i think a porter should . you taste what you smell , but the mouthfeel always leaves me thinking , `` why did i buy this again '' ? if you like the taste of porters but do not like the thickness and wish it felt more like a light beer , this is for you !
appearance : beautiful gold with wonderful tan foam . an exceptional look by any standards .  m : too much carbonation ; even more than spa red .

pours clear copper with a towering , dense 2-finger off-white head and tons of effervescence . fantastic stickage and lacing .  body is medium , but there 's almost zero carbonation - leaves the mouthfeel lacking . other than the weak mouthfeel , it 's quite solid .
extremely hoppy , and a beautiful colour .  the body is really watery for the style and unsatisfying despite the flavor being pretty good .
pours a deep , dark brown/black with a nice tan head . it certainly looks the way it tastes , or the way you are hoping it should look for a stout .  m - thin . very thin .

poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass a : beautiful hazy yellow-copper with a towering , rocky two-to-three finger head and sheets of lace s : hallertauer hops smell great -- tangy and spicy .  yikes ... this is supposed to be an ipa ? this tastes like a half assed version of an apa . thin , watery , no head , no lacing , very little taste . where the hell are the hops ? this is a pale ale right ? wow , not a good beer .

dark red-brown/mohagony body topped by a thick off-white lasting head with a good amount of lace left on the glass .  thin . thinner than their lager . kind of sad , really , as the thin body nearly ruins this otherwise nice stout .

clarity was just amazing to look at .  it 's cheap , surprisingly light-tasting ( for a 40 ) and packs a mighty whallop in terms of buzz . as a long fan of steel reserve 211 and st. ides , i admit that they do n't stand up to double malt in terms of taste and mouthfeel .
pours a two finger clingy tan head over a brilliant light copper liquid . head is large bubbled and soapy looking , but holds together well .  mouthfeel is on the watery side .

smell is quite strong . i could smell it after the pour from an arm 's length . very bitter and hoppy , slight sweet malt aroma .  smelled a little like fermented corn and seltzer water with a hint stale beer tastes exactly like it smells yet it is smooth on the palate felt like carbonated water in my mouth ... nothing more nothing less even with the above statements ... this beer is easy to drink ... i remember the days of throwing these thing back without sense of direction ... .they did the job and still do if i bring myself to drink them .
big substantial head . nice reddish-brown color .  t-again kinda thin ... .bready notes very slight coffee flavors coming through .
poured a beautiful amber color , crystal clear with 2 finger head thatleft great lacing in its wake .  feels flat for how much fizzing is going on .
this beer looks amazing . the smell reminds me alot of shiner bock , but much richer , ca n't say i am very impressed with how this smells though .  too thin and not very exciting .

poured from 12oz to a tulip glass pours an amazing melon shade , the cherry is very apparent in shade , like taking a a lager and adding a dash of cherry red to it - ending up in a beautiful color indeed .  watery porter with good bittersweet chocolate malt . finish is dry and watery , with overwhelming carbonation .
this beer is a beautiful , deep golden color . produces a moderate head that dissipates pretty quickly .  mouthfeel is too thin .

appreance huge creamy head on a straight pour . brown clear body that harbors red amber hues when held up to the light . solid head retention .  sweet , lacking much body . basically a soda pop with a very low abv .

the pour produced a thick , dense head nearly 2 inches thick . head lingered for a long time and left good lacing . surprisingly few bubble streams .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with no carbonation .

a - that said , this beer is far from bad with it 's black hole opaque vision and beautiful oily cling to my snifter .  first of all the palate was very thin , with hints of chocolate and a slightly smoke flavour .
mildly hazy brownish red with a fantastic , dense , creamy head with excellent retention and lacing , this is a phenomenal flemish red .  relatively poor mouthfeel .
heavy cascading action as i watch being drawn off the tap . the head is thick and creamy .  the palate is thin .

the fine and dense head got smooth and aired and it lasted nicely on the hazy and active golden color body .  it does leave a really nice lingering coffee flavor on your palate m : very thin . lacks carbonation .
almost perfect lacing , like somebody painted it on the glass .  mouthfeel is thin and flat .

pours a black with ruby highlights with a thick and creamy off-white head that retains well and laces the glass . it 's fun watching the nitro bubbles cascade to the top .  m : dry , i think the mouthfeel takes something away from the beer . overall , i like the complexity and smell but the mouthfeel totally ruins this beer for me .
smells simply fantastic !  m : mouthfeel is oily , almost cloying .

i know it is a fallacy to say this on this website , but here goes nothing : i am not a huge fan of ipas . i know , sorry , but it is the easiest beer to make and everyone goes crazy for it for some reason . i am just not a huge hop guy , and for an ipa , the hops are there , but not overpowering .  mouthfeel is flat and has little carbonation which surprises me .

this brew appears a clear copper color with constantly rising bubbles of carbonation and 2 fingers worth of frothy off-white head . quality retention with this cap and lacing appears all along the glassware with bubbly patches .  m - probably the biggest flaw with this beer . a bit thin on the body and a decent amount over carbonated . my only complaint is the mouthfeel , too much carbonation and not enough body .
poured into its own glass , this beer displays a deep reddish-amber hue and soft , thick head of foam .  finally , the finish of this thin bodied beer was short and watery .

strong citrus hop presence collides with a simply outstanding earthy-sweet malt nose reminiscent of caramelized onions mixed with brandied cherries and rye . sounds gross , smells sublime . well , it 's really sweet , bordering on cloying in fact ... but it 's saved by the hops . actually , it 's more than saved as it 's quite good , especially once it settles in and you 're able to adjust to it .  this beer is able to skate by because it 's not cloying and the sourness distracts for the most part , but i can only imagine how good this would be if it were properly carbonated .

the belgian style pale ale came out cloudy , deep golden , and bubbly , and readily formed a rocky two finger head , that kept rising up until it was sticking above the glass in a volcano shaped cone of bubbles .  woody creek white , flying dog 's 'new ' summer seasonal , pours as near white as one might imagine possible for a beer , which makes for an impressive look that is countered ( and unfortunately not enhanced ) by a fizzy , quick-to-dissipate head . across the tongue , this really just disappears , and the initial spice and malt flavors turn watery . this is not my favorite colorado wit nor my favorite flying dog brew .
large tan head forms and has good retention . plenty of lacing is left on the glass .  felt very flat and rather unpleasant on the palate .
